<SLUG> BC-NY-SQUEEGEE-COP-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEPARTMENT MAY CHARGE POLICE OFFICER   IN SQUEEGEE CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service     
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Police officials said Friday that they would probably
bring departmental proceedings against the officer acquitted of
criminal charges in the shooting of an unarmed ``squeegee man,''
but they said it would be difficult to establish violations of
police procedure because they would be using much of the same
evidence used in the criminal trial.
</P>
<P>
   The officer, Michael W. Meyer, 29, will most likely face
departmental charges of reckless endangerment and wrongful assault
of a person known to the department, and other, lesser charges,
said police officials involved in the department's inquiry into the
case. If found guilty of the charges by an administrative judge,
Meyer could face dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer was acquitted on Thursday of charges of assault and
reckless endangerment after a nonjury trial in State Supreme Court
in the Bronx. Two days earlier, the judge dismissed a charge of
attempted murder.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer testified that he shot in self-defense because he feared
that the ``squeegee man,'' Antoine Reid, would kill him during a
scuffle. The judge ruled that the prosecution had the burden of
proving a different motive, and had failed to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials noted that there is a less stringent standard
for conviction in a departmental trial than in a criminal case,
where the prosecution must prove its case beyond a reasonable
doubt. In a noncriminal proceeding, the standard is whether the
evidence shows that a charge is more likely than not to be true.
</P>
<P>
   But officials involved with the potential case against Meyer
admitted that after an acquittal on similar criminal charges, it
could be difficult to convince an administrative judge that an
officer had committed wrongful assault or reckless endangerment in
the confrontation with Reid on June 14, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you go after people who are not found guilty on a
technicality, or, because of evidence that was excluded in a
criminal trial, we could prosecute them differently,'' said one
police official. ``But in this case, I don't know if that exists.''
</P>
<P>
   The police official said that if the department's administrative
judge agrees with the verdict in the criminal case, it would be
difficult for the department to find Meyer guilty of similar counts
without additional evidence.
</P>
<P>
   An option, the official said, would be to try to persuade Meyer
to resign or to file a series of lesser departmental charges, which
would be less likely to result in Meyer's dismissal upon
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   But the officer's lawyer, Murray Richman, said Friday that Meyer
would not consider resigning from the force.
</P>
<P>
   ``A horrible thing happened, but he simply did nothing wrong,''
Richman said of the shooting.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The internal investigation expanded Thursday, after the trial
concluded, police officials said, because the Bronx district
attorney had asked the police Internal Affairs Bureau, which has
the power to compel officers to answer questions involving
shootings by officers, not to interview Meyer until the conclusion
of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer remains on modified duty, stripped of his badge and gun,
as he has been since the shooting on June 13 of last year. Friday,
Marilyn Mode, a spokeswoman for Commissioner Howard Safir, said
that when Meyer was first arrested and charged, the department drew
up charges that mirrored the criminal charges. ``We are currently
reviewing those charges for possible further departmental
disciplinary action,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer had been removed from patrol duty before the shooting
because he had accumulated an unusually high number of complaints
of using excessive force against civilians. Meyer was transferred
early last year from his patrol post in the 75th Precinct in East
New York, Brooklyn, and assigned to the Police Department's
building maintenance section, where he had little contact with the
public, police officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer, whose record also includes citations for valor, was one
of 16 officers removed from law enforcement duties under a program
to monitor potentially troubled officers who have six or more
complaints of excessive force filed against them with the Civilian
Complaint Review Board within five years.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that when they moved Meyer off patrol they could
not take away his service weapon without placing him on modified
duty, which involves formal departmental charges and a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The six complaints, which were filed since 1994, alleged that
Meyer pushed, shoved, punched and kicked citizens. The trial judge
ruled that evidence of the complaints was inadmissible at the
criminal trial because they had not been substantiated.
</P>
</TEXT>
