<SLUG> BC-BB0-YANKEES-METS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS DEFEAT YANKEES 5-2 AS SHEA STADIUM IS AGAIN TOUGH ON CLEMENS 
 
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Armando Benitez whipped a final strike past the New
York Yankees' Chili Davis Friday night, whirled in a full circle
and began pumping his right fist, once, twice, five times. Five
pumps, one for each of the runs the Mets scored off Roger Clemens,
five pumps for the magnificent performance of Al Leiter. Five pumps
for the Mets' badly needed big-game victory.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza's laser-beam three-run home run off Clemens in the
sixth inning broke a tie, and the Mets beat the Yankees, 5-2,
before 53,820 at Shea Stadium. Al Leiter (8-6), who saved the Mets
from a sweep at Yankee Stadium last month, limited the Yankees to
four hits in eight innings. ``Certainly it was an exciting
feeling,'' said Leiter. `` Piazza came up with the big home run.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, who have lost 2 of 3 games in each of the first three
series against the Yankees in interleague play, have a great
opportunity to win some bragging rights this weekend. The
struggling Andy Pettitte, who has five losses in his last seven
decisions, will pitch for the Yankees Saturday, against the Mets'
Rick Reed, and Orel Hershiser will pair off against the Yankees'
Hideki Irabu Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   After Piazza's home run, the Shea Stadium fans crooned Clemens'
first name: Roger, Roger, sung to the tune of Darryl, Darryl. This
place has never been kind to Clemens, who lost his only
regular-season start here in 1997. Of course, there was 1986.
</P>
<P>
   One of the lasting images from the World Series that year is
that of Clemens bent forward on the visitors' bench in the final
inning of Game 6, hands together in front of his face, hoping and
wishing and praying for three more outs so he could run onto the
field and celebrate the first Red Sox championship in nearly 70
years. But Shea Stadium and the Mets were not kind to Clemens that
night, and really, Shea Stadium has never been a happy place for
Clemens, who is trying to re-establish himself with the Yankees,
once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens knocked down a batter and struck out seven against
Boston May 27, and the Yankees expected him to take off after that.
But he continued to pitch inconsistently, without the dominance
expected of him. He whiffed 13 Texas Rangers June 17 and shut out
Detroit June 29, prompting Yankees manager Joe Torre to say Clemens
was getting stronger and ready to pitch the way he usually does.
</P>
<P>
   It still hasn't happened. He is making mistakes that are at odds
with his legend. When the Yankees acquired him in spring training,
they assumed he would be like David Cone, finding a way through
jams. Instead, he often pitches himself into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' Brian McRae dumped a double down the left field line
in the second inning, and with two outs, Rey Ordonez strolled to
the plate, his batting average .327 over his last 30 games. Leiter,
among the worst-hitting pitchers in the National League stood on
deck, bearing an .074 batting average. Clemens didn't want to
necessarily concede first base to Ordonez _ if he retired the Mets'
shortstop, then Leiter would lead off the next inning, and not
Rickey Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no reason to give Ordonez anything to hit. Clemens
wanted ``to get ahead in the count, early in the game,'' threw a
first-pitch fastball, Ordonez smacked a single through the middle
and the Mets led, 1-0, after two innings. (Clemens, incidentally,
came into the game with a 6.43 ERA in the first two innings of
games, 3.50 thereafter).
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees tied the game in the top of the third, before
Clemens retired the first two batters in the bottom of the third,
jumped ahead of John Olerud no balls and two strikes. Olerud took
two balls, leveling the count, and Clemens threw a splitter or a
fastball over the middle of the plate _ whatever it was, it was a
terrible pitch. Olerud blasted the ball off the bottom of the
scoreboard beyond the right field wall.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees regained control of this game briefly in the top of
the sixth, after Paul O'Neill doubled home Derek Jeter with the
tying run; there was nobody out. But O'Neill was thrown out while
trying to steal third base, a call O'Neill disputed vociferously
(replays showed he was safe on an extremely close play).
</P>
<P>
   Leiter rebounded, and the score was 2-2 when Clemens took the
mound for the bottom of the sixth, and immediately, he was unlucky:
Edgardo Alfonzo blooped a single that barely fell over the
outstretched glove of Chuck Knoblauch. ``The jam shot set up the
whole thing,'' Clemens later lamented.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud was next, and Clemens was extraordinarily cautious,
throwing hard stuff away until Olerud walked. First and second and
nobody out, Piazza due to bat. The Mets' slugger had hit into a
double play in his first at-bat - Piazza had just seven hits in his
last 47 at-bats with runners in scoring position, to that point _
but Piazza had homered off Clemens in June, and for his career, he
was 4 for 7.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens had to attack, that much Piazza knew. He fouled off a
slider, and took two fastballs out of the strike zone. Clemens
isn't the type to concede _ he wasn't going to throw a fastball
down the middle _ so he went with a slider. Posada, his catcher,
set up his glove low and away. Clemens' slider spun down and over
the middle, where Piazza often crushes the ball. ``
</P>
<P>
   Piazza crushed this slider, the baseball zooming over the
infield toward left-center, as if he had misjudged his club choice
and used a 2-iron to smash the ball out of bounds. ``The home run,
that was the backbreaker, obviously,'' said Clemens. ``That one
blow killed us.''
</P>
<P>
   Shea Stadium, the home of Clemens' Game 6 ghosts, erupted in
emotion; for once, Yankees' fans were outshouted. Piazza ambled
around the bases. Clemens kicked at the dirt around the rubber, as
if nothing had happened. That was not the case, of course.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees put a couple of runners on in the ninth inning
against Benitez, who had replaced Leiter, and the slugger Chili
Davis pinch-hit, representing the tying run. Benitez threw a
fastball, Davis missed, and Benitez whirled and pumped his fist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
