<SLUG> BC-FEDCO-BANKRUPTCY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCOUNTER FALLS VICTIM TO CONCEPT'S POPULARITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Fedco Inc. has said it filed for Chapter 11
bankruptcy and will sell its outlets -- a victim of the popular
discount department store concept it pioneered 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal is approved by bankruptcy court, Target would buy
Fedco's 10 general merchandise stores, three furniture and
appliance outlets, and its Santa Fe Springs headquarters and
distribution center for $120 million, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Under Chapter 11 reorganization, Fedco expects to meet its
financial obligations, which include severance for its
approximately 3,700 employees, spokeswoman Donna Walters said.
Money left over from the sale would go toward establishing a
nonprofit foundation to assist charities in areas where Fedco
maintained stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other words, there is a possibility that if everything goes
as expected, Fedco will continue to be a positive influence in the
communities,'' Walters said.
</P>
<P>
   Target, owned by Minneapolis-based Dayton Hudson Corp., expects
to convert six of the 10 general merchandise stores into Target
outlets, and will ``sell or dispose of'' the rest of the properties
in the package, said Patty Morris, a spokeswoman for the chain.
</P>
<P>
   It was too early to say which Fedco stores would be converted to
Targets, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still evaluating the sites to determine which ones would
be most advantageous to open as Target stores,'' Morris said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those locations are valuable locations in terms of potential
guest traffic,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, Target operates two outlets in Northridge and one each
in Pacoima, North Hollywood, Granada Hills and Woodland Hills in
the San Fernando Valley; one in Valencia in the Santa Clarita
Valley; one each in Lancaster and Palmdale in the Antelope Valley;
and stores in Alhambra, Puente Hills, La Verne, Duarte, Pasadena,
West Covina and San Dimas in the San Gabriel Valley.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Van Nuys and Pasadena stores, Fedco has
outlets in Los Angeles and Cerritos in Los Angeles County; Costa
Mesa and Buena Park in Orange County; San Bernardino and Ontario in
San Bernardino County; and Escondido and National City in San Diego
County.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the struggling nonprofit, membership retailer
had embarked on a remodeling program to improve its fortunes and
had completed work on two stores but lacked money for the rest,
Walters said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the discount landscape is now dominated by for-profit
chains.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have now is a bunch of very large for-profit
companies, and competition was very intense,'' Walters said. ``That
need (for discounters) is being filled by other companies. It's
time for Fedco to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
