<SLUG> BC-ZOO-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS BOASTS MORE ZOOS THAN ALL BUT FIVE STATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM PERRIN  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EMPORIA, Kan. _ Mayor Ray Toso knows he has a novelty here,
something few other cities of this size even dream about.
</P>
<P>
   A zoo.
</P>
<P>
   At a modest 6 acres, it isn't a big place. Until a few years ago
it was the smallest accredited zoo in the United States;
nevertheless, it's home to nearly 100 animal species and 500
specimens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until people actually see what's there, I don't think they
realize how nice a zoo a town this size can have,'' said Toso, a
nearly lifelong resident of Emporia, population 25,522. ``A lot of
people are surprised with it.''
</P>
<P>
   In most states, finding a small city with a zoo is unusual, but
not in Kansas, which has six zoos accredited by the American Zoo
and Aquarium Association. That's twice as many as Missouri and more
than all but five states, all of which are far more populous than
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a cultural phenomenon,'' said Mark Reed, director of the
Sedgwick County Zoo in Wichita, the state's largest zoo.
</P>
<P>
   All six accredited zoos _ in Emporia, Garden City, Hutchinson,
Manhattan, Topeka and Wichita _ were among the 20 most-visited
attractions in Kansas last year, based on figures reported to the
state Travel and Tourism Division. (Missouri's accredited zoos are
in Kansas City, St. Louis and Springfield.)
</P>
<P>
   Four other Kansas zoos that aren't accredited _ in Clay Center,
Dodge City, Great Bend and Independence _ also attract thousands of
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Both states have a number of federally licensed, private animal
exhibitors, some of whom bill their attractions as zoos. Some
cities, including Overland Park, have petting zoos or barnyard
animal exhibits.
</P>
<P>
   Collections at some of the smaller Kansas zoos are heavy on
animals native to Kansas or common elsewhere in the United States,
but also include traditional zoo favorites such as lions, giraffes,
bears and chimpanzees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's phenomenal. I don't know why Kansas has so many really
good zoos,'' said Scott Shoemaker, director of Sunset Zoo in
Manhattan. ``I don't know if it's just the character of people that
they want to have zoos and take care of them, or if there's
something in the history of Kansas where if you wanted to be a
legitimate city, you need a zoo.''
</P>
<P>
   There really isn't a simple explanation for why Kansas has so
many zoos, or why they've thrived for so many years, other than
that the communities simply value the zoos enough to support them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of it, people say there's nothing else to do, and there's
a lot of truism to that,'' said Reed, who came to Wichita in 1979
and is the leading figure in Kansas zoos.
</P>
<P>
   Annual budgets for the six accredited zoos range from $175,095
(Emporia) to $5.4 million (Sedgwick County). Local governments are
the largest money source.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the zoos trace their roots to the 1930s as projects
initiated by the Works Progress Administration. Some started with a
``monkey island,'' basically a moat surrounding a small colony of
monkeys.
</P>
<P>
   The only island still being used is at the Ralph Mitchell Zoo in
Independence, a city of about 10,000 in southeast Kansas. The
island used to have a monkey-scale jail and city hall, but only a
castle was left standing several years ago when the island was
renovated into a more natural habitat.
</P>
<P>
   Legend has it that Mickey Mantle once hit a 600-foot home run
onto the island from a nearby baseball stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The zoo's most unusual feature is a small canyon that has been
transformed into enclosures for a cougar and two black bears.
Visitors walk down steps into the canyon onto a boardwalk that
crosses a running stream. Both the cougar and the bears have room
to roam in natural-looking settings.
</P>
<P>
   Marlin Perkins of television's ``Wild Kingdom'' show visited
Independence in 1980 to help develop ideas to renovate the canyon
displays, which date to 1925.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the best mountain lion exhibit in the United
States,'' Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   The Emporia Zoo has come a long way since 1973, when it
consisted of a rectangular fenced area with two bison, deer, a
longhorn steer, a goat and some birds.
</P>
<P>
   Then David Traylor took over as director, and the zoo has been
growing since. The bison and deer remain, but the zoo expanded
across a street, and its collection now includes wallabies and
lemurs.
</P>
<P>
   The zoo is participating in an American Zoo and Aquarium
Association breeding program for cinerous vultures, a bird with an
8-foot wingspan. The bird collection is one of the zoo's
highlights, along with its well-tended grounds that include 12
manmade waterfalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people come in here, I want them to be able to escape to
wherever they want to be, whether they want to see animals or
not,'' Traylor said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sedgwick County Zoo opened in 1971 in west Wichita with one
exhibit, a big barn that has farm animals from Asia, Africa and the
United States. It's still a popular feature, especially with kids,
but only a fraction of what the zoo has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   Sedgwick County's animal collection is the 22nd largest in the
country, Reed said. The zoo has areas devoted to animals from North
America, Asia, Africa, Australia and South America, as well as an
indoor rain forest.
</P>
<P>
   Sedgwick County is also active in efforts to breed several
endangered species. The zoo even has two Komodo dragons. Last
summer at the Kansas City Zoo, a Komodo dragon on loan from
Minnesota was a special attraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their (animal) collection is pretty darn good,'' said Conrad
Schmitt, zoological curator for the Kansas City Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other Kansas zoos, Sunset in Manhattan receives praise
from peers for its chimpanzee exhibit, and Topeka for its gorillas.
Hutchinson is the most recent to receive accreditation, in 1997.
Reed thinks the Brit Spaugh Zoo in Great Bend may soon be ready to
make a run at accreditation.
</P>
<P>
   The 47-acre Lee Richardson Zoo in Garden City was the state's
second most- popular in 1998, with 262,651 visitors. There's a
drive-through fee of $3 per vehicle, but walking through is free.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the exhibits not only attempt to replicate natural
habitats, but also allow visitors to see the animals up close.
</P>
<P>
   At the rhino exhibit, signs read, ``Caution: Rhino marks
territory by urinating toward sidewalk.'' They aren't kidding.
During a recent visit, a Star reporter sprang back just in time to
avoid being splashed.
</P>
<P>
   A specialized zoo, the Rolling Hills Refuge Wildlife
Conservation Center near Salina, is scheduled to open to the public
in late summer or early fall.
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit center, dedicated to the conservation and
propagation of rare and endangered species, is already home to 65
species, including lions, rhinos, orangutans, tigers and giraffes.
</P>
<P>
   Of the center's 500 acres, 95 will be open to the public.
Rolling Hills and state tourism officials are hoping it will induce
more people to pull off Interstate 70 for a day or a night.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people visit Kansas for whatever reason, maybe history or
nature-based tourism, those people need other things to do,'' said
Claudia Larkin, state travel and tourism director. ``Zoos offer a
wonderful alternative, particularly for families.''  &LR; tag1:The
Star's John A. Dvorak stood dangerously close to a rhinoceros for
this story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 0017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
