<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5201 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TUSKEGEE-AIRMAN-KAN &LR;      07-10 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUSKEGEE-AIRMAN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE WHOLE WORLD SEEMED AGAINST US,' BUT AIRMAN KEPT STRIVING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE POPPER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jessie Scott, an unsung hero of a war within a war, raised his
head from the pillow on his nursing home bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our ranks are thinning fast,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott, in his early 70s, is a modest man. There is but one clue
in his room to indicate the honored ranks he once joined. It is a
small bronze plaque almost hidden behind some toiletries on his
dresser.
</P>
<P>
   It states that Scott was one of the ``original Tuskegee
Airmen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So many of the originals are gone now,'' Scott said. ``Not too
many of us are left to tell our story.''
</P>
<P>
   He can barely see the plaque now. His sight has been stolen by
diabetes and glaucoma, his mobility by other medical problems.
</P>
<P>
   But his perspective remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``That plaque is not important,'' he said. ``That's just a
little something for me. It's what we accomplished as a group
that's important. It's what we did that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   And what the Tuskegee Airmen did was glorious. With almost no
support, and confronted by the virulent racism infecting the U.S.
military establishment at the start of World War II, they created
one of the finest fighting units in American history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew what we had to do,'' Scott said. ``So we kept going
though the whole world seemed against us.''  &LR; BRK:`Something to
prove'
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the whole world was against them. For even as they
trained to fight fascism abroad, they confronted an Army Air Corps
filled with white officers who believed the very idea of black
combat pilots was absurd.
</P>
<P>
   That attitude had been bolstered by an Army War College report
concluding that black people lacked the intelligence and courage
for combat flying.
</P>
<P>
   That cruel and ludicrous report became near-doctrine despite the
remarkable valor demonstrated by black regiments in the Civil War,
the Spanish-American War and World War I.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the same old stuff over and over,'' Scott said. ``They
claimed our brains were too small to assimilate the knowledge
necessary to fly. And we heard all those things. But we didn't let
them get us down. We had something to prove.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1939, in a pioneering effort to disprove the War Department,
the all-black Tuskegee Institute in Alabama established an aviation
program for its students.
</P>
<P>
   It was there in 1942 that Scott fell in love with flying.
</P>
<P>
   By then, under growing pressure from the nation's black leaders,
the Army had grudgingly created a separate combat flight-training
school for black men at Tuskegee Air Field.
</P>
<P>
   It was the only such facility in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was there with that first group of Tuskegee Airmen, but I
was still too young to be a cadet,'' said Scott. ``I flew civilian
planes at first. I officially joined the program in 1944.''
</P>
<P>
   Between 1942 and 1944, more than 900 Tuskegee Airmen earned
their wings. Some 450 soon flew in combat.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest graduates of the Tuskegee program were organized
into the now-famed 99th Fighter Squadron. As more graduates joined
them, they later formed four squadrons.
</P>
<P>
   In all, they flew 1,578 missions, shot down 111 German aircraft,
never lost a bomber under their protection, and won 150
Distinguished Flying Crosses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tuskegee experience broke forever the myths that allowed
segregation, inequity and injustice to exist within a thin veil of
legitimacy,'' said Air Force Gen. Ronald R. Fogleman in 1995.
 &LR; BRK:Grounded
</P>
<P>
   Scott was scheduled to earn his wings in 1944, but in a twist of
near-cosmic irony he had to withdraw from the program because he
was found to be color-blind.
</P>
<P>
   Determined to serve, however, he enlisted in the Air Corps as a
flight mechanic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jessie Scott doesn't talk about himself, but he is a special
kind of man,'' said T. Len Nevels, a colonel in the Air Force
Reserves and a past president of the Heart of America Chapter of
the Tuskegee Airmen Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't going to let anything stop him. For every Tuskegee
pilot who got the glory, there were 10 supporting crew members on
the ground. And in my mind, Jessie represents the dedication of
those men and women and what they did to make it all possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their valor and loyalty, the Tuskegee Airmen, pilots and
ground crews alike, paid a constant price.
</P>
<P>
   ``The racism? Oh yeah, it was always there,'' said Scott. ``It
was there straight through in a hundred different ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Moved from field to field, black ground crews were constantly
assigned to a ``Squadron F'' suddenly created upon their arrival.
Their squadron was always fed and billeted in segregated quarters
and denied privileges granted to other enlisted men.
</P>
<P>
   In April of 1945, at Freeman Field in Indiana, 162 black pilots
and navigators, all commissioned officers, were arrested after
defying an order barring them from the officers' club.
</P>
<P>
   Three of those men were court-martialed, 13 received letters of
reprimand.
</P>
<P>
   It took the Air Force 50 years to reverse those discriminatory
proceedings.  &LR; BRK:`We were an example'
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Scott returned to Tuskegee to continue his
education. There he joined the ROTC and rose to become commandant
of cadets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can still see Jessie standing proud in front of the whole
corps of cadets,'' said Jim Wheat, who served on Scott's ROTC
staff.
</P>
<P>
   After graduation, Scott received a regular commission in the Air
Force, earned his wings as a navigator, became a maintenance
officer and made the service his career.
</P>
<P>
   Until his illness slowed him, he was one of the most active
members in the Kansas City branch of the Tuskegee Airmen's
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to know what it all meant?'' Scott said this week.
``Let me tell you a story.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Armed Forces Day in 1957, I was at Hamilton Field in San
Rafael, California. We marched in a parade that day, marched right
through the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were marching in special formation to show the roles of
different members of a cockpit crew. I was marching as a flight
leader...''
</P>
<P>
   He stopped speaking for a moment, lay back on his pillow and
wiped his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry,'' he said. ``I kind of break up a little when I
think about this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyway we came down the street, black and white officers
together, marching strong and tall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We turned a corner and passed a group of kids, some black,
some white.
</P>
<P>
   ``And a few kids pointed at me. I could hear them saying, `Look,
look, see, he's a flier, see his wings.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Those black children saw us, saw black officers wearing wings,
and they knew what it meant. Kids don't miss these things.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were an example and those kids knew it. You could see it in
their faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Tuskegee we became the first. We made it possible for kids
like those to follow us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
