<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE FRIVOLOUS LAWSUITS MEAN FEWER CONSUMER GOODIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   My descent into America's litigious maelstrom began, unknown to
me, two summers ago with the seemingly innocuous act of buying golf
balls. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The dozen Pinnacles came with the promise of a free golf glove,
which was a great deal given the reasonable cost of the brand. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many other golfers apparently felt the same way, and the company
couldn't meet the demand for the free gloves. So, it sent along a
sleeve of three balls with apologies and an explanation that due to
circumstances beyond its control, the supply of free golf gloves
had been exhausted. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No big deal. Any golfer, regardless of skill level, can always
use some extra golf balls. The golf balls that subbed for the glove
have long since met a watery grave, and life went on. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Until Thursday. That was the day another sleeve of three
Pinnacle golf balls arrived in the mail packaged with a notice from
the Cook County, Ill., Circuit Court explaining the details of a
class-action lawsuit involving the golf ball company and the suit's
proposed settlement. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The fine print offered a textbook case of how some Americans
have no qualms about abusing the legal system for fun and profit.
Inferring from the notice's particulars, it seems a couple of guys
weren't satisfied with golf balls in lieu of golf gloves. So they
apparently hired a lawyer to sue the Acushnet Co. for violating
Illinois consumer fraud laws. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The defendant denies all allegations of wrongdoing, but
``considers it desirable to enter into the settlement to avoid the
considerable expense and distraction of burdensome and protracted
litigation.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Loosely translated, the company is willing to pay a reasonable
amount of blackmail to get some litigious pests off its back. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What's the proposed settlement? It appears the lawyer will get
$100,000 if the court approves, and the named wisenheimers who
pushed the suit will get $2,500 apiece ``for their efforts in
litigating the case on behalf of the clients.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Everyone else apparently gets that extra sleeve of golf balls
that came with the court notice. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those such as myself who don't want to be included in the class
must go to the trouble of informing the court, which is hardly
worth the hassle or the postage costs involved. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This hardly is a triumph for consumer rights or interests. The
cost of the litigation to Acushnet isn't likely to raise the price
of its golf balls because of the highly competitive nature of the
golf ball market. Then again, it's unlikely Acushnet will be
dimwitted enough to undertake another marketing initiative offering
free goodies with the purchase of its products. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Acushnet's unfortunate experience won't be lost on
other equipment producers, which means golfers can expect fewer
promotions that benefit them. Meantime, the taxpayers are footing
the costs involved in the use of county court to pursue this
exercise in wretched litigious excess. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A generation ago, this sort of tomfoolery would have been
laughed out of any bar in which it was hatched. Now it passes for
acceptable, if not respectable, behavior, which truly is
depressing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So, tell 'em in Chicago, as Casey Stengel once put it, to
include me out. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 0023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
