<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PIAZZA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH RUNNERS ON BASE, PIAZZA SWINGS LIKE A HERO AND BRINGS THEM
HOME  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A year has passed and much has changed since Mike
Piazza's first summer at Shea Stadium. Now, after signing a
seven-year deal with the Mets last fall, Piazza is no longer viewed
as a mercenary. He no longer hears the boos at home, at least not
as regularly or as loud.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing was very much the same coming into last night's
game with the Yankees: Piazza was again struggling at the plate
with men on base. For nearly three weeks, he had been struggling at
the plate, period.
</P>
<P>
   With one sixth-inning swing Friday night, however, Piazza was
able to wash away the bad taste of his season-long futility with
runners in scoring position. Piazza was 7 for his last 48 (.146) in
such situations when he stepped to the plate against Roger Clemens
with runners on first and second in a taut 2-2 ballgame. Clemens
fell behind Piazza in the count, 2 and 1. Clemens threw a slider.
Piazza looked like he knew it was coming.
</P>
<P>
   In an instant, the ball was on a line for the bleachers in left
field. The crowd of 53,820 went wild. Piazza had his 18th home run
of the season, the biggest hit of the evening, and the Mets had a
three-run lead that would hold till the end.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, who was summoned for a curtain call, later legged out a
seventh-inning infield hit to finish 2 for 4 and raise his average
three points to .307.
</P>
<P>
   It was a welcome bit of heroics for Piazza. Before he hit the
home run, his frustration had been mounting. That much was evident
in the first inning when Piazza flung his bat toward the Yankees
dugout after he had grounded to short for an inning-ending double
play.
</P>
<P>
   Since rattling off a career-high 24-game hitting streak, Piazza
had entered this weekend's three-game series at Shea with only
eight hits in his last 42 times at bat (.190), and since June 23
had only one home run and five runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   The all-star catcher's numbers for the season were still
respectable: a .304 average, 17 homers, 49 runs batted in. But
Piazza was batting just .222 with runners in scoring position on
the year. With no one on base, Piazza was hitting .336. With men
on, Piazza was hitting .280. He was also struggling in games termed
close and late _ an esoteric statistic defined as a game in the
seventh inning or later in which the batting team is either leading
by one run, tied or has the potential tying run on base, at bat or
on deck. In those situations this season, Piazza is hitting .200.
</P>
<P>
   No one seemed very worried. Piazza went on a tear last August
and September, and all but carried the club offensively as it made
a run at the postseason. The Mets are expecting him to do the same
this season. Piazza finished 1998 with a .291 average with runners
in scoring position. His lifetime average with runners in scoring
position when the season began was .336.
</P>
<P>
   But as long as Piazza continued to struggle, there was always
the danger that the scowl that seemed etched into his face for much
of last summer might become a fixture at the plate again.
</P>
<P>
   That is because no one is harder on Piazza than Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike has real high expectations,'' Valentine said before
Friday night's game. ``Every at-bat seems like its either the first
or last at-bat of his career. I think he's just a little bit at a
loss right now. When a hitter doesn't feel good about his stroke,
it's like being in a rain forest without an umbrella. It's not a
real comfortable feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   For right now, at least, Piazza insists that he is fine, and
feeling at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, there was a lot of uncertainty in my situation,''
Piazza, who was traded twice, said before the game. ``That's
probably why there was some negative sentiment. A lot of people
probably thought I was going to be here for a short time only. But
I'm here. I chose to be here. The team chose for me to be here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a part of this organization, I'm a part of this team, and
I'm a part of this city now. That doesn't mean I'm exempt from any
criticism. And in this city, there is an edge to everything. But I
don't shy away from that.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't thrive on the negativity that goes along with playing
in New York either, though. But he can't help being critical of
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always feel like I should be playing better,'' said Piazza,
who has either been elected or selected to the National League
All-Star team in each of his seven seasons. ``But your are
undoubtedly going to go through ups and downs. As a player, you
have to try to stay off that roller-coaster. But it's not that easy
to do. Sometimes here everything seems like a season in itself. I'm
not shying away from that. I just know that's the way it is h%re.
You just have to realize there are times for atonement.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Friday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
