<HEADER>
A5224 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEGAL-SCHOLARS-ART-63     07-10 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEGAL-SCHOLARS-ART-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGAL SCHOLAR TO FINISH WORK KF HIS LATE MENTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Two nationally known black legal scholars
were separated by more than a generation but connected by a shared
view of the world. One died last winter. Now the other, in a final
tribute that is something like one man completing another's last
sentence, is finishing his friend's incomplete books and articles.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership offers a picture of one strand of modern black
legal thought. It also shows the intellectual ties forged by two
men with similar stories of personal achievement against enormous
odds.
</P>
<P>
   One of the men, the Harvard Law School professor Charles J.
Ogletree Jr., 46, is heir to a tradition of black participation in
the highest echelons of the legal system. The other, the retired
federal appeals court judge A. Leon Higginbotham Jr., who was a
legal scholar here at Harvard, was a trailblazer of that tradition
before he died at 70 in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judge Higginbotham is like a father figure to me,'' Ogletree
said in his office at the law school, speaking of his friend in the
present tense seven months after his death. ``I love the man and
have enormous respect for what he accomplished. I would do whatever
he asked to complete his work.''
</P>
<P>
   As it happened, Higginbotham died suddenly of a stroke and did
not have a chance to ask anyone to complete several projects,
including a critique of Justice Clarence Thomas of the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   Ogletree has taken up the assignment, with the enthusiastic
support of Higginbotham's widow, promising to deliver the final
published works in the voice of the man who often used his own life
story as parable for both the barriers and possibilities for
African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Leon Higginbotham, the son of a laborer and a maid who grew up
in the poverty of Trenton, contended with bigotry and segregation
and became one of the country's top judges as the chief of the U.S.
Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit, in Philadelphia. After he
retired from the court in 1993, he taught at Harvard, wrote and
served as a director of The New York Times Co.
</P>
<P>
   In a friendship spanning decades, Higginbotham and Ogletree
agreed that assaults on affirmative action and civil rights
generally had become central challenges for the legal system.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of his life Higginbotham attracted wide notice with a
rare public attack on Thomas. Thomas' ``retrogressive record'' on
the Supreme Court, Higginbotham said, was helping roll back the
progress of blacks.
</P>
<P>
   In a long interview over a lunch that he never touched and in
unfinished manuscripts he provided, Ogletree made it clear that the
final works of Higginbotham would continue the theme.
</P>
<P>
   A speech by the judge that Ogletree is reworking into a law
review article said, ``Justice Thomas has done more to turn back
the clock of racial progress than has any other African-American
public official in the history of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Ogletree, who represented Anita Hill in Thomas' confirmation
hearings, said neither he nor Higginbotham should be thought of
solely for their work as critics of Thomas. The judge and the
professor have both taught and written broadly on the legal system
and civil rights. But for legal scholars like himself, Ogletree
said, Higginbotham's critique of Thomas has become a focal point
for deep concerns about the legal system.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Ogletree said, his preparation of
Higginbotham's final observations about Thomas is especially
important.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is one of a small number of people,'' Ogletree said of his
friend, ``who were so successful that he did not have to incur the
headache of getting involved in the civil rights movement, and yet
he chose this as his life's work.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``It is such a contrast to Clarence Thomas, who has benefited
from the civil rights movement and has been hostile to it,'' the
professor continued. ``Judge Higginbotham thought it was important
to let the general public know that it is not necessary to stab the
people in the back after you have achieved your successes.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Arberg, the Supreme Court spokeswoman, said Thomas had no
comment. Thomas' supporters have said attacks on the justice are
the height of hypocrisy because they suggest that no black judge
could reach his conservative views in good faith.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, as Higginbotham's criticisms were widely
circulated, Thomas called criticism of him ``bilious and venomous
assaults'' and said he refused to have ``ideas assigned to me as
though I was an intellectual slave because I am black.''
</P>
<P>
   Ogletree said Thomas' appointment to the court had divided black
intellectuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very concerned,'' Ogletree said of Thomas, ``about the
trend that he has been part of to not only re-examine but curtail
the progress of the last four decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Ogletree said he and Higginbotham occasionally talked about
similarities in their pasts. Ogletree, the son of a laborer in
agricultural Merced, Calif., was the first in his family to
graduate from high school. He also graduated from Stanford
University and Harvard Law School, where, as a student two decades
ago, he first heard a speech by an inspiring judge named Leon
Higginbotham.
</P>
<P>
   Ogletree said the two men sometimes talked about how far each
had come in overcoming the obstacles to black success in the United
States. The judge, Ogletree said, always said success like his was
owing in large measure to the people who had helped him before
anyone had thought of programs called affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is something that resonates with me,'' Ogletree said. ``I
will never forget the people who pulled me up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 0051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
