<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.Y.-BLACKOUT-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAT WAVE TOLL CLIMBS TO 27 DEAD IN NEW YORK CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The number of deaths directly tied to the record heat
in New York City this week had risen to 27 through Thursday, a
spokeswoman for the city medical examiner's office said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The spokeswoman, Ellen Borakove, said the ages of the victims
ranged from 27 to 102.
</P>
<P>
   While the death count was small compared with the toll from a
1995 heat wave in Chicago that killed more than 500 people, the
heat wave was still one of the deadliest weather events here in
recent years, city officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Jerome Hauer, the director of the mayor's Office of Emergency
Management, said that most of those who died were elderly, and that
his office was reviewing the cases to understand how the heat
killed people and to find ways to avert such deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it's difficult to accept any deaths, we feel that the
city did all it could,'' Hauer said. ``But we're going to continue
to review each of the deaths to see what happened, to see if
there's something we could have done differently.''
</P>
<P>
   There appeared to be no clear link between the deaths and the
blackouts in upper Manhattan or on the Lower East Side, officials
said. The deaths in Manhattan were reported at hospitals throughout
the borough and by widely dispersed emergency workers. No deaths
were recorded at New York Presbyterian Hospital, the closest large
hospital to the area north of 155th Street where the most prolonged
power failures occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, 13 of the he!t-related deaths occurred in Manhattan,
12 were in Brooklyn, and two were in Queens, Ms. Borakove said.
</P>
<P>
   Hauer said the deaths illustrated the importance of keeping
track of those who are vulnerable, including elderly and
handicapped people who might not be able to leave their apartments.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the reasons we encourage New Yorkers in these
crises to check on their elderly neighbors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The deadliest heat wave recorded in New York City occurred in
July 1936, when the temperature in Central Park hit an all-time
high of 106 degrees and 76 deaths were attributed to the heat. But
21 of the deaths were from drowning, as those who could not swim
jumped into the rivers to cool off.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In 1995, when Chicago suffered its worst heat wave, 17 New York
City residents died of heat-related causes between July 17 and 31.
</P>
<P>
   When blazing heat lasts more than a couple of days, many older
buildings absorb and store solar energy and can bake for several
days after the weather breaks, according to federal studies
initiated after the 1995 heat wave in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Often, the temperature in rooms on high floors in old masonry or
stone buildings without ceiling insulation exceeds the temperature
outside, said Dr. Evan Mills, a scientist at the Lawrence Berkeley
National Laboratory in Berkeley, Calif. He used computer models to
study how heat affects buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The heat lingers most dangerously in older, uninsulated brick
and stone buildings in poor urban neighborhoods, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, city residents tend to suffer more because asphalt
and concrete in streets and other structures absorb heat and send
temperatures many degrees higher than in the suburbs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put all that together with poor communities who don't have
air-conditioning and you've got a problem,'' Mills said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
