<SLUG> BC-N.J.-TRUMP-CASINO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUMP IS PLANNING TO DEMOLISH ONE CASINO 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Donald J. Trump plans to demolish his World's Fair casino in
Atlantic City around the end of the year and may build a
4,000-room, $750 million gambling complex in its place, officials
of his development company said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Trump, who also owns the Trump Taj Mahal and the Trump Marina in
Atlantic City, has owned the casino property since 1989, when it
was run as a nongambling hotel called the Trump Regency, said
Nicholas L. Ribis, president of Trump Hotels and Casino Resorts.
</P>
<P>
   Gambling tables were added to the site in 1996, when the
building underwent a $48 million renovation and was reopened as the
World's Fair.
</P>
<P>
   Although the 21-story building has a long history in Atlantic
City, having originally been built as a Playboy casino, it has
struggled in recent years, routinely losing money, Ribis said. The
casino will be closed later this year in preparation for the
demolition, which is likely to cost between $3 million and $5
million, he said.
</P>
<P>
   When the building comes down, it will leave Trump in possession
of a 15-acre site that is the largest undeveloped site on the
boardwalk, Ribis said. He added that the site is particularly
valuable because it is adjacent to Atlantic City's brand-new
Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   Once the old casino comes down, Trump will decide whether to
open a new casino with a partner, sell the land or build his own
casino on the site, Ribis said.
</P>
<P>
   Construction could begin as early as 2001, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
