<SLUG> BC-OBIT-HARNETT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMAS HARNETT, CAREY CABINET OFFICIAL, DIES AT 75  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Me., Conn., Canada, Pa. Va.)   By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thomas Aquinas Harnett, a lawyer specializing in insurance who
was superintendent of the State Insurance Department in the 1970s,
died on Wednesday at his home in Ridgefield, Conn. He was 75 and
had formerly lived in Manhattan and Suffern, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cardiac arrest, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Harnett retired last year from the Manhattan firm of Lane &AMP;
Mittendorf and became a founding partner of Gallagher, Harnett &AMP;
Lagalante, also in Manhattan. There he continued to deal with
commercial litigation, and with insurance regulations pending
before governmental bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Hugh L. Carey named him state superintendent of insurance,
a cabinet-level position, in June 1975. Harnett resigned after two
years to return to the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   A native of the Bronx, he graduated from Fordham University
School of Education with a teacher's certificate in 1943 and
received his law degree from Fordham in 1949. In World War II, he
served with the Army Air Force in the Pacific and was awarded the
Air Medal.
</P>
<P>
   He taught product liability law as an adjunct professor at
Fordham University School of Law and had been a director of the New
York State Urban Development Corp. and a regent of the University
of Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Harnett is survived by his wife of 48 years, Doris Van Dien
Harnett; two daughters, Doris A. Harnett of Dixmont, Me., and
Kathleen H. Linger of Fairfield, Conn.; two sons, Thomas A., of
Gardiner, Me., and William A., of Toronto; two brothers, William,
of Bryn Mawr, Pa., and John, of Virginia, and four grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
