<HEADER>
A5233 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-N.Y.-POLITICS-NY     07-10 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-N.Y.-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE HIGH COST OF LONG ISLAND POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, July 10:
</P>
<P>
   Creating a fiscal crisis in a prosperous suburban county during
one of the biggest economic booms in American history takes some
doing, but the Nassau County executive, Thomas Gulotta, has pulled
it off. The county ended 1998 with a deficit of nearly $200
million, and is wrestling with another big projected gap this year.
Its ridiculous property tax assessment system, which has turned
challenging assessments into a local industry, is costing the
county more than $100 million a year in refunds. In the latest
blow, Standard &AMP; Poor's has announced that it is reducing the
rating of the county's bonds to BBB _ near junk status.
</P>
<P>
   Gulotta has relied on costly short-term borrowing to pay the
bills, while inventing increasingly outlandish ploys to paper over
a budget that is structurally out of balance. Earlier this year the
county got a $70 million infusion of cash from the Metropolitan
Transportation Authority in return for accepting $240 million in
long-term MTA debt. Next, Gulotta hopes to borrow against
anticipated future gains from the county's share of a national
tobacco settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Out-of-control labor costs, particularly in the police
department, are one of the main causes of the county's problems.
More than half of last year's deficit was due to cost overruns in
police salaries and benefits. The county must also reform its
assessment system, under which homes are assessed on the basis of
1938 construction costs and 1964 land costs.
</P>
<P>
   The system is impossible to administer, one of the reasons the
county winds up owing so much to homeowners for refunds from
assessment appeals. Astonishingly, the county sells bonds to pay
for those refunds, and its long-term debt has now ballooned to
almost $2.7 billion. The assessment system has been decried by
everyone from the county business community to the Justice
Department, which says it discriminates against minority
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Like New York City in the 1970s, Nassau County is being run by a
one-party political system that has become brain-dead from lack of
new blood. In this case, it is the Republican Party that has run
the government into the ground by spending money it did not have to
keep political allies happy. The Republicans do not seem capable of
reforming themselves and the Democrats do not appear to have the
capacity to challenge them. The only answer may be an outside
arbiter to put a spine in its fiscal policies.
</P>
<P>
   The county could get some breathing time if the state
Legislature approves a plan to raise the tax on property transfers.
But the Democratic-dominated state Assembly is demanding a price _
giving the state comptroller, Carl McCall, authority to oversee the
county's fiscal practices. Republicans are unhappy with the idea of
giving this power to a Democrat. But McCall's office has the
expertise to do the job, and his duties would only entail forcing
officials to do what they should be doing already _ engaging in
long-term financial planning and keeping spending within the bounds
of county income.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 0101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990710.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5238 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-MEXICO-     07-10 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-MEXICO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: MEXICO'S FEW REAL VOTERS FINALLY SPEAK OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By TINA ROSENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since 1940, Mexico's presidents have been chosen by an
electorate of one. Each president picked the next nominee of the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, and each nominee won
handily against largely token opposition, by fraud when necessary.
President Ernesto Zedillo has declared he will be the last
beneficiary of the ``dedazo,'' or the pointing of the finger.
Instead the PRI will have a national primary in November to choose
its candidate for the general election in July 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The primary is the system least susceptible to presidential
manipulation _ yet few doubt that it will ratify the candidate
widely believed to be Zedillo's favorite, Francisco Labastida
Ochoa. As has been the case with other PRI reforms, the question is
whether they will just cover up the continuation of authoritarian
habits.
</P>
<P>
   The need to reform the dedazo is clearer than ever to most
Mexicans since the publication of ``La Herencia'' _ the legacy _ by
the political scientist Jorge Castaneda, which will be published in
English next year. The book consists of long interviews Castaneda
conducted with all four living former presidents, as well as an
analysis that relies heavily on his conversations with dozens of
politicians who never made it to the top. It has quickly become
Mexico's best-selling political book ever.
</P>
<P>
   While it was clear to everyone in Mexico that each president
made his decision alone _ and later staged huge PRI rallies
supposedly demanding the nomination of the favorite _ the book
marks the first time the presidents have publicly said so. The book
portrays a system of serial despotism, where candidates win
near-absolute power not by wooing the public or defending their
policies in the media, but simply by fawning over the boss. It is
unlikely that any cabinet official who dreams he has a chance at
the nomination ever brought a president information that he did not
want to hear.
</P>
<P>
   Castaneda argues that the dedazo gave Mexico valuable stability
at a high political and economic cost. President Luis Echeverria,
for example, was determined to name his boyhood friend Jose Lopez
Portillo as his successor in the 1976 elections. To give Lopez
Portillo credibility and financial experience, Echeverria made him
his treasury minister. But this meant that Mexico could not carry
out a necessary devaluation of the currency or needed tax reforms,
both of which would have made Lopez Portillo unpopular. The result
was economic disaster _ Mexico's external debt tripled by the end
of Echeverria's term.
</P>
<P>
   Castaneda presents evidence that in 1981, the budget minister,
Miguel de la Madrid, hid the country's true fiscal deficit until
after Lopez Portillo had chosen him as the candidate, delaying a
needed devaluation of the peso. Some argue that de la Madrid was
himself deceived by the budget staff _ headed by Carlos Salinas,
whom he would name as Mexico's next president.
</P>
<P>
   Public officials all over the world hide bad news. But in
democracies, they are at least open to questioning by the press and
electorate. This is increasingly the case under the presidency of
Zedillo. The PRI has stopped stuffing ballot boxes. The opposition
governs in nine of 31 states and in Mexico City, and holds the
mayoralties of most big cities. The party is somewhat more
independent of the president's wishes. Mexico's press, moreover,
has grown more independent and assertive.
</P>
<P>
   But authoritarian practices persist. The gubernatorial election
on July 4 in the state of Mexico, the country's most populous,
featured widespread reports of PRI vote-buying and other kinds of
coercion. Two years ago, after the PRI lost control of the lower
house of Congress, its members attempted a boycott. Zedillo has
appointed the last two party leaders, after promising he would not.
Today as in the past, the PRI machine is rallying around the man
officials believe to be the president's candidate ( Zedillo denies
he has one), with the same ``spontaneous'' rallies by labor and the
party rank and file as in days of old. There will be a primary, but
Labastida's two main opponents _ both members of the PRI old guard
_ are given little chance.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida has become the front-runner without raising money or
building an organization. He is starting to, however, because the
real change in Mexico is that winning the PRI nomination no longer
guarantees the presidency. The nominee may well win if the two
opposition party candidates split the anti-PRI vote next summer.
But if one withdraws, then the PRI will have a real race. Zedillo's
record of democratizing his party has been excellent in one respect
_ the time when PRI candidates could count on a national victory
though Election Day fraud is over, probably forever. Even as
Castaneda underscores the costs of Mexico's elected dictatorship,
he has written the system's obituary. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 0104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
