<HEADER>
A5240 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-GUNCONTROL-NYT &LR;      07-10 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GUNCONTROL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SHOWING THE WAY ON GUN CONTROL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, July 10:
</P>
<P>
   There are signs that Congress may yet approve some gun control
measures this year despite last month's debacle in the House that
saw Republican leaders and a powerful Democrat, John Dingell of
Michigan, conspire to kill a modest gun control package already
passed by the Senate. The House version was so weak that even
supporters of gun control voted against it.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, plainly aware of his party's
vulnerability on the gun control issue, told The Washington Post
that the issue was not dead and that he saw room for a compromise
on a key sticking point _ the National Rifle Association's demand
that the period for conducting criminal background checks on
prospective purchasers at gun shows be limited to 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   That is not enough time for a thorough check, especially since
most gun shows occur over weekends, when state court files are
generally unavailable. But a 48-hour limit, which Hastert
apparently sees as the potential compromise, is also too short. If
the speaker want to convince Americans that his party supports
meaningful gun control, he and his colleagues will accept the
Senate's gun show provision, which allows up to three business days
for background checks.
</P>
<P>
   Some states, meanwhile, are taking aggressive steps of their own
to keep guns away from children and criminals. A week ago, for
example, the highest court in Massachusetts affirmed the power oF
the state attorney general to impose safety requirements on gun
manufacturers. Precisely how far this power extends is not yet
clear. But this path-breaking use of the state's consumer
protection statute to mandate new childproofing features on all
handguns sold in Massachusetts could become a model for other
jurisdictions around the country with similar consumer laws on the
books.
</P>
<P>
   In California, the state legislature has approved a bill
designed to help close off the gun supply to the illegal market run
by unlicensed dealers on the streets by limiting handgun purchases
to one a month. Benjamin Daniel Smith, the white supremacist who
went on a deadly shooting rampage, obtained the gun he is believed
to have used from just such a dealer in Illinois after failing a
background check initiated by a licensed seller.
</P>
<P>
   California's governor, Gray Davis, has yet to say whether he
will sign the bill. But this should not be a hard decision for
Davis, who emphasized gun control in his campaign last year.
Indeed, with the Governor lending a strong push, there is also a
very good chance that the legislature will soon pass the strongest
assault-weapon ban in the country.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey came close to joining the honor roll with a bill that
would have forced gun manufacturers to install computer chips and
other ``smart gun'' technology to make guns inoperable by anyone
other than the weapon's registered owner. Unfortunately, Donald
DiFrancesco, president of the State Senate, substituted an
essentially toothless version at the last minute, letting the gun
makers off the hook.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the momentum building in Massachusetts and California is
bound to reverberate elsewhere, as it should. But its immediate
effect is to make Congress, which was not looking so great to start
with, look even worse.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 0107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
