<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-SURVIVAL-GUIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD CUP SURVIVAL GUIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHARD GONZALEZ  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ U.S. coach Tony DiCicco has devised plans for
upending China in today's Women's World Cup Final at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a ticket, you'll need a survival plan.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100,000 _ including WWC representatives, vendors,
workers, media and the sold-out crush of ticket-toting fans _
figures to pose logistics nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Crushing traffic, a hot weather forecast and the security
details regarding President Clinton's presence top the list.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare yourself by arriving early by shuttle, with cool
clothing, bottled water (sealed only) and plenty of sunscreen.
</P>
<P>
   The championship game is slated for 12:50 p.m., preceded by the
Brazil-Norway matchup for third place at 10:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Pregame activities and a postgame celebration for fans are also
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   ``With media and Rose Bowl and World Cup PR people coming in and
out, I think we're going to have a pretty good flow (of people
arriving) during the first game,'' said Jim Granger of Contemporary
Services Corp., which staffs security manpower for numerous
Southland events.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than battle the crowds and gridlock, Rose Bowl general
manager Darryl Dunn proffers a gold-mine suggestion: ``Take the
shuttle.''
</P>
<P>
   Shuttles will be continuously departing from the Ralph M.
Parsons Corp. parking lot, located on the corner of Walnut Street
and Fair Oaks Avenue in Pasadena, near Old Town. The fee is $4 per
person. Otherwise, on-site parking is $10.
</P>
<P>
   ``From step-on to drop-off, I've been told it'll take 5 to 7
minutes,'' Dunne said of the limited-access trek.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Taking the shuttle), you have no problems with traffic,
losing your car in the jam-packed parking lots, getting boxed in by
the postgame activities. It's the best thing to do if you want to
avoid headaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit should pose less traffic problems than his
same-day decision to take in the U.S.-Germany quarterfinal match in
Washington D.C. on July 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're better prepared because we had advance notice,'' Dunn
said. ``We should be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Metal detectors may be implemented to gain stadium access.
That's only, of course, if you have a ticket.
</P>
<P>
   An additional 3,000 to 5,000 seats became available Tuesday when
WWC organizers made a venue walk-through and asked Rose Bowl
officials to remove tarp covering a row of seats close to the
field. They sold out in 82 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want the tarps off, we take them off,'' Dunn said.
``We're just the landlord.''
</P>
<P>
   Another walk-through was taken late Wednesday afternoon, but WWC
officials decided against opening very close seats with poor sight
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Water-misting ``cool zones'' also will be set up throughout the
stadium to help cope with any heat problems.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles-based Murray's Tickets reportedly had sold out of
choice seats, with behind-the-goal ducats commanding $135 apiece.
Ebay, an on-line auction company, was also taking skyrocketing bids
for tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Because of the hoopla,) I think people just want to be a part
of the event,'' said Steve Vanderpool, director of public relations
for WWC '99.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps a once-in-a-lifetime event, at that.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not like a Rose Bowl game ... it's bigger,'' Dunn
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
