<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCCER-PASADENA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD CUP FINALS KICK OFF IN PASADENA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY TROY ANDERSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. -- Soccermania overtook Old Town Pasadena on
Friday evening as hundreds of soccer fans converged on Colorado
Street in anticipation of today's women's World Cup championship
pitting the United States against China.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer moms, soccer dads, soccer kids and plain-old soccer fans
jammed a closed-off section of Colorado Street downtown, where they
had their faces painted with soccer balls and U.S. flags, bought
World Cup souvenirs and listened to the clashing cymbals and
pounding drums of a Chinese dragon procession.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the two men inside the yellow-and-red dragon
costume charged a Broomfield, Colo., family carrying American
flags.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it was because of our U.S. flags,'' said
39-year-old Cheryl Brosz, who along with her daughter was waving a
flag when the dragon came at them. ``They think it will help them
win tomorrow, but it won't work.''
</P>
<P>
   A soccer tournament that relatively few people knew existed a
month ago has gained such legitimacy and buzz that scalpers are
asking four times face value or more for tickets. A sell-out crowd
of nearly 90,000 people is expected today for the Women's World Cup
final at the Rose Bowl stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's not 120 degrees out, it should be bedlam,'' said
Woodland Hills attorney Stu Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   Vice president of Valley United Soccer Club's girls' program,
Steinberg is going to the Rose Bowl with a group of about 100
people, including his 13-year-old daughter, Jessie. They expect to
leave around 6:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids are just totally into this thing,'' he said of the
World Cup. ``I'm just as excited as they are.''
</P>
<P>
   The match will be broadcast to a national television audience by
ABC and will provide the American women a grand stage to display
their soccer skills and convince sponsors there is a need for a
professional league in this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is wonderful for kids to have role models like
these women,'' said Dallas, Texas, mom Teri Marshalek, a lifelong
soccer player who brought her 12-year-old daughter to Pasadena and
paid $110 for tickets to see the game. ``We live in Dallas and the
Dallas Cowboys are a bunch of spoiled brats. You see them getting
busted and dying of drug overdoses.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have that with the women's teams. They work hard,
live together and are very conscious of helping young girls.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team of photogenic female athletes has fueled
mainstream American interest in international soccer. But the game
was already a crowd-pleaser on the West Coast, thanks to decades of
immigration from soccer-crazed Latin America and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go to any school field on a Saturday morning and there are
hundreds of kids playing soccer,'' said Palo Alto resident Steve
Levy, who bought tickets for himself and his 17-year-old daughter,
Jennifer, a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is focusing on this game, but it is just the tip of
iceberg of this phenomena. It's been building at a grass-roots
level for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of those kicking soccer balls in inflatable soccer pens,
playing table soccer and feeling the booming beat of Asian drummers
Friday evening in Old Town Pasadena came from throughout the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Two Kansas City mothers left husbands behind and drove 1,700
miles with their daughters to see the game. They paid $110 a
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a brand new girls' sport that has really taken over,''
said Kansas City resident Lizzy Flanigan, 11, whose cheek was
freshly painted by a clown with an American flag as she mingled
with the crowds in Pasadena Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Lizzy was most excited about sneaking into a Pasadena hotel
where the U.S. women's team players were staying and getting a
picture taken with a player.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they first came out of the hotel they were screaming,''
soccer mom Colleen Flanigan said of her girls. ``That's when we
knew it was worth the 1,700-mile drive in the car.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City resident Brittany Bolton, 11, said she saw a soccer
player walking down the hallway and asked for her autograph.
</P>
<P>
   When forward Mia Hamm got into the elevator, 9-year-old Molly
Flanigan rushed to the door to get inside, but it shut before she
had a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were told to get off the fifth floor by security,'' said
her mother, Victoria Bolton. ``We knew they didn't want us around
anymore. They are pretty focused right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Identical twins from Albuquerque, N.M., painted their
fingernails with American flags for the event and came dressed in
World Cup T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are really into soccer now,'' said Donna Mark. ``We wanted
to go all out for the U.S. team.''
</P>
<P>
   Many in Old Town on Friday evening said they expect the U.S.
women's team to win but agree it's not going to be easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They play good; they play smart,'' said Pasadena resident
Saloman Cravioto, 18, whose dad gave him a ticket to the game as a
high school graduation present. ``They are better players than the
men.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison Lee, the women's soccer coach at California State
University, Northridge, will be at the Rose Bowl with former
teammates from her college days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody seems to have caught on to this,'' Lee said. ``It's
very special. It means a lot to the die-hard soccer fan -- and
coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing soccer since she was 5 and now in the national pool of
the Olympics training program, April Milado, 15, of Canoga Park is
thrilled at the widespread appeal women's soccer has suddenly
gained through today's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone I know in the Valley is going,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
