<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For SATURDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, July 10, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-MILITARY (Moscow) _ Reflecting its growing dependence on
nuclear weapons for defense, Russia's military carried out mock
nuclear strikes in a major exercise last month, the Defense
Minister said today. The exercise was the largest since the
collapse of the Soviet Union. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-MONTENEGRO (Cetinje, Yugoslavia) _ With Slobodan Milosevic
crippled and presiding over a state that will take years to
rebuild, the Montenegrin government, once careful not to provoke
its Serbian partner in Yugoslavia, is swiftly moving toward
independence. By Chris Hedges. (Scheduled to move by 7:30 p.m. ET
in ``i'' news file.) 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent tho NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   KASHMIR (Muzaffarabad, Kashmir) _ Through the lens of a funeral
for six martyrs, a look at the complex relations among Pakistanis,
Indians and Mujahideen in the conflict over Kashmir. By Barry
Bearak. 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo and map are being sent to NYT photo and graphics
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LUNG-SCAN (Undated) _ After a report about a new study by
researchers at Cornell Medical Center showing that CT scans could
provide early detection of lung cancer in smokers, the voice mail
system at Cornell's chest scanning center was full. New York
University, which participated in the study, reported a similar
flood of calls. The Mayo Clinic in Rochester, Minn., which
announced its own study of the scans a few weeks ago, received more
than 3,000 phone calls within a few days. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly Religion Column. By Peter
Steinfels.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ANTI-CLINTON-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ With calls to ``pillory
Hillary,'' conservative and Republican organizations are mobilizing
to raise millions of dollars all over the country to crush Hillary
Rodham Clinton's all-but-certain Senate candidacy in New York. By
Don Van Natta Jr. 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SPICE-TRADE (Singapore) _ On a clear day, Singaporeans can see
recession-wracked Indonesia from their southern shore. From their
living room, Seah Soo Lin and his son Jeng Jye can smell the
archipelago's budding recovery. Cinnamon, pepper, nutmeg and
cloves: an aromatic bounty sits packed in a jumble of cardboard
boxes on the floor. Outside on the patio, sandalwood chips are
piled into a mound on a table. For the last 30 years, Seah's small
family-run company, Chop Wee Kiat, has traded Indonesian spices and
fragrant woods, buying in places like Timor and Sumatra and selling
to customers from Bahrain to Tokyo. By Wayne Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-GROCER-EXPAND (San Francisco) _ Only a month ago, Webvan
Group Inc., a Silicon Valley startup that sells groceries online,
was taking its first orders from customers. Friday it placed a
sizable order of its own, asking Bechtel, the engineering and
construction giant, to build distribution and delivery centers in
26 markets. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   WEBSTOCKS-QUIET-PERIOD _ The restrictions on quiet periods are
quite fuzzy. And while many companies and their underwriters
refrain from saying anything publicly during the time immediately
preceding and following initial public offerings, more companies
are saying more than they have in the past. Internet companies in
particular are eager to provide business progress reports and to
continue announcing deals. By Andy Wang.
</P>
<P>
   EURO-DOLLAR (Frankfurt, Germany) _ It was supposed to be a
symbol of new strength and unity, but little more than six months
after 11 European nations adopted the euro as a new single
currency, it has become a source of anxiety. In a slide that has
surprised most economists, the euro has steadily declined against
the dollar from nearly $1.18 at its introduction on Jan. 4 to just
above $1.01 by the end of Friday. Global investors have begun
demanding a risk premium when buying euro-denominated bonds. By
Edmund L. Andrews. 1,800 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   No staff-written Op-Ed columns for Saturday's paper.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SOC-WCUP-WOMEN (Los Angeles) _ A soccer tournament that
relatively few people knew existed a month ago has gained such
legitimacy and buzz that scalpers are asking four times face value
or more for tickets. The match will be broadcast to a national TV
audience by ABC and will provide the American women their grandest
stage on which to display their soccer skills and to convince
sponsors that there is a need for a professional league in this
country. By Jere Longman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NAZI-ART-AUCTION (London) _ The most prized painting in
Christie's blockbuster sale of treasures looted by the Nazis and
returned to the Rothschild family this year by the Austrian
government _ Franz Hals' portrait of the Amsterdam merchant
Tieleman Roosterman _ was bought for a record $12.8 million by the
Cleveland Museum of Art. By Carol Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   LEISURE-TIME (Undated) _ Do Americans work more or have more
leisure time? Researchers find evidence for both answers. By Janny
Scott. 1,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   CITIZEN-ACTION (Undated) _ On the rapid growth of citizen-led
groups as agents of major social change. By David Bornstein. (1500
words)
</P>
<P>
   PUBLIC-EROTICA (Undated) _ On erotica, when the private becomes
public. By Edward Rothstein. (1300 words)
</P>
<P>
   TV-HUNLEY-REVIEW (Undated) _ Sunday on TNT, ``The Hunley.''
Reviewed by Ron Wertheimer.
</P>
<P>
   TV-LANDOWSKA-REVIEW (Undated) _ Sunday on PBS, ``Wanda
Landowska: Uncommon Visionary.'' Reviewed by Anthony Tommasini.
