<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990710.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5274 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-ROCKIES-LA     07-10 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-ROCKIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS BEAT ROCKIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Make contact, and the runs will come.
</P>
<P>
   That was the Angels' theory heading into their three-game series
against the Colorado Rockies at hitter-friendly Coors Field, and
the strategy paid off in Friday night's 9-6 victory before 44,122.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Angels' third consecutive victory, and their fifth in
seven games. They had 15 hits, including four home runs, two
doubles and a triple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contact is a big deal here,'' Angels manager Terry Collins
said before the game. ``You make contact, you get hits.''
</P>
<P>
   Troy Glaus hit two homers (Nos. 13 and 14), the first
multi-homer game of his career. Garret Anderson (No. 13) and Reggie
Williams (No. 1) also homered.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson and Randy Velarde had three hits apiece in support of
starter Chuck Finley, who was just good enough to earn his first
victory in his last seven starts, his previous win coming June 2
against Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Finley (5-9) gave up five runs and eight hits in 51/3 innings,
and got relief help from Jarrod Washburn, Mark Petkovsek and Troy
Percival, who earned his 23rd save. It also was Percival's 19th
consecutive save, tying Lee Smith (1995) for the club record.
</P>
<P>
   Finley had been especially bad in his previous three starts,
allowing 21 earned runs in 112/3 innings. The problem was his
mechanics, but he said he made strides toward correcting the
problem Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was throwing straight to the plate tonight more,'' he said.
``I'm not pulling off my pitches, I'm staying with 'em longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to keep moving in that direction, I'm getting close.
I'm not there yet, but I'm definitely not moving backwards.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time Finley pitched here in 1997, he was struggling but
began a personal 14-game winning streak in a 4-1 victory (1 run in
71/3 innings).
</P>
<P>
   Friday's performance wasn't quite as good as the one two years
ago, but he'll take the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if five runs here is good or bad, he said.
``Everything hit in the air you just hold your breath. You just
don't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to go through a psychiatric evaluation if you sign
with these guys and pitch in this park. I don't know how they do
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though he didn't dominate the game, he pitched good,
Collins said. ``You're going to give up four or five runs here,
that's the nature of the beast. Hopefully this gets him going.
</P>
<P>
   Finley was quick to say the offense won the game Friday, not
him. And Collins credited hitting coach Rod Carew for his advice to
the hitters in a pregame meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rod harped on it in the meeting -- don't ever think you have
enough runs, Collins said. ``Don't ever stop. I thought our
approach was good tonight. And we got some runs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels took a liking to the ballpark right away, as Anderson
ripped a two-run homer and Glaus hit his first homer (estimated at
441 feet) to give the Angels a 3-0 lead in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus, who is hitting .333 (9 for 27) in July, homered again in
the seventh inning and now trails only Mo Vaughn for the team lead
in homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might be the only guy in this room who thinks he's doing
fine,'' Collins said of Glaus, who raised his average to .233.
``You guys (reporters) tried to get him sent to the minor leagues
for a couple weeks now. But he's fine. You're going to have ups and
downs, but that's the nature of the beast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, he's struggled at the plate, but if he hadn't save 150
runs with his glove I don't know where'd we be.''
</P>
<P>
   Percival hasn't blown a save opportunity since May 1. But this
one didn't come easy. Singles by Larry Walker and Vinny Castilla
brought Todd Helton to the plate representing the tying run with
two out in the ninth. Helton popped out to Darin Erstad in shallow
left to end it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
