<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-MONARCHS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKS' STREAK ENDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The Los Angeles Sparks' six-game winning
streak came to a sudden end as Sacramento beat Los Angeles 77-72 in
front of 5,436 at the Forum on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Yolanda Griffith had 24 points and 11 rebounds for the Monarchs
(10-4), who took over sole possession of second place in the
Western Division.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks, who dropped into third place at 9-5, started out
slowly and could never catch the Monarchs, who were playing their
second game in less than 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to figure out a better way for us to get
started,'' Sparks coach Orlando Woolridge said. ``I'm going to do
something different with the lineup. I may not do it until after
the break. It may start Sunday. I have to do something to
jump-start us.''
</P>
<P>
   Seldom-used La'Kesiha Frett is starting to make a name for
herself and might get a starting role. After coming off the bench
to score a career-high 13 points in the Sparks' win at Phoenix on
Wednesday, she led a slow-starting squad with 11 first-half points
and finished with 15 points. But her valiant effort couldn't revive
the Sparks, who played catch-up to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks trailed 44-36 at the half and fell back 56-42 with
15:59 to play after the Monarchs opened the second half with a 12-6
run.
</P>
<P>
   But following a timeout, the Sparks responded and slowly began
to chip away at their deficit. They made a concerted effort after
Allison Feaster made back-to-back 3-pointers to reduce the deficit
to seven for the first time since early in the first half. Frett
scored a basket and then Penny Toler, Lisa Leslie (16 points) and
Frett each went to the line to convert two free throws to trim the
lead to 59-58.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie made a three-point play with 1:53 left but missed three
of four free-throw attempts over the next minute as the Sparks
trailed 73-69. Ruthie Bolton-Holifield made three of her four
attempts to secure the Monarchs' first win in three starts against
the Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   The Monarchs didn't look like a fatigued team that had played
(and defeated the defending champion Houston Comets) less than 24
hours before.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're feeling good actually,'' Griffith said. ``Offensively
and defensively, we're feeling good. We kept our composure and got
this victory.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks will host the Phoenix Mercury on Sunday at 1 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
