</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GOALIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCURRY, GAO ARE GOAL ORIENTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM BARRERO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ They are international rivals and sporting
colleagues, forming a bond simply because they happen to play the
same position.
</P>
<P>
   But United States goalkeeper Briana Scurry doesn't know much
more than that about her counterpart, Gao Hong of China.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd think in all the times we've played one another, we
would know more,'' Scurry said. ``But you know, we have different
training schedules, stay at different hotels. When we get to town,
they're leaving, so it hasn't left much time.''
</P>
<P>
   The result of today's Women's World Cup final may well hinge on
which goalkeeper plays better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the game's going to come down to the keepers,'' U.S.
forward Tiffeny Milbrett said. ``With Bri, she has kept us in games
and she has won games for us because she has stopped balls that
were probably, for sure, in the back of the net.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. coach Tony DiCicco has had an up-close view of both
goalkeepers through the years. DiCicco works closely with the U.S.
keepers during training sessions, and last year Gao worked a summer
camp with DiCicco.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a really neat person,'' DiCicco said of Gao. ``She
speaks Japanese and we had a couple of our coaches that had played
in Japan, so that was the way we communicated (at the camp). She's
a great personality, a credit to the sport and an outstanding
goalkeeper.''
</P>
<P>
   Gao certainly makes it look easy, although she hasn't been
tested much during China's run to the final. In five matches, Gao
has faced just 21 shots, allowing only two goals for a
tournament-best 0.40 goals-against average.
</P>
<P>
   One of those goals came in the second minute of China's first
game against Sweden, a 2-1 victory and its toughest test to date.
</P>
<P>
   During Friday's practice at the Rose Bowl, Gao's instincts
seemed sharp and her athleticism was evident in making several
difficult saves appear routine.
</P>
<P>
   Whether at practice or during a game, Gao's aw-shucks approach,
with her shoulders wavering from side-to-side as she waits for a
shot to come her way, gives the scene a calming effect for the
Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Following Friday's practice, no Chinese players were made
available to the media, although many in the horde of about 50
wanted to speak to Gao. She appeared almost apologetic when told by
a Chinese official to walk to the waiting team bus instead of
answering reporters' questions.
</P>
<P>
   Gao waved to reporters and in a loud voice in perfect English
said: ``See you tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll see Gao sometimes just smile out there,'' DiCicco said
of game situations. ``She'll kind of smile and laugh and it's that
kind of confident body gesture.''
</P>
<P>
   Gao's unflappable, happy-go-lucky approach seems in direct
contrast to Scurry's now-famous, stone-faced appearance that grabs
the attention of her teammates during games.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm playing, I'm usually pretty serious,'' Scurry said of
what she refers to as her `Death Stare.' ``I think my play is more
my way of giving leadership on this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Scurry boasts similar numbers to Gao, having faced 24 shots in
five games and allowing three goals for a 0.60 goals against
average, ranking second in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Gao can stop some and make some crucial saves, then the
Chinese might be on top,'' Milbrett said. ``If Bri can come back
and earn her money like she's been doing this whole tournament,
then we might end up on top.''
</P>
<P>
   DiCicco said both keepers are fairly similar in style.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both very athletic and that's probably the key
ingredient to their games,'' DiCicco said. ``Technically, they are
not necessarily the model goalkeepers, either of them, but they
sure get to a lot of balls.''
</P>
<P>
   DiCicco said a key for the U.S. will be to keep its focus and
not allow Gao to establish momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has some weaknesses and we're hoping to expose those,''
DiCicco said of Gao.
</P>
<P>
   But when all is said and done, DiCicco feels more than fine with
Scurry as his last line of defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going into this event, Gao is a good goalkeeper and a lovely
lady,'' DiCicco said, ``but Briana Scurry is the best goalkeeper
here in the World Cup and, I think, the best goalkeeper in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an edge in goal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
