<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAIT'LL THIS WHOLE THING GETS EVEN BIGGER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ You'll see the best in women's soccer today.
Only not by looking at the Rose Bowl field.
</P>
<P>
   Look in the stands, at the teen-ager grinning through her
braces.
</P>
<P>
   Look in the living room, at the 6-year-old bouncing on the sofa
in front of the TV set.
</P>
<P>
   Look in the crib, at the baby girl asleep and oblivious to
United States-China and Women's World Cup '99.
</P>
<P>
   Because one of them is the best in women's soccer, or is going
to be, you just wait.
</P>
<P>
   The best in women's soccer is four years, a dozen years, or a
generation away.
</P>
<P>
   Women haven't played organized soccer for as long they've
competed in basketball, tennis or gymnastics. Compared to those
sports _ not to mention softball, golf and any number of Olympic
events _ women's soccer is behind the curve in attracting and
cultivating talent.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. women's national team? It didn't exist until 1985.
</P>
<P>
   The effect is plain to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is,'' conceded Jarl Torske, thick-bearded assistant
coach of the Norwegian team that lost in the semifinals to China,
``much room for improvement in all aspects of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   I could give this a negative spin and say a lot of what has
passed for world-class soccer in the past three weeks simply stank
_ sloppy passes, easy giveaways, porous defense, shallow rosters
and one-sided matches (5-0 China in the !ital!semis!off!).
</P>
<P>
   I prefer to take the optimistic angle: As entertaining as this
Women's World Cup has been, the soccer is only going to get better
as more girls and women _ and talented female coaches _ are drawn
to the sport.
</P>
<P>
   This is baseball in 1900, on its way to the 1950s. This is
football in 1920, on its way to the 1970s. This is basketball in
1940, on its way to the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Savor the thought. A sport whose Golden Age hasn't come and gone
but lies straight ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Women's World Cup president and CEO Marla Messing refers to the
thousands of girls she expects to register for soccer leagues this
fall because they want to ``be like Mia (Hamm).''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. midfielder Julie Foudy notes that the mere existence of
girls' soccer leagues shows how far the sport has come already.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of our older players, like Christine (Lilly) and me,''
said Foudy, in her 12th year on the national team, ``we grew up
playing on boys' teams, coached by fathers who didn't always know
what they were doing.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. defender Kate Sobrero, in her second year on the team,
thinks she represents the improvement so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 22 and (backup defender) Lorrie Fair is 20,'' Sobrero
said. ``I think we're better than (their veteran teammates) were at
our age.''
</P>
<P>
   Sobrero thinks ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``In another 20 years,'' she said, ``somebody who's really good
now will probably be average.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. forward Cindy Parlow sees the evolution occurring even
faster than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the game has evolved just from the '96 Olympics to the
'99 World Cup,'' said Parlow, the youngest member of the United
States' gold-medal team in Atlanta. ``And I think the game will get
faster, get better and go to a whole new level.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago, U.S. coach Tony DiCicco pointed out, the United
States won the Women's World Cup in China with a team made up
almost entirely of college players. Of the '99 roster, only Lorrie
Fair of North Carolina still has college eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   Top players are remaining players for longer than they used to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll say the men's game is a bit more sophisticated,'' DiCicco
said. ``But the level of the women's game has improved so much
tactically, and athletically, too.''
</P>
<P>
   It's fair to wonder if further improvement is exactly what
women's soccer needs. After all, if the soccer could be better,
600,000 American ticket buyers don't seem to give a damn.
</P>
<P>
   And don't the precise ball control and tight defenses of
world-class men's soccer produce exactly the kind of 0-0 games we
unsophisticates detest?
</P>
<P>
   Well, you can't stop progress. I'll take my chances on faster,
stronger, nimbler players.
</P>
<P>
   It's going to be fascinating, seeing if women's soccer can
sustain its instant popularity in the years ahead. The guess here:
Today's final is only the beginning for the U.S. and the world.
</P>
<P>
   Just wait until their feet catch up to their charisma.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
