<HEADLINE>
CSUN'S PONCIANO CONFIDENT HE'LL BE CLEARED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Amid speculation his job was in jeopardy, Cal
State Northridge coach Ron Ponciano finally met Friday with school
administrators investigating possible NCAA violations by CSUN's
football program.
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano left the five-hour meeting confident he will be
vindicated, and said he will submit a written report Monday
refuting two of the findings uncovered in the probe.
</P>
<P>
   The university is expected to conclude its investigation
Tuesday, according to Ponciano, and a final decision regarding
penalties and/or Ponciano's fate should come Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very good that the information I will provide on those
two allegations will be more than sufficient,'' said Ponciano, who
would not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   University officials did not comment on the meeting or
acknowledge it even took place. A campus spokesman said late Friday
afternoon that there were no developments regarding the football
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The university has nothing to report,'' CSUN public
information officer John Chandler said.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation is the result of an anonymous letter that the
school received May 19 alleging a number of NCAA violations.
Ponciano has denied any wrongdoing and left Friday's meeting even
more convinced that he is not guilty of anything.
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano said he was not asked to resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing that happened that surprised me,'' Ponciano
said. ``It was pretty much what I expected.''
</P>
<P>
   The probe has apparently cost one CSUN coach his job. Offensive
coordinator Rob Phenicie resigned Wednesday amid speculation he
would be forced to do so.
</P>
<P>
   School officials won't say if Phenicie was asked to step down
because of possible infractions. But considering Phenicie turned
down two other coaching jobs this offseason to stay at Northridge,
it is doubtful he suddenly decided to quit less than a month before
the opening of practice.
</P>
<P>
   Phenicie declined comment on the resignation on the advice of
his lawyer. He did say Wednesday that he felt the Matadors players
were being ``dealt a bad hand'' in the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Phenicie's departure left Ponciano wondering if his job was at
stake too. Ponciano said earlier this week he was eager to fight
for his job and confront allegations that he has termed ridiculous.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 0237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
