<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 02:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5281 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      07-10 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARCIA STRONG, BUT M'S CAN'T GET TO DODGERS' VALDES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Randy Johnson trade residual was everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   On the mound, the what-might-have-been started against the
partial down payment Friday night at aging yet still functional
Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Under the palm trees and flickering lights, the rejected one
upstaged the accepted one.
</P>
<P>
   Ismael Valdes was a few pitches better than Freddy Garcia, the
near-miss Mariner outdueling the real deal 5-0 before an impatient
crowd of 44,653. The Dodgers right-hander threw seven walk-free
innings before turning things over to his bullpen to complete the
shutout. He had to be at his best because Garcia was brilliant at
times.
</P>
<P>
   The prize bounty of the eventual Johnson trade struck out a
career-best 10 batters before leaving after just five innings of
duty.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome pushed the Mariners (42-43) under .500 again and
left them with their third straight defeat, while giving the
over-priced and underachieving Dodgers (37-47) a much-needed boost.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-three weeks after these same two teams failed to sign off
on their much-discussed transaction _ Johnson to the Chavez Ravine
club for Valdes and a host of others _ Valdes (7-7) showed off the
arm skills that proved so tempting to Seattle front-office execs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Valdes could have been one of us,'' Mariners third baseman
Russ Davis said. ``That's kind of weird.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican national brought heat, resilience and even a little
nastiness to the first of three interleague encounters.
</P>
<P>
   Sending an early message, Valdes plunked the Mariners' Alex
Rodriguez in the shoulder the first time he faced him. He hit
Davis, sending him out of the game with a bruised right forearm,
when Garcia retaliated against Mark Grudzielanek. He let it rest
when Garcia bounced one off Adrian Beltre.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just take your lumps and keep going,'' said Davis, who was
unable to throw after getting hit and will likely sit out the rest
of the series. ``Both guys were throwing the ball inside.''
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, Valdes refused to give in when the Mariners
threatened with a pair of baserunners in each of the first three
innings. Easy grounder, strikeout and difficult popup were his
rally-killers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just kept everyone off balance,'' Ken Griffey Jr. said.
``He got outs when he needed them, and we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia (9-5) did nothing to make the Mariners want to rescind
the Johnson trade. He just made a few ill-timed mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   In the second inning, Garcia hit Beltre and served up a single
to Greg Counsell. One out later, the rookie right-hander grooved
one to Mark Grudzielanek, who lifted a three-run home run over the
Ron Cey commemorative sign in left-center, with a leaping Griffey
missing the ball by inches.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw him jump up and go after it, I said, `Don't do that
to me,''' Grudzielanek said.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth Dodgers run came across in the fifth inning when
Mondesi walked, Devon White reached on a fielding error by Mariners
second baseman David Bell and Counsell socked a one-out single to
left.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia was lifted after throwing 123 pitches. He had hit that
pitch count four other times but had worked his way into the
seventh or eighth innings on each occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Garcia had his moments. He struck out the side in the
first inning in entertaining fashion after putting two runners on.
Fans booed lustily as the Dodgers flailed away at Garcia's changeup
and even a curve outside and in the dirt. He struck out Raul
Mondesi, Todd Hundley and Grudzielanek twice each.
</P>
<P>
   ``He worked himself out of a heckuva mess in the first inning,
but in the second he didn't,'' Mariners manager Lou Piniella said.
``He had 61 pitches in the first two innings _ that's a complete
game. He labored out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers got another run in the seventh off reliever Paul
Abbott, on Grudzielanek's single for a career-best fourth RBI.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners came up with nothing, shut out for just the second
time this season. Four times they put two runners on. Twice they
had runners reach third. A diving catch by Grudzielanek with his
back to the plate denied a certain run in the third inning. A
botched double-steal attempt quelled another rally in the seventh,
with Tom Lampkin getting tagged out returning to third base.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes scattered seven hits before leaving when he hit his own
pitch count, 118.
</P>
<P>
   He was able to do something even Johnson has found near
impossible lately with Arizona: Earn a victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
