<HEADLINE>
MONDESI'S MINDSET: HIT RESTART BUTTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Dodgers are playing dismal
baseball and Raul Mondesi is performing terribly at the plate. And
the more either try to improve, the worse it gets.
</P>
<P>
   So before the Dodgers opened a three-game series with the
Seattle Mariners on Friday, Mondesi proclaimed it a new season.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi hadn't homered in 92 at-bats. He had nine RBI since May
31, and it's no coincidence the Dodgers were 10-23 since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to have 300 more at-bats, so I'm going to act like
this is the beginning of that,'' said Mondesi, who homered 18 times
before June. ``I know I haven't hit a home run in 100 at-bats, but
I'm going to have so many more. That's what I'm thinking about
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of it has to do with the typical problem plaguing the
Dodgers this season. When Mondesi batted with the bases loaded and
one out in the first inning against the Mariners, instead of trying
to hit the ball the other way or just get a fly ball to score a
run, he struck out with big swings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm trying to do too much,'' Mondesi said. ``I
feel tight right now. It's never been like this before. I can get
in slumps but at least I hit the ball hard. I can't hit it hard
right now. I'm swinging like a rookie.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson has rested Mondesi a few times
lately, which Mondesi doesn't like, especially when he's not
expecting it. Johnson also has drawn raised eyebrows from Mondesi
by moving him throughout the lineup. Mondesi has batted anywhere
from leadoff to sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just getting to know Mondesi,'' Johnson said. ``I like his
attitude. He plays hard. I think sometimes, when things aren't
going his way, he forces things. He doesn't try to be a good
hitter, he tries to be aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Mondesi) or anyone else, it's good to get him a blow once in
a while. Sometimes you get that look of `Why are you picking on
me?' I'm trying to help him. But I don't worry about him. It lasts
an hour, two hours. It's just learning about players, then learning
about me.''
</P>
<P>
   Cromer update: Tripp Cromer returned to the team after
undergoing evaluation for what was diagnosed as an irregular
heartbeat and said nothing wrong was found. Cromer was examined by
Dodgers team physician Dr. Michael Mellman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctor said 80 percent of the time it's not an anxiety
attack, it's arrhythmia,'' Cromer said. ``That's what he thought it
was.''
</P>
<P>
   Cromer, 31, left the Dodgers on Tuesday in Denver and returned
to L.A. to be examined after experiencing spells in which he had
trouble breathing. He said Dr. Mellman couldn't identify the
problem, which occurred five times in the past few weeks. He gave
Cromer a devise to carry around that's like the size of a credit
card and measures his heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said if it happens again, hold it up to my chest and it
will get a reading,'' Cromer said. ``Then I can give it to him and
he can read what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   In the mean time, Cromer began working out with the team again.
He's eligible to come off the disabled list July 20.
</P>
<P>
   Karros sits again: Johnson continued with his plan of not
staying status quo. A day after Eric Karros hit his 15th and 16th
homers, he sat Friday and Todd Hollandsworth started at first.
</P>
<P>
   Karros has sat two of the last four games. Also, Craig Counsell
started at second in place of Eric Young.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about Eric Karros,'' Johnson said. ``He's having a
good year. I'm worried about the other people. It's getting
Hollandsworth and Counsell going. It's 25 (guys). That's what I'm
trying to get across.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners start a pair of left-handers in the final two games
of the series, which figured heavily into the equation.
</P>
<P>
   FYI: Right-hander Antonio Osuna pitched 12/3 innings in his
second rehab start for Single-A San Bernardino. He walked two
struck out two and didn't allow a hit. Johnson said Osuna will most
likely be activated after the All-Star break, which would give him
one or two more rehab outings.... The Dodgers were 21-17 in
interleague games since their inception, but 3-6 this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
