<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-MARLINS-TRADE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIAMONDBACKS LAND ESTABLISHED CLOSER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 Editors: Nunez has tilde over second `n' 
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Friday was an emotion-filled day for the Diamondbacks. The
organization parted with two players it had nurtured and counted on
for the future.
</P>
<P>
   But the bottom line was that Arizona got the man it wanted _ the
man it needed _ if it expected to remain in the race for the
National League West Division title.
</P>
<P>
   The trade was another example of the now-rather-than-later mode
that pushed managing general partner Jerry Colangelo into signing
several veteran free agents after the club's first season in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Mantei, a right-handed closer with 10 saves, a 1-2 record,
a 2.72 ERA and 50 strikeouts in 36 innings, is expected to don No.
31 and join the Diamondbacks today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognized we had a hole to fill and we were able to come
up with an outstanding closer,'' Colangelo said. ``He's young
(Mantei turned 26 on Wednesday), not a guy in his mid-30s, not an
aging closer.''
</P>
<P>
   The main emotion in the clubhouse Friday was excitement. Players
and others in the organization were already anticipating the
arrival of Mantei, acquired in a trade with the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a sense of sadness with the departure of
right-hander Vladimir Nunez as part of the deal. He had come to the
organization as a 20-year-old Cuban refugee in February 1996, had
grown into a man and considered many on the coaching staff to be
father figures.
</P>
<P>
   And there was the question of whether right-hander Brad Penny,
the second part of the equation, would have fulfilled his potential
with Arizona. The Diamondbacks had not wanted to part with Penny,
the organizational Pitcher of the Year in 1998. The third departure
is mysterious at the moment _ a minor league player to be named
later.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of a closer became a necessity when veteran
right-hander Gregg Olson, who saved 30 games in 1998, struggled
with inconsistency and injury. The young pitchers who then
attempted to fill the role _ including Nunez and Korean
right-hander Byung-Hyun Kim _ also were inconsistent.
</P>
<P>
   Of the departure of Nunez and Penny, General Manager Joe
Garagiola Jr. said: ``This is why you develop young players. If you
can acquire a player that goes on your major-league roster, it is
the same as if you got that original player to the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mantei throws the ball between 95 and 99 mph, has an
above-average curveball and he wants to be out there. He wants the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's pursuit of Mantei was no secret. Nor was their
interest in Montreal right-hander Ugueth Urbina. Mantei, who began
his career with the Seattle Mariners and pitched for the Tempe club
of the Arizona Instructional League, had heard the talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``If something was going to happen, I didn't want to sit around
and wait (until the July 31 trading deadline),'' Mantei said. ``I'm
excited about what's going on. From what I've seen of Arizona, it's
a team that is interested in winning and winning now. It should be
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Mantei said his pitching approach focuses on ``the last three
outs of the game. That's all I think about, getting guys out and
throwing strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Damian Miller said Mantei ``has closer-type stuff. He should be
a big help for us.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Nunez ``was developing into a pretty good pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Nunez was developing a close relationship with Kim, who had a
neighboring locker, despite the language barrier.
</P>
<P>
   The normally happy Kim wore a long face as he walked through the
clubhouse. Asked about Nunez, he put both fists up to his face and
rubbed his eyes, as if he were crying.
</P>
<P>
   Nunez and his wife, Wendy, just bought a house in the area and
became parents for the second time. He was stunned by the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went in to the office (Manager Buck Showalter) and he told
me. My body stopped,'' said Nunez, who was 3-2 with one save and a
2.91 ERA in 27 games. ``I've been here for four years. It's been
like my school. This is where I learned how to pitch. The coach
(Mark Connor) was like my father. I just want to thank everybody
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Nunez will be joining fellow Cuban and friend Livan Hernandez on
the Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter said it was tough to tell Nunez, ``because he was
family. Mark (Connor) was all choked up. ``There are no givens, but
we think Matt Mantei has the potential to do a quality job for us
for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Mantei is making $735,000 in 1999 and will be eligible for
salary arbitration at the end of the season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
