<HEADLINE>
EDMONDS, SALMON MAKE TRIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Anaheim Angels center fielder Jim Edmonds made the trip
to Colorado, the first time he's traveled with the team this season
since having surgery on his right shoulder April 19.
</P>
<P>
   With Tim Salmon (sprained left wrist) also on the trip, there is
reason for the Angels to look ahead to the second half of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Both are working with hitting coach Rod Carew _ Edmonds is
hitting off a tee and Salmon is hitting soft toss. Of the two,
Salmon is closer to returning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're moving up on the program,'' Salmon said. ``Between
myself, Rod and the trainer, we have some (return) dates we're
talking about, but that's between us. The only thing that will stop
us is a setback.''
</P>
<P>
   With no setbacks, Salmon probably will begin taking live batting
practice next week, begin a rehab assignment the following week and
join the team around Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds' initial target date of mid-August seems to be on
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Even without Salmon and Edmonds, the Angels' offense has been
scoring runs lately. And Salmon said the front office deserves
credit for not rushing into a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believed having patience to not make a move would pay off,''
he said. ``(The front office) believed the guys we had in spring
training would win. We lost some guys but if we get guys back we
can still win. Seven-and-a-half games out is not insurmountable.
We've just got to get us clicking as quickly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Salmon warned that his return doesn't mean the
Angels will be instant contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as I think I can bring to the team, I'm not a
savior,'' he said. ``Once I come back, I've still got to find my
swing.''
</P>
<P>
   Coors strategy: Angels manager Terry Collins knows the ball
carries well at Coors Field and runs come fast and furious. But he
said it's not the home runs that lead to so much offense as much as
it is the expansive outfield, particularly from left-center to
right-center.
</P>
<P>
   Collins goes against the rule of thumb most managers use when
setting up their defense here. Most play all three outfielders
deep, but Collins has his outfielders play in on the corners and
deep in center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the home runs here, it's the hits down the lines and
in the gaps,'' he said. ``There's a lot of room out there. I
managed so long in Albuquerque (where the air is thin) and I
managed against Denver in the American Association, so I tried
something different. Sometimes it works, sometimes you get burned.
But for the most part I've been fairly successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Also: Pitcher Ken Hill (inflammed right elbow) is expected to
throw during the weekend. He's due to come off the disabled list
Friday.... Utility player Steve Decker has left the team and went
to Illinois for the funeral of his mother, who died earlier in the
week.... Second baseman Randy Velarde extended his hitting streak
Friday to eight games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 0249EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
