<DOCNO> NYT19990710.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 02:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5289 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BICKLEY_TRADE-AZR     07-10 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BICKLEY_TRADE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM PROVES HE KNOWS WHAT HE'S DOING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one's laughing at him anymore. No one's joking about his job
title, ridiculing his credentials, wondering how in the world he
landed such an important position armed only with a surname.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Joe Garagiola Jr. sealed the deal that may save the
season. The Diamondbacks acquired Matt Mantei, a flame-throwing
closer, an emphatic answer equipped with a 98 mph heater. It is a
bold stroke, a credit to an organization that recognizes the
importance of now. And it is another steal in Bazooka Joe's growing
list of heists.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a right-handed Billy Wagner, exactly what you're
looking for in the position,'' the general manager said. ``This
just proves that we're not up there eating popcorn.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes you get lucky, sometimes the stars align in your
favor, and sometimes the perfect deal falls into your lap. But
there is a pattern here, and the acquisition of Mantei is stunning.
Not for what the Diamondbacks acquired, but for what they gave up
in return.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's`` Miami Herald,'' printed hours before the trade was
consummated, Florida Marlins Manager John Boles issued the company
line. They were an organization that believed Mantei was the best
young closer in baseball and he wouldn't come cheap.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't trade (Mantei) unless you are overwhelmed,''
Boles said. ``Somebody has to knock our socks off.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that Vladimir Nunez and Brad Penny are headed to Florida,
it's safe to assume Boles is still wearing his socks.
</P>
<P>
   So how does a team desperate for a closer end up soaking a team
with all the leverage? A team not compelled to trade Mantei? It is
a question only the Marlins can answer, and judging by the reaction
of one of their beat writers, a question they will face repeatedly
in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Mantei is 26, and although he's had rotator cuff and elbow
problems, he's been healthy for two seasons. His strikeout ratio is
fabulous, and his curveball is wicked in contrast to his fastball.
He makes $735,000, and while basically dealing with a rebuilt arm,
he is not a short-term investment. He could be the closer well into
the next century, an All-Star in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see Mantei and (the Expos' Ugueth) Urbina as very similar
guys,'' Garagiola said.
</P>
<P>
   That may be a stretch, but the trade will significantly lift the
clubhouse spirit, a team that will no longer dread the late innings
or silently despise the bullpen. The trade gives the Diamondbacks
everything they need to win the division. And best of all, it
proves that the Diamondbacks are philosophically sound, a franchise
aware that you seize the opportunity to win championships _
whatever it takes.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years ago, the White Sox dealt a prospect named Sammy Sosa
for a veteran slugger named George Bell. Sosa developed into a
genuine superstar, while Bell retired to his gas station in the
Dominican Republic. But even now, no one questions the trade
because it helped the Sox win a pennant. That's the way it works.
</P>
<P>
   But there is little risk here. Though Urbina would've required a
few players and the swimming pool in right field, Mantei arrives at
bargain-basement cost, as if he were a designer item somehow
labeled with the wrong price tag.
</P>
<P>
   ``Always a great feeling when you get one across the finish
line,'' Garagiola said.
</P>
<P>
   Especially when it's a steal, and this is not foreign territory
for Garagiola. He hung with the Tony Womack deal until its
fruition. He peddled Karim Garcia for Luis Gonzalez ``and''
$500,000. And now this.
</P>
<P>
   Once there was a time when Bazooka Joe was a punch line, an easy
target, the subject of ill humor across the league. A man thought
to be nothing more than a figurehead keeping the seat warm, holding
a title without power or knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   It's July, and no one's laughing anymore. And no one is calling
Buck Showalter the general manager without a title.
</P>
<P>
   That job is already taken. By a man seriously underestimated in
baseball circles. A man who must apologize to no one. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at dan.bickley(at)pni.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
