<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-COMETS-MERCURY-NYTNS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCURY COMES UP SHORT AGAINST COMETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even as the Mercury plays better and better, its WNBA playoff
chances grow dimmer and dimmer.
</P>
<P>
   The unfairness of that reality was hammered home again Friday
night as a third straight improved performance _ this time against
the highest caliber opponent _ ended in a fifth straight loss. The
Mercury slipped another notch deeper into the Western Conference
cellar.
</P>
<P>
   By turning away two shots from Jennifer Gillom in the final 18.7
seconds, the two-time champion Houston Comets held on for a 71-70
win at America West Arena. The Comets, who lost 74-63 at Sacramento
Thursday, have not lost two straight since the end of the 1997
regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Van Chancellor would never agree, but Houston (12-2) could
have absorbed the loss without any long-term effect other than hurt
pride.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury (3-9), five games out of playoff position with 20 to
play, has no such luxury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do need a W, because we don't want to get comfortable with
losing and saying, `Next time, next time, next time,' '' Gillom
said. ``Gosh, if we play like we played tonight and just a few
things go our way, the Ws are coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad we're playing LA (Sunday) because there is a lot of
hostility toward us in LA right now. And that's what we need, to
play with hostility, because it makes us play harder.''
</P>
<P>
   The greatest hostility in the first meeting of the 1998 WNBA
finalists this season was not between the teams _ the Comets
clearly were dragging from the travel between tip-offs 22 hours
apart _ but mutually against the officiating.
</P>
<P>
   Mercury Coach Cheryl Miller's return to the bench for the first
time since surgery on a ruptured Achilles tendon Wednesday lasted
until 5:16 remained, although she easily could have picked up her
second technical foul and second ejection of the season earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant coach Howie Landa also was on the verge of his second
technical of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Comets forward Sheryl Swoopes took a T with 1:04 left after she
made a clean steal from Lisa Harrison, who tagged Swoopes only to
have the personal foul go against Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Gillom made the technical free throw and Harrison both of hers,
closing the Comets' lead to 69-68. When Houston's Cynthia Cooper
then missed a 17-footer, Marlies Askamp rebounded and was fouled by
Polina Tzekova. Askamp's two free throws at the 39-second mark gave
Phoenix its first lead since 12:37 of the first half.
</P>
<P>
   But as in Games 2 and 3 of last year's league finals, Swoopes
had an answer, spinning left past Askamp for a 10-footer with 18.7
seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Mercury used three timeouts thereafter to plot
perhaps a season-saving shot, Swoopes was among those coming up
with enough defense to deny Gillom, who almost manufactured a
league Most Valuable Player award out of such heroics last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather have gotten the ball a little bit closer to the
basket,'' she said of the final attempt, a 17-footer from the
baseline. ``I pushed off the block and got my fadeaway shot off. It
felt good when it left my hand, and any time it hangs on the rim,
it's a good shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was going to get Tina (Thompson) one-on-one from
the high post (on my first attempt), but when I drove in I felt
Swoopes and I stepped back, and they both came at my shot and got a
piece of it. Same thing on the other side, the same two players,
but I got enough room to get the shot off.''
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes had 18 points and Cooper 15, but Thompson was held to
nine, the first time this season that all of Houston's Big Three
haven't achieved double figures.
</P>
<P>
   Mercury point guard Michele Timms had a 22-point game that was
most brilliant for her defense vs. two-time MVP Cooper, whom she
will team with as West starting guards at the inaugural All-Star
Game on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to take positives from this game,'' Timms said.
``It was a good game, we played well in patches. They're the top
team in the league, so it was a positive for everyone tonight.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
