<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TEAM ROLLING UP ITS SLEEVES  
 WOMEN FACE CHINA TODAY IN CUP CHAMPIONSHIP MATCH 
</HEADLINE>
 CUP-ADV-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM THOMAS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The record crowds, presidential visits, media
hype, TV commercials and overwhelming receptions from fans and
dignitaries at every stop are nice, thank you.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. national team players appreciate all that, as do, of
course, the 1999 Women's World Cup organizers and FIFA,
international soccer's governing body.
</P>
<P>
   But it seems as if the Americans have to keep reminding everyone
</P>
<P>
   that, gosh darn it, this thing isn't over.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't come all this way _ through five matches in five
cities from coast to coast in 16 days, not to mention all the
training before and between _ to settle for being here. They didn't
go through it all to sign autographs, mug with Letterman and shake
hands with Clinton. They didn't even do it just to talk to
sportswriters about the same things, over and over and over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of people think this tournament would not have
reached its full potential unless we reached the finals,'' U.S.
Coach Tony DiCicco said on the eve of today's Women's World Cup
championship match at the Rose Bowl. ``There wouldn't have been as
much excitement and sellout crowds if we'd been eliminated in the
first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``But for us, this tournament won't reach its full potential
until we walk out of here with gold medals around our necks.''
</P>
<P>
   All that stands in way of the Americans' second Cup title in
three tries is a cozy little country of 1.2 billion people called
China, which, incidentally, has produced a pretty fair women's
soccer team.
</P>
<P>
   OK, the Chinese are a little _ no, a lot _ better than pretty
fair. Is ``outstanding'' too strong a word?
</P>
<P>
   ``China is an outstanding team,'' DiCicco said. ``They have
great personality players, and where they've really come on in the
past few years is in the support players. They've found and
developed some good young talent, much like we have.''
</P>
<P>
   China comes into the title match having scored the most goals
(19) and owning the top defense in terms of fewest goals allowed
(2).
</P>
<P>
   Piloting the offense is Sun Wen, who is tied for the Cup lead in
goals with seven. She may be the fastest striker to play in the Cup
and is supported by four other swift attackers in Zhao Lihong, Liu
Ailing, Liu Ying and Jin Yan. All figure to test the American
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to be ready for everything,'' said captain Carla
Overbeck, who will be joined in the back by Joy Fawcett, Kate
Sobrero and Brandi Chastain. ``China is a dangerous offensive team.
We'll have to play solid defense individually and as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans' top scorer is Tiffeny Milbrett with three goals,
but the U.S. has had scoring from nine other players. The U.S.
attackers, which also include Mia Hamm, Cindy Parlow and Michelle
Akers, appear to have an advantage in both height and speed on the
Chinese defense.
</P>
<P>
   But don't get the idea this will be a high-scoring affair.
Chances are that few goals will be scored, in part because the two
best goalkeepers in the world will be minding the nets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Great Wall of China'' vs. ``The Rock.''
</P>
<P>
   Gao Hong has allowed only two goals and Briana Scurry three in
their respective teams' five matches. Scurry has been challenged
more often, particularly against Brazil in a semifinal last
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes down to it, the deciding factor might be something
other than soccer skills _ one of the intangible elements of
sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been in more situations like this than they have,''
Milbrett said. ``I think our experience gives us an edge. And I
think we might be a little more competitive than they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Overbeck says the memory of being ousted in the semifinals of
the 1995 Cup provides added inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was depressing; we were all crying,'' Overbeck said. ``It
was a big letdown after winning the Cup in '91 and expecting to win
it again in '95.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it also might have been the best thing that has happened
to us. We all gathered on the field after the game . . . and we all
agreed that we were going to remember this feeling and not let it
happen again.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
