<HEADLINE>
BIG HONOR FOR BIG UNIT?  
 LIKELY TO BE ALL-STAR STARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though it hasn't been announced officially, it appears that
Diamondbacks left-hander Randy Johnson is the choice of National
League Manager Bruce Bochy to start Tuesday's All-Star Game at
Boston's Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Bochy, the manager of the defending NL champion San Diego
Padres, apparently has told those close to the Padres that Johnson
is his choice and that Philadelphia Phillies right-hander Curt
Schilling will follow Johnson to the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling is a product of Phoenix's Shadow Mountain High School.
</P>
<P>
   If Johnson knows, he wasn't saying Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're asking the wrong guy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bochy called Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter on Friday to
discuss the situation, but Showalter was not immediately available.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who makes his final start before the All-Star break
today in an interleague game against Oakland, is 9-6 with a 3.03
ERA and 200 strikeouts in 145 innings. He could easily be 12-3, but
he has lost his last three starts via shutout, and his team has
only given him three hits of support.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference announcing his All-Star selection earlier
this week, Johnson said it would be an honor to start, but he also
said that there were other pitchers who had better records.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I do get into the game, there might be a few lefties I've
never faced before,'' Johnson said with a laugh, referring to his
American League days with Seattle and not seeing many left-handed
hitters when he pitched.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's normal schedule would not be interrupted by the
All-Star appearance. He normally throws on the side on the third
day after he pitches in a game and has the fourth day off. So
throwing two, perhaps three innings on Tuesday would not be
unusual.
</P>
<P>
   That would allow him Wednesday off before his next scheduled
start at Texas on Thursday to start the second half of the season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
