<HEADLINE>
GRUDZIELANEK LIFTS DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In a dismal season when the Los Angeles Dodgers
respond to nothing for the long-term and fans have little to
embrace, something finally happened to excite folks.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Grudzielanek drove in a career-high four runs _ three with
a second-inning homer _ and made a stellar defensive play, while
Ismail Valdes pitched seven innings as the Dodgers beat the Seattle
Mariners 5-0 Friday in an interleague contest at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The outing came after Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone
addressed the team for nearly 45 minutes in a closed-door meeting
to deliver a candid message: The season isn't over, the Dodgers
aren't done, and if you think otherwise maybe you don't belong
here.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Dodgers' third meeting in less than a week, which
equals the number of wins they've had during that span.
</P>
<P>
   But the after-effect was the Dodgers' first shutout win since
May 3. They've won two straight for the first time in two weeks.
They haven't won three straight since a five-game streak April 27
to May 1.
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek, who spent 28 days on the disabled list, has seven
RBI in the past two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a lot of energy, gives a lot of energy. That's why I
missed him,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``He's more
patient at the plate. I thought he had a real good, solid approach
when he came back.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of that is because of extensive batting cage sessions with
hitting coach Rick Down. Unable to swing with his right hand,
Grudzielanek used a smaller bat and hit only with his left hand for
weeks in the cage during his disabled list days.
</P>
<P>
   After missing five weeks with a broken right hand, the result of
punching a wall after hitting into a double play in Pittsburgh,
Grudzielanek has seven hits in his past 14 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first part of a swing is when you go down to the ball with
(the left hand), and that's what he was doing,'' Down said. ``It's
what I told him from the get-go. I told him to look for the reason
why (the injury) happened. He worked on it, and it will make him a
better hitter in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers failed to score in the first with the bases loaded
and none out _ Todd Hundley, Raul Mondesi and Devon White each
struck out _ but unlike pervious games when the Dodgers (37-47)
would go stale, they came right back.
</P>
<P>
   They put two runners on in the second, and with one out
Grudzielanek drove a Freddy Garcia (9-5) pitch over the left-center
field fence to give the Dodgers a 3-0 lead. It was Grudzielanek's
third homer and first since April 25. He added an RBI single in the
seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at some old tapes and saw that I was hitting the ball
the other way,'' said Grudzielanek, who batted leadoff for the
second time. ``They can put two fielders over there and I'm still
going to try that. That's what I did when I had my (All-Star) year
(1996). If you do that, you'll be able to turn on some pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek's offense was the show, but his catch in shallow
left field in the fourth kept the Mariners scoreless. With Dan
Wilson on second and two outs, Grudzielanek tracked down Brian
Hunter's blooper and made stretching, back-hand catch before
falling to grass.
</P>
<P>
   It helped Valdes (7-7) win for the second straight start after
losing a career-high five in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Though Valdes has given up 19 homers this season and the
Mariners lead the majors with 149, Seattle hitters were baffled.
Valdes allowed seven hits, struck out four and didn't walk a
batter.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes' performance also sent a reminder to the Mariners of what
they missed. He was nearly traded last season for a deal involving
Randy Johnson, but Seattle pulled out at the final instant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think about things like that,'' said Seattle's Ken
Griffey Jr., who went 1 for 3 with two strikeouts against Valdes.
``That's (the media's) job to come up with the creative stuff.
Randy was going to get traded. If it wasn't (Valdes), it was going
to be someone else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 0305EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
