<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP_DICICCO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEET THE MAN BEHIND THE WORLD CUP WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM THOMAS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ During the U.S. team's earth-shaking run
through the Women's World Cup, this nation has been captivated not
only by the Americans' performance, but by the personalities of the
players and the compelling stories that surround the team.
</P>
<P>
   There's megastar Mia Hamm; the struggles of Michelle Akers, who
suffers from chronic fatigue syndrome; the ``soccer moms,'' Carla
Overbeck and Joy Fawcett; the self-described ``fly in the milk,''
Black goalkeeper Briana Scurry; and many others.
</P>
<P>
   So many, in fact, that it can be difficult to stand out among
this interesting and diverse collection of young women.
</P>
<P>
   Unless, of course, you sport a mustache.
</P>
<P>
   The bushy-lipped guy directing traffic during practices and
matches is Tony DiCicco, the full-time coach, sometimes father
figure and all-around orchestrator of the team that will play China
today for the World Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
   Getting to this point has not been easy. DiCicco had a difficult
task when in 1994 he took over a team that was the reigning Cup
champion and was expected to keep that crown a year later. In
addition, he had to follow Anson Dorrance, who not only led the
national team to the first Cup title, but was the winningest
college coach ever at North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   DiCicco, a graduate of Springfield College in Massachusetts and
a professional player for five years in the American Soccer League,
had no prior head coaching experience at any of the higher levels.
</P>
<P>
   He knew that unless he continued to produce a winner, the
critics would be standing on his doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm well past that, but I did have that feeling when I first
took over,'' DiCicco said last week. ``The team was the world
champions. When you think that way, it takes away from your ability
to coach the best way you can.''
</P>
<P>
   DiCicco's ability to coach was called into question after the
U.S. team lost to Norway in the semifinals of the 1995 World Cup.
According to assistant coach Lauren Gregg, that loss was a turning
point for DiCicco and the U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened in 1995 gave Tony the freedom to make changes
and go in his direction,'' Gregg said. ``He started using his
strength, which is in the tactical part of the game. He is a real
student. Every opportunity he has to get better, he takes advantage
of. No one spends more time watching tapes, analyzing and
discussing them, than Tony does.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's learned how to lead women, how to lead teams, and brought
an incredible tactical sophistication on both sides of the ball.
The results are what you see now.''
</P>
<P>
   The first result was a gold medal in the 1996 Olympics. Now,
DiCicco has led the Americans to a berth in the World Cup
championship match.
</P>
<P>
   ``He deserves a lot of credit,'' said Overbeck, the veteran team
captain. ``He came back after '95 and made huge changes. For one,
he went from a marking defense to a zone that has worked out really
well. As the game has evolved, he has kept up and helped to
continue the success.''
</P>
<P>
   Said DiCicco: ``I'm a much better coach now. . . . I know more
about handling people.''
</P>
<P>
   The 50-year-old coach, who is the father of four boys, has what
defender Lorrie Fair calls 20 daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the perfect fit for this team because he's fatherly,''
Fair said. ``But he's a coach first, which we all respect.''
</P>
<P>
   The respect, Overbeck said, is something DiCicco has earned.
</P>
<P>
   ``His personality plays a big part in it,'' she said. ``He knows
soccer, but just as important, he knows how to get the most out of
every player. He's very supportive and open-minded. He'll go to the
captains and ask for suggestions, get other input.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of that has made for a great relationship between Tony and
the team, and is a huge reason for our success.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
