<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-IMPACT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUP'S IMPACT ON YOUTH MAY BE APPARENT IN THE FALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Those who wonder what impact the Women's World Cup
will have on soccer in general and women's sports in particular
should get part of their answer this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Women's World Cup President and CEO Marla Messing predicts youth
soccer leagues will be flooded with girls wanting to play this
fall. She says enrollment in youth leagues will hit record numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see hundreds of thousands of girls register in the fall
that otherwise wouldn't have registered if not for this event,''
said Messing. ``They want to be like Mia Hamm and Julie Foudy and
play in a Women's World Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Nelson, a regional coordinator and coach of American Youth
Soccer Organization teams in Torrance, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The girls are seeing there's an opportunity,'' said Nelson, a
father of four girls. ``My youngest knows the girl players by name
now. Where she was big on Ken Griffey Jr., it's Mia Hamm now.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 8.6 million soccer players in the United States, 2.5
million are girls, according to AYSO. About 635,000 boys and girls,
ages 5-18, play in AYSO's 1,000 leagues nationwide. Forty percent
are female.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson is projecting an enrollment of 44 percent girls in his
region's leagues this fall, up from 38 percent five years ago. The
first female players allowed in AYSO in 1971 now are mothers, and
he credits them with enrolling their daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The WNBA helped us be successful by showing the way as a
(professional women's) league,'' said Messing. ``Hopefully our
success will help other women's sports be successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been like a cultural shift, and the way the tournament
caught fire, we've tipped into something. We think this will be a
seminal moment, that people will look back in 20 years and say,
`That event is responsible for the development of women's sports.'
''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 0308EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
