<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES_NOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HLINKA WAS NEVER THE NO. 1 CANDIDATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite media speculation that Ivan Hlinka, coach of the Czech
Republic National Team, was in line to become an assistant on the
staff of Coyotes first-year Coach Bob Francis, he was never the top
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were interested in him and we did discuss the job with him,
but we did not make him an offer for the position,'' Coyotes
General Manager Bobby Smith said. ``We thought the other guys we
hired were better suited for our situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith and Francis announced earlier this week that former NHL
Coach Rick Bowness and veteran assistant coach Wayne Fleming will
round out Francis' staff.
</P>
<P>
   It was thought that the Coyotes' interest in luring Hlinka to
the United States was tied to the attempt to re-sign Group II free
agent Robert Reichel, who reportedly is seeking a contract in the
$3 million-per-year range and is prepared to stay in the Czech
Republic and become a full-time player/coach for the national team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it will have any effect on Robert's decision,
but you don't put together a coaching staff to appease a player,''
Smith said. ``The numbers Robert Reichel is asking for haven't
changed since before we talked to Hlinka.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not something we are going to agree to, either. We're
not close at all.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Safronov signed &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Coyotes have signed defenseman Kiril Safronov, 18, their second
first-round choice and the No. 19 pick overall, to a three-year
contract. No terms were announced.
</P>
<P>
   Safronov, a solid stay-home blueliner who at 6 feet 2 and 196
pounds is said to have a nasty streak and a physical game, played
last season for St. Petersburg in Russia and was the youngest
player on the Russian World Junior Team that captured the world
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Many scouts think Safronov could develop into a top NHL
defenseman in a couple of years. He will report to the Coyotes'
training camp in August. If he doesn't make the team, he will
either be assigned to AHL Springfield or join the Quebec Remparts ,
the Quebec Major Junior Hockey League team that drafted him on
Thursday. &QL; 
 &QL; 
No arbitration? &QL; 
 &QL; 
Of the Coyotes' six Group II free agents, those who can attract
offer sheets from other teams while Phoenix maintains the right to
match those offers, four _ Reichel, goalie Nikolai Khabibulin,
defenseman Stan Neckar and enforcer-type Sean Gagnon _ own the
right to take their case before an arbitration hearing if they
choose.
</P>
<P>
   The deadline for filing for arbitration is July 15, but Smith
said he thought the matter was moot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we will have anyone who goes to arbitration,''
Smith said. ``Some are too young, and some think that leverage-wise
they have a better chance to negotiate for what they want
throughout the summer than by going to arbitration.''
</P>
<P>
   Arbitration hearings will be held Aug. 115.
</P>
<P>
   Eligibility depends on a sliding scale determined by the age
they signed their first contract and number of years of NHL
experience. Players who signed between 18 and 20 must have five
years experience in the league. Those who signed at 21 must have
four; 2223, three years; 24, two years; 25 and older, one year.
</P>
<P>
   Wingers Shane Doan and Tavis Hansen are each one year short of
qualifying for arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said Friday he has not had any discussions with his Group
II players or their agents since making mandatory qualifying offers
to maintain their rights before the July 1 NHL deadline. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Adios, Corky &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reports are that the New York Rangers are wooing checking line
center/penalty killer Bob Corkum, an unrestricted free agent, and
are willing to pay him anywhere from $1.3 million to $1.5 million
per season.
</P>
<P>
   If so, Smith said Corkum had priced himself out of the Coyotes'
interest range.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assume that Bob Corkum will be playing for another team next
year,'' Smith said. ``He will end up getting an offer that we will
be unwilling to match.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, who already have spent a reported $54.4 million on
wingers Theo Fleury, Valeri Kamensky and defenseman Stephane
Quintal this week, have made a noticeable impact on the NHL salary
structure for unrestricted free agents, although Smith said he
didn't expect it to carry over for Group II free agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all Group III stuff that doesn't affect Group II players
or those going to arbitration at all,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
