r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ATHLETICS-D-BACKS     07-10 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ATHLETICS-D-BACKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIAMONDBACKS AGAIN HAVENO STING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was hard to tell which frustration was greater: Andy Benes'
failure to record victories in back-to-back starts for the first
time this season, or his teammates' failure to once again beat up
on a pitcher who has been punched around by the rest of baseball
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Like, for instance, Jose Jimenez. Or, in this case, Gil Heredia.
</P>
<P>
   The answer was pretty much a dead heat, but the net result was a
5-2 loss to the Oakland Athletics on Friday night. It was Arizona's
14th loss in its past 21 games and only the Athletics' sixth win in
their 26 road games.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Heredia, who played for the University of Arizona,
entered the game with an 5.77 earned run average and a 4-5 record
that was shakier than the numbers indicate. Of his four victories,
just one, a 3-2 win over Toronto, came against a team playing above
.500 baseball.
</P>
<P>
   But Heredia, 1-3 with a 7.77 ERA in his past nine starts, did
what veteran pitchers often do. He kept himself out of major
trouble and coming up with the big pitch when he didn't, holding
the Diamondbacks to one run on eight hits before leaving after the
sixth inning and 83 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   He escaped a first-and-third situation in the second by striking
out Benes, and a bases-loaded, one-out situation in the fourth by
getting Benes to ground into a force out at the plate and retiring
leadoff hitter Tony Womack on a meek ground out to second.
</P>
<P>
   The only run the Diamondbacks produced off Heredia and his 86
mph fastball came in the third when Womack, who had two singles and
a double, led off with a single, stole second and went to third on
catcher Ramon Hernandez's throwing error. He scored on a single to
right by Luis Gonzalez, who also doubled home Womack in the
seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the frustration was Arizona's inability to touch
Oakland reliever Buddy Groom, who six times this season has failed
to retire a batter during an appearance. Groom had retired just 10
of the 23 batters he faced in his past 11 outings, but he pitched a
scoreless eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Benes, like Heredia, had stopped a three-game losing streak in
his last start, a 17-5 win in a sauna bath against St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   But he apparently is one who believes that statistics never lie.
The Athletics entered the game with the worst batting average in
the major leagues (.230) with runners in scoring position, and
Benes seemed intent on putting that statistic to the ultimate test.
</P>
<P>
   After breezing through the first two innings, thanks in part to
a fielding gem from third baseman Matt Williams on Hernandez's
rocket down the line, Benes committed the unpardonable sin of
walking Heredia. A single and a walk later the bases were full with
one out.
</P>
<P>
   He escaped by striking out Ben Grieve and getting Jason Giami on
a fly to shallow left that Williams handled.
</P>
<P>
   The stats were correct.
</P>
<P>
   He found himself with the bases loaded again in the fourth
thanks to a pair of walks and a throwing error by shortstop Andy
Fox, but again escaped damage by striking out leadoff hitter Tony
Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there was something to this statistic thing.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, when one puts statistics to the test, one should
know all of them. While Oakland is anemic with runners in scoring
position, they are second in the America League in drawing walks
and rank fifth in homers.
</P>
<P>
   And Benes battle with shaky control caught up with him in the
fifth, when he got stuck in a fatal rut.
</P>
<P>
   He opened the inning by issuing his fifth walk of the game to
Miguel Tijada. His first pitch to Grieve, who was stranded in
scoring position in the first after doubling, landed in the
right-center-field bleachers after a 413-foot flight, giving the
Athletics a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The pattern repeated itself. He walked Giambi, his sixth of the
game, and his first pitch to Matt Stairs found a home in the
right-field seats some 403 feet away. Oakland led, 4-1, but, hey,
neither time was there a runner in scoring position!
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, despite Benes' control problems in the two previous
innings, the Diamondbacks had nobody warming up in the bullpen, and
Benes escaped further damage. But not without sending center
fielder Steve Finley against the wall to retire Hernandez and then
sending him to the warning track to catch Ric Chavez's rocket.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez gave Oakland a 5-2 lead with a two-out solo homer to
left off Greg Swindell, the first of four Diamondbacks' relief
pitchers. That also included the major league debut of rookie Erik
Sabel, who became the first Diamondback draftee (42nd pick in 1966)
to make a game appearance for the team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
