r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-STEWART-AZ     07-10 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-STEWART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOKIE IS `NONE OF THE ABOVE'  
 BUT STEWART IS ALL YOU'D WANT IN A DRIVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Question: With 17 of 34 NASCAR Winston Cup races in the books,
what has been the season's top story?
</P>
<P>
   A: Jeff Gordon, former world-beater, dropping to an unaccustomed
fifth place in the drivers standings.
</P>
<P>
   B: Dale Jarrett atop the points ladder.
</P>
<P>
   C: No driver punching out another driver on pit road.
</P>
<P>
   D: None of the above.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of the above,'' answered car owner Robert Yates, whose
two-car stable includes Jarrett. ``Tony Stewart has been the
biggest story.''
</P>
<P>
   How big? THIS big.
</P>
<P>
   Although a rookie, Stewart has been extraordinarily productive.
</P>
<P>
   He has been as high as No. 5 in the standings and enters
Sunday's race at New Hampshire International Speedway in sixth,
only 19 points behind Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Despite no wins, Stewart, 28, has shown a keen resilience in the
face of potential calamity.
</P>
<P>
   After 17 races during Gordon's rookie season in 1993, he had
five DNFs.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart has one. He also has four top-five and nine top-10
finishes, which is the kind of sparkling consistency a driver needs
to penetrate the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   Should Stewart remain positioned in the top 10 throughout the
remainder of the season, he will become the first rookie in nearly
20 years to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Jody Ridley finished seventh in his first NASCAR season in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, however, is quick to remind everyone there are
mitigating circumstances for the early success.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all honesty, I've probably had the better end of the deal
compared to the other rookies this season,'' Stewart said. ``I've
stepped into an established team (Joe Gibbs Racing) that finished
in the top 10 in points the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a teammate (Bobby Labonte) to reflect off of, and
(rookies Buckshot Jones and Elliott Sadler) don't have a teammate
to go to during practice and say, `My car feels like this or that.
Does your car do the same thing?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's honesty is admirable.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no one can deny his immense talents, which have prompted
some to believe he is the best seat-of-the-pants racer to come
along since A.J. Foyt.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one way, (Stewart's impact) is a surprise,'' Ernie Irvan
said. ``It's a surprise because most of the time, rookies, no
matter what, come in and they tear up a bunch of stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony Stewart is a great race car driver. He's right on the
playing field with a guy like Jeff Gordon. There's no way you can
just take his abilities and toss them into a pile.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great race car driver, and he's been a very smart race
car driver.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe lucky, too, Stewart hinted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured at this point in the season if you went to our race
shop, you'd see (Labonte's) cars in one piece on one side of the
room, and the other side of the room would look like a salvage yard
with front and rear clips off of them,'' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart gives much credit to remaining mostly in one piece to
crew chief Greg Zipadelli.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was legal to marry two people, I'd marry my fiancee and
I'd make sure Greg was tied in there somehow, so he couldn't get
away, either,'' Stewart said. ``I don't think I've found anybody
more intense than Greg.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how good a day or how bad a day we're having, Greg
is always trying to find something else to make us a little better.
That's probably the thing I like about him the most. He never
quits.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither does Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Three times this season, Stewart has qualified for the front
row, including one pole position. Stewart's top finish, however,
has been fourth, which he's done three times.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Stewart manages to poke his head along with the Home
Depot Pontiac Grand Prix into victory lane before the season ends,
however, is not something he loses sleep over.
</P>
<P>
   ``This series is all about consistency,'' said Stewart, a past
Indy Racing League champion. ``It means more to me to finish in the
top-five three or four weeks in a row than it does to win one week
and finish 30th the next week, and crash the week after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys (the media) are more antsy about me winning a race
than I am.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
