r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-MIDYEAR &UR; RE     07-10 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-MIDYEAR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASCAR AT THE HALFWAY MARK: HOW THEY STAND 
</HEADLINE>
  REPORT-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seventeen NASCAR Winston Cup races down, 17 to go. Before we say
adios to the first half of the season, how about one final peek
over the shoulders: &QL; 
 &QL; 
By the numbers &QL; 
Although 17 NASCAR Winston Cup races remain, don't bet against Dale
Jarrett maintaining the series lead and capturing the driving
title. The last time the leader at the midway point failed to win
the championship was 1992, when Davey Allison lost the crown to the
late Alan Kulwicki. Actually, Kulwicki edged Bill Elliott by 10
points, the closest race in NASCAR history.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, Richard Petty overcame a 187.25 point deficit, the
farthest any driver has rallied to capture the driving title.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1949, when the series was founded, there have been 1,847
races.
</P>
<P>
   Nine drivers have won races this season: Jeff Gordon (four),
Jeff Burton (three), Dale Jarrett (three), Bobby Labonte (two) and
one each by John Andretti, Dale Earnhardt, Terry Labonte, Mark
Martin and Rusty Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   At this point last season, 220 points separated the top five
drivers. This year, Jarrett leads No. 5 Gordon by 394 points.
</P>
<P>
   There have been 325 lead changes this season among 36 drivers,
or an average of 19.1 lead changes per race.
</P>
<P>
   Burton has led 892 laps this season, 79 more than runner-up
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon tops Burton in miles led, however, with 1,099.47. Burton
has led 1,046.65 miles. Jarrett (773.86 miles) has led when it
counted most . . . at the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Labonte has completed 6,855.55 miles out of a possible
6,877.07.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-six percent of the top-five finishes have been recorded by
only five drivers: Jarrett (13), Bobby Labonte (12), Martin (11),
Gordon (10) and Burton (10).
</P>
<P>
   Lap-leader bonus points can mean the difference between winning
the championship or not. Gordon has earned 80 such points this
season, five more than Burton and Bobby Labonte. Jarrett has 55
bonus points.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Ford tough &QL; 
Ford Taurus drivers have won eight races, two more than Chevrolet
Monte Carlo drivers and five more than Pontiac Grand Prix drivers.
</P>
<P>
   After 17 races in 1998, Pontiac had only 20 top-10 finishes. The
manufacturer has 48 this season.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has 43 of the 85 top-five finishing positions this season
(50.6 percent). Pontiac and Chevy each have 21 (24.7 percent).
</P>
<P>
   After 4,993 laps, Ford has led 2,699, and Chevy has led 1,386. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
First-year blues &QL; 
Aside from Tony Stewart, who is sixth in the drivers standings,
it's been a long season for other rookies. Elliott Sadler is 31st
on the ladder, followed by Buckshot Jones (44th) and Stanton
Barrett (52nd). &QL; 
Is there a doctor in the house? &QL; 
Ask Martin if he'd like to do last weekend's Pepsi 400 at Daytona
International Speedway all over again. Martin, perhaps the fittest
driver on the beer-and-burger circuit, crashed in practice and
initially was diagnosed with a fractured wrist. Despite much pain,
Martin still drove and finished 17th.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the race, Martin contemplated trying to cut the
cast off his hand. Two days after the race, it was learned Martin
also had suffered a broken rib and a broken tibia plateau in his
left knee.
</P>
<P>
   Surgery on Martin's knee was performed Wednesday, but he doesn't
plan on sitting out Sunday's race at New Hampshire International
Speedway. Martin also must undergo lower-back surgery on Nov. 23,
two days after the season finale. Do they give purple hearts in
NASCAR? &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Psst, can you spare a dime? &QL; 
Chief mechanic Scott Eggleston was fined $50,000 for an illegal
insert in the intake manifold, which was discovered during prerace
inspection last Saturday. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tidbits &QL; 
Jarrett has a 5.94 finishing average.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Hamilton is one of four drivers to start all 17 races and
not lead a lap.
</P>
<P>
   There have been 12 sweeps in 118 chances since 1990. Gordon was
the only driver to do it last season, sweeping the two races at
Rockingham.
</P>
<P>
   It pays to belong to a multicar stable. Of the 85 top-five
finishes, 81 (95 percent) have been recorded by multicar teams.
Roush Racing leads with 21, followed by Joe Gibbs Racing (16),
Robert Yates Racing (14) and Hendrick Motorsports (11).
</P>
<P>
   Poor Michael Waltrip. He is winless in 411 career starts,
including 17 this season. Rick Mast is next at 292.
</P>
<P>
   Several drivers have gone more than 50 races without a win. For
good guy Dave Marcus, it's been a 457-race winless drought. Brett
Bodine last won 282 starts ago. Other notables include Ken Schrader
(252), Darrell Waltrip (211) and Elliott (144).
</P>
<P>
   Several drivers also have gone many races without a top-five
finish. Brett Bodine last did so in the 1994 Brickyard 400, 154
starts ago. Has it really been nearly two years for Kyle Petty and
Elliott, who last recorded top-five finishes in September 1997? &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
WHO'S HOT/WHO`S NOT &QC; 
HOT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some examples of the good, the bad and the ugly:
</P>
<P>
   One reason Dale Jarrett has moved into the series lead is 14
straight top-10 finishes. Jarrett began the season in 36th after
finishing 37th in the season-opening Daytona 500. He hasn't
finished worse than 11th since Daytona.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Labonte has 13 top-10 finishes, including two wins.
</P>
<P>
   Do you think rookie Tony Stewart has greatly benefited from
having Labonte as a teammate? Stewart has posted nine straight
top-15 finishes. &QL; 
NOT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ted Musgrave has only one top-10 finish this season.
</P>
<P>
   Two drivers with famous last names are struggling. Kyle Petty
has finished 27th or worse in four of the past six races, and
Michael Waltrip has finished 37th or worse in four of the past six
races. Ugh.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone at Roush Racing is a success story. Johnny Benson
only has two top-10 finishes.
</P>
<P>
   Has anyone seen Ricky Rudd? In 17 starts this season, Rudd, who
has won at least one race in 16 consecutive seasons, is still
seeking his first top-10 finish. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
ON SECOND THOUGHT . . . &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nearly five months ago, staff writer Mark Armijo attempted to
predict which NASCAR Winston Cup drivers would finish in the top 10
and therefore receive invitations to ``sit on the stage'' at the
Waldorf-Astoria Hotel in New York City, the site of the
season-ending awards banquet. The following are Armijo's
predictions, current standings, analysis and adjusted predictions. &QL; 
Preseason Current &QR;   &QR; Comment Adjustment &QR;
</P>
<P>
   1. Dale Jarrett 1st &QR;   &QR; Nice guys finish first, too. 1st &QR;
</P>
<P>
   2. Jeff Gordon 5th &QR;   &QR; Four wins, but also four DNFs. 4th &QR;
</P>
<P>
   3. Mark Martin 3rd &QR;   &QR; Needs to string together more wins. 5th &QR;
</P>
<P>
   4. Jeff Burton 4th &QR;   &QR; Already has career-high three wins. 2nd &QR;
</P>
<P>
   5. Bobby Labonte 2nd &QR;   &QR; Has Team Gibbs replaced Team Hendrick?
3rd &QR;
</P>
<P>
   6. Rusty Wallace 8th &QR;   &QR; Inconsistency is a killer. 8th &QR;
</P>
<P>
   7. Jeremy Mayfield 10th &QR;   &QR; Should be stronger. 11th &QR;
</P>
<P>
   8. Dale Earnhardt 7th &QR;   &QR; The Intimidator still has it. 6th &QR;
</P>
<P>
   9. Terry Labonte 12th &QR;   &QR; Was series champion only three years
ago. 12th &QR; 
10. Bobby Hamilton 14th &QR;   &QR; Lack of teammate hurts. 14th &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 0317EDT &QL; 
