<SLUG> BC-BANK-CELLUCCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE GOVERNOR SEES BENEFIT TO FLEET-BANKBOSTON MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Bucking the tide of political protest against New
England's largest bank merger, Governor Paul Cellucci said Friday
that the Fleet-BankBoston combination was good for the region.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci, speaking for the first time about the deal, set
himself against an array of Democratic officials from Massachusetts
and Connecticut who have forcefully criticized the $16 billion
transaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Boston and Massachusetts to have a financial institution
like this is a huge plus for our economy and the economy of New
England,'' Cellucci, a Republican, said in an interview Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But he suggested that industry regulators might take the unusual
step of forcing the new bank to make concrete promises to carry out
its multibillion-dollar community investment proposal.
</P>
<P>
   An unusually large number of elected and appointed officials
have criticized or opposed Fleet's acquisition of its former rival,
which is expected to gain regulatory approval later this year. The
officials have been joined by hundreds of community activists, who
are worried about the merger's impact on competition.
</P>
<P>
   Critics include US Representatives Barney Frank of Newton and
Michael E. Capuano of Somerville, State Senator Dianne Wilkerson of
Roxbury, attorneys general in Massachusetts and Connecticut, and
Boston Mayor Thomas M. Menino. They say the combined bank's plan to
provide $14.6 billion for affordable housing, small business loans,
and urban revitalization projects may not be sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   Community groups that channel Fleet housing loans to low-income
borrowers are upset that the new Fleet has said it will not sign
any concrete agreements to work with specific groups. Activists
groups worry that without agreements, some of the $14.6 billion
will go unspent.
</P>
<P>
   But Cellucci said regulators might move ``to attach a condition
to the merger that ensures that commitments are fulfilled.'' He did
not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   While Cellucci said his principal concern about the merger was
the 5,000 jobs that the combined company will eliminate, he said
the booming economy would absorb laid off workers.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci joined opponents to the deal on one point. He urged the
combined bank to sell some of the $14 billion in assets it is
divesting to meet antitrust rules to community banks. ``We need to
continue to have competition and small banks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet took a drubbing at a public hearing held earlier this week
by the Federal Reserve Bank of Boston, whose parent, the Federal
Reserve Board, must approve the merger.
</P>
<P>
   A second public hearing, at the State House, is set for Tuesday.
At that session, Cellucci will join state banking commissioner
Thomas Curry, Treasurer Shannon P. O'Brien, and Department of
Revenue Commissioner Frederick Laskey in discussing the
Fleet-BankBoston merger's impact on the community. The session,
which is open to all, is organized by the Board of Bank
Incorporation, a state agency that must approve the combination.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Leonard, the board's secretary, said board members
``would likely ask a lot of questions on a variety of topics,''
ranging from capital investment in the community to urban
investment proposals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
