<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following 1999 All-Star Game
stories Saturday for use by NYTimes News Service clients. All
stories will bear the BOS designator and move under the Sports (s)
category code.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions, contact the NYTimes News Service desk at The
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ALLST-WILLIAMS (Boston) _ With the AL down a run and two men
on in the bottom of the ninth at Detroit's Briggs Stadium in 1941,
Ted Williams hits a towering homer to give the AL a 7-5 victory. By
Gordon Edes. 1185 words.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ALLST-HUBBELL (Boston) _ In 1934, Carl Hubbell had the
impossible dream come true: The left-handed Hubbell struck out five
of the greatest hitters of his or any other era -- Babe Ruth, Lou
Gehrig, Jimmie Foxx, Al Simmons, and Joe Cronin -- in succession.
By Bob Ryan. 1260 words.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ALLST-BLACKS (Boston) _ The 1949 All-Star Game was the first
time black players were selected: Jackie Robinson, Roy Campanella
and Don Newcombe from the Dodgers on the NL, and Larry Doby from
the Indians for the AL. By Michael Madden. 1390 words.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ALLST-TV-COLUMN (Boston) _ The '50 midsummer classic, was
historic because NBC made it the first All-Star Game to reach a
national audience. By Howard Manly. 870 words.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ALLST-MUSIAL (Boston) _ In one of the more dramatic All-Star
games, Stan Musial hit the first pitch off Frank Sullivan over the
screen in Milwaukee's County Stadium to win it for the Nationals in
1955. By Bob Ryan. 1255 words.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ALLST-ROSE (Boston) _ Maybe it was the hometown Riverfront
Stadium crowd, or maybe it was just Pete Rose's way of playing hard
all the time, but when Rose came charging home in the 12th inning
in the 1970 game, he plowed into Indians' catcher Ray Fosse,
injuring both players but allowing the NL to win its eighth
straight over the AL. By Steve Fainaru. 1530 words.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ALLST-JACKSON (Boston) _ In 1971 Reggie Jackson hit one of
the longest home runs in history when he walloped Dock Ellis' pitch
at Tiger Stadium in the third inning. The shot hit the light tower
on top of the second deck in right-center field. By Larry
Whiteside. 990 words.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ALLST-MOMENTS (Boston) _ Moments historical and hysterical.
The All-Star Game has provided some of both. By Marvin Pave. A
wrapup. (2 takes)
</P>
