<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, July 11:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-ASSESS (Jerusalem) _ As Prime Minister Ehud Barak sets
off on an ambitious course to forge a comprehensive peace in the
Mideast, he heads out into a region of several aging leaders weary
of the logjam of Israeli-Arab hostilities. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   BELGRADE-MILOSEVIC (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ During his 12 years
in power, whenever Slobodan Milosevic has been on the ropes most of
the punches have been thrown here in the Serbian capital. But
Belgrade, so far, has been a conspicuous wallflower in the growing
anti-Milosevic movement that has found expression across the
country in the last two weeks. This city has about a fifth of the
Serbian republic's population and about 40 percent of its educated
middle-class, yet all the action has been in the boondocks. By
Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   CONGO (Lusaka, Zambia) _ The signing of a cease-fire agreement
meant to end the war in Congo stalled for hours Saturday as two
factions within one of the rebel groups contested which one of them
would sign the document. By Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DEMONSTRATION (Beijing) _ Nearly 1,000 members of a
spiritual movement known as Falun Gong held a two-day demonstration
inside government headquarters in a southern Chinese city this
week, a human rights organization reported Saturday. Undeterred by
a recent crackdown on Falun Gong in Beijing, where China's leaders
appear alarmed by the size, organization and secretive nature of
the movement, the demonstrators entered the inner courtyard of
Communist Party headquarters in Nanchang, the capital of Jiangxi
Province, on July 6 and 7. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-AID-CUTS (United Nations) _ Mark Malloch Brown, the new
chief of the U.N. Development Program, had barely moved into his
spacious office with its panoramic views of the East River and the
United Nations when he got some bad news. Denmark and Germany,
mainstays of his agency's $2 billion dollar budget, were slashing
their annual contributions. By Judith Miller/
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GYPSIES (Kosovo Polje, Yugoslavia) _ Crammed into a
schoolhouse, 30 to a room, or living in pitched tents on the school
grounds, their horses tethered nearby, the Gypsies of Kosovo are
living in a precarious state. Always at the bottom of the social
pile in this sectarian society, they have now hit their nadir. By
Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIOLA-DIVIDE (Dajabon, Dominican Republic) _ Despite market
days and a new political will to forge a closer relationship, Haiti
and the Dominican Republic remain nations living side by side yet
worlds apart. By Mireya Navarro. (With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-PAST-ABUSES (Rio de Janeiro) _ Nearly a decade and a half
of democracy have erased the abuses of military rule from the
memory of most Brazilians. But two cases dating from that
unpleasant 21-year period have suddenly been thrust into the
national spotlight, creating embarrassment and discomfort for the
current civilian government, which had no involvement in the
original events. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-ERADICATION _ When Pino Arlacchi, the director of the U.N.
International Drug Control Program, addressed the General Assembly
13 months ago and proposed eliminating opium poppy and coca leaf
cultivation in 10 years, his strategy was greeted with polite
skepticism. But Arlacchi says that his timetable for eradicating
the raw ingredients for heroin and cocaine around the world is, if
anything, running ahead of schedule in some countries, though he
acknowledged difficulties in others. By Christopher S. Wren.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TEACHER-BOOM _ After years of shying away from the field, a
growing number of college students, including those from elite
liberal arts colleges, now say they want to be schoolteachers. By
Mary B.W. Tabor. (With photo, graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   CITIZEN-KHRUSHCHEV (Providence, R.I.) _ Four decades after his
father, Nikita S. Khrushchev, provocatively vowed from the Kremlin,
``We will bury you,'' Sergei N. Khrushchev awaits American
citizenship, happily prepared to pledge allegiance to the United
States as its newest patriot. By Francis X. Clines. (With a photo.)
</P>
<P>
   IOWA-STRAWPOLL (Des Moines, Iowa) _ Six years ago, when he first
started running for president, Lamar Alexander never figured the
toughest test he would face in his grinding quest would be a straw
poll. But it has come down to that for the former Tennessee
governor, as well as for half a dozen other hopefuls seeking the
Republican nomination in 2000. As Alexander put it, when 10,000
Iowa Republicans gather in Ames next month for the party's
traditional presidential straw poll, the results will add up to
more than ``just another straw in the wind.'' By B. Drummond Ayres
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ELDERLY-DRUGS (Philadelphia) _ Not just paying for all their
medications, which Clinton wants Medicare to help with, but keeping
all the pills straight, defines the lives of many older people. We
talk to them. By Sara Rimer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-TAXCUT (Washington) _ After nearly two decades in which
their desire for big tax cuts was overwhelmed by efforts to
eliminate the federal budget deficit, Republicans in Congress will
set out in the coming week to pass the largest and most broadly
distributed tax reduction since 1981. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   UPSIDEDOWN-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ Major candidates in the 2000
presidential campaign, their assumptions turned upside down in the
early going, are scrambling to revise their strategies and retool
their political machines for a contest that has opened far more
swiftly than either the Democrats or the Republicans foresaw. By
Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   FAA-AIRTOUR-SAFETY (Washington) _ Ever since the collision of
two aircraft filled with tourists in the Grand Canyon 13 years ago,
safety officials have urged the Federal Aviation Administration to
step up its oversight of air tours. After a spate of air tour
accidents in Hawaii, the FAA promised in 1995 to write new national
rules by the end of 1997, calling it ``a high priority.'' But it
has not happened yet. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN _ On Clinton's poverty tour. By Bob Herbert.
</P>
