<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 11:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5330 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UPSIDEDOWN-CAMPAIGN-2     07-10 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPSIDEDOWN-CAMPAIGN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS CAMPAIGN STARTS SWIFTLY, BOTH PARTIES ARE SCRAMBLING 
</HEADLINE>
  (With IOWA-STRAWPOLL) 
(nk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Major candidates in the 2000 presidential campaign,
their assumptions turned upside down in the early going, are
scrambling to revise their strategies and retool their political
machines for a contest that has opened far more swiftly than either
the Democrats or the Republicans foresaw.
</P>
<P>
   The crowded Republican field has produced a breakaway front
runner and the Democratic incumbent who seemed like a shoo-in for
nomination no longer seems quite so assured.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Vice President Al Gore has abandoned his intended Rose
Garden strategy. Texas Gov. George W. Bush has amassed enough cash
to abandon the system of federal campaign financing, and Sen. Bob
Smith of New Hampshire plans to abandon the Republican Party this
week, fully seven months before his home state's primary.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the year, advisers to Gore boasted that they had
discouraged other Democrats from entering the race. Many predicted
that the candidacy of former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey would
be only a trifling obstruction on an unimpeded course to the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But because Bradley has collected an impressive campaign
treasury of $11 million (Gore has $18.5 million) and is viewed as a
credible contender by the political establishment, the Gore
campaign has shifted from its preoccupation with gearing up for a
general election and is putting more emphasis on trying to knock
out Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Republican officials say they are surprised that
Bush has become so popular and has piled up so much money that he
seems to have practically smothered the Republican field. Many
Republicans had predicted that the contest would be the most
vigorous free-for-all their party had endured in decades. Instead,
many of Bush's 11 rivals are struggling to see whether they can
stay afloat past the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conventional wisdom has been totally thrown out the
door,'' said Scott Reed, who ran Bob Dole's losing race for
president in 1996. ``The Republican race started out as the first
open nomination fight in over 40 years. Now Bush is dictating the
timing and agenda of the whole race. He's smoking. Gore, on the
other hand, had bluffed everyone else out of the race and finds
himself in a very competitive two-man race.''
</P>
<P>
   Tad Devine, a Democratic strategist who is a veteran of decades
of campaigns, said: ``This is a level of engagement that I've never
seen in the presidential nominating process. We're in uncharted
waters because we've never seen a race this engaged so early in a
calendar cycle.''
</P>
<P>
   Campaigns, of course, are notoriously unpredictable. With seven
months before the first votes are cast in a primary or caucus,
today's front-runner could easily be tomorrow's loser.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the perception _ fueled by polls, fund-raising figures and
pundits _ that Bush is dictating the Republican race and that Gore
faces a spirited contest is already, in significant ways, affecting
how they and their rivals are battling for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Buffeted by Bradley and the political potency of Bush, Gore has
shelved his plans to devote much of this year to a strategy in
which he had intended to stay above politics, devote himself to
official duties and not even formally announce his candidacy until
the fall. Instead, Gore has already announced and moved much faster
than planned to lay out his positions and distance himself from
President Clinton. And he already has shaken up his staff.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who had expected to battle other Democrats before
emerging as the chief alternative to Gore, has also adjusted his
game plan. Instead of attacking Gore and struggling to get
television coverage, Bradley has opted to lie low because the
one-on-one dynamic has guaranteed that he will be taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The changed dynamic has also accelerated Bush's strategy.
Because he has emerged so quickly, he has hired staff members and
put his campaign in gear far ahead of schedule. He had initially
planned to decide in the fall whether to reject federal subsidies,
allowing his campaign to spend beyond federal limits. Now his
campaign is set to announce this month that it will not accept
public money. And Bush has felt less pressure to appeal to specific
constituencies of the party and has embarked on a general-election
approach, to appeal to a broad swath of the electorate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has also upended the strategies of his rivals. Several
contenders have laid out specific policy initiatives earlier than
they had planned in an effort, as yet unsuccessful, to gain a
toehold in the polls. Several campaigns said they no longer felt
they had to raise table stakes of $20 million this year to be
competitive. They say that because Bush has already collected $36
million, he has already won the money race, and they feel less
pressure to solicit money.
</P>
<P>
   The dynamic has driven Bush's rivals to concentrate even more on
pivotal early states like Iowa and New Hampshire because they do
not have the resources to compete with Bush and Steve Forbes, the
multimillionaire publisher, in California, which has moved up its
primary date.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're liberated,'' said Ronald Kaufman, a Republican
national committeeman from Massachusetts who supports Bush. ``But
the trouble for them is it's one less opportunity to show that
you're relevant to the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Many political strategists and academics said they had never
seen the contours of a presidential season shift so early and so
rapidly. They said it was partly because of a compressed calendar
of primaries that virtually guarantees that party nominees will
emerge by mid-March.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conventional wisdom in primary seasons is almost always turned
on its head,'' said Larry M. Bartels, a professor of politics and
public affairs at Princeton University. ``But there's a feeling of
desperation among the minor candidates that if they can't get some
traction in the next couple of months, it's going to be impossible
for them to carry on.''
</P>
<P>
   One contender who is feeling the heat is former Tennessee Gov.
Lamar Alexander, who has not stopped campaigning since he lost the
Republican nomination in 1996 but thus far shows no signs that he
is gaining steam.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to feel for the guy,'' said Charles E. Cook Jr.,
editor of a nonpartisan political report. ``He's done everything
anyone ever told him to do'' to capture the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to explain his predicament, Alexander gently excoriated
the press for excessively focusing on the purported triumph of Bush
_ and the woes of Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``TV now overdoses on everything, whether it's Michael Jordan
and Wayne Gretzky's retirement or climbing all over everyone to
conclude a race eight months before anybody votes,'' Alexander
said. ``If all you do is cover the front-runner and take a poll
about what you've just reported, then you very quickly make a
front-runner rather than follow a front-runner. The other side of
it is it can change equally fast. Whether it will correct itself, I
don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A vivid demonstration of the dynamic on the Republican side was
on display at the summer convention of the Republican National
Committee, which ended Saturday in Philadelphia. In interviews,
delegates said they had to stay neutral because they represented
the national party. But then, one after another, they admitted
privately that they were on the Bush team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barring some major bombshell about George W., there's a lot of
pressure to try to complete the coronation early,'' said Dwight
Sutherland, a Republican national committeeman from Kansas.
``Bush's people here are putting the arm on us: `Will you formally
endorse? Will you come out tomorrow?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has gathered so much momentum that Georgette Mosbacher,
co-chairwoman of the campaign of Sen. John McCain of Arizona,
sounded practically like a convert. ``When you see that bandwagon
shipping out, you want to be on it,'' she said. ``It's amazing how
quickly wallets open up.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only was Bush the talk of the meeting, but signs of his
dominance were unmistakable. For example, no campaigns opened up
hospitality suites, a ritual at party gatherings. The session was
so controlled by Bush's operatives that Thomas Rath, a committeeman
from New Hampshire who backs Alexander, said, ``This is Austin
north.''
</P>
<P>
   Some campaigns explained that Bush was so beloved among the
party establishment that they did not bother to come to
Philadelphia. One long-shot contender who did, Alan Keyes, a former
State Department official who barely registers in the polls,
implored party members not to anoint a nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was talk among some Republican conservatives of
mounting third-party challenges as a protest against Bush. Smith is
expected to announce such an effort this week.
</P>
<P>
   Yet while the shape of the race seems so clear, many experts
cautioned that people should not be fooled. After all, polls show
that most of America is not paying attention to the presidential
contest right now. Eleven Republicans are still counting on the
Bush balloon to burst.
</P>
<P>
   And it is only a matter of time, many Democrats say, before Gore
rebounds. Despite many signs of stumbling in his campaign, he is
still trouncing Bradley in virtually every poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how Gore loses,'' said Robert M. Teeter, a
Republican pollster in Michigan. ``Doesn't he have a lock on the
Democratic machinery?''
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman put it this way: ``Never in history has a sitting vice
president lost the nomination.'' Referring to the party's national
convention in California, he added: ``Bill Clinton isn't going to
let his VP not get the nomination, even if it means flying every
delegate to Los Angeles on Air Force One and Air Force Two. Because
his legacy is shaky enough as it is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 1124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
