<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 11:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5340 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-ASSESS-2TAKES     07-10 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ASSESS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDEAST'S RIPE MOMENT: LEADERS TIRED OF LOGJAM
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ As Prime Minister Ehud Barak sets off on an
ambitious course to forge a comprehensive peace in the Mideast, he
heads out into a region of several aging leaders weary of the
logjam of Israeli-Arab hostilities.
</P>
<P>
   It would seem that the moment is particularly ripe for
successful negotiations, after hopes were dashed, expectations
lowered and relations soured during the tenure of Barak's
predecessor, Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Even Syrian President Hafez Assad is making cooing noises in
Barak's direction. Assad, 69, and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat,
also 69, are said to be eager because of their ages and health
problems to hammer out deals sooner rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, too, having invested so much time in
assisting Middle East peacemaking, is determined to see significant
progress during his final year in office.
</P>
<P>
   Whether this confluence of interests translates into the dawn of
a new peacemaking era, erupts into violence or fizzles into a new
stalemate of intransigence remains to be seen. Many who believe in
peace see this as a moment of positive expectations, but history
also teaches that skepticism or wariness is in order.
</P>
<P>
   ``This minuet of peace is by no means a foregone conclusion,''
Abraham H. Foxman, director of the Anti-Defamation League, said
this week during one of his frequent trips to the region to see
Israeli and Arab leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, 57, a highly decorated former general who won a
resounding mandate at the polls, is certainly diving straight into
the maelstrom. He set off on a whirlwind diplomatic tour two days
after moving into the prime minister's office on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday in Alexandria, he saw Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak, who effusively praised the new prime minister as a man of
peace. On Sunday afternoon, Barak is scheduled to hold his first
meeting with Arafat at the Erez checkpoint between Gaza and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday night, he is supposed to see King Abdullah of
Jordan in Aqaba, Jordan. On Wednesday in Jerusalem, Barak ends his
regional meetings by seeing Turkish President Suleyman Demirel. And
on Thursday, he starts a weeklong trip to the United States with a
visit to President Clinton at the White House, and then concludes
his journey with visits to England and Spain.
</P>
<P>
   From the day he was elected, Barak has made it clear that he
views his most significant mission as being a
warrior-turned-peacemaker, ending, as he often says, ``100 years of
bloody conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   He made it clear by the composition of his coalition that peace,
rather than domestic social issues, was his priority. And by the
very fact of assembling such a broad coalition _ representing
nearly two-thirds of the parliament _ he communicated that he
envisioned making difficult decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason to put together a coalition that large and
unwieldy is so as to be able to absorb blows and defections and
still presumably be stable enough to move ahead with territorial
concessions,'' said Joseph Alpher, Mideast director for the
American Jewish Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In his inaugural address early last week, Barak personally
addressed Arafat and Assad, informing them in a televised address
that he wanted to start a new chapter. He spoke a language of
empathy rare for an Israeli leader and in stark contrast to the
hostility of the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not only cognizant of the sufferings of my own people,''
Barak said, ``but I also recognize the sufferings of the
Palestinian people.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak has now entered an exploratory phase. A very disciplined
strategist, he tends to collect information and review it carefully
before devising a plan. No concrete results are expected out of his
diplomatic visits, although there could be the announcement in
Washington of the scheduling of a meeting with Assad.
</P>
<P>
   But there are no advance teams and Barak, who is serving as his
own defense minister, will not be traveling with a broad entourage
of advisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Skepticism could derive from the fact that Barak, who is an
unknown quantity, is also very much a one-man show,'' Alpher said.
</P>
<P>
   In the next week, Barak, who says he is seeking to restore trust
on all sides, will be feeling out his new peace partners as he
tries to compose a plan of action.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are expectations of huge progress, but Barak is quite a
cautious guy,'' said Efraim Inbar, a professor at the Begin-Sadat
Center for Strategic Studies at Bar-Ilan University. ``My theory is
that the peace process is very robust. There are great social
forces pushing all sides toward minimizing the conflicts. Everyone
is tired, and everyone knows he can't realize his dream. The idea
of a greater Israel is gone, the idea of a greater Palestine is
over, the idea of a pan-Arab nationalism is dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, I think everyone is very pragmatic. This
liberal notion of trust is pure nonsense. I imagine Barak's aiming
for an armed peace at best.''
</P>
<P>
   While Barak has said publicly that he plans to move forward
simultaneously on the Palestinian and Syrian tracks, there is a
question of pacing. It would be difficult to pursue both at the
same time with the same intensity.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have predicted that Syria, which represents more
of a military threat than the Palestinians, could take priority.
Barak has pledged to withdraw Israeli troops from southern Lebanon
within a year and he sees that in the context of a peace agreement
with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a certain neatness to making a deal with Syria that
has fascinated several Israeli leaders,'' said Itamar Rabinovich,
president of Tel Aviv University and a former diplomat who headed
Israel's delegation to Syria from 1992 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Syria is a state,'' he continued. ``It's always easier to deal
with a state than a society or community like the Palestinians.
Also, it has an authoritative government that may be hard to
negotiate with, but insures good implementation.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabinovich and other analysts say they believe that Syria has
been sending out signals of readiness just as Barak has indicated
that he is prepared to withdraw from most of the Golan Heights in
exchange for peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``A different type of music is coming out of Damascus,''
Rabinovich said. ``It is much more inviting, much more positive and
much more forthcoming.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Assad apparently regrets giving up the opportunity to negotiate
a peace deal in the early 1990s by taking too hard a line. He held
several secret talks with the Israelis during Netanyahu's
government _ through an intermediary, Ronald Lauder, the American
cosmetics businessman. Now he supposedly sees Barak's government as
a second window of opportunity, and one opening up at a time when
Syria's economy is failing and when he is considering passing the
reins of authority to his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``Syria is partner to the hope of Prime Minister Ehud Barak to
put an end to war,'' the Syrian Foreign Ministry said in a
statement last week.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is unclear how far Assad is willing to bend. To date,
he has been unwilling to make any public gestures to the Israeli
people that would send a message of reconciliation. He has been
unwilling to open discreet channels of communications that would
allow high-level Syrians and Americans, for instance, to take a
walk in the woods and establish the parameters of negotiations. And
he has been adamant that an Israeli promise to withdraw from the
Golan Heights is not something to negotiate but rather the
necessary prelude to dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, while formally Assad's position remains the same,
there have been signs that he is willing to be more flexible. The
Syrians have said, for instance, that the redeployment of the
Syrian army is a Syrian decision, which indicates that this is a
negotiable subject.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations with the Palestinians are likely to be far messier
and more complex. Barak committed what the Palestinians consider to
be a diplomatic faux-pas by waiting weeks after his election to
call Arafat, who is notoriously sensitive and given to such
formalities .
</P>
<P>
   Also, Barak has unnerved the Palestinians by suggesting that
they consider skipping over the final two phases of the Wye
agreement, which was negotiated early last fall in Wye, Md., and
suspended late last fall by the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Advisers to Barak have said that he will propose to Arafat that
the two sides go straight into expedited final status negotiations
and look broadly at all remaining issues. The final status
negotiations are supposed to conclude the peace process, resolving
the most sensitive issues, like Jerusalem, borders and refugees.
Israeli analysts have said that Barak might pledge future
recognition of a Palestinian state in exchange.
</P>
<P>
   If Arafat objects, though, Barak has said he will move forward
on the Wye agreement, and army officials are reportedly making
preparations for a handover of more land in the West Bank this
summer.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Palestinians view the idea of postponing the execution of
the Wye agreement with great trepidation, as a sign of
foot-dragging.
</P>
<P>
   ``We absolutely, totally and utterly reject even the idea, or
the mere thinking about it, and we urge Mr. Barak not even to
suggest if he means and intends to build trust,'' said Saeb Erekat,
the chief Palestinian negotiator.
</P>
<P>
   Erekat said the Palestinians were impatient and want to see
Barak take quick action. They expect a quick handover of land, a
return of Palestinian prisoners and a total change in atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to wait anymore,'' he said. ``We are tired of
waiting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
