<HEADER>
A5353 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAWYERS-CHARACTER-REV     07-10 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWYERS-CHARACTER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEYOND THE BAR EXAM: A QUESTION OF CHARACTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   To win admission to the bar in New York state, law school
graduates are asked to deny under oath that they have ever belonged
to any group ``advocating or teaching that the government of the
United States, or any state or any political subdivision thereof,
should be overthrown.''
</P>
<P>
   That question, with its echoes of McCarthyism, is part of a
character review that is as essential to becoming a lawyer in the
United States as passing the bar exam.
</P>
<P>
   The arcane character-and-fitness process, conducted in the
strictest secrecy, got some rare public attention after a series of
drive-by shootings last weekend in the Midwest that may have been
touched off by the denial on moral grounds of a law license to the
leader of a white supremacist group.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Nathaniel Smith, who killed himself last Sunday as the
police closed in on him, was a disciple of Matthew Hale, a white
supremacist whose appeal for a law license had been rejected by the
Illinois bar on July 2, just hours before Smith began his shooting
spree. Hale said that Smith might have taken the rejection as a
sign that the group's rights were being trampled upon.
</P>
<P>
   Court officials in several states said denials of law licenses
on ideological grounds were common in past decades, but are now
rare. Today, denials almost always involve financial problems, drug
or alcohol abuse, or conviction for several serious crimes. Child
support has become a major issue, and applicants in New York have
been turned down for being more than three months behind in their
payments.
</P>
<P>
   Other financial problems that can prevent admission to the bar
include unsatisfied judgments and failure to honor agreements to
pay off credit card debts. And applicants have been denied
admission if they lost time in school because of drug or alcohol
problems, but had not sought treatment, or had multiple convictions
for driving under the influence of drugs or alcohol. In some cases,
the officials said, applicants withdrew their requests for
admission when they realized the bar officials had obtained
information about their problems.
</P>
<P>
   Hale, who graduated from law school and passed the bar
examination, was rejected by the Illinois Bar Association's
Committee on Character and Fitness last December. The panel said
his racist activities demonstrated that he did not have the fitness
of character to qualify as a lawyer. He heads a white supremacist
group called The World Church of the Creator, advocates white
separatism, and has said he would prefer not to represent black
clients.
</P>
<P>
   In rejecting Hale last December, the panel said, ``History tells
us that extermination is sometimes not far behind when government
power is held by persons of his racial views.'' Hale has said he
plans to take the case to the U.S. Supreme Court, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Extreme cases like Hale's notwithstanding, some experts think
the moral standard for admission to the bar is not taken seriously
enough. Hale was among 25 rejections out of 3,200 applicants in
Illinois last year; in Manhattan and the Bronx, fewer than 10 out
of 2,600 applications were rejected. Nearly all the rejections
involved financial or substance-abuse problems, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Immoral character should not exclude only the Hales,'' said
Richard Zitrin, a San Francisco lawyer who is the co-author of
``The Moral Compass of the American Lawyer'' (Ballantine, 1999). He
said reviews of applicants are not tough enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``All kinds of people are flying below the moral-character radar
because too often that element of admission is a rubber stamp,''
Zitrin said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, James Cohen, the chairman of the legal education
committee of the Association of the Bar of the City of New York,
said the reviews have become largely proforma. He recalled the case
of a law student who had three felony drug convictions but was
admitted on the ground that he had demonstrated rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   In most states, Cohen said, reviewers know only what the
applicant reports about convictions, debts and other problems.
Lying on an application can lead to disbarment, but Cohen said it
is unlikely that fudgers will be caught. And he said anyone who has
negative information about an applicant is unlikely to intervene,
partly out of fear of being sued.
</P>
<P>
   Character and fitness checks, which vary in form and seriousness
from state to state, have their roots in the 12th century. They are
justified on the theory that the court must be able to rely on a
lawyer's word, and attorneys must be trusted with clients' money.
</P>
<P>
   But the standards have varied over the centuries, and critics
say the checks have been used in different eras to prevent members
of minority groups and suspected communists from practicing law.
Several law professors said reviewers should focus on a small list
of criminal offenses like embezzlement that might have a bearing on
the practice of law, and should stay away from free-speech issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old elephants harrumph and say the standards of the bar
are deteriorating and this is no time to yield,'' said Geoffrey
Hazard, a legal ethicist at the University of Pennsylvania. ``But
they are generating a ton of paperwork for very little
consequence.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the critics' complaints is that the standards are vague.
In New York, for instance, an applicant must demonstrate to a
committee run by the state Supreme Court that he or she ``possesses
the character and general fitness requisite for an attorney and
counselor-at-law.''
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Rhode, a law professor at Stanford University who has
studied character committees, said the criteria that exist are
applied with great inconsistency. She found, for instance, that a
committee in one part of a state had rejected applicants based on
parking and fishing offenses, while a committee in another part of
the same state had approved a convicted child molester.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their character flaws, lawyers in Manhattan, at least,
seem to be a patriotic bunch. Confronted with the question about
whether they had ever plotted to overthrow the government, not one
applicant in the last 10 years has answered, ``Yes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 1223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990710.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 12:23 </DATE_TIME>
