<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990710.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 12:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5357 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUGITIVE-FINANCIERS-R     07-10 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUGITIVE-FINANCIERS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE STYLES OF THE RICH AND FELONIOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By LESLIE EATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The duffel bag full of diamonds makes for a great plot twist, no
doubt about it. Also the ``to do'' list that began, ``Launder
money.'' All in all, the tale of Martin Frankel is already making a
most satisfying addition to the lore of that most modern of
outlaws, the fugitive inancier.
</P>
<P>
   There have been a surprising number of them in the last three
decades, with Robert Vesco being perhaps the most notorious. And
their stories serve as a reminder that even millions of dollars of
loot cannot buy happiness, at least when you're on the lam. A good
safe haven is hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel was a reclusive stock trader who operated from
Greenwich, Conn., where secretive money managers are thick on the
ground. But last year, while John Meriwether and the crew at
Long-Term Capital Management were legitimately losing billions of
dollars through complex trades and threatening the foundations of
the world financial system, prosecutors say Frankel was engaged in
a rather different economic activity: looting insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel disappeared in early May, shortly before firefighters in
Greenwich were called to one of his estates to douse a smoldering
filing cabinet. Investigators found, among other things, the ``to
do'' list, as well as astrological charts created to help answer
the question, ``Should I leave?''
</P>
<P>
   The stars must have been auspicious; Frankel has disappeared,
along with millions (perhaps billions) of dollars, according to
prosecutors and court documents. A diamond dealer has confirmed
that he sold Frankel $10 million worth of stones, and that
associates of the financier packed them up in two suitcases and a
duffel bag.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel is believed to be hiding in Europe now, but only after
having looked into countries elsewhere that have been safe havens
for other financial fraudsters.
</P>
<P>
   One was Brazil, where Ronald Biggs has become something of a
tourist attraction. Biggs helped pull off Britain's Great Train
Robbery in 1963, and escaped from prison in 1965; he surfaced in
South America in 1970, and has since managed to fend off all
efforts to extradite him (Brazil's excuse was that Biggs had
fathered a son there who would be hurt if his father was sent back
to face the music).
</P>
<P>
   Another spot Frankel studied, according to documents he left
behind, was Israel, which grants citizenship to almost any Jew who
chooses to immigrate (gangster Meyer Lansky was an exception).
</P>
<P>
   But Israeli citizenship did not help Eddie Antar, also known as
Crazy Eddie, whose chain of electronics stores collapsed in 1989.
He disappeared shortly thereafter, and prosecutors and lawyers for
the company's shareholders discovered that Antar had spirited
millions of dollars to Switzerland, Lichtenstein, England, Canada
and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Antar may indeed have been a little nuts; the U.S. marshals got
on to him after he demanded that Swiss police help him get access
to a frozen bank account. He had apparently been living the high
life on several continents under several names but was based in
Israel, where he was arrested in 1992; he was sent back to the
United States, where he ultimately pleaded guilty to racketeering.
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland may be the best haven of all, depending on what you
are charged with. Tax evasion is not cause for extradition there,
which is why Marc Rich is flourishing in the Alpine town of Zug. A
commodities trader accused of tax cheating, he fled to Switzerland
in 1984, and until 1994 ran an extremely successful trading
operation.
</P>
<P>
   For foreign-born swindlers, the United States appears to be a
popular destination. The Irish Times recently reported on the case
of Finbarr Ross, whose financial empire collapsed in 1984 owing
investors millions of pounds. He was arrested last year in
Oklahoma, where he had become an ordained minister at the Light of
Christ Church in the small town of Talequah.
</P>
<P>
   Caribbean islands may seem alluring, but they do not always work
out. In the 1980s, J. David Dominelli convinced San Diego's high
society that he was a crackerjack currency trader who would make
them millions. He wasn't and he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   When his scheme collapsed, he fled to Montserrat, a British
colony where he had set up a bank. Maybe he shouldn't have held
that news conference; in any event, he was booted out and sent back
to Miami, where he was arrested. He was sentenced to 20 years for
fraud and tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping a low profile can be hard for truly proficient
fraudsters. David Friedland, a former New Jersey state senator,
faked his death by staging a scuba-diving accident in the Bahamas
in 1985. Soon he was indicted for stealing $20 million from a union
pension fund.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, he turned up in the Maldive Islands in the
Indian Ocean, which is pretty much as far from everything as a
fugitive can get. But his flashy style and success as a businessman
(he had a chain of scuba shops) had attracted too much attention,
federal marshals said after they arrested him in 1987. They added
that he had posed for a photo used on a tourism postcard, which may
not have been a great move, stealth-wise.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to fugitive financiers, nobody beats Vesco,
who could have been dreamed up by Graham Greene (or Ian Fleming).
To avoid charges that he had stolen more than $200 million from a
European mutual fund, Vesco fled in 1972 to Costa Rica, which at
the time was a haven for the legally challenged.
</P>
<P>
   Buying influence seems to have been part of his modus operandi;
in addition to contributing to Costa Rican officials, he made an
illegal $200,000 campaign contribution to Richard Nixon. He was
also indicted in the United States in 1989 on charges of organizing
drug smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   One problem with buying governments, however, is that they do
not always stay bought. In the late 1970s, Vesco was forced to move
to the Bahamas, and then, in the 1980s, to Cuba. He appeared to
live under the protection of Fidel Castro, and maintained the usual
trappings of a successful financial fugitive: houses, cars, planes,
yachts and flunkies.
</P>
<P>
   But three years ago, Cuba charged Vesco with fraud in connection
with a company that was supposed to be developing a cure for
cancer. He was convicted and, when last heard of, was serving a
13-year sentence in a Cuban prison.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear exactly what ran out, Vesco's money or his luck
(or Castro's patience). But at least it narrows the search for the
latest fugitive financier: Frankel probably has no plans to move to
Havana.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 1234EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990710.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 12:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0030 &Cx1f; var-z
