to Miami, where he was arrested. He was sentenced to 20 years for
fraud and tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping a low profile can be hard for truly proficient
fraudsters. David Friedland, a former New Jersey state senator,
faked his death by staging a scuba-diving accident in the Bahamas
in 1985. Soon he was indicted for stealing $20 million from a union
pension fund.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, he turned up in the Maldive Islands in the
Indian Ocean, which is pretty much as far from everything as a
fugitive can get. But his flashy style and success as a businessman
(he had a chain of scuba shops) had attracted too much attention,
federal marshals said after they arrested him in 1987. They added
that he had posed for a photo used on a tourism postcard, which may
not have been a great move, stealth-wise.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to fugitive financiers, nobody beats Vesco,
who could have been dreamed up by Graham Greene (or Ian Fleming).
To avoid charges that he had stolen more than $200 million from a
European mutual fund, Vesco fled in 1972 to Costa Rica, which at
the time was a haven for the legally challenged.
</P>
<P>
   Buying influence seems to have been part of his modus operandi;
in addition to contributing to Costa Rican officials, he made an
illegal $200,000 campaign contribution to Richard Nixon. He was
also indicted in the United States in 1989 on charges of organizing
drug smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   One problem with buying governments, however, is that they do
not always stay bought. In the late 1970s, Vesco was forced to move
to the Bahamas, and then, in the 1980s, to Cuba. He appeared to
live under the protection of Fidel Castro, and maintained the usual
trappings of a successful financial fugitive: houses, cars, planes,
yachts and flunkies.
</P>
<P>
   But three years ago, Cuba charged Vesco with fraud in connection
with a company that was supposed to be developing a cure for
cancer. He was convicted and, when last heard of, was serving a
13-year sentence in a Cuban prison.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear exactly what ran out, Vesco's money or his luck
(or Castro's patience). But at least it narrows the search for the
latest fugitive financier: Frankel probably has no plans to move to
Havana.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
