<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5363 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELDERLY-DRUGS-ART-530     07-10 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELDERLY-DRUGS-ART-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ELDERLY, PILLS ARE BLESSING AND CURSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By SARA RIMER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Talking over lunch last week in the dining room
of the American Postal Workers House, a federally subsidized
residence for the elderly, 87-year-old Leah Greenstein pulled from
her purse a well-worn card on which she keeps a list of her
medications.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take Synthroid _ that's for my thyroid _ I take two of
them,'' she said, reading from the list. ``Prinvil _ that's for
high blood pressure _ two a day. Ecotrin _ that's coated aspirin;
it doesn't affect the stomach _ to prevent a heart attack or
stroke. Prilosec _ that's for digestion. Vioxx _ I just started
that a few weeks ago. That's the newest drug for arthritis.''
</P>
<P>
   In all, Mrs. Greenstein, whose ailments include high blood
pressure and colitis, takes 12 prescription medicines daily.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has put the cost of prescription drugs at the
center of discussions in Congress on Medicare, but for millions of
older people like Mrs. Greenstein, their multiple medications
always seem to be part of the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   As people live longer and acquire more chronic ailments, the
pharmaceutical industry has supplied an endless stream of remedies,
and paying for prescriptions and keeping all the pills straight is
a daily concern.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Greenstein considers herself lucky. She qualifies for a
Pennsylvania program for low-income elderly under which she pays
just $6 a month for each prescription (still, times 12, that's a
chunk of her monthly Social Security check of $712). If she had to
pay for the drugs herself, an official with the program estimated,
they would cost $600 to $700 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pain in the neck,'' said Mrs. Greenstein, who manages
her medication with the efficiency of the bookkeeper she was for
many years. ``Sometimes I say to my doctor, `Why do I need all
these drugs?' He'll take me off one, and add two more.''
</P>
<P>
   Medicare, the federal health insurance program for the elderly
and disabled, does not include prescription drugs, and with the
availability of new drugs to treat the ills of old age, along with
the high cost of much of that medication, many old people who do
not receive state aid are struggling to pay the bill. Clinton has
proposed adding a drug insurance plan to Medicare under which
premiums would be waived for low-income people.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 13 states that provide some form of prescription-drug
coverage for the poor elderly, Pennsylvania has one of the most
generous, said Thomas Snedden, the program's director. The program,
financed by the state lottery, pays $250 million on prescriptions a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, with strict income limits, it covers only a fraction of
the state's elderly. With an annual Social Security income of
$17,000, Alice Wiley, a 75-year-old retired seamstress in West
Philadelphia, earns too much to qualify. Mrs. Wiley, who had a
recurrence of breast cancer, has recently started taking Tamoxifen,
two pills a day, at $3 a pill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just going to do without it,'' Mrs. Wiley said. ``I
can't afford it. My son paid for it.''
</P>
<P>
   To Mrs. Wiley, each pill is precious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sit right down to the table with that pill and hold it real
fast,'' she said. ``You don't drop that pill.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mrs. Wiley is also on high blood pressure medication, which she
says costs $6 for 24 pills.
</P>
<P>
   At the Jacob and Esther Stiffel Senior Center in South
Philadelphia, Thursday was a belated Fourth of July party. Men and
women in their 70s and 80s sang and danced to the music of a live
band. Between sets, many of them talked about the medications that
they say keep them well enough for them to continue showing up at
the center that sustains them.
</P>
<P>
   Like Leah Greenstein, many of the women carried handwritten
medication lists in their purses.
</P>
<P>
   Esther Welsh, 77, who has diabetes and recently underwent
surgery for breast cancer, has 10 different drugs on her list,
including Tamoxifen, Synthroid and Diovan, which she takes for high
blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Welsh and her husband, David, who are retired tile
contractors living on a fixed income, are enrolled in an HMO that
allows them to pay $15 for each brand-name prescription, and $10
for the generic ones. Even so, with monthly prescription-drug bills
of about $150, they say they have had to stop going out to dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most important part of our lives,'' Welsh said,
pointing to the white piece of paper that listed his wife's drugs.
``It keeps her alive.''
</P>
<P>
   When Zelda Somers was younger, her passport, with stamps from
all over South America, Spain and other European countries, marked
her as a world traveler. Now, at 82, Mrs. Somers, who recently
suffered a heart aneurysm, does not venture much beyond home, the
senior center and the doctor's office.
</P>
<P>
   And these days she carries a ``medication passport,'' a small
brown booklet, distributed by the Pennsylvania Department of Aging,
in which she keeps meticulous track of the eight drugs her doctor
has prescribed.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Somers, who ran a food market with her late husband, is
well acquainted with her pharmacist.
</P>
<P>
   ``One time the doctor forgot to tell me that when he put me on a
new drug I should stop taking another one,'' Mrs. Somers said. ``My
pharmacist told me, `Zelda, when you take this, you can't take
that.'''
</P>
<P>
   For Bea and Sam, a couple in their 80s who declined to give
their last name, taking prescription drugs has become a ritual of
married life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get two little medicine cups,'' said Bea, a former
secretary. ``He gets five pills. I give them to him every
morning.''
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to get confused about who is taking what, and how
much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take Inderal,'' said Sam, who used to work at the Navy Yard
here.
</P>
<P>
   Bea broke in. ``No, you're not on Inderal,'' she said. ``I'm on
Inderal. We both take Prilosec. That's marvelous. It keeps the acid
from forming in the stomach.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same table, 83-year-old Bessie Schwartz, who takes heart
medication and Prilosec, said, ``This is what keeps us alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Schwartz, who earned her living making lampshades, has had
two heart attacks. She said her mother did not have the benefit of
modern medicine and prescription drugs. She had high blood
pressure, and died of a stroke in 1932. She was 51.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 1250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
