603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even before NATO's bombs stopped falling in
Yugoslavia, the Pentagon's war planners and like-minded lawmakers
on Capitol Hill started asking a question that would have seemed
unthinkable not long ago: Is America's military too small?
</P>
<P>
   In the decade since the Soviet bloc fell apart, the nation's
four major armed services have steadily shrunk, both in size and
weaponry. In 1989 there were 2.13 million men and women on active
duty in the Army, Navy, Air Force and Marines. In 1999 there are
1.36 million, a 36 percent drop.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, though, the number of peacekeeping missions,
relief efforts and other military operations has proliferated _
from the Persian Gulf to the Caribbean, from Bosnia to Kosovo.
Eight years after Saddam Hussein was evicted from Kuwait, the
United States and Britain still patrol over much of Iraq from bases
in the Persian Gulf and Turkey. And since last December, U.S.
pilots have been skirmishing with Iraq's air defenses every few
days.
</P>
<P>
   From missile shots against Islamic terrorist Osama Bin Laden to
drug interdiction in Latin America, the Pentagon's commanders say
the U.S. military today is as consumed with what they call
``operations other than war'' as a much larger force was with
fighting Cold War proxy battles and preparing to stop a Soviet
invasion of Western Europe. The new assignments, they complain, are
straining the downsized military, perhaps to the breaking point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a situation where we have a smaller force and we have
more missions,'' Defense Secretary William Cohen told the Senate's
defense appropriations subcommittee in May. ``We are wearing out
systems. We are wearing out people.''
</P>
<P>
   Such assertions seem to guarantee a renewed debate about just
how large a military the United States needs _ particularly since
the questions have arisen just as the Clinton administration and
Congress are eyeing enormous budget surpluses and considering the
first increases in the defense budget since the early years of
Ronald Reagan's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Although the increases proposed so far have been earmarked for
new weapons, repairs and training, they have also opened the
possibility of expanding personnel, which is by far the most costly
item in the budget because it involves salaries, pensions and
benefits. And that, to some, is no coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the services are positioning themselves for the fight
for their part of the budget surpluses,'' said Steven Kosiak,
director of budget studies at the Center for Strategic and
Budgetary Assessments in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's 78-day air war against Yugoslavia was a resounding
victory for the U.S. military. But the war also exposed weaknesses.
At the height of the bombing, the United States had more than 800
aircraft and 37,500 people committed to the fight. The Air Force,
in particular, was strained, with 40 to 45 percent of its entire
force somehow involved _ a higher percentage than was devoted to
war in either Vietnam or the Persian Gulf, according to a senior
officer. In certain areas, the strain was even greater.
Three-quarters of the force's aerial tanker crews, for example,
were used in the air war.
</P>
<P>
   The effort forced the Pentagon to scale back operations
elsewhere, raising questions about the nation's ability to fight
two major regional wars at once, a core tenet of the military's
strategic planning.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, pulled out aircraft
patrolling northern Iraq from a base in Turkey to devote them to
pummeling Yugoslavia. (When the United States launched air strikes
against Iraq last December, three months before the Kosovo war,
aircraft were diverted from hurricane relief in Central America.)
</P>
<P>
   Now that NATO's war is won, the problem has not eased, but
simply shifted to the ground. The Army is sending 7,000 soldiers to
keep the peace in Kosovo, most of them from Germany, with no
prospect of leaving soon. There are 7,700 troops in support or
refugee-relief roles in Albania and Macedonia. Nearly four years
after the civil war ended in Bosnia, there are still 6,000 soldiers
deployed there. The U.S. presence in South Korea _ now at 37,000
soldiers _ is nearing its 50th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   This commitment to ever more scattered operations overseas is
perhaps an inevitable manifestation of America's global
pre-eminence, and that sense of permanence is behind the calls for
a reversal of the military's steady downsizing.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Charles Krulak, who recently retired as commandant of the
Marine Corps, said his service needs 5,000 more marines, which
would raise the total to 177,000. The Army's new chief of staff,
Gen. Eric Shinseki, said rethinking the size of the Army _ now at
467,000 soldiers _ was his first priority. Privately, Army
officials say 500,000 would be better.
</P>
<P>
   With the military already facing problems recruiting young
Americans, it is not clear how that could be accomplished. But on
Capitol Hill, lawmakers have heartily endorsed the idea _ and not
just Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to add enough personnel to the force to meet the
demands of the post-Cold War world without wearing out so many of
the wonderful men and women on whom our security depends,'' said
Rep. Ike Skelton of Missouri, the ranking Democrat on the House
Armed Services Committee, in a floor speech July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Other lawmakers agree the military is strained, but say the
solution is to scale back its operations. They cite the 270
soldiers still deployed in Haiti and the 870 serving in a
multinational observer force on the Sinai Peninsula that has
monitored the Israel-Egypt peace since 1982. Republicans would like
to see the U.S. troops leave Bosnia, even though peace there is
tenuous.
</P>
<P>
   Many military analysts, however, say that the problem may not be
as serious as military officers paint it, and that solving it may
not require more troops. These critics say the size of the force
does not matter as much as how well the force is managed.
</P>
<P>
   In the world today, only China has a larger military, with an
estimated 2.5 million troops but nothing like the technological
prowess of the United States. Russia has just over one million men
and women in arms, but they are demoralized, underequipped and
underpaid (when paid at all).
</P>
<P>
   Kosiak said the U.S. military was still arrayed very much like
it was during the Cold War, when hundreds of thousands of troops
hunkered down in Europe and waited for World War III.
</P>
<P>
   The services, especially the Army, have been slow to adapt to
the increase in smaller-scale operations, he said. The military
does not need more troops, he added; it needs to streamline its
bureaucracy so it can better employ the ones it has.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are operations,'' Kosiak said of today's missions,
``that a military as large as the United States military should be
able to carry out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
