<DOCNO> NYT19990710.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 12:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5368 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.N.-AID-CUTS-NYT &LR;      07-10 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-AID-CUTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. POVERTY AGENCY VYING WITH AID OFFICES FOR CASH 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JUDITH MILLER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Mark Malloch Brown, the new chief of the U.N.
Development Program, had barely moved into his spacious office with
its panoramic views of the East River and the United Nations when
he got some bad news. Denmark and Germany, mainstays of his
agency's $2 billion dollar budget, were slashing their annual
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The German Cabinet, citing its obligation to limit its budget
deficit under Europe's single-currency agreement, announced that it
was cutting its contribution to the world body's main foreign aid
arm by 50 percent, or $25 million. Denmark, too, announced a 23
percent cut to finance a pledge it had made to rebuild Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Kosovo crisis has intensified the already fierce
competition for dollars among relief and development agencies and
makes it all the more likely that the search for funds will consume
much of Malloch Brown's tenure.
</P>
<P>
   The decline in contributions, which are voluntary rather than
mandatory like U.N. dues, are not limited to Denmark and Germany.
America's portion of the budget has been dropping, too.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent issue of the journal Foreign Affairs, James Gustave
Speth, an American who headed the agency for six years before
Malloch Brown took over on July 1, called Washington's donations
``particularly stingy.'' While Nordic countries contributed about
$16 per capita to the agency, Speth complained in a recent
interview, America's per capita contribution stood at 50 cents.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing his country's reduction, Poul Nielsen, Denmark's
development minister, who had been Europe's candidate for the job
of leading the agency, denied that the cut was what a Danish
journalist called a ``devious'' act of ``revenge'' for not having
won the post.
</P>
<P>
   While Malloch Brown declined to discuss Denmark's motives in an
interview last week, he expressed his ``alarm'' that a country with
such a long history of generous giving to the world's poor would
``tax Africa to fund Kosovo.'' Denmark, he added, underscoring his
concern, risked setting ``a dangerous trend'' that he hoped other
donors would not follow.
</P>
<P>
   As for Germany, the new administrator, as the agency's chief is
known, vowed to ``fight'' the Cabinet's decision through friends in
the German government and, if necessary, reverse the planned cuts
in parliament, which is expected to consider the issue this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Malloch Brown framed the challenge to get more money for his
agency as primarily one of marketing. Employing the free-market
jargon so fashionable in the development community these days,
Malloch Brown stressed the need to promote his agency's
``comparative advantage'' in advancing development through ``good
governance.''
</P>
<P>
   Projects that foster democratic, honest, responsible government,
the rule of law, competent, unbiased judicial systems and
commercial codes, private organizations and partnerships between
government agencies and commercial and nonprofit partners made aid
dollars go further, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Malloch Brown, who was previously vice president for external
affairs at the World Bank, said he intends to use his communication
skills to enhance his agency's reputation and promote its
credibility.
</P>
<P>
   While he praised his predecessor, Speth, who is now the dean of
Yale University's School of Forestry and Environmental Studies,
Malloch Brown's emphasis on giving the agency a higher profile
seemed to imply that Speth had been less than successful in this
regard.
</P>
<P>
   The Development Program has almost 6,000 employees in 130
offices throughout the world and disperses more than $1 billion of
its $2.4 billion budget to help fight poverty and underdevelopment.
Recently, Malloch Brown gave his far-flung team a pep talk,
delivered via audio and video-conferencing. He warned the staff
that to continue being a ``relevant'' player in development, the
agency had to ``reinvent'' itself.
</P>
<P>
   Articulate, energetic and experienced in relief work, the
46-year-old British national was a popular choice among U.S.
officials and many relief workers, who felt that Speth had placed
too little emphasis on integrating emergency assistance into
long-term development aid.
</P>
<P>
   But Europeans, increasingly resentful of the United States for
failing to pay the $1.6 billion in back dues it owes the United
Nations, had campaigned intensively for their candidate, Nielsen,
to lead the agency, and Secretary-General Kofi Annan's selection of
Malloch Brown, a long-time associate, caused a diplomatic stir.
</P>
<P>
   Malloch Brown's World Bank background is the source of another
concern. Some fear that the bank, which lends $22 billion of
development aid a year, may come to dominate the agency's
activities.
</P>
<P>
   Malloch Brown vowed that he would not permit the World Bank to
``swamp'' his agency. But, he added, it was an ``open secret'' that
he expected to be judged partly ``by my relationship with the World
Bank.'' He urged development proponents not to think of the
relationship as a rivalry for clout, but rather as an ``opportunity
for partnership.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 1254EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
