<DOCNO> NYT19990710.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 13:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5373 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-PAST-ABUSES-NY     07-10 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-PAST-ABUSES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABUSES OF FORMER MILITARY RULERS IS HAUNTING BRAZIL TODAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By LARRY ROHTER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ Nearly a decade and a half of democracy
have erased the abuses of military rule from the memory of most
Brazilians. But two cases dating from that unpleasant 21-year
period have suddenly been thrust into the national spotlight,
creating embarrassment and discomfort for the current civilian
government, which had no involvement in the original events.
</P>
<P>
   The more ticklish and emblematic of the pair is the formal
reopening of the so-called Riocentro case, named for an arena where
on April 30, 1981, some 20,000 supporters of left-wing causes had
gathered for a concert. Minutes before the show was to begin, two
bombs exploded in the parking lot, killing an army sergeant and
severely wounding a captain.
</P>
<P>
   Contradicting news reports that named the two soldiers as the
perpetrators, a military investigation eventually concluded that
the men, who worked for the army's political intelligence division,
had been victims of a plot by left-wing terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Now prosecutors say that original inquiry was ``an absurd
fantasy'' marred by ``innumerable contradictions,'' and have vowed
to discover and try those who ordered and covered up the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``The farce of the Riocentro military inquiry has been a bone
long stuck in the throat of the national citizenry,'' Nilmario
Miranda, a left-wing congressman, said in welcoming the move. ``The
decision to reopen the case is an act of justice and respect for
the historical truth.''
</P>
<P>
   The belated investigation comes fast on the heels of another
controversy, over the nomination of Joao Batista Campelo as the new
chief of the federal police. No sooner had Campelo been named
Brazil's top law enforcement official than a Roman Catholic priest
came forward to say that he had been tortured in 1970 during
interrogations Campelo supervised.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the accusations, President Fernando Henrique Cardoso
stuck by the choice, and in five hours of dramatic televised
testimony in mid-June, Campelo denied the accusation, declaring,
``I have never seen an instrument of torture in the police stations
where I worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, reporters uncovered documentary evidence that supported
the priest's account. Campelo stepped down, apologizing for ``the
serious political situation'' he had created.
</P>
<P>
   As in the reluctant defense of Gen. Augusto Pinochet by Chile's
civilian government, the re-emergence of such issues here years
after the military left power indicates that ``the scourge of the
past doesn't go away,'' but can ``come back to haunt you'' in
unexpected ways, said Richard Millett, an American expert on the
Latin American military.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has found a good way to dispose of these skeletons in
the closet because there probably isn't one,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   A few of Campelo's more hard-line supporters, however, have
drawn a different conclusion. ``That's what happens when you
torture but don't kill,'' said Jair Bolsonaro, a retired military
officer here who is now a member of Congress, representing a
right-wing party.
</P>
<P>
   Cardoso rebounded quickly from the Campelo debacle, replacing
him with an officer who had also served in the secret police during
the military dictatorship but has the political advantage of being
the first black to be named Brazil's top police official.
</P>
<P>
   It will be more difficult, political analysts predicted, for the
president to find a palatable solution to the revived Riocentro
case.
</P>
<P>
   A former professor of sociology, Cardoso, like many other
intellectuals then on the left, was himself persecuted by the
military during the years of dictatorship, which lasted from 1964
to 1985, and went into exile for several years. But his father was
an army general who is still admired by the nationalist wing of the
armed forces, and during his five years in office, the president
has cultivated better ties with the military while simultaneously
reducing its power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing the government wants to do is get involved
seriously with this and destabilize things,'' said Alexandre
Barros, a political consultant in Brasilia. With the armed forces
having recently been deprived of Cabinet rank, their wages and
pensions frozen and a civilian minister of defense imposed on them,
Cardoso would prefer to ``circumvent or isolate this issue so that
it doesn't do greater damage,'' Barros said.
</P>
<P>
   But Gen. Newton Cruz, the retired former director of Brazil's
National Intelligence Service, has told reporters that he was
notified in advance of the planning of the attack and knows who
ordered it. He has also said he will refuse to divulge any
information if he is called to testify in a court or at public
hearings that the Brazilian Congress may hold, an act of defiance
that could lead to an institutional showdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hearings may clarify things, but whether anyone will be
punished is another question,'' said David Fleischer, publisher of
a political newsletter and a professor of political science at the
National University of Brasilia. ``There will probably be a general
catharsis and clarification, but it is doubtful that those who
perpetrated it will be identified or punished.''
</P>
<P>
   Military prosecutors who are involved in the new investigation
argue that neither the statute of limitations nor a 1988 political
amnesty apply to the Riocentro case. That has led to speculation
that at least the wounded captain, who is now a colonel still on
active duty, may be charged _ or offered as a sacrificial lamb to
appease civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an institution, the armed forces are trying to redefine
their role in society,'' Barros pointed out. ``All the generals who
were involved in this are probably either retired or dead, so what
you have is a younger generation of officers who want to get rid of
this stain and reposition themselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
