<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5399 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IOWA-STRAWPOLL-NYT &LR;      07-10 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-STRAWPOLL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR GOP CONTENDERS, STRAW POLL LOOMS LARGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Six years ago, when he first started running
for President, Lamar Alexander never figured the biggest test he
would face in his grinding quest would be a straw poll. But it has
come down to that for the former Tennessee governor, as well as for
half a dozen other hopefuls seeking the Republican nomination in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   As Alexander put it, when 10,000 Iowa Republicans gather in Ames
next month for the party's traditional presidential straw poll, on
Aug. 14, the results will add up to more than ``just another straw
in the wind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The stakes are higher now than before,'' he said last week.
``All the money and media and hype going into this campaign have
changed and speeded things up. This time Ames will show the nation
who's ready. It's the big political event of 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   It has not always been like that. For years, Iowa's
first-in-the-nation February caucuses were the start of the
candidate winnowing process. But now the Iowa straw poll looms as
the starting point, even if at heart it is nothing but an
unscientific beauty contest that elects not a single convention
delegate.
</P>
<P>
   Never in its 20-year history has the poll been accorded such
importance. It has been considered a good tool for building
election enthusiasm but never a tool for seriously measuring
candidate readiness. And like all presidential straw polls, it has
no great history of predicting winners, no great surprise for a
poll typically won by the candidate who can bus in the most
supporters, pay their $25 entrance fees, then wine, dine and
entertain them sumptuously and say not a word if some get carried
away and try to vote twice.
</P>
<P>
   Two developments have speeded up the winnowing dynamic. First,
there is the huge early lead that Gov. George W. Bush of Texas has
taken in national polls and in raising money. Add to that the
``front loading'' of next year's caucus and primary schedule, to
the point that the nominating process will almost be over before it
begins.
</P>
<P>
   This confluence of front running and front loading has left many
candidates, among them Alexander, scrambling desperately almost
from Day 1 to find the money and traction needed to rise above
single digits in the polls. Many currently trail the governor by a
daunting 35 points or more and, as a result, are already on the
ropes.
</P>
<P>
   As many political professionals and pundits see it, a big Bush
victory in Ames would effectively eliminate maybe half of the field
of 12 Republican candidates and would considerably lengthen the
odds for those left standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming out of Ames this time, it's a good bet that only the
top three finishers and the candidates who greatly exceed
expectations will have the means and realistic reason to
continue,'' said Dee Stewart, the executive director of the
Republican Party of Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Bush, the candidates most often mentioned as having a
good shot at finishing in the top tier are Steve Forbes, the
multimillionaire publisher, and Elizabeth Dole, the former Red
Cross president and wife of Bob Dole, the 1996 Republican nominee.
In the second tier are Alexander, former Vice President Dan Quayle,
Pat Buchanan, the commentator, and Gary Bauer, a family-values
advocate. The last tier includes Rep. John Kasich of Ohio, Alan
Keyes, the broadcaster, and Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain of Arizona, the 12th candidate in the
Republican field, says he will not compete in the Ames poll.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that he has been campaigning almost nonstop in Iowa
for six years, Alexander appears to have one of the best campaign
organizations in the state. He managed to finish fourth at Ames in
1995, but was out of the race by early March 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to exceed expectations,'' he said as he set off on a
23-day, 60-county tour of the state in a bus named ``Exceeding
Expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, who finished third at Ames in 1995, sees Ames 1999 in
starker terms. He, too, is struggling mightily for traction now,
like most hard-right and Christian conservatives in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Grim Reaper is going to be waiting outside the gates of
the Ames fieldhouse,'' he said while campaigning in Des Moines last
week. ``About five or six of those fellas may never survive. Women,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Bush is taking Ames seriously. Since he jumped into
the race last month, he has by all accounts put a big,
smooth-running campaign organization in place in the state. Topping
that off, on Wednesday he paid a whopping $43,500 to get prime
space outside the Ames fieldhouse for entertaining and feeding his
supporters _ roughly 10 times what most candidates paid.
</P>
<P>
   He has drawn criticism and raised eyebrows, however, for thus
far making only one Iowa visit and for scheduling only five
additional days of campaigning between now and Aug. 14. He may lead
his nearest rivals, Mrs. Dole and Forbes, by better than 3-to-1 in
statewide polls, surely a comfortable edge, but that edge does not
automatically translate to a 3-to-1 lead in a straw poll.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Forbes, like Alexander, plans to spend the better
part of three weeks campaigning in Iowa between now and Aug. 14. He
predicts that he will make a ``respectable showing'' in Ames, but
he insists that however he fares and whatever conclusions people
draw about the results, he will stay in the race _ with the money
to compete _ until the final nominating vote next summer in
Philadelphia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 1316EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990710.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5401 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-10 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: CONFRONTING POVERTY IN AMERICA: IF NOT NOW, WHEN? 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BOB HERBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Bill Clinton's mood was upbeat. The appearance
with Gov. Gray Davis and Magic Johnson at the high school in Watts
had gone well. Now he adjusted his long legs in the back seat of
the limousine and began answering questions about his effort to
draw private investors to some of the poorest regions of America.
</P>
<P>
   The president contends that there are ``new markets'' to be
tapped, and therefore ``money to be made,'' in such chronically
distressed areas as Appalachia, the Mississippi Delta, the vast
Pine Ridge Indian Reservation in South Dakota and inner-city
neighborhoods like Watts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not like either the Great Society of the '60s or the
great neglect of the '80s,'' said Clinton. ``This is about getting
good jobs into the inner cities and rural areas by building an
economic infrastructure that is part of the private economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will send legislation to Congress this week that calls
for $1.6 billion in federal tax credits and loan guarantees that
are designed to stimulate $15 billion in private investments over
five years.
</P>
<P>
   There are skeptics, especially among those who think Clinton
should have done more for the poor during his first six years in
office. Without question, he should have. And this is a modest
effort at a time when the nation could afford a much grander
assault on poverty.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's proposal is, at least, a start. And if even this
modest effort fails to win approval at a time when the nation is
experiencing its greatest prosperity ever, it would mean that we
truly care nothing at all about the poor among us.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional approval is not a lock. With the nation enjoying a
spectacular budget surplus, the Republican Party is looking lustily
at another big tax cut. It is not much interested in initiatives
that might bring struggling Americans into the economic mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   The president scoffed at the GOP tax-cut plans, saying, ``If you
pay for their tax cut and their defense proposals, it would restore
the deficit and dramatically cut our investments in the areas of
education and health care and the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``It would be a terrible mistake to walk away from our
education obligations, and it would be, I think, very dumb to
restore the deficit if we can avoid it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then a grin crossed his face. ``You know,'' he said, ``the
Republicans have made a lot of money out of our economic policy.
That's one of the reasons they can afford to finance their
campaigns so generously. They've done well.''
</P>
<P>
   Without mentioning George W. Bush by name, the president said it
was as if the Republicans had decided, ``OK, you've made us a lot
of money. Now we want to be in power again, and change the economic
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   His grin broadened. ``Keep in mind,'' he said, ``I'm for a tax
cut, too. I just think it ought to be affordable.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit to Los Angeles came at the end of a four-day
tour of impoverished regions across the nation. In some cases he
visited people experiencing gruesome levels of distress, including
a woman at the Pine Ridge Reservation who lived with 28 others in a
five-bedroom dwelling.
</P>
<P>
   These are the glory days of our prosperity. If now is not the
right time to offer help to those who are really hurting, to
Americans who live in shacks and caves, and with barely enough food
to survive, then when?
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the interview with Clinton, I asked if he and the
first lady are committed to living in New York even if she loses
her bid for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   He referred to a conversation they had in 1993, when he said to
Mrs. Clinton, ``Ever since you came to Arkansas in 1973, we've
lived where my work dictated, and where I wanted to live.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he told her that at the end of his presidency he would
have to spend a lot of time in Arkansas establishing his
presidential library and center. ``But I said, `I will live
wherever else you want to live.' And she had told me years ago that
she wanted to go to New York. And I said, `That's fine with me. I
love New York. I'll be happy to live there.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So I'm going to divide my time between New York and Arkansas,
no matter what happens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 1327EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
