<DOCNO> NYT19990710.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5407 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAA-AIRTOUR-SAFETY-AR     07-10 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAA-AIRTOUR-SAFETY-ART-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAA MISSES DEADLINE IN SETTING RULES FOR AIR TOURS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Hawaii, Md., Fla., Calif., Alaska)  (Exclusive) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ever since the collision of two aircraft filled
with tourists in the Grand Canyon 13 years ago, safety officials
have urged the Federal Aviation Administration to step up its
oversight of air tours. After a spate of air-tour accidents in
Hawaii, the FAA promised in 1995 to write new national rules by the
end of 1997, calling it ``a high priority.''
</P>
<P>
   But it has not happened yet, and around the United States this
summer, hundreds of tour operators _ no one knows just how many _
are carrying tens of thousands of tourists under the old, loose
requirements. And though the data are so sketchy that nobody knows
the odds, statistically speaking, these tourists appear to be
holding some of the riskiest air tickets money can buy.
</P>
<P>
   As long as they do not fly more than 25 miles from where they
take off and land, tour operators are exempt from many rules. For
example, they do not have to limit their pilots to eight hours of
flying a day, and during the intense summer season, some fly
longer. Their pilots do not have to pass an annual flight check, or
a quiz conducted in flight or in a simulator. The planes need not
carry a maintenance log on board.
</P>
<P>
   After the accidents in Hawaii, the FAA issued special temporary
rules for the Grand Canyon and Hawaii, cutting accidents there
sharply, but nationally accidents have stayed at about 10 a year,
and the government is struggling to decide what it wants to require
in the rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just frustrating,'' said Barry Sweedler, director of the
National Transportation Safety Board's office of recommendations,
which has repeatedly called for changes. ``This is a situation
where everybody agrees that this is a good thing to do, and we are
now three and a half years since the board had asked the FAA to
have this completed.''
</P>
<P>
   A report by the inspector general of the Transportation
Department concluded in May that the new rule ``has been delayed
too long and should be moved forward quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   The FAA began writing special regulations for air tours after a
collision on June 18, 1986, between a helicopter and a twin-engine
plane in the Grand Canyon, which killed 25 people and left wreckage
on the canyon wall. The rule established traffic patterns and
barred planes from the canyon itself.
</P>
<P>
   Helicopter accidents in Hawaii killed 23 people from 1989 to
1994.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Grand Canyon and Hawaii, from April 1995 to June
1998, the inspector general's report counted 31 accidents resulting
in 25 deaths and 52 injuries, and policy-makers are confident that
they can cut those numbers sharply with better regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Better regulations will not prevent all crashes, but experts
point to several crashes that new rules could have made less
likely.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the pilot of a single-engine Waco died, along with
two passengers who had bought tickets for a 15-minute flight on
Aug. 24, 1997, near Ocean City, Md.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot, who was qualified as an airline pilot and a flight
instructor, radioed to the plane owner that he had ``two female
passengers on board who wanted a thrill,'' according to the
safety-board report. But he was apparently overconfident; witnesses
said he was trying to do a loop and lost control at a low altitude.
At the higher altitude required under stricter rules, he might have
recovered, according to the inspector general's office.
</P>
<P>
   Two people died and one was seriously injured when a Bell
helicopter came apart in flight in Marathon, Fla., in April 1994.
Maintenance personnel had botched a previous repair and had skipped
a required inspection.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nelligan, a spokesman for the inspector general, said the
FAA could have caught these lapses more easily if they had occurred
under the group that is not exempt, which gets scheduled
inspections; the exempt group is subject to inspection at any time,
but FAA inspectors look at them only sporadically, Nelligan said.
</P>
<P>
   Others point out that exempt tour operators have reasons beyond
the fear of the FAA to stay safe. ``Almost always, the guys doing
the flying are the guys who own the company,'' said James Coyne,
president of the National Air Transportation Association, a trade
association that includes repair stations, flight schools, airport
operators and others.
</P>
<P>
   He said they had a strong incentive to preserve their businesses
and themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike airlines, companies running tours do not have to report
operating data, so calculating accident rates is guesswork. But an
air tour appears to be far more dangerous per passenger mile than a
regularly scheduled flight and, the inspector general's report
suggests, much more dangerous than an air taxi, too, because those
usually fly at higher altitudes over fixed routes.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Gilligan, the FAA's deputy associate administrator for
regulation and certification, said that she wished regulations for
tour operators had been issued, but that the agency had been busy
drafting other rules and lacked the legal and technical staff to
write more.
</P>
<P>
   But, Ms. Gilligan said, even if tour operators were regulated
only under the looser rules that apply to the smallest commercial
operators, there were still strict requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as though any Joe can jump in a plane and fly
tours,'' she said. And the special rules for Hawaii and the Grand
Canyon cover most of the tours, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the operators are so varied that writing a rule to
cover them all is difficult. Some are primarily ``fixed base
operators,'' the companies that sell fuel and other services at
small airports, and offer air tours on a casual basis, while
others, like those at the Grand Canyon, run the aviation equivalent
of tour buses.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At Barnstorming Adventures, located at McLellan-Palomar Airport
near Carlsbad, Calif., Kate Lister and her husband, Tom Harnish,
operate six single-engine airplanes, including two open-cockpit
biplanes, both built in the 1920s, which they would almost
certainly have to retire under rules now being contemplated.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons have little to do with safety, Ms. Lister said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, she said, the biplanes were built with a metal skid
where the tail touches the ground, and sometime in the 1930s
someone added a wheel instead. But the planes fly under a standard
certificate that specifies the original design, with the skid.
</P>
<P>
   If she had to meet airline rules, she said, the discrepancy
would have to be corrected, but it would take many hours of work by
engineers to prove that the wheels, in use now for more than 60
years, were safe.
</P>
<P>
   The planes are well maintained and careful records are kept, Ms.
Lister said, but the logbooks are not on the planes. ``Holy moly,''
she said in a telephone interview. ``Nope, we don't comply with
that one. There's not a lot of storage space in a 1929 open-cockpit
biplane.''
</P>
<P>
   Other parts of the rule could be easy to apply, she said, like
the number of hours of experience her pilots must have and the
limit on the number of hours per day.
</P>
<P>
   But companies that give tours that are already in the more
regulated group want their competitors regulated the same way.
``They're putting people in the airplane for money, and we all need
to operate under the same regulation,'' said Jay Hudson, the
director of operations at Hudson Air Service, in Talkeetna, Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   If the policy-makers in Washington have open-cockpit biplanes in
mind at all, they are approaching the issue only slowly. The FAA's
1997 deadline came and went. A year later, the agency actually
finished work on a proposed rule, and sent its draft to the
secretary of transportation and the Office of Management and Budget
for approval, the last step before publishing it for public
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Then the FAA changed its mind, and pulled the rule back for more
work. Ms. Gilligan said staff members realized that the rule they
had drafted would cover air tours that ran only a day or a week a
year, like those at a county fair, and could ban many of them. So
it wrote an exemption.
</P>
<P>
   A new draft went to the transportation secretary last month, and
agency officials are hopeful they can get it issued formally by
late summer, so the public comment period can begin. That leaves
the possibility of having a rule in place by next year, although no
one is sure, because there is certain to be voluminous comment. And
even after the rule takes effect, operators would probably have a
year to comply.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
