<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5417 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-FAULKNER-NYT &LR;      07-10 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-FAULKNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL NOTEBOOK: NEW FROM FAULKNER, AN OLD STORY 
</HEADLINE>
  ( nk ) 
 By DUDLEY CLENDINEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the spring of 1948, with tensions rising in the South and
Southern Democrats rebelling against the civil rights program
President Harry Truman had proposed to Congress that February, a
New York literary agent sent a short story by William Faulkner to
The Atlantic Monthly and Harper's Magazine. It was a fractured
time. World War II, by wrenching Americans out of their accustomed
lives and routines, had forever broken the foundation of
segregation _ the assumption by blacks and whites alike that the
system was ordained and enduring. That it would change was not yet
clear, but the earth had cracked. In July, Truman ordered an end to
discrimination in the armed services and civil government ``as
rapidly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The dominant character in the story that Faulkner had typed,
down in Oxford, Miss., was a stubborn black man named Lucas
Beauchamp, who wore the old broadcloth coat, the gold watch chain
and silent self-assurance of his white, slave-owning grandfather,
Carothers McCaslin. His very presence in town was sometimes enough
to enrage young rednecks, and for whatever reason, Harper's and The
Atlantic Monthly turned the story down. The magazines had published
Faulkner's fiction before America entered the war, including a
story about Beauchamp and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   But the rejected story was about the relations between Beauchamp
and whites. It was culled from the front part of a novel,
``Intruder in the Dust.'' That novel, published in the fall of
1948, was about a white boy who saved Beauchamp from the false
accusation of murdering a white man. But the unpublished Beauchamp
short story, which emerged for the first time last week in the
pages of the Virginia Quarterly Review, offers a different
revelation. There, in Faulkner's words, undiminished by time, is
all the texture, the back-country manners, the flavor and scent of
a racial structure long collapsed, a way of life forever gone. It
is stunning, reading it, how the past rushes back. One can smell
the dark, rich nuances and tensions of Mississippi, 1948. It is
even more poignant to finish this story and realize how far we
still are from achieving its end.
</P>
<P>
   For this is a story of instruction about giving and accepting on
terms of mutual respect. It is the 12-year-old white boy, cold and
wet from a fall in the creek, who is commanded by Beauchamp to
follow him to his cabin. There he is wrapped in the black man's
quilt and warmed by his fire. But Beauchamp is no servant. He will
not be paid, and the challenge for the boy is to accept the gift,
and therefore the authority and humanity of the man who gave it. It
is a story about freedom, about black strength and competence, and
about white acceptance, and acknowledgment, and respect. More than
50 years later, those are still issues in America and the world, as
well as in Mississippi. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 1348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
