u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGO-ART-550&AMP;ADD-NYT     07-10 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGO-ART-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGO TRUCE STALLS AS REBELS ARGUE OVER WHO WILL SIGN IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUSAKA, Zambia _ The signing of a cease-fire agreement meant to
end the war in Congo stalled for hours Saturday as two factions
within one of the rebel groups contested which one of them would
sign the cease-fire document.
</P>
<P>
   As 300 senior diplomats, international observers and journalists
waited for seven hours inside the Great Hall of the Mulungushi
International Conference Center, and several heads of state and
senior ministers did the same in a back room, negotiators were
apparently arguing over whether Ernest Wamba dia Wamba or Bizima
Karaha would sit in the red chair with the ``RCD'' label in front
of it.
</P>
<P>
   Wamba dia Wamba founded the RCD, the Congolese Rally for
Democracy, but has headed only a splinter group since being ousted
by Emile Ilunga, and his deputy, Karaha.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the legitimate leader of the RCD and should sign on its
behalf,'' Wamba dia Wamba said. Ilunga said that was unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   For a historic meeting hailing what African politicians have
said is ``an African solution to an African problem,'' it also
displayed problems of organization. No one seemed to be in charge
and no explanation of what was going on was given to the delegates,
who included foreign ministers and ambassadors as they sat in the
room from 9 a.m. to 4 p.m. Rumors spread, and no announcements were
made as to when or whether the signing might take place.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all my years in Africa, I've never seen anything like
this,'' said a senior Western diplomat who attended as an observer.
``You usually have contentious issues to iron out in these
negotiations, but you make sure they're ironed out before you
invite all the heads of state for a signing. You don't let someone
start claiming squatter's rights to a chair.''
</P>
<P>
   Zambia's president, Frederick T.J. Chiluba, announced on
national television Friday night that the signing would take place
at 10 a.m. the following day. Saturday morning, President Laurent
Kabila of Congo landed at the Lusaka airport at 11:15 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   On word that Kabila had arrived, a dozen television cameras were
clicked into place on their tripods and 50 microphones were put in
front of Chiluba's designated chair. Then nothing happened.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Wamba dia Wamba came in alone and sat in the chair of
the rebel faction he used to lead.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he was doing, he replied: ``Who can dictate to me who
signs for the Congolese people? Why can't we both sign? I should be
signing it.''
</P>
<P>
   As the hours dragged on, the only other diplomat to join him at
the table was the Angolan defense minister, Kunda Paihama. About 4
p.m., as it looked as if the signing might be a complete failure,
Wamba dia Wamba received a message that sent him off into a back
room, apparently for negotiations to resolve the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Seven heads of state, including Kabila, were supposed to endorse
the deal, with other regional leaders witnessing the signing,
Zambian mediators said. Besides Congo, signers of the pact are to
include Rwanda and Uganda, which are backing the Congolese rebels,
who accuse Kabila of corruption, mismanagement and warmongering;
Zimbabwe, Namibia and Angola, which have backed Kabila out of
financial and security interests, and South Africa. Zambia would
sign too, as the host country.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   President Eduardo Dos Santos of Angola sent his defense minister
to sign in his place.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the leaders who were in Lusaka Saturday are expected by
Monday at the summit meeting of the Organization of African Unity
in Algiers.
</P>
<P>
   When Kabila arrived at the airport Saturday morning, he said he
was ``more than hopeful.'' Other leaders expressed similar
optimism.
</P>
<P>
   A 30-page peace plan adopted by regional defense and foreign
ministers on Wednesday was completed after two weeks of often
acrimonious talks by officials and mediators in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
   The cease-fire document calls for the guns in Congo to fall
silent within 24 hours and for a joint military commission to
administer the accord and oversee all fighters. It also allows for
the creation of a unified army after a 90-day national dialogue
under a ``neutral facilitator'' on Congo's political future and for
peacekeepers from the Organization of African Unity or the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   The pact provides for an operation that is intended to
strengthen peace by tracking down Hutu militias and any other armed
groups. The enforcers involved in such an operation can, according
to the pact, use ``persuasive or coercive measures'' to disarm them
and hand over ``mass killers, perpetrators of crimes against
humanity and other war criminals'' for trial by the international
war crimes tribunal on the Rwandan genocide.
</P>
<P>
   The Hutu militiamen are implicated in the 1994 genocide in
Rwanda of Tutsi and moderate Hutu. The Tutsi-dominated government
entered Congo to fight them, but Congo accuses Rwanda of seeking to
seize territory.
</P>
<P>
   The accord allows rebels to hold their territorial gains, which
amount to nearly half of the vast mineral-producing country
formerly known as Zaire, until a dialogue on restoring state
administration to all areas is concluded. Those talks are supposed
to open within 90 days of the pact being signed.
</P>
<P>
   Karaha said on Friday that the dialogue meant that the parties
would agree ``by consensus'' on a ``new presidency, new government
and new institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That is what we agreed on with Kabila's representative in
Lusaka,'' he said, suggesting that only a new political arrangement
and a new Congolese army could bring stability to Congo. Whether
Kabila will agree to any such arrangement seems open to doubt.
</P>
<P>
   The accord calls for the deployment of U.N. peacekeepers after
120 days, the disarmament of armed groups in 120 days and the
withdrawal of all foreign troops in 180 days, subject to a
``definite schedule'' for those withdrawals to be drawn up by the
joint military commission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 1351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990710.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5421 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REPUBS-TAXCUT-ART-2TA     07-10 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-TAXCUT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP IS BECOMING MORE AGGRESSIVE ON TAX REDUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Refiling to include graphic advisory.)  (ART ADV: Graphic on Republican tax proposals is being sent to NYT
graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) &HT;    (nk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After nearly two decades in which their desire for
big tax cuts was overwhelmed by efforts to eliminate the federal
budget deficit, Republicans in Congress will begin this week to
debate the largest and most broadly distributed tax reduction since
1981.
</P>
<P>
   They will have to overcome opposition from President Clinton and
most Democrats in Congress, as well as indifference among voters,
who consistently rank tax cuts below issues like improving
education and shoring up Social Security when asked about their
priorities. The specifics of the emerging Republican proposals are
the opening gambits in what will be months of partisan maneuvering
over taxes, and the debate promises to present both parties with
difficult choices about whether to compromise or fight it out on
the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   But new projections, however speculative, showing that budget
surpluses will grow faster than anticipated have energized
advocates of big tax cuts and heightened the long-running
ideological debate over the size and influence of the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of his party's revived assertiveness on the issue, the
chief Republican tax writer in the House, Rep. Bill Archer of
Texas, the chairman of the Ways and Means Committee, announced
Saturday that the centerpiece of his bill will be a measure
Democrats thought they had headed off: a reduction of 10 percent in
all personal income tax rates. His committee is expected to vote on
the package this week.
</P>
<P>
   The change, which would be phased in gradually over 10 years,
would cost roughly $400 billion in that period, nearly half the
$864 billion in tax cuts that Archer intends to include in his
bill. Among the bill's other features is a reduction in the capital
gains tax.
</P>
<P>
   The Archer plan, which would bring the current 15 percent tax
bracket down to 13.5 percent, the 28 percent bracket to 25.2
percent and the top 39.6 percent bracket to 35.6 percent, is
anathema to liberals, who say it favors the wealthy who need it
least. But such a reduction is a long-held goal of conservatives,
who say it does nothing more than give the biggest tax cuts to
those who pay the most taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Archer's proposal further hardened positions on both sides.
White House officials and congressional Democrats say the growing
budget surpluses presents an opportunity to prepare for long-term
challenges like the aging of the population while paying off the
national debt and investing prudently in areas like education and
health care. A big tax cut, they said, would not only endanger
those objectives, but risk plunging the nation back into a morass
of budget deficits.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say they too are all for improving education and
dealing with social issues. But they say there is so much money on
the table that the only way to prevent Washington from spending it
on ever-expanding entitlements, additional bureaucracy and
pork-barrel projects is to send as much of it as possible back to
taxpayers, who can use it more productively than the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason for this surplus is because taxpayers are
paying too much, which is why they deserve a refund,'' Archer said.
``And if we don't cut taxes now and the money stays in Washington,
the politicians will surely spend it. Republicans are determined to
protect taxpayers who ultimately get stuck with the bills.''
</P>
<P>
   The very magnitude of the projected surpluses suggests there is
room for compromise. But for now, both sides are gearing up for
several months of all-out partisan warfare, starting with a vote on
Tuesday or Wednesday in the Ways and Means Committee on Archer's
bill.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials say Clinton is not against tax cuts,
noting that he has already put down a bid in the form of his
proposal for $250 billion in tax breaks over the next decade
intended to spur more retirement savings among low- and
middle-income families.
</P>
<P>
   They said, however, that he would stick to his strategy of
demanding that any tax cuts await the resolution of efforts to
shore up Social Security and Medicare, both of which face financial
problems in coming decades as the baby boom generation grows old.
</P>
<P>
   But the White House is now adding another argument to its case.
Administration officials said the surplus estimates being relied on
by Republicans were predicated on domestic spending being held to
levels that were politically unrealistic and that would require
deep cuts in everything from law enforcement to Head Start over the
next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, White House officials said, the surplus projections
have been exaggerated by a technical factor. The portion of the
surplus that both parties agree is up for grabs, the part generated
by general tax revenues rather than payroll tax receipts that are
nominally earmarked for Social Security, is $996 billion over the
next decade, according to the Congressional Budget Office.
</P>
<P>
   But the $996 billion figure assumes that all of the surplus goes
to paying down the national debt, thereby reducing interest costs
to the government. To the degree that the money is used for tax
cuts or anything else, interest costs will be higher than assumed,
reducing the size of the surplus _ by $179 billion over 10 years,
according to an estimate by the administration. That means, in the
administration's view, that an $864 billion tax cut would return
the government to a deficit a decade from now _ a conclusion that
Republicans, who use slightly different numbers, dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``The path we've laid out is a balanced allocation of the
surplus,'' said Jacob J. Lew, the director of the White House's
Office of Management and Budget, previewing a line of attack
administration officials plan to employ in coming days and weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go down the other route and put everything into a tax
cut, sucking up all the dollars, it leaves you either with
devastating cuts to programs that would be impossible to deliver on
because they'd be unacceptable to the American people, or you'd end
up with deficits,'' Lew said.
</P>
<P>
   Having just recovered from the deficits created in part by the
Reagan-era tax cuts and the agonizing choices they forced upon the
nation, Lew said, the country should resist again going down a
tax-cutting road ``that's very difficult to turn back on.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The tax-cutting packages presented in pieces over the last few
days by Archer and his counterpart in the Senate, William V. Roth
Jr., R-Del., who is chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, are
opening gambits in what is likely to be months of maneuvering over
the nation's priorities as it shifts into an era of fiscal plenty.
</P>
<P>
   Roth's proposal is slightly smaller than Archer's, at no more
than $792 billion over 10 years, and it specifically leaves room to
deal with one of Clinton's priorities, adding prescription drug
coverage to the Medicare system of health insurance for the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   But both versions are chock-a-block with proposals that have
been little more than pipe dreams for Republicans in recent years,
from eliminating the tax on estates to reversing the quirk in the
tax code that penalizes many married couples.
</P>
<P>
   While Republicans expect that neither version will make it into
law intact, given Clinton's opposition, they are hopeful that some
of the ideas could be included in any compromise.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the sparring over taxes will go a long way toward
determining how the parties address a variety of related issues,
from Social Security and Medicare to breaking a logjam in Congress
over next year's spending bills. And with Republicans and Democrats
alike torn over whether confrontation or compromise will play
better with voters, it will shape their strategies as they head
into the 2000 election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Many members of both parties in the House would prefer fighting
it out over fiscal policy on the campaign trail rather than cutting
a deal, judging that staking out a clear ideological position will
help them as Democrats fight to wrest control of the chamber from
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to solidify Republican support for a bill they
can campaign on, based on the fact that they know this bill will be
so irresponsible that the president will be forced to veto it,''
said Rep. Charles Rangel of New York, the senior Democrat on the
Ways and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is more complicated in the Senate. There, moderate
Democrats are open to a substantial tax cut, and Republicans are
trying to make it easier for them. The plan introduced by Roth on
Friday was built around a middle-class tax cut far more palatable
to Democrats than the approach taken by Archer in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Some Senate Democrats also see an opportunity to neutralize tax
cuts as a political issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats have largely captured the education and
environmental issues, and have an expanding advantage on guns and
abortion,'' said Sen. Robert G. Torricelli, D-N.J., who
co-sponsored a bipartisan $345 billion tax cut proposal earlier
this year. ``There is no reason for us to lose on the tax issue.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The most critical factor may prove to be Clinton's calculation
about which way to go.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 he brokered a bipartisan compromise that gave the
Republicans a tax cut while protecting Democratic spending
priorities. In 1995 the president played a partisan standoff on the
budget to his advantage, reasserting his authority and invigorating
his party after its defeat in the 1994 midterm elections. This time
around he has reasons to go both ways.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Republicans believe that failure to press their
tax-cutting agenda as far as possible could accelerate the slide in
their electoral fortunes since 1994 by alienating the conservative
base that handed them control of Congress. Indeed, tax cuts are
almost as much a moral issue for Republicans as an economic issue.
</P>
<P>
   A high tax burden, Roth said Saturday in delivering the weekly
Republican national radio address, ``undermines the fundamental
values that dictate that you _ the individuals and families who
worked to create this economic expansion _ should be able to use
this surplus for you and your loved ones.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
