<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, July 11, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Low humidity will cover a large area from the northern Plains to
the Northeastern states as a sprawling zone of high pressure
strengthens over the Midwest. Sunshine will be plentiful in most
areas, but a jet stream disturbance will bring variable clouds and
a few mountain showers to northern New England. Daytime
temperatures will be within a few degrees of seasonal values across
these regions. Overnight, clear skies and light winds will promote
rapid dissipation of the daytime warmth. As a result, pre-dawn
temperatures will average 6 to 12 degrees below normal.
</P>
<P>
   A stalled front, marking the transition zone between sultry
conditions over the Gulf of Mexico states and the much less humid
air to the north, will be the focus for abundant clouds and
numerous thundershowers. Local flooding rains will occur,
especially in portions of the Tennessee Valley and southern
Appalachians where recurrent thundershowers pass over the same
areas. Variable clouds and sunshine will occur near the Gulf of
Mexico coast, but scattered thunderstorms will form in the heat of
the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Southwest will stay unsettled as moist air continues to be
drawn into the region by high-level winds from the southeast.
Afternoon thundershowers will erupt over many mountain peaks from
the southern Rockies to the southern Sierra. Weak winds around
20,000 feet will result in slow-moving thunderstorms heightening
the risk of flash flooding. Meanwhile, most of the Northwest will
be sunny and hot.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Lightning Detection
</P>
<P>
   Bolts of lightning can often appear to strike randomly. But
networks of lightning detectors suggest patterns that may help
forecasters predict the growth of thunderstorms. Conventional radar
tracks storms by detecting microwave radiation reflected by
precipitation. The heavy rain and hail in strong storms reflect
more radiation. Lightning detectors show that the greatest
electrical activity in a storm often precedes the heaviest
precipitation by about 15 minutes. Thus, detection of increasing
number of lightning bolts may be used to predict the sudden growth
of a thunderstorm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
