<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BRADLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE BURDEN OF INEVITABILITY  
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, July 11:
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley is having an enviable political moment. His race
for the presidency no longer seems as quixotic or self-indulgent as
it did only a few months ago. The former senator and basketball
star suddenly has status, which in today's politics translates as
the hefty $11 million now simmering in his campaign treasury. Thus,
the political class, including democratic donors and journalistic
commentators, is sniffing an unexpected contest, and giving this
underdog his break. Added weight is allotted to his earnest words
and even what once may have sounded deadly dull has now been
labeled refreshing and unpackaged.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all for Bradley, he is not doing so well as to be
pronounced the front-runner. That dangerous position has been
inherited by Vice President Al Gore, who seems to be under attack
even by people who say they admire him, really, as a nice and smart
person who could have invented the Internet, even if he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Being out front, at this stage, means that success is already
discounted and any failure or even confusion is a sign of doom. The
first nick in Gore's campaign was delivered by Bill Clinton, with
his famous commentary about the weaknesses of the Gore operation.
That set off a debilitating debate that neither man seems able to
extinguish. There have also been reports of tension between the two
over Gore's sudden criticism of Clinton's conduct in the Lewinsky
affair. Whether there is real tension or simply a calculated
separation strategy, the impact has been damaging to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   This White House melodrama is only one of the irritants at the
Gore campaign headquarters in Washington. Across the country, the
campaign of Gov. George W. Bush of Texas for the Republican
nomination has won the donor Lotto, amassing more than $36 million
in four months. Bush, whose charm has already taken on legendary
proportions, also strayed into Hollywood recently, drawing rave
reviews from some of the very movie stars who provided both glitter
and real gold to Democratic presidential campaigns in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a fairly hefty lead in the polls for the nomination,
Gore has been facing the kind of campaign staff turmoil that
activates Washington's political salons, where the talk is that
there is something close to panic reigning at Gore central. The
change that has brought the vice president the most deserved
criticism is the addition of Carter Eskew to help with media
matters. Eskew is a talented image maker, but he is well known as
the architect of the tobacco-industry campaign for a better deal
from Congress in recent years. His tobacco credentials would seem
to be at odds with Gore's heart-wrenching story at the Democratic
convention in 1996 about how his sister died of cancer from
smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Front-runners, of course, usually survive such perils on the way
to the nomination _ Bob Dole and Walter Mondale come to mind. But
the wounds of a rough primary season can prove costly in the
general election. Jimmy Carter never fully recovered from Ted
Kennedy's primary challenge in 1980. Gore has particular reason to
worry because Bradley is hardly an electrifying figure and few
people expected he would present a serious threat to the vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential politics, a civic exercise that thrives on
unpredictability, is once again providing its little surprises. The
Republican race was supposed to be the busy one, the Democratic
side a done deal. Now, it appears the scripts have shifted, as Gore
looks for his footing outside Bill Clinton's White House.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 1358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
