<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-FOREIGN-AID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A NEED FOR FOREIGN AID 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, July 11:
</P>
<P>
   For a nation of America's wealth, providing aid to alleviate
misery in the poorest countries is a worthy cause. But foreign aid
is also important to protect U.S. interests. Assistance that helps
prevent foreign political conflicts or economic calamities can
reduce the need for far more costly future U.S. involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has ignored this rule, and is once again embarked on an
effort to slash foreign aid. Such assistance, which pays for
everything from military training for U.S. allies to disaster
relief, already makes up less than 1 percent of the federal budget.
</P>
<P>
   Spending on aid has dropped by more than 50 percent in
inflation-adjusted dollars since 1985. The Senate last month
approved a foreign operations appropriation for 2000 that is $800
million less than this year's $13.5 billion total, and $1.9 billion
less than President Clinton's request. The House appropriation is
expected to be even lower.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has justifiably threatened to veto
the appropriations bill unless money is added to pay for programs
to dismantle nuclear weapons in the former Soviet Union and to
support the Wye River peace agreement between Israel and the
Palestinians, as well as to restore cuts to dozens of other
programs, including the Peace Corps. The White House also strongly
opposes language in the spending bill that could limit the
administration's options in managing the situation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Critics often point to past failures. During the Cold War aid
was doled out to corrupt anti-Communist regimes that did nothing to
improve the conditions of the poor. But aid can be effective in
relieving poverty if it is used to strengthen civil society and
nurture reform. The Clinton administration has tried to put money
into programs that promote democracy-building, community-based
economic development and local initiatives on environmental
protection and health care.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly half of the current aid budget supports military or
security-related objectives, and is likely to stay that way. Israel
and Egypt alone now get about 40 percent of the total. A modest
share of the budget is spent on refugee and emergency aid. Only
about a third of the budget goes to traditional development
activities running the gamut from child immunizations to
microcredit programs. Development programs with long-term promise
tend to suffer the cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Development experts have become smarter about how to use aid to
improve economic and social institutions. The World Bank recently
reported that an extra $10 billion in aid annually could lift 25
million people out of poverty if the money was directed to
countries with sound fiscal policies and a healthy public sector.
While more countries are meeting these criteria, total development
assistance worldwide from industrialized nations has dropped by
one-third since 1991, with Washington leading that decline. The
trend is tragic given how much needs to be done to help the more
than 1 billion people in extreme poverty who live on less than $1 a
day. The Clinton administration's goals for foreign aid are not
particularly ambitious. But Congress' effort to trim back the
meager funds is a shortsighted national shame.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 1359EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
