</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SPORTS AND SEX ARE ALWAYS TOGETHER
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In another time, I pitched a proposal on the sexual implications
of sports to a magazine called Eros. The rejection letter came
swiftly; the editor said there were no such implications because,
as any fool could see, sports was pure sex in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   At the time (this was before two Yankees pitchers switched
wives), I thought he overstated the situation. But now I'm
wondering if he was on to something. At the least, sex has sold
sports as subliminally as it has sold cars and beers, which in turn
are sold by sports.
</P>
<P>
   More directly, if you start in this century with the promotion
of the hypermasculine Babe Ruth and go on through the sexually
ambiguous Babe Didrikson, the current selling of the American World
Cup team as the babes of soccer seems like a logical arc.
</P>
<P>
   Sexuality may be so intrinsic to sports that unless the audience
is sexually comfortable, the game just won't sell.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't mean that the players have to be sexually alluring.
It just means that they can't be threatening. A lovely lesbian may
be bad for business if you are pushing a traditional family
package. Forget a gay man. Meanwhile, a female shot-putter who uses
steroids that give her manly muscles and a mustache may so
reinforce gender stereotypes that she threatens only her drug-free
competitors. And the same goes for a wife-beating linebacker who
feels whole only in the midst of a 'roid rage.
</P>
<P>
   There is a wonderful midland Babbittry to the selling of the
World Cup team. The enthusiastic complicity of the players evokes
the car washes and bake sales that many of them once ran to raise
money for their youth traveling teams. They are on a mission, for
their sport and for themselves, and if that means a little
cheesecake (or a lot in at least one case), sacrifice is the name
of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The implications here are not that the players are sexually
available, but that they are ``normal,'' that they are proper role
models for all the girls who will buy shoes and gear (and
eventually cosmetics that won't run or cake late in the match?).
For the World Cup team to crack into the male-dominated
merchandising mart as a group and as individuals, they must dispel
the aura of homosexuality that was hung on women's athleticism as a
way of stifling their emerging physical and political power.
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, a Faustian bargain here. Women's tennis had
to sell cigarettes to survive; let another generation decide how
many lung cancer casualties were worth that important cultural
victory. Also, there is a betrayal of all the lesbians whose
enormous contributions to many sports should not be forgotten in
the hetero happy hours where soccer babes entertain potential
sponsors; the so-called ``meet the shooters at your local Hooters''
syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   All this bubbles up in the same season that 18-year-old
Alexandra Stevenson, who may be the future of tennis as well as of
interracial relations, wowed us by becoming not only the first
female qualifier to reach the semifinals at Wimbledon but also the
first whose father was a legendary basketball player. After a
Florida newspaper printed Alexandra's birth certificate, Julius
Erving issued a statement acknowledging paternity.
</P>
<P>
   OK, Editor Eros, there must have been sex here, too. And,
naturally, there were agitated, if not hysterical reactions. There
was justifiable concern that Erving's relationship with Samantha
Stevenson, a pioneering sportswriter whose work has appeared in The
New York Times, would be used as evidence against women's access to
male games. There is no question that sleeping with a subject is
unethical, a conflict of interest, although it seems healthier, at
least more human, than many of the relationships between dominating
male sports figures and sycophantic male sportswriters and
broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   It was these sycophants, more than athletes and coaches, who
fought hardest to keep women out of press boxes, much less locker
rooms. They were afraid that women would adulterate their
testosterone moments, the mutual masculinity they fantasized in
their same-sex access. Tell me there isn't sex in all this, too.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, well, having lusted in vain for Billie Jean King in the late
'60s, I can take no moral high ground here. People who live in
glass columns should probably not even turn over stones, much less
throw them. And like any healthy sports fan of any gender or sexual
orientation, I say the more flesh the better. What do you think
male or female basketball, volleyball and ice skating are about? If
the World Cup soccer babes are hot, let another generation worry
about their impact on the sporting ozone layer.
</P>
<P>
   It's progress. Eros magazine went out of business years ago,
probably done in by Sports Illustrated. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 1402EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
