<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MACDONALD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: U.K.)  
 ANGUS MACDONALD DIES AT 60; WAS SCOTTISH BAGPIPER OF NOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By NICK RAVO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Angus MacDonald, whose verve and virtuosity made him one of the
world's best and best-known bagpipe players, died on June 25 in a
hospice in Edinburgh, Scotland, where he lived. He was 60.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was pancreatic cancer, said a friend and fellow
professional bagpiper, Donald McBride of Edinburgh.
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald served in the Scots Guards, a military unit in the
British army, for 30 years and held the rank of pipe major. He also
spent several years as the personal piper to Queen Elizabeth II and
won numerous major piping awards, including the Clasp and the Gold
Medal, both of which are sponsored by the Highland Society of
London.
</P>
<P>
   ``He probably was one of the best this century in light music _
dance and marching pipe music,'' said Paula Glendinning of Ashton,
Md., a former student of MacDonald's who is now the editor of The
Voice, a bagpipe magazine in Baltimore. She said he also won awards
for his classical music composed for the Scottish Highland
bagpipes, called piobaireachd.
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald was influential as a teacher, too, giving instruction
and performances in many nations. Indeed, few people have become so
identified with the bagpipe, one of the oldest instruments known to
man, dating back to the Middle East 4,000 years ago. The instrument
played today _ inimitable with its combination of shrillness backed
by a deep bass line _ is about 300 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``He traveled all over the world, and that's why he is so well
known,'' Ms. Glendinning said.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a Cameron Highlander, MacDonald was born on Oct. 20,
1938, in Glasgow, Scotland. He discovered his passion for bagpipes
in the pipe band at the Queen Victoria School in Dunblane and rose
to the position of boy pipe major.
</P>
<P>
   He left school at 15 and joined the Scots Guards in 1953 as a
piper. He rose through the ranks and in 1965 became pipe major and
household piper to the Queen.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, MacDonald was reassigned to the Guards Depot piping
school at Pirbright. Four years later, he joined the Scots Guards
recruiting team, where he became something of a pied piper with his
performances. He later served as senior instructor at the Army
School of Piping and piper to the governor of Edinburgh Castle. He
became a member of the Order of the British Empire in 1983, the
same year he retired.
</P>
<P>
   After his retirement from the military, MacDonald taught at the
Piping Center in Glasgow, the world's foremost piping institution.
He also traveled, training pipers from Northern Ireland to Oman to
Malaysia. And he performed in many countries, including the United
States, where he had a large following.
</P>
<P>
   Besides winning the Clasp and the Gold Medal, MacDonald won
several other bagpipe awards. including victories in the Grant's
Scotch Whisky Championship at Blair Castle.
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald is survived by his daughter, Fiona MacDonald of
London.
</P>
<P>
   In a forward to the 1993 reprint of the 1927 book ``The Piper in
Peace and War'' by C.A. Malcolm, MacDonald said of Scottish
regimental pipers: ``They have been, and still are, some of the
best ambassadors this country has.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 1405EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990710.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5432 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-HOOKER-NYT &LR;      07-10 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-HOOKER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHAEL K. HOOKER, CHANCELLOR, UNIVERSITY OF NORTH CAROLINA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Md., Va., Mass., Vt.)  (js) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael K. Hooker, the chancellor of the University of North
Carolina who took a high-technology, community-oriented approach to
higher education, died on June 29 at UNC Hospitals. He was 53 and
lived in Chapel Hill, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was complications from non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, the
university said.
</P>
<P>
   Taking up the reins at his alma mater in 1995 as its eighth
chancellor, Hooker made computer literacy and close ties to North
Carolina's citizenry the hallmarks of his administration. He
promoted an initiative to require all freshmen to have laptop
computers for their academic work next year, as well as a pledge to
insure that the university serve the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is only one reason to have a public university, and that
is to serve the people of the state,'' Hooker stated as his creed.
``That should be the touchstone of everything we do: whether it's
in the interest of North Carolina and our citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Hooker, the school of education's Web site offered free
links to public school systems in the state. Teachers and educators
from all of North Carolina's 117 school districts were trained on
the site to use its database of lesson plans.
</P>
<P>
   Under his guidance, Internet-based courses were introduced at
the undergraduate and graduate levels to make the university more
accessible to state residents.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kenneth Hooker was born in Richlands, Va., the son of a
coal miner, and was the first of his family to graduate from
college. He received a master's degree in 1972 and a doctorate in
philosophy in 1973 from the University of Massachusetts, and then
started teaching at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   Hooker went to Johns Hopkins University as an assistant
professor in philosophy in 1975 and successively served as
assistant dean, associate dean and dean until 1982, when he was
named president of Bennington College. He was president of the
University of Maryland at Baltimore County from 1986 to 1992, and
president of the University of Massachusetts system from 1992 until
his return to Chapel Hill three years later.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote scholarly articles on medical ethics and edited
``Descartes: Critical and Interpretive Essays'' (1978) and
``Leibniz: Critical and Interpretive Essays'' (1982).
</P>
<P>
   Hooker's marriage to Anna Hostettler Burns of Baltimore ended in
divorce. He is survived by his wife, Carmen; a daughter from his
earlier marriage, Alexandra Hooker of Baltimore; his mother,
Christine Hooker of Roanoke, Va., and his wife's two daughters,
Jennifer and Cyndi Buell of Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 1406EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990710.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5443 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-GARCIAPARRA11-COX     07-10 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GARCIAPARRA11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fame's a monster at Fenway
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ No one can deny that Boston Red Sox shortstop Nomar
Garciaparra inspires devotion among his fans.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two months, a computer hacker tried to cast nearly
40,000 All-Star votes for the former Georgia Tech star via the
Internet. Major League Baseball caught on and threw out the votes,
but Garciaparra didn't need the extra help to win the fan balloting
over the New York Yankees' Derek Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   But while an overzealous fan in cyberspace is one thing, people
invading his personal space is another matter entirely. Before
Friday's game against the Atlanta Braves _ the seventh game
Garciaparra has missed because of a groin injury _ he talked about
the perils of popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``People do crazy things,'' said Garciaparra, 25, the 1997
American League Rookie of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Is that flattering or scary?
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I find it flattering when people are bum-rushing us at the
hotel for an autograph and your clothes are all marked up?'' he
asked. ``Am I scared because I have no safety and security, or is
it flattering because people want (his autograph)? People are going
to look at it any which way. I look at it (this way): I just ruined
a $200 shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   But then Garciaparra, sipping a sports drink at his locker,
turned serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fun when you get followed home,'' he said. ``They're
running through red lights and cutting off people to get to you.
(I'm thinking) how am I going to get out of this one?''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra said he's been followed twice from Fenway Park, once
last year and once this year. He finally evaded his stalkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't go home,'' he said. ``I drive around the city looking
for police.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra said he feels bad when fans go to such extremes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ruins it for the people who just want the honor of shaking
a person's hand,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that he still goes to restaurants in Boston's North
End.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still do my thing,'' he said. ``I don't see myself as a
celebrity. I'm not any more special than anybody. I just happen to
be on TV and play at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people in Boston are great to me. It takes two seconds to
say hi to somebody and shake their hand. As long as they're not
disrespectful, I'm going to give them the same respect back.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra has gone so far as to lecture an adult who pushed a
little kid out of the way to get an autograph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `You think you're more important than this little kid
smiling?''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra made a lot of kids smile Friday when he popped into
a baseball camp at Georgia Tech to visit his former coaches. ``That
was fun,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The work began when he arrived at Turner Field. He ran a few
sprints and tested his agility.
</P>
<P>
   The groin injury, Garciaparra said, ``Felt good today, better
than it did (the day before). If I have another good day tomorrow,
we'll go from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra injured himself in Baltimore running out a triple in
the ninth inning and missed two games. He returned to the lineup,
then aggravated the injury July 2 in Chicago going from first to
third.
</P>
<P>
   ``He likes to play, and he only goes at one speed,'' said Red
Sox manager Jimy Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra was putting up exceptional numbers dueling Jeter and
Seattle's Alex Rodriguez for the All-Star starting position when
the injury struck.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Garciaparra batted .394 with four home runs, two
triples, 12 doubles and 16 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know my numbers,'' he said. ``I don't want to know
them. I don't pay attention to them. Numbers are irrelevant to me.
I just know the team's playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra will try to build on a 17-game hitting streak when
he returns to action.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very annoying,'' he said of sitting out, ``regardless of
the year I'm having. I just don't like sitting around watching the
game. When I know I can play and they're giving me a day off,
that's fine. When I can't play due to something physically holding
me back, I can't stand it. I hate it. It drives me crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not sure if he'll be able to play Tuesday in the All-Star
Game, but that doesn't grate on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now that's not on my mind,'' he said. ``I'm more
concerned with getting out there and playing. And winning.''
</P>
<P>
   This will be Garciaparra's second All-Star Game. As a rookie in
1997, he had one at-bat and flied out to right field. He also won
the Home Run Derby for rookies and thoroughly enjoyed himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my attitude toward the All-Star Game is different,''
he said. ``I don't play for them, I don't care about them. I play
with All-Stars every day. You're in the highest level in the world,
and you have to still separate that more. Are you kidding me?''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra realizes that his achievements may not be separated
from Jeter and Rodriguez for another decade. He says it's an honor
to be mentioned in the same sentence with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good time to play baseball,'' Garciaparra said. ``I
think it's an even better time to be a fan.''
</P>
<P>
   A respectful fan.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
