<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5444 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-JACKIE-ROBINSON11     07-10 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-JACKIE-ROBINSON11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Small Georgia town honors a favorite son
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Ga. _ Jackie Robinson was just a toddler when his mother
took the family to California in search of a better life and he
returned to his southwest Georgia birthplace only once.
</P>
<P>
   But Charles Copeland, 91, hasn't forgotten that day nearly 50
years ago or the pride he and everyone else in Cairo's black
community felt.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson _ the man who smashed the color barrier in baseball and
brought hope to so many people _ was returning to his roots.
</P>
<P>
   It was Jackie Robinson Day and thousands turned out in
mid-October 1949 for a parade through Cairo in honor of the
Brooklyn standout.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was Robinson in town, but so were Dodgers teammates Roy
Campanella and Don Newcombe, plus Larry Doby, the first black
player in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was about the biggest thing to ever happen here,'' said
Copeland, a retired school principal. ``Everyone was so proud of
Jackie. You didn't have to be a baseball fan to appreciate what he
had done. Young people today don't really understand.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why Dr. Linda Walden, the only black physician in Grady
County, is determined to keep Robinson's legacy alive in Cairo _ an
agricultural center of about 9,000 residents near the Florida line
that is known for its cane syrup and okra.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jackie showed that, no matter how humble your beginnings or
how big the obstacles, you can make a difference if you have the
dream and get the opportunity,'' said Walden, a cousin of Robinson.
``That lesson is as important today as it was 50 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Walden is founder and president of the Jackie Robinson Cairo
Memorial Institute Inc. The nonprofit organization is raising funds
to built a culture and recreation center in Robinson's honor. The
facility would include a small museum and a bronze statue of
Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   The target date for groundbreaking is early next year, perhaps
Jan. 31 _ Robinson's birthday. But fund-raising has been slow.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the rural South, and things don't move fast,'' said
Walden, who grew up in Florida but returned to Cairo to open a
family practice in 1996. ``But honoring Jackie has been too long in
coming. He is an icon, and his legacy needs to be preserved. That
he was born in the sticks of South Georgia is very much a part of
his story. It shows where he came from and what he had to
overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, Cairo made little note of Robinson. But in 1996 the
baseball field for the Cairo High School Syrupmakers was renamed in
honor of Robinson. Then in 1997 _ the 50th anniversary of Robinson
joining the Dodgers _ a 10-mile stretch of Ga. 93 became Jackie
Robinson Memorial Highway. A wall of fame at the Roddenbery
Memorial Library features photos of Robinson and his brother, Mack,
a 1936 Olympian.
</P>
<P>
   By next year, a state historical marker should be in place to
mark where Robinson was born in 1919, off Hadley Ferry Road in the
Rocky Hill community, near Beachton and south of Cairo. The house
burned years ago, and only one of the two chimneys remains.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Roosevelt Robinson was the youngest of five children born
to Mallie McGriff Robinson. Husband Jerry, a sharecropper on the
Sasser Plantation, deserted the family shortly after Jackie was
born. In May 1920, when Jackie was about 16 months old, Mallie
Robinson and her children boarded a westbound train about midnight
and headed for Pasadena, Calif., where a brother lived.
</P>
<P>
   Mallie Robinson returned to Cairo occasionally to visit a
sister, but Jackie did not come back for nearly 30 years. Grady
County _ about one-third black _ remained segregated, but by then
Robinson was a national hero.
</P>
<P>
   Brooklyn had just played the New York Yankees in the World
Series, and the Jackie Robinson All-Stars were beginning a
barnstorming trip. One game was in Atlanta, where a record 25,221
overflowed Ponce de Leon Park for an exhibition game the preceding
spring between the Dodgers and the Atlanta Crackers.
</P>
<P>
   The barnstorming tour had to be cut short, but not until after
Robinson drove to Cairo with Campanella, Newcombe and Doby for a
day in his honor.
</P>
<P>
   Newcombe, now director of community relations for the Dodgers,
still remembers the turnout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cairo isn't a very big place, but the streets were packed,''
said Newcombe, Rookie of the Year in 1949. ``They had a big parade,
and everybody turned out.''
</P>
<P>
   A collection was taken up for Robinson, but he declined the
monetary gift, instead asking for a country-cured ham. When he got
back to New York, however, his California-reared wife, Rachel,
looked at the salt and mold on the ham and threw it away; she
thought it was spoiled.
</P>
<P>
   During a visit to Atlanta several years ago, Rachel Robinson
said her late husband was deeply touched by his reception in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said there were so many people who walked in from the
countryside to see him,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Robinson had gone home.
</P>
<P>
   JACKIE ROBINSON
</P>
<P>
   Born: Jan. 31, 1919, in Cairo, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Death: Oct. 24, 1972, in Stamford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Early years: Youngest of five children born to Jerry and Mallie
Robinson. Moved with mother and siblings to California as a toddler
in 1920. He grew up in Pasadena, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   College: Football, basketball and baseball star at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Family: Married Rachel Isum in 1946 after serving in the U.S.
Army in World War II. Had two sons, Jack Jr. and David, and one
daughter, Sharon.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball career: Broke the color barrier in major league
baseball with the Brooklyn Dodgers in 1947. Named Rookie of the
Year. Batted .311 during 10-year career. Led National League with a
.342 average in 1949, when he was named NL MVP. Played in six World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Fame: Elected in 1962, his first year of eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   Uniform number: 42, retired by all major-league teams in 1997 as
part of the 50th anniversary celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
