<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5445 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARE11-COX     07-10 2221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CARE packages hope, help in Kosovo
 &HT;    By Keith Graham
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Kosovo _ Marshall Burke's workday is already more than
15 hours old.
</P>
<P>
   It began with a trip to Cegrane, a refugee camp in Macedonia,
where he talked with farmers agonizing over their return to the
ruined villages of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   It is ending with a conversation with a journalist at a run-down
hotel in Skopje, Macedonia's capital.
</P>
<P>
   Burke has spent the past 14 years with CARE, often traveling
from crisis to crisis around the world. Yet he is far from jaded.
</P>
<P>
   Although he is exhausted and sticky with sweat, he talks about
the people he has met that day:
</P>
<P>
   _ A farmer angry because his barn has been destroyed by Serb
paramilitaries and worried about how he will feed his family with
no crop to harvest.
</P>
<P>
   _ A refugee mother so stressed out she cannot produce milk for
her baby.
</P>
<P>
   _ A cardiologist who was forced from his home and now is trying
to make ends meet by driving a truck for a relief agency.
</P>
<P>
   Burke wonders: How do you make those people real? How do you
bring their feelings to life for people back home in America?
</P>
<P>
   Burke still is touched by the stories of individuals.
Ultimately, he believes, the hope brought to them by the CARE
staffers now fanning out across Kosovo, Macedonia and Albania is
what the relief and development agency is all about.
</P>
<P>
   But Burke _ a 49-year-old north Atlanta resident who once ran a
bar in Tucson, Ariz. _ is also a big-picture man.
</P>
<P>
   Now the executive director for development in the Southeast for
Atlanta-based CARE USA, Burke earned a Ph.D. in desert ecology
before he owned a bar. In his spare time, he started a nonprofit
organization in Tucson to help people with AIDS. He has spent much
of his career with CARE teaching people better agricultural methods
and ways to use natural resources without destroying the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   He takes pride in the fact that the organization he works for is
one of the world's largest private international development and
relief agencies.
</P>
<P>
   CARE, he says, springs into action for emergencies like the war
that sent hundreds of thousands of refugees fleeing from Kosovo.
Its workers do ``some of the dirtiest, most difficult and dangerous
jobs'' in crisis-ridden countries, not only here in the Balkans,
but in Africa, Asia and Central America.
</P>
<P>
   But, while some CARE workers are responding to the emergencies,
others keep working steadily in more than 60 countries helping
people learn to read, dig wells or improve their health.
</P>
<P>
   The agency began by dispensing the CARE packages that helped
rebuild Europe following World War II. Unfortunately, Burke says,
many Americans have paid little attention since.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Atlanta, he has seen the blank stares when he talks
about his work _ until he says, ``You know, the CARE package.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my great dreams,'' Burke says, ``is that if CARE should
say it was going to leave Atlanta there would be as much hue and
cry as there would be if the Braves were to say they were
leaving.''
</P>
<P>
   Seen through the eyes of Marshall Burke, CARE is a beautiful
sight. Through the eyes of Inose Tatsuya, it is not so pretty, at
least at this moment.
</P>
<P>
   Near the U.S. military command post in the Kosovo town called
Urosevac by the Serbs and Ferizaj by ethnic Albanians, Tatsuya and
a Japanese television crew are waiting for a CARE team scheduled to
assess damage in the devastated village of Kacanik.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the team is already a half-hour late for the
trip's start, and Tatsuya is worried he won't get the footage he
needs. ``They change their plans all the time,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Three CARE staffers finally arrive, but before going to Kacanik
there are detours: A satellite phone is set up for a call. The CARE
team has to go to a warehouse where food is being unloaded. There
is a break for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Then, more than two hours after the Kacanik survey was to begin,
the apologetic CARE driver announces he is low on fuel and needs to
return across the border into Macedonia to fill the tanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delays, delays, delays,'' says Fatos Bajinovci, an ethnic
Albanian who witnesses the scene.
</P>
<P>
   So it goes sometimes, says Wendy Driscoll, a Nairobi-based
spokeswoman for CARE temporarily assigned to the Balkans. ``A lot
of your time is hurry up and wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Assignments for staffers are often in flux. CARE must coordinate
its work with other humanitarian agencies and local authorities.
There are concerns about the security of staffers in an area
riddled with land mines and still torn by violence. Vehicles and
fuel are in short supply, and communication with staffers in the
field can be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the border with Macedonia, a team of CARE workers is
operating a way station for refugees returning to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are giving food packets,'' says Agron Destani, 24, an
ethnic Albanian from Macedonia who had worked as an airport clerk
before joining CARE on a three-month contract. ``A lot of people
are crossing.''
</P>
<P>
   Refugees are given flour, meat spreads, jam, sardines, cheese,
pretzels, cooking oil and soap. In a single day, nearly 15,000
people get this kind of assistance.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Destani and the other CARE workers must fend
off Macedonian police officers who think they deserve bags of food.
A Macedonian soldier suddenly sprays water from a hose into the
hot, dusty site where the way station has been set up, turning it
into a sea of mud before the CARE staff can persuade him to stop.
Then a United Nations truck accidentally knocks down the lean-to
where the food is kept.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day sort of presents a new challenge,'' says a
philosophical Kevin Romano, 25. From Washington, he had been
studying at the London School of Economics before coming to work
for CARE seven weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are bad days. There are good days,'' agrees Loic Cohen,
32, a Frenchman who worked for Action Against Hunger before joining
CARE. ``It's a bit messy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``CARE,'' one staff member jokes, ``is the Austrian way to spell
chaos.'' CARE workers, it seems, are people who like to go about
doing good _ especially if it involves a lot of going about.
</P>
<P>
   But, ultimately, there is a method in the madness.
</P>
<P>
   In the Balkans, Marshall Burke explains, ``We've had an
emergency for three months. We have not had time to catch our
breath.''
</P>
<P>
   The pace has been hectic. Before NATO began its airstrikes on
Yugoslavia, CARE had operated programs in Serbia, Kosovo and
Montenegro. That operation, based in offices in Belgrade and in
Pristina, Kosovo's capital, closed just before the NATO bombardment
began March 24. Three CARE workers did not make it out of
Yugoslavia. They were arrested and are still held on spying charges
CARE officials call absurd.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as refugees began flooding from Kosovo into neighboring
Albania and Macedonia, CARE opened offices in those countries.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantan Marge Tsitouris, director of the emergency group for
CARE USA, was named interim emergency coordinator for the region
and shuttled back and forth between Albania and Macedonia with
files in her backpack.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the refugees started going over, we said we've got
refugees and we've got a job to do,'' the 22-year CARE veteran
explains.
</P>
<P>
   CARE Australia, which had spearheaded the Yugoslav operation,
led the new programs in Macedonia. Atlantan Bob MacPherson was
initially sent in as team leader in Albania, working with staff
members from CARE Canada and CARE Germany, but that assignment
ended when a car he was traveling in went over a cliff. With
MacPherson recovering in a hospital in Germany, CARE Canada took
over leadership in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Carsten Voelz, a German who is CARE's regional coordinator for
the Fier, Albania, area, says staff from Canada, Germany, France
and Norway, as well as the United States, have helped. ``This was
really a combined action,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   It was also an action that produced new demands every day. Sites
had to be found for refugee camps: An old firing range, for
instance, became the site of the CARE-managed Stenkovec II camp not
far from the Kosovo border in Macedonia. The size of the camps
burgeoned. At Cegrane, another CARE camp in Macedonia adjacent to a
village of less than 5,000 people, the number of refugees swelled
to more than 40,000.
</P>
<P>
   CARE had to scramble to find enough tents to house them.
Latrines had to be built and cooking facilities set up. Because the
available sites were poor, drainage problems became a constant
battle.
</P>
<P>
   Staff had to be brought in from other countries or hired locally
to run the camps. And with the numbers of refugees mushrooming,
just figuring out how much food would be needed each day was an
enormous challenge _ not to mention how much babyfood and how many
diapers.
</P>
<P>
   In all, CARE managed five camps as well as an intake center and
a separate food distribution program in Albania and two camps in
Macedonia. At their peak, they housed 93,000 refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Workers for CARE and other humanitarian agencies had already
begun planning _ and finding funds _ to house the refugees through
what promised to be a long war.
</P>
<P>
   Then, almost as swiftly as the refugees had left Kosovo, they
were returning to it on the heels of a peace-keeping force that was
pushing out the Yugoslav military and Serbian paramilitaries.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the whole process began in reverse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already had a war. Eight hundred thousand people have
left their country, and now 800,000 people are going back,'' says
Tsitouris, 59. ``You never got organized.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, CARE is getting organized. As the refugees pushed back into
Kosovo, so did CARE staff, many of them specialists with eyes
attuned to the needs of people returning to devastated lands.
</P>
<P>
   Some looked at housing, others at food and agriculture or
health. And, despite all the hurry-up-and-wait moments and the
changes of plans, they were bubbling with ideas by the time Burke
called a daylong session to exchange ideas.
</P>
<P>
   From that session and later ones about specific programs,
outlines of plans began to emerge _ plans sent back to the offices
of CARE USA and other CARE country headquarters and circulated
among donors. Some of the plans address the immediate emergencies;
others look further down the road to a time of real rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
   The most pressing problems include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Shelter: With as many as 70 percent to 80 percent of houses
burned in some villages, families may have time to refurbish only
one room before the cold Kosovo winter. In the Ferizaj area, Andrew
Gilmour, 35, a Canadian who is CARE's shelter coordinator, thinks
10,000 to 20,000 stoves may be needed. Doors, insulating materials,
windows and beds also are badly needed. Gilmour hopes no more than
eight people will have to share a room by winter.
</P>
<P>
   _ Food: Kosovo was never self-sufficient in food. Now many
farmers have no crop at all. CARE workers want to help get those
farms working again. Seed will be needed, and in some cases tools
must be supplied and machinery repaired. ``There's also a huge
demand for chickens,'' Burke says.
</P>
<P>
   _ Health: CARE has been operating mobile health clinics,
offering pediatric and gynecological treatment for refugees in
Macedonia and Albania. Those programs will shift to Kosovo, now.
The agency also will work to bring rural health clinics up to
standard. Much of the clinics' equipment is old; some of it has
been stolen.
</P>
<P>
   _ Land mines: No one really knows how many land mines have been
left behind by the Serbs, but CARE will attempt to remove as many
as possible and educate the public about the dangers.
</P>
<P>
   In another move to strengthen efforts in Kosovo, Beat Jakob
Rohr, a CARE USA staffer who previously headed CARE operations in
Peru, Mozambique, Kenya and Nicaragua, has been appointed to head
the Pristina office.
</P>
<P>
   The search is on to find new funding for these programs or shift
funds already in the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   With major donors, Burke says, ``I think CARE's reputation is
such that if you call and say you're from CARE you will get what
you need. That's true even when I call people I have never met and
probably never will.''
</P>
<P>
   Out in the field in Kosovo, a couple of hours drive away from
their office in Pristina, CARE workers Andrew Gilmour and Bob
MacPherson, on his first assignment since being released from the
hospital in Germany, are bouncing over rough roads. Gilmour has
just met with other humanitarian organizations to discuss Kosovo's
housing crisis. MacPherson and a consultant have been assessing
sites where land mines may lurk.
</P>
<P>
   In need of diesel for their four-wheel drive Toyota, they head
for one of the few functioning service stations in the area.
Villagers have assured Gilmour the diesel there is not watered down
as it is in most places.
</P>
<P>
   The tank filled, they return to the road. But, rounding a bend
past a burned out Yugoslav tank, they discover warning signs
erected by peacekeeping forces. Land mines are on both sides of the
road.
</P>
<P>
   Then the engine begins to whine, and the Toyota chugs to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Land mines on both sides of the road. Water in the gas tank,''
says MacPherson, 53, laughing. ``It doesn't get any better than
this.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
