<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BROPEN-COURSE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The toughest track: Carnoustie
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ There will be no fluke champion this week
at the 128th British Open. The survivor at the formidable
Carnoustie Golf Links will have pushed his spikes through a gantlet
of diabolical rough, wind and relentless length.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the golf ball around Carnoustie will be tough even if
such mild conditions as those enjoyed by participants at Loch
Lomond remain in the area. However, if the more typical nasty stuff
swings in off the North Sea, anything is possible. Par could become
a fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever nature brings, one aspect will remain constant.
Carnoustie is a long, perilous golf course that should satisfy both
traditionalists and sadists.
</P>
<P>
   The first-round 64 that Colin Montgomerie produced at Carnoustie
in the first round of the 1995 Scottish Open _ ``7:10 a.m start,
flat calm,'' he recalled _ is a mark not likely to be touched this
week under a typically tough Open setup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they'll only realize what that was like when they get
there and find out that 64 is a bloody good score around there,''
Montgomerie said. ``And I wouldn't expect it to be beaten.... It's
playing very long. From the word go, it's just the most demanding
links course that we have, and it's great that it's back on the
Open rotation. It's been 24 years since we played there last (in
the British Open), and that's too long, really.''
</P>
<P>
   A break in the weather might be the only break available.
Carnoustie plays 7,361 yards to a par 71 with these four finishing
holes: par-4 15th, 472 yards; par-3 16th, 250 yards; par-4 17th,
459 yards; and par-4 18th, previously a par-5, 487 yards, with the
twisting Barry Burn 30 yards in front of the green.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the weather conditions are like they can be, it may make
Pinehurst look easy,'' David Duval said. ``The fairways tend to be
narrower than Pinehurst's were. You have grass that is seven feet
tall everywhere, and wind and rain.... It could be very difficult.
If it's blowing 30 (mph) every day, you could see an 8-over,
10-over type of winning score.''
</P>
<P>
   With winds blowing about 20 mph last weekend at the Western
Open, Tiger Woods called it ``wonderful preparation'' for
Carnoustie.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who reclaimed the world's No. 1 ranking with last
weekend's victory, played the course last week with Mark O'Meara
and friends. He found severe pot bunkers and Barry Burns that wind
through the course. Several downwind holes can produce birdies, but
just as many will require two stout shots to reach in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think Carnoustie is a strong player's course,'' Ernie
Els said. ``The winner will be a strong player, somebody who can
hit the ball in the wind, hit the driver strong and has a good
short game. It's not a short-hitter's golf course. You've got to
hit the golf ball there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When the wind is blowing, Carnoustie is probably the toughest
course in Britain,'' said Michael Bonallack, secretary of the Royal
&AMP; Ancient Golf Club, which runs the tournament. ``And even when
it's not blowing, it's probably the toughest.''
</P>
<P>
   When Gary Player won there in 1968, he never broke 70. When
Woods played Carnoustie in 1995-96 in the Scottish Open, he hit
5-iron, 5-iron one day, then driver, driver the next on the
459-yard 17th. It's an understatement to say the wind is a factor.
</P>
<P>
   Why has it taken 24 years for a British Open to return to
Carnoustie? Some say it's because the Royal &AMP; Ancient did not wish
for its beloved St. Andrews to be upstaged by a track many think is
superior. The course also went through a down period of maintenance
in the 1980s, and until recently the hotel accommodations near the
site were inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   As for the difficulty that should promote daily moaning and
groaning among the players, Montgomerie said: ``Good. I hope it's
as tough as they bloody well can get it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
