</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BROPEN-GUIDE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Handicapping the British Open
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   FIVE WHO CAN WIN:
</P>
<P>
   _ Tiger Woods: He should be the favorite, despite Scot Colin
Montgomerie's reputation around the place and Sergio Garcia's
Tigermania-like run through Europe. Having reclaimed his No. 1 spot
in the rankings from David Duval, Woods is enjoying his highest
confidence mark since winning the Masters in 1997. Woods has won
three of his last four events _ the Deustche Bank Open on the
European Tour, the Memorial and the Western _ and finished two
shots behind Payne Stewart at the U.S. Open. Woods played
Carnoustie as an amateur in the 1995 and 1996 Scottish Open.
</P>
<P>
   _ Colin Montgomerie: Holds the Carnoustie course record at 64,
which is mind-boggling, and will be the co-favorite, with Garcia,
among European fans. Hasn't enjoyed much success at his own Open _
missing the cut three of the past four years _ but senses a
potential comfort zone at Carnoustie.
</P>
<P>
   _ David Duval: Certainly he has the length and power to beat the
ball through the wind or out of the high grass. Tied for 11th last
year at Royal Birkdale. Has played Carnoustie in recent years for
fun, not in competition.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sergio Garcia: Has never played Carnoustie, but it might not
matter. ``El Nino'' can do very little wrong lately, winning his
first European Tour event, the Irish Open, then contending at Loch
Lomond.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ernie Els: Tied for second, behind Tom Lehman, in 1996 at
Royal Lytham. Long, strong, wide-based player who should be a great
fit for Carnoustie, even in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   FIVE WORTH A LOOK
</P>
<P>
   _ Payne Stewart: How can you not list him among the contenders
after the guts he displayed at Pinehurst? Two-time runner-up in the
British in 1985 and 1990. And his knickers fit the scenery.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jim Furyk: He might not have the length to keep up with the
big boys this time, but he has been a steady force in the British
with a tie for fourth and a solo fourth the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lee Westwood: Everybody keeps waiting for his big arrival, and
winning at New Orleans last year wasn't it. Has played a few times
at Carnoustie in the Scottish Open and British Amateur and likes
the course. With a healthy shoulder, he says his tee-to-green game
has never been better.
</P>
<P>
   _ Phil Mickelson: No more baby beeper problems. Best finish has
been a tie for 24th at Royal Troon in 1997. Anybody who can flop it
from anywhere should be a factor with this much high grass.
</P>
<P>
   _ Davis Love III: Came close at the Masters, but was never a
factor at Pinehurst. Last time anybody got excited about him, he
was backboarding the ball into the hole with his chip at Augusta's
16th. Top 10s in his last two British Opens.
</P>
<P>
   FIVE TO FORGET
</P>
<P>
   _ Nick Faldo: Giving slight indications of a revival, but
doesn't have the concentration that used to be part of his everyday
routine. Last two Opens have been forgettable. Has not contended in
a major since his fourth place at Royal Lytham in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   _ Darren Clarke: Tied for second behind Justin Leonard at Royal
Troon in '97, but missed the cut last year. Maybe he's cooled down
finally about the Irish Open. He bypassed the tournament upon
finding out that while John Daly received appearance fees of nearly
200,000 pounds, he was offered zilch.
</P>
<P>
   _ Scott Hoch: If his equipment company, Yonex, didn't request
that he attend the British Open, he would be back in Orlando. If he
ever contends in the tournament, it will be an accident.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tom Watson: Sure, it would be a great story if Watson could
contend 24 years after he won at Carnoustie. But he's getting ready
for the Senior Tour and no rough _ not 4-foot fescue.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jose Maria Olazabal: Normally, he would be one of the
favorites. But the Spaniard is attending with his right hand still
mending. He broke it at the U.S. Open, slamming it against his
hotel wall after an opening 75.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
