</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-KUCHAR11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A year later, Kuchar barely on British map
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOCH LOMOND, Scotland _ Matt Kuchar came here a year ago unable
to tell the difference between reality and fantasy. The lush
countryside of central Scotland deepened the dream.
</P>
<P>
   What more could there be for Kuchar, a 20-year-old golfer from
Georgia Tech who had won the U.S. Amateur, contended in the Masters
and U.S. Open and appeared with Jay Leno on ``The Tonight Show''?
Nothing but the decision: Kuchar was only a telephone call away
from accepting millions of endorsement dollars to turn
professional.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, everything was kind of a magic-carpet ride,''
Kuchar said Friday, while standing outside the scoring tent at the
Standard Life Loch Lomond Invitational. ``It's a lot different now.
I think maybe you try and live up to those same dreams that came
true last year, and it's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   While this year's phenom, 19-year-old Spaniard Sergio Garcia, is
exciting all of Europe on his way to the British Open, Kuchar has
become a golfing afterthought, last year's news.
</P>
<P>
   He'll be in the Carnoustie area today and Monday, trying for an
Open spot the blue-collar way, as a qualifier at the Monifieth
Links.
</P>
<P>
   After a third round of even-par 71 Friday at Loch Lomond, he and
his mother, Meg, walked around the course and were hardly noticed.
By the time Kuchar landed in Glasgow a year ago, millions of golf
fans had watched him successfully compete at Augusta National and
the Olympic Club and charm a nation with his constant smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've totally dropped off the map yet,'' Kuchar,
21, said. ``I think people still do recognize me. There's not the
hype there was last year, but you can still see people snickering
and pointing, `There's the amateur kid, Matt Kuchar.' That's still
enjoyable, but it's not as great as it was last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the act is different. Kuchar's sometimes controversial and
always demonstrative father, Peter, is in Florida and not carrying
his son's bag. His absence is a combination, Matt said, of finances
and common sense. Last year, a local caddie probably could have
saved a couple of strokes. This year, Matt employed a Loch Lomond
gent he knew only as ``Joe,'' with no last name given. A local
caddie also will work for him at the Open qualifier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very expensive for us amateurs to travel,'' Matt said.
``Dad's paying for this trip. I'm sure if things weren't going on
at home, he would be here.''
</P>
<P>
   One month after the 1998 British Open, Matt and his father
announced that Matt would remain at Georgia Tech. After a mostly
lost 1999 season, punctuated by a disastrous performance in the
NCAAs (81-77), Kuchar will return to Tech for his senior year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really happy with my decision,'' he said. ``It's something
that weighed a lot on me, and I've still thought a lot about, but I
always come back to being happy with what I've done. . . . Most
guys I talked to were really unsure. They kept me confused as to
the boat that I was in. They tried to put themselves in my shoes
and most of them said, `Matt I don't know what I would do if I were
you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens, nothing is likely to match the fanfare
of last summer, when Kuchar followed a tie for 21st in the Masters
with a tie for 14th in the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``His window was open the widest the Monday after the U.S. Open
in 1998,'' said agent Vinnie Giles of Pros Inc. in Richmond, Va.
``That's the biggest, widest window he was probably going to find
as an amateur unless he did something pretty phenomenal thereafter.
Now, here we are a year later, and it's obvious his window has got
some dust on it.''
</P>
<P>
   If there's a plus side for Kuchar, the golf industry was in such
a depressed state last year that small contract numbers were
available. Maybe his game and the promotional budgets will be
better in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Kuchar concedes that he did not handle ideally the distractions
accompanying his amazing run. In fact, he pushed himself to the
limit, and it affected his game. Behind in his studies from the
extra travel and competition that accompanied the U.S. Amateur
title, Kuchar needed 21 hours last term just to get on time for
graduation. Only now is his game beginning to come back to form.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people know the different pulls you have on your
schedule,'' he said. ``When you get to a certain level, everybody
seems to want a piece of you. Sure, you get to do so many great
things, but when it comes down to golf, you don`t seem to be quite
as focused. So I lost a little bit of that, and it was a tough year
trying to relive it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinehurst epitomized the slide. He showed up unprepared and
weary from the Palmer Cup matches and missed the cut by eight shots
with rounds of 76-79.
</P>
<P>
   ``You either have it or you don't, and you're stuck with
whatever game you show up with,'' Kuchar said. ``At a major
championship course, if you don't have your A game, the course is
going to eat you up, and it did that to me. . . . Finally, my
game's starting to come around a little bit again. I'm able to see
those shots come off the way they used to.''
</P>
<P>
   He had no guarantee that a different decision would have
extended his wonderful ride. Garcia turned pro and has had amazing
success. England's Justin Rose turned pro and became a golfing
disaster, playing in 22 events before making his first cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt for Justin,'' Kuchar said, ``but I didn't find myself
thinking, `Hey, that could have been me.' . . . I still think
things will work out in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
