<HEADER>
A5449 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHALE-TRAINERS11-COX     07-10 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHALE-TRAINERS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Students learn how to train dolphins
 &HT;    By Paul Lomartire
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ SeaWorld trainer Lindsay Rubincam seemed a bit
harsh.
</P>
<P>
   She scolded Heather Zeigra, 13, for simply dangling her hand in
a huge killer-whale pool at the theme park's Shamu Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heather, don't do that,'' Rubincam warned. ``That water is
their home, and they might not like it. If they don't know you,
you're an intruder to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Heather had paid $349 to be a SeaWorld trainer for a day and get
a close-up look at what Rubincam and other trainers do for a
living.
</P>
<P>
   One thing she does is respect the killer whales _ particularly
on this day, since a calf had just been born.
</P>
<P>
   The birth made the whales hyper-protective of their 36-foot-deep
pool home, Rubincam said. And though her words seemed a bit
impatient at the time, they proved wise a week later, when a man
was found dead in a killer whale's tank.
</P>
<P>
   Early Tuesday, Daniel Dukes' nude body was found draped on the
back of 11,000-pound Tilikum, a male killer whale in a
breeder/research pool. Some time Monday night, while trainers
charted data on the newborn at another pool and security patrolled
the area, the 27-year-old man apparently went for a swim with
22-foot Tilikum, the largest killer whale in captivity. An autopsy
released Wednesday concluded that Dukes drowned in the frigid
52-degree water.
</P>
<P>
   The pools at Shamu Stadium are also classrooms for SeaWorld's
popular Trainer-For-A-Day program, which started in January. Two
people a day spend about eight hours working with SeaWorld's
dolphins and whales _ all under the watch of professionals such as
Rubincam.
</P>
<P>
   Most participants are in their early 20s or teens, like Zeigra,
who's from Raleigh, N.C., and her partner, Kathleen Reilly, 15,
from Long Island, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Dukes' death will not jeopardize the program, a SeaWorld vice
president said Wednesday. In fact, it might do the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who wants to see what we actually do can sign up and
see firsthand, and it's not just a show,'' said Chuck Tompkins,
vice president for animal training. ``You see backstage. We have
nothing to hide.''
</P>
<P>
   Tilikum is the only killer whale at SeaWorld that trainers won't
swim with _ because he's more than twice the size of performing
female whales and, as a breeding male, too unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very cautious around him,'' said Tompkins.
</P>
<P>
   Tilikum is a one-trick whale. For daily shows, a trainer runs
along the perimeter of the performing pool, and Tilikum's massive
body splashes the first rows of spectators.
</P>
<P>
   The SeaWorld death wasn't the only bad marine mammal news this
week. Researchers told The New York Times that studies of dolphins
in the wild have revealed that the mammals have the power and
capacity to kill.
</P>
<P>
   Tompkins has heard it all before.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other side of this story is you're talking a very small
percentage of extreme activists who have a narrow opinion on
animals in captivity from dogs to cats to horses to cows. Their
opinion is that none should be under the care of man, but we know
that's not realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   If not for marine theme parks, Tompkins asked, where could
scientists do long-term research on killer whales? The whales are
believed to be smarter than dolphins and fiercer than sharks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way that somebody could come in here,'' continued
Tompkins, ``see what we do, spend time with the trainers and accuse
us of not taking care of these animals.''
</P>
<P>
   Trainers treat orcas gingerly
</P>
<P>
   For Heather and Kathleen, training started with a 7 a.m.
wet-suit fitting. Then it was on to the fish room to fill buckets
with precise amounts of sardines, herring and other fish for
dolphins and whales used in the ``Terrors of the Deep'' shows.
</P>
<P>
   There's dirty work involved _ including scrubbing buckets and
the fish room _ but then comes the fun. Wannabe trainers feed the
dolphins and learn the arm signals that tell dolphins when to leap
and flip.
</P>
<P>
   After lunch, the teens moved ``backstage'' at Shamu Stadium.
They tossed food into giant whale mouths and saw up close how orcas
are trained.
</P>
<P>
   Rubincam told the teens that trainers aren't allowed to even
stick a toe in a killer-whale pool until they've completed a full
year of training. ``And then the contact is extremely limited.''
</P>
<P>
   Each killer whale has a specific trainer, Rubincam explained
while a female whale named Umma practiced swimming on her side,
waving a fin.
</P>
<P>
   The girls got to help Rubincam work with Taku, a 5-year-old
male, as he learned a trick called a belly breach. The trainer used
a white pole with what looked like a pom-pom at the end to signal
Taku.
</P>
<P>
   The young trainers took turns slapping the water, a signal for
Taku to leap, and held the pole that the killer whale tried to
touch with his arched tail.
</P>
<P>
   Both teens are considering careers with marine mammals.
</P>
<P>
   That career choice is based on passion, not cash. A trainer's
salary starts just below $15,000 annually, and a senior trainer
with 15 years' experience can earn $35,000.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing about this week's death in a killer-whale pool,
Heather remembered how cautious Rubincam and other pros were.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were a little bit tenser around the killer whales than
the dolphins.''
</P>
<P>
   And now she knows why.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
