<HEADLINE>
MALCOLM CARPENTER, 77, SCIENTIST WHO STUDIED BRAIN-MOTOR LINK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (js) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Malcolm Breckenridge Carpenter, a retired neuroanatomist who
helped map the pathways of the brain that coordinate movement and
equilibrium, died on June 25 at Hershey Medical Center in
Pennsylvania. He was 77 and lived in Hershey.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a heart attack, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter's work shed new light on motor disorders, particularly
those caused by diseases of the basal ganglia, the interconnected
groups of masses of gray substance deep in the cerebral hemispheres
and in the upper brain stem. His contributions furthered research
into defects in the neural networks responsible for ailments like
Parkinson's disease.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter was the author of a standard textbook, ``Human
Neuroanatomy,'' which went into its eighth edition in 1983. It was
translated into a score of languages and remains in use in some 200
medical schools worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   He also wrote ``Core Text of Neuroanatomy'' (fourth ed., 1991),
and, with J.C. Madigan, ``Cerebellum of the Rhesus Monkey,''
(1971). He was a past president of the International Basal Ganglia
Society, consultant to the National Institutes of Health, associate
editor of the American Journal of Anatomy, and a member of the
editorial boards of Neurology, Neurobiology and the Journal of
Comparative Neurology.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter, who was born in Montrose, Colo., graduated from
Columbia College in 1943 and received his medical degree at the
Long Island College of Medicine in 1947. He completed his residency
at Columbia University, joined the department of anatomy in 1953
and rose to full professor in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976 he became chairman of the department of anatomy at the
Uniformed Services University of the Health Sciences in Bethesda,
Md. He was chairman until 1987 and retired as professor of anatomy
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Carolyn Sloan Carpenter, died in February, after
nearly 50 years of marriage. He is survived by three sons, Dr.
Duncan B., of Saddle River, N.J., Gregory S., of Glencoe, Ill., and
Rustin I., of Acton, Mass.; a sister, Patria Barbary of Taos, N.M.,
and eight grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
