<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FEMALE CHAMPIONS TAKE OVER ROSE BOWL
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA , Calif. _ Pompoms fluttering on the sidelines,
starlets twinkling in the stands. This was the traditional feminine
presence in the hallowed oval called the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, as this century runs out, there was not a drum
majorette in sight. Instead, 22 women from China and the United
States were tearing up the Rose Bowl lawn, kicking a round ball
with the side of their boots in the championship game of the
Women's World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   In the famous den where Roy Riegels of California ran the wrong
way with a fumble in the college Rose Bowl, where John Riggins
rumbled for a winning touchdown for Washington in the professional
Super Bowl, there were players named Sun Wen and Mia Hamm.
</P>
<P>
   Now the women are part of the legacy, with over 90,000 fans
packing the joint, making it the largest crowd to watch a women's
soccer game anywhere in the world, and presumably the largest crowd
to watch a women's sports event in history.
</P>
<P>
   The fans were here to cheer for the Americans, a zestful bunch
that has been building for a decade and was now trying to hold off
the Chinese, who have come on strong in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans had won the first women's world soccer
championship in China in 1991, and then won the Summer Olympic
Games gold medal in 1996, and now there was something else at stake
_ the possibility of a professional league.
</P>
<P>
   The quest for financial backing from corporate America is now
linked with the legacy of a packed house in perhaps the most famous
football/soccer stadium in North America.
</P>
<P>
   The American players, women from their late teens to their early
30s, have their own takes on playing in the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Waking up on New Year's Day, temperature in the 80s, the Rose
Bowl on television,'' said Julie Foudy, from Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I picture all the roses in the parade,'' said Michelle Akers
of Seattle. ``My father and stepmother are watching the game on
television. I get bored and I go outside and kick a soccer ball.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're asking the wrong person,'' was the smiling response of
Tracy Ducar, a reserve goalkeeper, who has been part of the soccer
generation for just about all of her 26 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there's an alliance of four bowls now, but I still
think of the Rose Bowl as the biggest bowl game of all,'' said
Saskia Webber, another reserve goalkeeper from Princeton, N.J., who
added, ``My mom's from Holland, and she knows about the Rose
Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rose Bowl became part of American mythology back in the days
of radio, when Jack Benny and his merry band would pack themselves
into Benny's ancient Maxwell and bumble their way to the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   One can imagine Benny showing up Saturday and turning to his
wife and his sidekicks and saying: ``Mary! Don! They're kicking a
ball all over the Rose Bowl! Rochester! Dennis! Those are ...
women!''
</P>
<P>
   The Rose Bowl has become identified with soccer, starting with
the 1984 Summer Games, when Olympic patrons filled the stadium to
watch teams from Brazil and France. The huge outpouring for soccer
led to the United States being awarded the 1994 men's World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The famous arena had its tragic, spectacular and tedious
moments. In a first-round game, Andres Escobar of Colombia
deflected the ball into his own goal, and was gunned down
mysteriously when the team returned home.
</P>
<P>
   In the round of 16, Romania and Argentina played a show-time
Magic-Bird 3-2 game, and then in the finals, Italy and Brazil
played a dreary scoreless tie that ended with Roberto Baggio
missing a penalty kick.
</P>
<P>
   With Major League Soccer moving into the Rose Bowl in 1996, the
15 largest soccer crowds in the United States have now taken place
in the Rose Bowl. But women had never set a competitive foot in the
Rose Bowl until March of this year, when the American women played
an exhibition with Mexico, followed by a game by the home-team
Galaxy of the MLS.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans beat Mexico, 3-0, in the first game, after which
was heard the sound of many thousands of drivers gunning their
engines. Since then, these women have become even more of a
national attraction. ``I came to a game in 1994 when the men drew
90,000 for a game with Mexico,'' Webber said the other day. ``Most
of those fans were Mexican-Americans, and that was great, but this
time most of the fans will be Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, fans have jammed into this sunken bowl to see
Pacific 10 champions battle Big Ten champions, sometimes for the
national title. This is where Ryan Leaf of Washington State could
not get off a final pass against Michigan in the 1998 Rose Bowl.
This is where Leon Lett of Dallas frolicked foolishly only to have
Don Beebe of Buffalo strip him of the ball on the 1-yard line in
the Super Bowl in 1993. This is where Taffarel of Brazil and
Gianluca Pagliuca of Italy let nothing get past them for 120
minutes in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is the stadium where Gao Hong and Briana Scurry defended
their goals in 1999. Now the Rose Bowl will have a history of women
who did not twirl a baton, but rather kicked a ball far down the
field. Halfway back in this fading century, Jack Benny would have
been speechless.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 1449EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
