A5457 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-ECKSTEIN-NYT &LR;      07-10 0447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ECKSTEIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARRY ECKSTEIN, 75, PROFESSOR WHO STUDIED POLITICAL CULTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (js) 
 By ERIC PACE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harry H. Eckstein, a political scientist who argued that a
critically important role in determining whether democracy
succeeded in a country was played by the country's political
culture, or what he called its authority patterns, died on June 22
in Hoag Hospital in Newport Beach, Calif. He was 75 and lived near
Newport Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was heart failure, the University of California at
Irvine said in announcing his death.
</P>
<P>
   At his death, Eckstein, who lived in Nazi Germany as a boy, was
distinguished research professor of political science at the Irvine
campus, where he had taught since 1980. He previously taught at
Harvard and Princeton universities.
</P>
<P>
   His view of the importance of a country's political culture in
the success of democracy, and not just its constitution and formal
institutions, was very influential among political scientists in
the United States and abroad, beginning in the 1960s, said Walter
F. Murphy, who retired in 1995 as the McCormick Professor of
Jurisprudence in Princeton's department of politics.
</P>
<P>
   And Gabriel A. Almond, a political scientist who taught at
Stanford University, wrote in 1998 that Eckstein had ``won a
lasting place in the systematic literature on the properties and
conditions of democratic stability.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Eckstein's theory, ``governments perform well to
the extent that their authority patterns are congruent with the
authority patterns of other units of society,'' like families,
schools and workplaces.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said Eckstein had found ``that the Norwegian system was
very compatible with democracy, because you could criticize, you
could have give and take.'' But in the Germany that Eckstein had
known as a boy, Murphy said, ``the father ruled the family; in the
school, the professor was God, etc., and his argument was that it
was almost impossible to have a democratic system unless you
changed that subculture as well.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He believed that you could do that,'' Murphy said, ``but you
had to work to change it.''
</P>
<P>
   Eckstein, born into a Jewish family in Schotten, Germany, was
brought to the United States when he was 12, lived in Columbus,
Ohio, and went on to obtain bachelor's, master's and doctorate
degrees, all in political science, from Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   His first four marriages ended in divorce.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, the former Marlene Hamilton, whom he
married in 1995; a son, Jonathan Eckstein of Princeton, N.J.; a
stepson, Eric Sterling Ament of Ruidoso, N.M., and two
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 1450EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990710.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5458 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     07-10 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: AN UNFULFILLED DREAM FROM RICKY BYRDSONG
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Ill., Ky., La., Mich., N.J., Pa.)  (rk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ricky Byrdsong was buried in Atlanta on Saturday, eight days
after he was killed in Chicago in a racist's rampage that left two
dead and several wounded. The athletic community remained in a
state of shock.
</P>
<P>
   The former Northwestern basketball coach was a well-liked member
of a sprawling coaching fraternity. Among those attending memorial
services in Evanston, Ill., last Wednesday were Big Ten
Commissioner Jim Delany; former Michigan coach Steve Fisher; former
Arizona players Sean Elliott and Steve Kerr, now with the San
Antonio Spurs; and Eastern Kentucky Coach Scott Perry.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Washington, commissioner of the Southwestern Athletic
Conference, was still shaken. ``You always hear about people being
killed, but very seldom do you hear about someone you knew _ and
knew well,'' Washington said from his office in Louisiana. ``This
blew us away. I mean, he was out there trying to get a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington gained national prominence as executive director of
the Black Coaches Association, which he co-founded in 1988. The
organization was begun to address issues pertaining to the
participation and employment of members of minority groups in
intercollegiate athletics. The association's goal was to help
minority-group members become coaches or administrators at the high
school, collegiate or professional levels.
</P>
<P>
   As executive director of the BCA, Washington grew close to
Byrdsong. They were assistant coaches who climbed the ladder and
pushed against the barriers that kept black assistants as
recruiters but locked them out of head-coaching positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky was a friend to everybody,'' Washington recalled. ``He
was an active member. He was never out front, but you could depend
on him to support you. That's what he brought to the table.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, though, the fact Byrdsong was out of coaching at the
time of his death underlines the failure of the association to
adequately take care of its members by creating an old-boy and
old-girl network of its own. Byrdsong was named the coach at
Northwestern in 1993. In his first season the Wildcats had their
first winning season in 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   But during a game at Minnesota in February 1994, Byrdsong left
the bench, walked into the stands, chatting with fans and
exchanging high-fives. Blaming stress, Byrdsong then took a 12-day,
four-game leave of absence. He was dismissed after the 1996-97
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The episode at Northwestern was just devastating to him,''
Washington said. ``I don't think he ever bounced back.''
</P>
<P>
   To suggest that the BCA could have saved Ricky Byrdsong's life
is a stretch. He was the victim of a random shooting that could
have occurred anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Washington feels the association could have played a more
forceful role in helping Byrdsong get back into the coaching
profession.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the black coaches could have pulled him in,''
Washington said. ``That was what the BCA was all about. When a guy
lost his job, when a guy was in trouble, we came to his aid. We
stayed in contact, tried to get counseling. Nobody picked up the
phone and used connections to get him a job with Nike. No one
called and said, `Let me give you an administrative assistant job.'
The whole reasoning for the BCA was to help each other. Now we're
back to this where we eat each other alive.''
</P>
<P>
   What has happened to a movement that, only a few years ago, had
television executives and college administrators panicked over the
prospect of a proposed boycott? Washington said what has happened
is that contentment brought about by the illusion of progress has
created a false sense of accomplishment. The very nature of
Byrdsong's violent death underlines deeply rooted problems that
still need to be addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has happened to us is that now that the movement has done
its job, so now brothers don't think the Black Coaches Association
had anything to do with them getting their jobs,'' Washington said.
``It's almost like black folks thinking Rosa Parks had nothing to
do with where they are today.''
</P>
<P>
   The BCA is in transition, establishing offices in Somerset, N.J.
But it is also moving from its early grass-roots passion to a more
sophisticated approach that uses the power of law and the enormous
pool of minority athletes to pressure the system for inclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Washington stepped down as executive director in 1998 to become
the commissioner of the Southwestern Athletic Conference. The BCA's
board of director's subsequently announced the appointment of C.
Timothy Stoner, a Philadelphia-based lawyer, as Washington's
replacement. The transition has not been smooth, nor the
relationship amicable.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring the Black Coaches Association's board of directors
initiated legal action against Washington in federal court. The
BCA's suit against Washington sought an injunction and an
accounting of finances handled by Washington while he was executive
director. Washington denied any impropriety and asserted a claim of
his own against the BCA for money allegedly due to him. Washington
and the BCA have agreed to submit the dispute to binding
arbitration in place of litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Stoner said the association embraces the mission that Washington
outlined more than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we move forward the BCA will be in position to make sure
our coaches, our student athletes and our officials have a voice,''
he said. ``We want to organize athletes at the high school level;
we want to use legal pressure to get more minority coaching jobs.
When someone reaches the level of being a Big Ten coach, like
Ricky, there should have been other options.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 1455EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990710.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5459 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEMINGWAY11-COX     07-10 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEMINGWAY11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Papa's long gone, but memories linger
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY WEST, Fla. _ He drove ambulances in Spain during World War
I, he wooed the literary elite in Paris, he fished for marlin off
Havana, he stalked mountain trout in Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   But no place seemed to have a stronger hold on Ernest Hemingway
than Key West, the funky end-of-the-continent fishing village that
the bearded ``Papa'' called home for most of the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   As the nation gears up to celebrate Hemingway's 100th birthday
July 21 _ events are scheduled in Michigan, Illinois, Boston and
Havana _ many fans of the Nobel Prize-winning author will make
their pilgrimage here.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists: A curse and blessing
</P>
<P>
   About 10,000 Hemingway devotees are expected for the 19th annual
Hemingway Days Festival, a 10-day event that begins Friday and
includes offerings as diverse as a famous look-alike contest, a
marlin tournament, a short story contest and maybe even a mock
running of the bulls down Duval Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``The connections are just so deep,'' said Andy Newman, a
publicist for the event. ``In so many ways, Hemingway is an icon
for Key West.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, put in terms that Hemingway himself might admire, ``It's an
excuse to have a literary festival in a bar,'' said Karen Thurman,
another festival organizer.
</P>
<P>
   But for all its panache and posturing, for all its spiritual
kinship with Hemingway's lifestyle of manly fun, the festival takes
place against the backdrop of a city struggling to cope with
rampant growth and its own spectacular success as a tourist mecca.
</P>
<P>
   Key West today is far from the simple, sleepy village where the
famous author spent his mornings pecking at a typewriter in the
study of his stately Spanish Colonial home on Whitehead Street and
his evenings at Sloppy Joe's Bar hefting drinks and swapping
fishing lies with his decidedly nonliterary buddies.
</P>
<P>
   Hemingway's home is still the center of a picturesque district
of gingerbread-trimmed homes with wide porches and lush,
overhanging tropical greenery, and Key West's streets are still
narrow avenues into a quaint, scaled-down past.
</P>
<P>
   But condos and parking garages now dot the crowded landscape,
while cruise ships disgorge 500,000 passengers a year to traipse
down Duval Street's riot of T-shirt shops and souvenir emporiums.
Trendy cafes and upscale guest houses with facades fit for
Architectural Digest charge New York prices.
</P>
<P>
   Housing costs have risen so steeply that many low-paid tourism
workers must crowd three and four people into one- or two-bedroom
apartments that go for $1,500 or more a month, while the cost of a
tumbled-down shack in the historic district might top $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   Water contamination problems from a badly needed sewer line
replacement project have made swimming near the shore a hazard,
while state regulators have imposed a strict construction slowdown
throughout much of the Keys because the area doesn't have the
infrastructure _ roads, schools, sewers, etc. _ to handle the
booming population.
</P>
<P>
   And federal regulators recently outlawed the popular practice of
renting out small enclosed rooms that hundreds of homeowners added
beneath their houses on stilts. The ban will lessen the area's
vulnerability to hurricane losses, but has made the affordable
housing crisis even more acute.
</P>
<P>
   It's all enough that ``Papa'' might load up his famous fishing
boat and head for some simpler, undiscovered island were he still
around.
</P>
<P>
   But locals seem to realize they're at something of a crossroads.
A recent round of public hearings was aimed at the soul-searching
question of tourism's impact, with a commission listening to dozens
of complaints from residents who say that while visitors bring
scads of money, they are also too loud and rowdy and leave too much
trash in the streets and on the nearby coral reef.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have too many tourists visiting Key West,'' said
Richard Malas, who runs a tropical drink stand near one of the
town's popular beaches, which has been mostly deserted lately
because of the water contamination problems. ``It's really killing
the infrastructure, but without the tourists, we have no
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Novelist still a strong presence
</P>
<P>
   Business leaders seem aware that the problems must be addressed,
and steps are being taken. The city has started a $53 million sewer
line replacement project _ work being done strictly with local
funds _ and there is talk of creating affordable housing so that
workers won't flee the area.
</P>
<P>
   City leaders have just passed an ordinance to tighten pollution
rules for the hundreds of boaters who dock at area marinas, while
new regulations stemming from creation of the Florida Keys National
Marine Sanctuary are curbing damage to the coral reefs.
</P>
<P>
   And whatever the problems, it's clear that Key West still holds
a mythical, mystical power over thousands of visitors. Couples with
hands entwined stroll the tree-shaded streets at night as a fresh
ocean breeze ruffles the greenery, while families laugh at the
curious collection of street performers who gather at Mallory
Square each sunset for an only-in-Key-West celebration.
</P>
<P>
   And hundreds still line up each day to pay homage to ``Papa,''
touring the grounds of his home, petting offspring of his famous
six-toed cats, dipping a toe in his swimming pool, admiring the
room where he labored over masterpieces.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a rift two years ago with some of Hemingway's
descendants who wanted a cut of the festival's profits, and
problems this year attracting corporate sponsors, it seems clear
that some kind of festival honoring the famous author will always
be held in Key West.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers say the interest is just overwhelming _ and comes
from all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got an in-flight magazine for Japan Air, Michael Palin
from the BBC and a Swedish television network all doing stories
this year,'' said Thurman. ``The amount of attention is just
amazing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
