<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-KOCH-BEAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOCH IS OUT OF HOSPITAL; BEAME IS TREATED FOR PAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After being treated successfully for what doctors
called a moderate heart attack, former Mayor Ed Koch left the
hospital Saturday, wreathed in smiles and trailed by reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no fear of death,'' he said at a news conference
beforehand at New York Weill Cornell Center of Presbyterian
Hospital, wearing a pale blue shirt and suspenders. ``But I want to
go all at once, not slice by slice.''
</P>
<P>
   As Koch soliloquized on the benefits of regular exercise and on
the misfortunes of those without health insurance, another retired
mayor was being treated downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Former Mayor Abraham Beame, 93, was reported to be in
satisfactory condition at New York University Medical Center after
being admitted with chest pains Friday night, a hospital spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Koch, 74, an exercise enthusiast accustomed to daily 6 a.m.
workouts, said he would not yet return to the gym. However, he said
he would continue to write his opinion column and movie reviews,
and planned to see the new Spike Lee film, ``Summer of Sam,''
Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   His doctors said that the heart attack Koch suffered July 1 was
the result of a clogged artery. They performed angioplasty to clear
out the blockage and reopened the vessel.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Timothy Sanborn, director of the Weill Cornell cardiac
catheterization laboratory, said that Koch's heart muscle has
already made significant recovery. ``We have the bionic man here,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Koch and Beame appeared together as recently as June 28, joining
former Mayor David Dinkins in a protest against Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's efforts to revise the City Charter.
</P>
<P>
   On that day, with their own political woes behind them, the
former mayors seemed to share the sentiment that Koch expressed
Saturday upon leaving the hospital: ``Life has been very good to
me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 1508EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990710.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5466 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARENTING-BOOK16-COX     07-10 0362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARENTING-BOOK16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Practical parenting examples book's focus
 &HT;    By Emily Rahimi
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ If you are sick of reading parenting books that
are peppered with lists and advice, Dr. Kyle Pruett has a solution.
</P>
<P>
   In his latest book, ``Me, Myself and I: How Children Build Their
Sense of Self'' (Goddard Press, $19.95) Pruett guides parents on
how to shape children from 18 months to 36 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moms and dads hardly have time to look at the labels in their
clothing, besides reading a textbook,'' he said. ``There is a lot
of science but I disguise the fact.'' As a result, this book has
simple language and includes many examples to help parents
strengthen their relationships with their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the end of babyhood, where children become
themselves,'' said Pruett. Because most people do not have a memory
before the age of 5, many feel that this time is not significant in
a child's life. However, Pruett said this is not true, ``the first
years really last forever.''
</P>
<P>
   He said a variety of people, including men, women, parents and
grandparents, find this book useful, as well as people who are
considering having children: ``It helps them think of whether they
are ready.''
</P>
<P>
   As a father of three, ranging in age from 27 to 5 months, Pruett
has firsthand experience. Residing in Guilford, Conn., he has
practiced child and family psychiatry for more than 20 years,
working as a clinical professor of child psychiatry at Yale
University and writing for many parenting and family magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Pruett also works with national agencies for the assistance of
young children. He is president of Zero to Three: National Center
for Infants, Toddlers, and Families, an early childhood development
think tank, and a founding member of Father to Father, chaired by
Vice President Al Gore, which is a campaign to unite men in being
positive influences in children's lives. Additionally, he is a
presidential appointee and consultant to the Committee on Preschool
Children of the American Psychiatric Association.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
