</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990710.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5467 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ANDRO-DEBATE-3TAK     07-10 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANDRO-DEBATE-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A YEAR AFTER MCGWIRE'S RECORD, ANDRO IS IN A QUIET LIMBO 
</HEADLINE>
   A Special Report  
(See also BBO-ANDRO-LIMITS.) 
(EDS: An abridged version, BBO-ANDRO-DEBATE-SHORT, will also be
filed.) 
(lh) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON and JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It took Lee Stevens of the Texas Rangers 11 years _ parts of
nine seasons in the minor leagues, and two full ones in Japan _ to
finally stick in baseball's major leagues. Stevens, 32, is not
wasting his shot; he's chasing every edge he can get.
</P>
<P>
   Androstenedione is one of those edges.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, who has hit 14 home runs and driven in 48 runs so far
this season, said that during workouts last winter he used
androstenedione, the diet supplement whose sales have exploded
since Mark McGwire, the first baseman for the St. Louis Cardinals,
acknowledged using it last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to take it for a month, take two or three weeks off
and then go back to it just to keep shocking your body,'' Stevens
said recently of his off-season androstenedione use. ``It was doing
something for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens' use of androstenedione _ many experts believe it is
tantamount to a steroid _ has produced no great public comment,
much less any kind of controversy, and he is hardly a rarity in his
unhidden but largely anonymous use of androstenedione. In fact,
baseball officials, from union leaders to individual trainers on
major league clubs, estimate that from 5 to 10 percent of the 750
players in the major leagues have used, or are using,
androstenedione. Others in the medical community suspect the number
is higher.
</P>
<P>
   So a year after McGwire acknowledged using the supplement smack
in the middle of his record-breaking, 70-homer season, baseball and
androstenedione remain in a quiet limbo. More than a few experts
believe it is a convenient stall.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball has not banned or discouraged the use of
androstenedione, a product that, while sold legally over the
counter and over the Internet in the United States, is banned by
the National Football League, the National Collegiate Athletic
Association and the International Olympic Committee as a
performance-enhancing and potentially harmful drug. Baseball's top
officials have stuck to their position that they will neither
condone nor discourage use of the supplement until the sport's
scientific study of its effects is completed.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of baseball's stance believe that the sport's failure to
act aggressively against the use of androstenedione in part has
been influenced by a reluctance to diminish McGwire's record.
Baseball officials, including the commissioner and a senior
official with the players' union, reject that assertion.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever baseball's motivation in delaying action on
androstenedione, critics of the supplement regard Lee Stevens as
being, in many ways, the face of the danger they forecast a year
ago. Stevens says that androstenedione is legal, that it has
baseball's blessing, and that he takes it without worry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt more intense in my workouts,'' said Stevens, who does
not use the supplement during the season. ``And I did get a lot
stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   For the experts alarmed by androstenedione, players like Stevens
are engaged in conduct that could harm their health. The experts
are also worried that the players have popularized androstenedione
use among American youngsters, and have set back the effort to
clean up the problem of drug use in sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Olympic movement, the National Football League and the
NCAA have all outlawed andro,'' said Barry McCaffrey, the retired
general who heads White House drug control policy. ``And we have in
place this huge apparatus to keep drugs away from youth in America.
But since McGwire's revelation, andro sales have gone up five- to
tenfold. You can get it everywhere, classified as a food
supplement, which sounds so benign. In fact, I'll bet we have a
problem. And if it's dangerous, we better get it off the shelves.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent interviews with more than four dozen major-league players
and team trainers, as well as with more than a dozen medical
experts, make clear that the subject of androstenedione use remains
a common and thorny topic in clubhouses. Players swap theories and
concerns; trainers by and large are against using the supplement,
but are limited in what they can do to prevent its use; team
officials abide by baseball's public position of neutrality, but
have become alarmed by regular reports that use among
minor-leaguers is on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, baseball has a great responsibility,'' said Bud
Selig, the commissioner of baseball. ``I want to be very careful
that we are proceeding with all of the empirical data that one
should have. And it doesn't exist at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   THE PROS AND CONS: EXPERTS REACT TO BOOMING DRUG
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Don Catlin runs the Olympic drug testing laboratory at UCLA
and helped set up the drug protocols for the NFL, which bans the
use of androstenedione.
</P>
<P>
   At work each morning, Catlin checks his e-mail and finds
by-now-familiar notes from colleagues around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say things like, `What in the world is going on in
America?' '' Catlin said. ``They can't understand how something
like andro, which their countries all banned a long time ago, is
prevalent in America. We're generally seen as the protectors
internationally, with a government committed to fighting drug abuse
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is very embarrassing. Androstenedione is a steroid,
there's no question about it. It shouldn't be available.''
</P>
<P>
   Catlin's opinion is shared by many other experts on drug policy.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Charles Yesalis, a Penn State professor and co-author of
``The Steroids Game,'' is frequently asked how androstenedione can
be sold legally over the counter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say: `It beats me. It makes no sense at all,' '' Yesalis
said.
</P>
<P>
   While baseball is correct that there are few reputable, clinical
studies of androstenedione, interviews with more than two dozen
physicians, researchers and endocrinologists showed little
variation when it came to assessing androstenedione's status as a
supplement and its potential for harm.
</P>
<P>
   With rare exceptions, most believed androstenedione, or andro,
as it is commonly known, should be re-classified as an anabolic
steroid, or at least be made a prescription drug. Most worried that
additional research will in time prove that andro, especially taken
in high doses, significantly raises testosterone levels in the
blood and perhaps levels of the female hormone estrogen. An excess
of either is linked to a host of health problems.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Iowa State University study of 30 young men found that
andro did not help build muscle but did raise the risk of heart
disease, pancreatic cancer and breast enlargement. The study has
been criticized _ not so much by the supplement industry, but by
doctors who believe it understated andro's threat because the test
subjects took dosages far smaller than many body builders routinely
ingest.
</P>
<P>
   Androstenedione is a synthetic form of a male hormone that
occurs naturally in the body and is converted to testosterone. It
was developed by doctors in the former East Germany, who began
experimenting on athletes with powerful steroids in a
state-sanctioned effort to dominate athletics. Documents salvaged
by the German molecular biologist Werner Franke just after the
unification of Germany disclosed how the East Germans used andro,
which was not yet banned by the International Olympic Committee, in
the 1988 Olympic Games in Seoul. Andro was taken to prolong the
effects of the more powerful anabolic steroids that competitors had
stopped taking weeks before the Games to avoid a positive test for
steroids.
</P>
<P>
   In a nasal spray form, andro was used immediately before
competition. German doctors said in a patent application for
androstenedione at the time that this would raise the testosterone
levels of experienced elite athletes by 237 percent in just 15
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt like a volcanic eruption,'' said the East German
Olympic swimmer Rick Hannermann.
</P>
<P>
   Andro came on the U.S. market only a few years ago and is
available over the counter because of the 1994 Dietary Supplement
Health and Education Act. Passed despite the objections of the Food
and Drug Administration, the law produced a new product class: Food
or diet supplements that can be sold without passing any premarket
testing and without any government agency's attesting to their
safety or effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   To the $15 billion supplement industry, andro has been a
bonanza, with derivatives surfacing all the time. But not everyone
in this marketplace condones how it has been marketed to
teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young teens shouldn't be using any of these things,'' said Dr.
Scott Connolly, a physician and the founder of MET-Rx, a national
retailer of supplements including the compound androstendiol, an
androstenedione derivative. ``At the same time, there is this
belief that testosterone is bad for you. But there is abundant data
that the normalization of testosterone in the body throughout life
has many benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Connolly said he sees a market that serves avid body builders,
power athletes, and perhaps an aging male population and women
combating obesity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not antiregulation,'' he said. ``But let's take time to
intellectually examine this. A quick decision would be foolish.''
</P>
<P>
   WHAT THE PLAYERS SAY: DISCOUNTING RISKS DESPITE THE FEARS
</P>
<P>
   Mike Simms, a third baseman for the Texas Rangers, used andro
last season. He did not notice any significant results, and
stopped. He said his decision not to try it again was cemented when
he began to read that andro could have minimal effects in building
strength and disastrous effects for his health.
</P>
<P>
   ``One article said instead of raising testosterone, it raised
estrogen,'' Simms said. ``I don't know if that's been proven
medically, but when you start hearing stuff like that, that's not
going to help your baseball career.''
</P>
<P>
   Curiosity and confusion about andro, as well as its use, exists
throughout major-league clubhouses a year after McGwire set off
both outbursts of outrage from his detractors and spirited defenses
from his supporters. Mike Piazza of the New York Mets said he tried
andro several years ago, but found it ``overrated'' and gave it up.
Tony Gwynn of the San Diego Padres said andro is talked about
regularly, and used by some.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have discussions about this all the time,'' Gwynn said.
``What if it's the last year of your contract, and you feel you're
not playing well? With the kind of money out there, could creatine
or andro or steroids make a difference in your play? And if you
only take them one year to prolong your career, would it really be
dangerous to your health?''
</P>
<P>
   Most players are more reluctant to speak publicly about their
interest and use. Of the more than 50 players interviewed in recent
weeks, only four admitted to having at least tried andro. Baseball
officials say they believe the number of users is likely higher.
Gene Orza, the associate general counsel for the players' union,
said ``a good number'' of players might be users, probably some on
every major-league team. A handful of team trainers interviewed
said 5 to 10 percent _ 37 to 75 players _ was probably an accurate
figure.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The trainers said they were instinctively against players using
andro. But the trainers, as well as a team doctor in California,
said several reasons might account for the willingness of players
to risk taking the supplement: a belief that it is safe because it
is available; an athlete's sense of invincibility, and a skepticism
about expert opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most professionals have a very nonfatalistic outlook on
life,'' said Larry Starr, a trainer for the Florida Marlins who has
been in baseball for 28 years. ``I don't know if it's a sense of
indestructibility, but it's a sense of being able to withstand most
things, to be able to conquer most things. I think that's the way
they approach this.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an approach that some baseball officials feel has even
greater appeal for young players trying to make it to the majors.
Jim Duquette, an assistant general manager for the Mets, said two
players at the organization's Class A level were taking andro
earlier this year and were eventually sent for counseling.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there is a chance to make millions of dollars, some of
them think the risk is worth it,'' Duquette said. ``What we're
trying to tell them is, `You're talented enough to do it without
it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Other players interviewed about andro and baseball's position of
neutrality offered a mix of understanding, mild criticism and
dispirited resignation. Most said they felt the union was playing
the proper role in defending their right to take it while pushing
for more definitive information. Others said andro should be
outlawed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't sound like it's too good for you,'' said Joe
Girardi, the catcher for the Yankees. ``It's amazing the research
they've come out with. It doesn't really help you. If anything, the
stuff is going to hurt you. I don't understand why people would
take it. I mean, yeah, I think it should be banned.''
</P>
<P>
   But Girardi and others said that, at least in part because
baseball has no drug-testing policy in place anyway, enforcement of
any kind _ either through persuasion or policy _ would most likely
be futile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys are going to do whatever they have to do to keep up with
the times,'' said Damion Easley of the Detroit Tigers. ``It doesn't
matter what the union or anybody else says. They'll do whatever
they have to do and worry about the consequences later.''
</P>
<P>
   A WORK IN PROGRESS: BASEBALL'S STUDY IS CALLED A STALL
</P>
<P>
   When McGwire admitted last year that he had been taking, and
would continue to take, androstenedione, baseball officials and the
leaders of the players' union came to an agreement. Noting the
legality of andro, they pledged to conduct their own study to
evaluate the product's effects and risks. Two Harvard researchers
undertook the task.
</P>
<P>
   Critics at the time said the study was turning standard drug
product evaluation on its head, by opting to condone the use of a
substance that might be harmful.
</P>
<P>
   Now, nearly a year later, the researchers remain at work. In an
interview, one of the researchers, Dr. Benjamin Leder, conceded
that he ``agreed with about everything that was written'' in the
recent Iowa State study that asserted andro use might increase the
risk of heart disease or cancer. And Leder said he agreed with the
suggestion of the study's author that the federal government
``carefully consider intervening and removing androstenedione and
its derivatives from the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he would recommend to a weekend athlete interested in
experimenting with andro, Leder said: ``I'd tell them little is
known about andro and its possible effects, both beneficial or
toxic side effects. Taking anything when not much is known about it
is risky.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig and Orza said they were unmoved by the current thinking of
the Harvard researchers, and they emphasized that they were
determined to wait until the study was done before coming to a
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the scientists conclude it's something risky, we'll tell
the players it's risky,'' Orza said. ``We're not going to be shoved
into this decision.''
</P>
<P>
   To its critics, baseball's approach seems to be a cynical answer
to a worry about soiling McGwire's record by acknowledging that
during his record-breaking season, he used a substance that might
have artificially made him stronger and less susceptible to injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``The behavior of baseball has been ignorant and arrogant,''
said John Hoberman, a University of Texas professor whose has
studied the use of steroids by East German athletes. ``Andro is a
gateway drug to the use of anabolic steroids in the mainstream of
America. Baseball's position is just irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   One major-league executive, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity, said that baseball is cognizant of ``protecting''
McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   Both Selig and Orza ridicule such claims, calling them
``unfair'' and ``nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   After announcing early in the year that he intended to use andro
until it was declared illegal or prohibited by baseball, McGwire
has said little about his use of the substance. When he was asked
about his use of it last August, he told reporters that he actually
used andro to improve his sex drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for your sex life,'' McGwire said. ``I'm serious.
You guys think I'm joking, but I'm serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever McGwire's rationale for using andro, he has always had
defenders who have argued that whatever the medical or ethical
wisdom of his use of andro, it could not have played a significant
role in his hitting 70 home runs. Those defenders remain in force.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't have talent, no drug is going to make you be a
better player,'' said Tim Raines, the former Yankee who is now with
the Oakland Athletics. ``Maybe you'll get muscles, it might build
up your body, but it won't make you a ballplayer. You have to have
talent. McGwire didn't get big last year. If there was a guarantee,
I'd be taking it. We all would be taking it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 1520EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990710.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5470 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ANDRO-DEBATE-SHOR     07-10 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANDRO-DEBATE-SHORT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A YEAR AFTER MCGWIRE'S RECORD, ANDRO IS IN A QUIET LIMBO 
</HEADLINE>
   A Special Report  
(EDS: This is an abridged version of BBO-ANDRO-DEBATE.) 
(See also BBO-ANDRO-LIMITS.) 
(lh) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON and JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It took Lee Stevens of the Texas Rangers 11 years to finally
stick in baseball's major leagues. Stevens, 32, is not wasting his
shot; he's chasing every edge he can get.
</P>
<P>
   Androstenedione is one of those edges.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, who has hit 14 home runs and driven in 48 runs so far
this season, said that during workouts last winter he used
androstenedione, the diet supplement whose sales have exploded
since Mark McGwire, the first baseman for the St. Louis Cardinals,
acknowledged using it last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to take it for a month, take two or three weeks off
and then go back to it just to keep shocking your body,'' Stevens
said recently of his off-season androstenedione use. ``It was doing
something for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens is hardly a rarity in his unhidden but largely anonymous
use of androstenedione. In fact, baseball officials, from union
leaders to individual trainers on major-league clubs, estimate that
from 5 to 10 percent of the 750 players in the major leagues have
used, or are using, androstenedione. Others suspect the number is
higher.
</P>
<P>
   So a year after McGwire acknowledged using the supplement during
