u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ANDRO-LIMITS-NYT &LR;      07-10 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANDRO-LIMITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM THE HIGHEST LEVEL, A CALL FOR ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BBO-ANDRO-DEBATE.) 
(lh) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those eager to limit the availability of the dietary supplement
andro-stenedione include Barry McCaffrey, President Clinton's
antidrug chief, who last week said he is trying to finance a study
that could lead to the substance's being labeled a steroid, and
thus ordered off retail shelves across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to expedite the examination of androstenedione and
determine whether it can be classified an anabolic steroid under
the Anabolic Steroids Control Act,'' McCaffrey said.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that sales of androstenedione have exploded since Mark
McGwire acknowledged using the supplement last year during his
70-homer season, McCaffrey said: ``I'd like to get an answer on
andro as a steroid before the first game of this year's World
Series.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, McCaffrey has appealed to the Drug Enforcement
Administration. If the DEA can be convinced that andro is an
anabolic steroid, it can remove all andro-related products from
store shelves immediately, even though the diet supplement has yet
to be linked to any health-related problems in clinical studies.
</P>
<P>
   The steroids control act sets out a three-prong test for
determining what substances are to be registered as steroids. The
substance or drug must be chemically related to testosterone; it
must be pharmacologically related to testosterone (other than
estrogens, progestogens and corticosteroids); and it must be proven
clinically to promote muscle growth.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey said he believes there is ample data to prove that
andro meets the first two criteria for a steroid, leaving the
muscle-building criteria as yet unproven. Such a study, conducted
on animals, would take a few months and cost approximately $25,000,
McCaffrey said. McCaffrey's office is trying to locate funding for
the testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andro is a precursor to testosterone and there's also reason
to believe that a significant amount of the andro now available is
falsely labeled and also contains testosterone,'' McCaffrey said in
a recent interview. ``Products laced with testosterone are already
illegal. And there's no question that excessive testosterone use
poses significant, immediate risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have this huge apparatus in place to keep drugs away from
our youth, and here's a way for young athletes to sidestep doctors
and their parents and order this off the Internet,'' McCaffrey
said. ``There is a growing eagerness to set high school records to
get college scholarships and a growing belief that you've got to
chemically engineer the body to so.''
</P>
<P>
   Supplement makers and representatives of the billion-dollar
sports supplement industry say their androstenedione products are
safe, produced and sold legally, and are not anabolic steroids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Androstenedione is a safe product,'' said Michael Ford,
executive director of the National Nutritional Foods Association.
``Every time there's a big-selling dietary supplement, it suddenly
becomes controversial.''
</P>
</TEXT>
