<HEADLINE>
U.N. PLANS FORCE IN CONGO AFTER CEASE-FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (With CONGO)  
(lh) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The United Nations is preparing to send a large
peacekeeping force to help stabilize Congo once a cease-fire is
signed, despite reservations by the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan is preparing to recommend that
the Security Council send a force of between 15,000 and 20,000
soldiers, mainly drawn from African countries.
</P>
<P>
   But the United States has expressed its misgivings about the
likely size and expense of such an operation, officials and
diplomats say, evidently fearful that Congress will balk at paying
its 31 percent share of the bill at a time when it is already
paying for peacekeeping operations in Bosnia and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, when Secretary General Boutros Boutros-Ghali
proposed sending a 4,700-member force to suppress the genocide
under way in Rwanda, the United States blocked the plan, citing the
tight new restrictions President Clinton had placed on U.S. support
for new peacekeeping operations the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   But officials here say Annan feels strongly that having played a
prominent role in ending the conflicts in former Yugoslavia, the
United Nations must in all fairness do as much to help restore
peace to Congo.
</P>
</TEXT>
