u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-COLUMN-NIXON-NYT &LR;      07-10 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-COLUMN-NIXON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW JERSEY COMMUNITY REMEMBERS AN EX-RESIDENT EX-PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SADDLE RIVER, N.J. _ Some people in Westchester County, N.Y.,
are atwitter and others are aghast at the possibility that the
President and Mrs. Clinton might settle there at the end of the
Clinton presidency. If they do, they will hardly be the first
former presidential family to head this way. After all, Ulysses S.
Grant retired to East 63rd Street in Manhattan, Grover Cleveland
retired to Princeton, N.J., Theodore Roosevelt went back to
Sagamore Hill on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   And there was Richard M. Nixon, wishing to be closer to his
daughters and their families in New York and Philadelphia, who was
the last former president to choose the New York suburbs for his
retirement home.
</P>
<P>
   After living for several years in Manhattan, Nixon moved to this
north Bergen County Republican redoubt in 1981 and stayed for
almost nine years in a big house on five wooded acres. He is
remembered here today as the private man in the coat and tie who
was devoted to his staff, generous to children and liked to keep to
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be completely different with the Clintons,''
said Saddle River Police Chief Robert Re, who headed Nixon's
private security detail from 1985 on. ``Just think of the Clinton
entourage.''
</P>
<P>
   People in the plusher parts of Westchester County may fret at
the prospect of a boisterous ex-president and his politically
ambitious wife moving to their neighborhood, but Saddle River
quickly learned that, at nearly 70 years old, Nixon was beyond the
tumult of public life when he moved here, and once settled, he
spent his years more as a half-remembered headline than as a
continuing event.
</P>
<P>
   With Mrs. Nixon in frail health, the Nixons did not join a
church, did not take up with a circle of local friends, and did not
join the Valley Club, a social group for couples of a certain age
and rank in Saddle River.
</P>
<P>
   When he traveled, it was in one car with a plainclothes man at
the wheel, but no outriders or escort vehicles. He got his hair cut
by Dominick Parisi in Ho-Ho-Kus, ate lunch at Valentino's in Park
Ridge, and after giving up the commute to his office at Federal
Plaza in Manhattan, worked in an office in adjoining Woodcliff
Lake.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrations? ``Now and then, we'd have some kids along the
road going, `Heyyy, Tricky Dick!''' Re said, doing a pretty good
two-armed Nixon victory salute. ``But what's that? That's
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   There were visitors, but mostly dignitaries and statesmen. Not
the people next door. ``I don't think he had a friend who could
call up and say, `Hey, let's go bowling,' '' said Mario Perillo,
the head of a tour company and a neighbor of the Nixons. ``To most
people, he was the lonely figure with the flashlight, walking his
dog at night.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet everyone seemed to know what Nixon was doing in his house:
writing. Four books came out of Saddle River, all on foreign policy
and all best sellers. If he made a local impact, it was as the
famously generous man in a coat and tie at Halloween, handing out
candy and printed cards bearing the message, ``President and Mrs.
Nixon wish you a happy Halloween.''
</P>
<P>
   By then, Re said, the former president could even laugh at the
occasional trick-or-treater in a Nixon mask.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Clintons, the Nixons used friends and former staff
members to scout the New York region for suitable houses, and they
looked in Westchester and on Long Island, too. The Secret Service
wanted a house on several acres, to allow a decent security buffer,
and they wanted proximity to New York City, a secluded pool for
Nixon to swim in, and a backyard deck for Mrs. Nixon, said Kathy
O'Connor, the former president's chief of staff at Saddle River,
and now the assistant executive director of the Richard Nixon
Library and Birthplace in Yorba Linda, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved that house,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the house is owned by an overseas businessman and seems
from the outside a bit gloomy and unlived-in. Evidence of elaborate
security cameras is everywhere, but it's old stuff, Re said.
</P>
<P>
   The room off the garage that had been the former president's
security ready room is now a small gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Saddle River Mayor Theodore Anthony said: ``I think Mr. Nixon
just wanted to live a quiet life to make up for whatever happened
in his past. I think he was just trying to rebuild.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
