<HEADLINE>
GEHRIG'S UNIFORM IS SOLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., N.Y.)  (bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Florida man paid $451,541 at an auction Friday for the flannel
pinstriped New York Yankee uniform worn by Lou Gehrig 60 years ago
when the first baseman declared himself the ``luckiest man on the
face of the earth.''
</P>
<P>
   The winning bidder was identified as a South Florida sportsman,
who wanted to remain anonymous until Tuesday or Wednesday, said
Marty Appel, a spokesman for Leland's auction house in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Leland's was uncertain if anyone would pay as much as $295,000,
the minimum bid set for the size 46 uniform, the centerpiece of a
two-day sports auction done entirely by telephone, fax or online.
But three bidders pushed the price up five times from the minimum,
with the winner concluding it by phone.
</P>
<P>
   The uniform ranks as the third most expensive article of sports
memorabilia, after the $3 million paid for Mark McGwire's 70th home
run ball and the $640,500 paid for a rare Honus Wagner tobacco
card.
</P>
<P>
   The four sellers of the uniform paid $306,000 two years ago to
buy it from Barry Halper, the New Jersey collector who is a limited
partner in the Yankees. Halper acquired it in 1971 from Gehrig's
widow, Eleanor, who swapped it for six bottles of J&AMP;B scotch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
