<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAMS IN NEW BALL PARKS LOOK TO THEIR ROLE MODEL 
LOTS OF LOSSES AT THE BREAK 
AN ABUNDANCE OF ROOKIE PITCHERS 
DODGERS READY TO DEAL
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Cleveland Indians set the standard. Beginning this Thursday
with the Seattle Mariners, a growing group of teams will try to
achieve it: move into new park, sell it out every game, finish
first every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Indians are one of the great success stories of the
'90s,'' Gerry Hunsicker, general manager of the Houston Astros,
said. ``They are the exception rather than the rule. There have
been other new parks that have emerged in the last few years and
nobody has come close to duplicating what the Indians have done. So
doing that would be somewhat of a stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   The new park has been only one ingredient in the Indians'
remarkable turnaround, a team well on its way to its fifth
consecutive division championship after it had endured seven
successive losing seasons and 13 of 14 before moving into Jacobs
Field in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not only the new park that created their success,''
Hunsicker said, ``but a lot of other things beginning with the
structure of the organization and what they've been able to
accomplish within the organization. A new ball park doesn't
guarantee anything. It still comes back to the people running the
organization and the team you're able to put on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are one of four teams that will move into new parks
next season. They will leave the Astrodome for the Ballpark at
Union Station. The San Francisco Giants will exit 3Com Park, nee
Candlestick, for Pacific Bell Park. In Milwaukee, the Brewers will
abandon County Stadium for Miller Park. The Detroit Tigers will
forsake 88-year-old Tiger Stadium for Comercia Park.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners will ignite the mass migration this Thursday when
they play the San Diego Padres at brand spanking new Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   The question all of these teams have to ponder is this: Are they
in the position they wanted to be for their move; that is, are they
prepared to try to capitalize on their new parks the way the
Indians did? The answers vary.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros and the Giants, who have held first or second place
all season, are in better shape than the Mariners, the Tigers and
the Brewers. The Mariners, on the other hand, have some elements,
namely Ken Griffey Jr. and Alex Rodriguez, that the Tigers and the
Brewers don't have.
</P>
<P>
   But will they have them for long? ``We've received a commitment
from ownership to do what we can to extend their contracts beyond
2000,'' said Chuck Armstrong, the club's president. ``Ownership has
assured us the resources are there to try to retain them.''
</P>
<P>
   The future of Griffey and Rodriguez, who could become free
agents after the 2000 season, recently became a hot topic of
discussion in Seattle when they were linked, fairly or not, to a
dispute between the Mariners and the Public Facilities District,
the agency that oversaw construction of the $517 million park, over
payment of $100 million by which the cost exceeded the budget.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners, who have not resembled contenders all season,
conceivably could still challenge Texas for the American League
West title, but they would have to discover some pitching to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it matters what our position is this season,''
Woodward said. ``The fact that we're moving into the stadium should
put us in a very nice situation in this market. It gives us half a
season to experience the stadium and see if it's more hitter
friendly or pitcher friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said he would like to see the Mariners become more fan
friendly. ``We'd like to improve ourselves a little bit, possibly
on the trade front, and hopefully win the AL West again,'' he said.
``We hope moving into Safeco Field will give us a boost.''
</P>
<P>
   The executive was talking about a playing boost. On the economic
side, he estimated that revenue could rise by about $9 million or
$10 million beyond what it would have been at the Kingdome for the
remaining 42 home games. Other new parks, he said, have created an
additional $18 million to $25 million a year. Woodward cautioned
that no one should be fooled by the advantages of a new park.
</P>
<P>
   ``A new stadium won't make a small-market club a big-market
club,'' he said. ``The Mariners won't become the Yankees. But it
will enhance your present position.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers and the Brewers are in the shakiest positions as they
approach their new parks, because they haven't progressed as
rapidly as they had expected.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Tigers were ready to take their run at the Indians'
standard, Randy Smith, their general manager, said: ``If you had
asked this question in April, I'd have said we're right where we
want to be. But guys who have been productive for us in the past
haven't been productive. We still feel we have a lot of talent on
this club, but we need a star or a face guy that elevates everyone
around him. That's our goal between now and next season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers, who fired their pitching coach Friday, are certainly
not on track to finish close to .500 or a game or two over, which
is what Smith said he had expected. They are, in fact, playing at a
rate that would give them a record only a victory or two better
than last season's 65-97.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Smith said, ``I think we're a heckuva lot closer to winning
than being the club our record indicates.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he showed how closely he has studied the Indians'
development. ``They were 76-86 before they moved into Jacobs
Field,'' he said. ``We have a chance to approach that or do better
even though we haven't played well.''
</P>
<P>
   But returning to reality, Smith acknowledged that the Indians'
feat ``may be a once-in-a-lifetime thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Sal Bando knows how Smith feels. As general manager of the
Brewers, he has presided over disappointment, too. ``The ideal
situation would be to be more competitive than we are at the
present time,'' Bando said. ``The worst scenario would be that we'd
be in the middle of the pack, then add some pieces to be
competitive in our first year in the new stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   But, noting the process the Brewers began in 1994, he added:
``You've got to be right on in your predictions of when your guys
are going to mature. We may be one year behind or two years behind,
but right now we aren't where we thought we'd be.''
</P>
<P>
   Like his counterparts, Bando is envious of the Indians' success
but said: ``One thing you don't have now that you did then was the
ability to take Joe Carter and his million-dollar contract and
trade him and get prospects. Today you can't trade your $8 million
player and do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians traded Carter nearly 10 years ago, a year before he
could become a free agent, for Sandy Alomar Jr. and Carlos Baerga,
who grew into part of the nucleus that took Jacobs Field by storm.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Tigers, the Brewers' plan to increase their payroll for
next season, but Bando was wary about how he would be able to go
about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is who will be out there and can we get him,'' he
said. ``If we want him, others will, too, and will we be able to
spend what others will?''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, solid contenders for the third successive season,
don't have the problems the Brewers and the Tigers have.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've more or less accomplished our goal of being the best
team, the best organization we can be going into the new park,''
General Manager Brian Sabean said. ``If you can accomplish that,
the new park will enhance things. The new park won't make us a
better team or organization. You have to do that with people first.
I think we've succeeded in doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Sabean said, the Giants look forward to maintaining their
position and the increased revenue the new park will bring.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, who are working on their third consecutive division
championship, have a similar outlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started our plan a couple years early,'' Hunsicker, their
general manager, said. ``We've allowed our payroll to increase
rather significantly in anticipation of moving into the new park.
We had a solid nucleus we wanted to try to keep in place going in
there. I'm pleased with what we have.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
