<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: what we have.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lots of Losses at the Break
</P>
<P>
   When Steve Trachsel pitches for the Chicago Cubs Saturday night,
he will be going for his 13th loss. The last pitcher who reached
the All-Star Game break with at least 13 losses, Elias Sports
Bureau research reveals, was Bill Wegman of the Milwaukee Brewers,
who suffered his 14th loss in 1993 in the team's 81st game July 6
and didn't start again that season. He spent more than two months
on the disabled list with a strained forearm and a stomach
disorder. Fourteen losses in 81 games can do that.
</P>
<P>
   The last National League pitcher who achieved that ignominious
level of 13 losses was Jose DeLeon of Pittsburgh, who had a 2-13
record at the break in 1985. He finished the season with a 2-19
record after spending four weeks in the minor leagues and then,
after returning and reaching 19 losses, being relegated to the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   An Abundance of Rookie Pitchers
</P>
<P>
   The major leagues, by necessity, are filled with rookie
pitchers. Some of them even win a game now and then. Jose Jimenez
of St. Louis has become the best known rookie pitcher because he
pitched a no-hitter against Arizona and beat Randy Johnson while
doing it.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Weaver of Detroit, Odalis Perez of Atlanta, Kris Benson of
Pittsburgh and Freddy Garcia and John Halama of Seattle have
pitched and won enough for fans to start recognizing their names.
</P>
<P>
   But who among those fans can identify Pat Daneker, Gil Meche,
Jeremy Powell, Wade Miller and Mike Fyhrie? They are rookie
pitchers who made their first major league starts last week:
Daneker for the Chicago White Sox, Powell for Montreal, Miller for
Houston and Meche and Fyhrie against each other in a game between
Seattle and Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers Ready to Deal
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers, embarrassed beyond belief, are trying
to make some moves to shake up their last-place team. The baseball
grapevine says they are trying to trade Ismael Valdes, one of their
underachieving starting pitchers, and have talked with Detroit
about a swap of first basemen, Eric Karros for Tony Clark. ... The
Colorado Rockies, who have unsuccessfully tried to trade Darryl
Kile, their disappointing starting pitcher, have apparently decided
to expand their efforts in remaking their disappointing team. Dante
Bichette and others are available. The team's ownership has
discovered that the hiring of manager Jim Leyland at $2 million a
year was not the answer. ``They've found out that Don Baylor was
not the problem,'' an executive of another team said, referring to
Leyland's predecessor. ... A rumor surfaced last week that Bud
Selig had just completed his first year as commissioner. Try
telling that to Sue Selig, his wife. She knows that he has been
commissioner for seven years, longer than five of his eight
predecessors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
