<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOATING-ADMIRALS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH BOAT UNDER WRAPS FOR ADMIRAL'S CUP  
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to offshore racing, few regattas in the world
compare to the Champagne Mumm Admiral's Cup. Like sterling on
damask, it is a prestigious yacht-racing affair seldom tarnished by
the avant-garde of open sailboat design.
</P>
<P>
   But the French are hearing none of that this year. In a test of
will and foresight, the Admiral's Cup team from France is arriving
in Cowes, England, with an odd duck under glass. It comes in the
form of a wing-shaped mast, steep topsides and a narrow hull. To
heighten the yacht's mystery, the 50-foot Krazy K-Yote Two has been
kept under wraps like a new sports car at an auto show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either it's a great boat, or it's not,'' said Ken Read,
helmsman for the U.S. team's 50-foot rival, Idler, a Nelson/Marek
design. ``When we see it on the race course for the first time,
it's going to be a case of, `Uh-oh,' or `We're OK' We're going to
know in five minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   The eight-race series is to begin Thursday off Cowes. Nine
international groups are entered, including three-boat teams from
England, Germany, Italy, Australia, the Netherlands and the United
States, and groups from Europe and the British Commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
   Each will race with a prerequisite complement of three boats: a
big-boat, a 50-footer rated under handicapping rules; a
medium-sized boat, a Sydney 40 rated under its one-design class
rules; and a small boat, a Mumm 36, governed by its class rules.
</P>
<P>
   How is it then that one of the big boats of the fleet, the
French Krazy K-Yote Two, can keep word about its design so quiet?
By not sailing it until the day of the race start, that's how.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the problems with innovative things like this is that
the rule-makers try to eventually ban them,'' said David Schwarz,
president of Goetz Marine Technology, the company in Bristol, R.I.,
that made the French boat's controversial mast. ``Good or bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The sports' handicap rules are like moving targets on water,
ever changeable, ever maddening to boat owners and architects. If a
design is innovative, the rule-makers try to discourage its
duplication as a way of reducing costs for other owners.
</P>
<P>
   But for a yacht's designers and builders, new ideas at the
higher echelons of the sport are sales for the future that tend to
filter down to the recreational boater. The winged mast on the 1983
America's Cup yacht was one such example.
</P>
<P>
   Still, on the Admiral's Cup level, the hullabaloo about the
French boat may be more hot air than haute coup. ``I saw it sailing
over the weekend,'' said U.S. team captain Bob Towse. ``It is
radical. But I wouldn't want to guess how it will do. There are no
slow boats out there. No boat will be easy to beat. They're all
well sailed. I think it will be difficult for any boat to win this
Admiral's Cup. We've got the people on our team, and we've made the
preparation. But we've also got the competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   In a rare accommodation in racing's elite, Towse bowed out from
the 50-foot division for this Admiral's Cup to one of his own
keenest rivals, United Technologies chief executive George David,
of Hartford, Conn., who owns Idler. In three previous Admiral's Cup
events, Towse, who is a managing director of Morgan, Stanley Dean
Witter &AMP; Co., the brokerage firm, came close to winning by bringing
a series of big boats that he personally owned and named Blue
Yankee.
</P>
<P>
   In the event this week, Towse will be chartering a new Sydney 40
from its builder, Bashford Boats of Australia. He has named the
yacht Blue Yankee Pride, and stacked its decks with highly seasoned
yachtsmen who have Olympic and America's Cup backgrounds. They
include Steve Benjamin, Peter Isler and Jim Brady. The United
States' small boat, the Mumm 36, is named Ciao Baby.
</P>
<P>
   Read, who was the big-boat helmsman on the victorious U.S. team
in the 1997 Admiral's Cup, said he believed the winner this year is
a toss-up. ``That's the million-dollar question,'' he said. ``On
Idler, which is the only boat I have any control over, we have tons
of experience and an owner who will let us do anything we want to
do to make the team better. From my personal standpoint, I feel
we're going to do great. But as a team, it's a tough read.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
