<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5483 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      07-10 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL NOTEBOOK: IF PHILLIPS COMES BACK, HE MAY BE SUSPENDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the National Football League, a 1,000-yard season and the
seduction that is talent can go a long way to repairing a checkered
past. If you dragged your girlfriend down three flights of stairs,
punched her in the head and then kicked her in the chest, all can
be forgiven if the talent is there. If you are jailed for 23 days
because of a probation violation and drunken driving, you will get
another chance. Accused of assaulting a second, and then later a
third woman? No problem _ a team will come calling anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Phillips . . . he's baaacckk. Or at least on his way to
a return in the National Football League. Although he has more
baggage than an airline during the Christmas holidays, Phillips
will probably join an NFL team this summer after a great year in
NFL Europe. Phillips was the league's most valuable player on
offense, rushing for a record 1,021 yards _ just 288 yards fewer
than the total he rushed for in his two NFL seasons _ and scored 14
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL had wondered whether Phillips would ever break out and
show the talent that made him a first-round draft pick of the St.
Louis Rams in 1996. He finally did it in Europe and now teams are
stumbling over themselves to get another shot at him.
</P>
<P>
   The league office is taking a much more cautious approach,
though. Indeed, Phillips could face disciplinary action should he
sign with an NFL team.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips' resume is disturbing. In 1995, at the University of
Nebraska, Phillips was found guilty of assaulting his girlfriend
after a brutal attack in which he dragged her down several flights
of stairs and then beat her. He received one year of probation,
then violated it in late 1996 when he was arrested on a drunken
driving charge. He was jailed for 23 days. That was followed by a
no-contest plea after he was charged with threatening the police
when they responded to a woman's assertion that Phillips had
assaulted her at a hotel party in Nebraska in early 1997. Although
assault charges were not filed against him, the incident resulted
in four lawsuits, which were later settled out of court.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams finally tired of Phillips' problems, which included
sleeping through or arriving late for a number of team meetings,
and released him on Nov. 20, 1997. Two weeks after he was cut, the
Miami Dolphins signed Phillips to a two-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   While he was with the Dolphins, Phillips was accused of twice
punching a woman in the face at a Miami-area nightclub after she
refused to dance with him. A month later, the Dolphins released
him, and last February Phillips pleaded no contest to misdemeanor
battery and was sentenced to six months' probation.
</P>
<P>
   It is that last arrest on which the league office is focusing
because it occurred after the NFL adopted its violent-crime policy.
That policy states that any player who is convicted of a violent
crime must undergo league-sponsored counseling and may be suspended
without pay.
</P>
<P>
   Under the policy, a plea bargain is considered the same as a
guilty verdict, which means that if Phillips signs with an NFL
team, he could conceivably be suspended for a significant portion
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The length of any such suspension would be up to commissioner
Paul Tagliabue. Phillips is expected to meet with Tagliabue within
the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   As far as the NFL is concerned, just because he stayed out of
trouble in Europe does not mean the league will forget what he did
while he was playing with Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Ravens coach Brian Billick met with Phillips in Atlanta last
Thursday, and Phillips is expected to visit with Ravens owner Art
Modell and others in the organization next week. Modell said
Baltimore will not sign Phillips until he has a clear understanding
about whether Phillips is going to be suspended and for how long.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he is going to be suspended for a year,'' said Modell,
``what is the point in signing him?''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there remains strong interest in him from more than half
a dozen teams, including two of the best.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips visited the Green Bay Packers and the San Francisco
49ers last week. The 49ers may want Phillips to replace Garrison
Hearst, whose playing days could be over because of a condition
similar to the one that ended the career of the two-sport star Bo
Jackson almost a decade ago. Hearst, who broke his left ankle in a
playoff game against Atlanta last season, is no longer receiving a
sufficient supply of blood to the bone.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay general manager Ron Wolf believes Phillips has matured
and can stay out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``During his stay in NFL Europe, he has not had one ounce of
trouble,'' Wolf said. ``I am not unsympathetic to the troubles he
has been in and the pain he has caused other people, but I think he
has matured.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf is one of the smartest men in the business. But other
executives and coaches are smart, too, and some of them also
believed that Phillips was a better man. One was coach Jimmy
Johnson, whom Phillips completely bamboozled.
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference in Germany last month after winning the
offensive MVP award, nothing but the right words came out of
Phillips' mouth. He said he was humble and happy to have a second
chance in Europe. He weighed 240 pounds when he played for the
Dolphins but is now a slim 210.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely a better player than I was in St. Louis and
Miami,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But is he a better person? Only Phillips knows the answer.
</P>
<P>
   Strahan Frets
</P>
<P>
   The Giants defensive end Michael Strahan is becoming impatient
with the pace of his contract negotiations. The potential deal
could make Strahan one of the five highest-paid players in the
game. When that kind of money is being discussed, of course the
Giants are going to be meticulous. Strahan should be happy because
negotiations are picking up. The Giants made an offer to Strahan's
agent last Friday. There is a slim chance that a deal could be
reached by the time training camp begins at the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Since safety Tito Wooten was cut by the Giants last month, he
has received interest from only one team, the New Orleans Saints.
</P>
<P>
   A sign that players are becoming as familiar with computers as
they are first downs: A survey at the NFL's rookie symposium this
summer, in which players are indoctrinated over a three-day period
about life in professional football, showed that 69 percent of the
drafted rookie class use e-mail. In the next millennium when a team
wants to track down a player in the off season, they may use e-mail
instead of leaving phone messages.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore Ravens offensive players are enamored of Brian
Billick's play designs because they are difficult for a defense to
predict.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
