<SLUG> BC-NY-LONGISLAND-HEAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAT CAUGHT LONG ISLAND UTILITY WITH NO MARGIN FOR ERROR 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GARDEN CITY, N.Y. _ About 109,000 homes in Nassau and Suffolk
counties lost power during the recent heat wave, officials at the
Long Island Power Authority said Saturday. And they are grateful
the number was so low.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, as temperatures reached 100 degrees and power
consumption set a record of 4,590 megawatts, LIPA's engineers were
poised to shut down power across Long Island in waves, tens of
thousands of homes at a time, to prevent an uncontrollable
blackout.
</P>
<P>
   Only a series of pleading phone calls to government officials,
college presidents and corporate executives, who agreed to send
workers home early, let the power authority avoid such drastic
measures, officials said. The early closings saved a crucial 140
megawatts.
</P>
<P>
   The margin was so slim, officials said, largely because the
power authority could not buy extra electricity from other
utilities in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditionally, we can import from Con Edison over several
lines that traverse the Rockaways,'' said LIPA chairman Richard
Kessel. ``We couldn't do that on Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   Kessel said LIPA's vulnerability to shortages in imported
electricity, and thus its need for more of its own, were the
biggest lessons of the heat wave, which caused the worst crisis in
the year since the authority took over Long Island's electrical
system. The lights were back on in the last few thousand affected
homes by Thursday afternoon, a spokesman for the authority, Michael
Lowndes, said.
</P>
<P>
   As a first response, Kessel is expected to announce plans Monday
to build new power plants on the Island capable of generating
another 200 to 300 megawatts of electricity.
</P>
<P>
   The existing power plants on the Island can produce about 4,000
megawatts of power, which was more than enough on even the hottest
day of the year until the summer of 1995. But peak usage has been
growing here by leaps and bounds, just as it has all over the
metropolitan area, driven by the proliferation of home computers
and other electronic devices, a rising population and a boom in
homebuilding characterized by ever-more-spacious houses that need
cooling on the hottest days.
</P>
<P>
   To supplement its own power production, the power authority
imports electricity over six lines: two from Westchester County,
three from Jamaica, Queens, and one beneath the Long Island Sound
from Norwalk, Conn. Taken together, those lines can carry a maximum
of about 1,100 megawatts, said William Balet, executive director of
the New York Power Pool, a consortium of the state's eight major
utilities.
</P>
<P>
   The Norwalk cable was under repair, however, leaving about 900
megawatts of import capacity, and on paper, at least, that would
have been more than enough to cover Tuesday's peak energy demand.
But as Kessel said: ``Capacity isn't energy. You could have all the
capacity in the world, but if the energy isn't available at a given
time and you need it, it's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Kessel said the power authority also is proceeding with a plan
to build another underwater cable, this one between Shoreham, in
Suffolk, and New Haven, Conn., which will be capable of carrying
600 megawatts.
</P>
<P>
   But Gordian Raacke, executive director of the Citizens Advisory
Panel, a court-appointed watchdog group, called Kessel's plans a
``knee-jerk response.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what they always say _ let's build more power plants,''
Raacke said. ``And a cable to New England isn't going to get us
anywhere, because the people in Connecticut aren't going to be
willing to send the power over here during heat waves.''
</P>
<P>
   Kessel defended the authority's investment in the new cable by
saying a number of large power plants were expected to open in New
England over the next decade, providing ample supplies for that
region. The cost of the underwater cable could be as much as $200
million, according to some estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Kessel said LIPA was also investing heavily in energy efficiency
and conservation programs. But he warned that with power
consumption rising by 4 percent a year _ in part because the
authority has cut electrical rates _ new generators and
transmission lines from other regions were essential to meet
demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're spending $32 million each of the next five years on
that, to promote solar power and fuel cells and research and
development, and all kinds of things,'' he said. ``That's all
great, but that alone is not going to be able to meet the
extraordinary growth in electric usage on Long Island in the next
five years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
