<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOURDEFRANCE-SOIGNEUR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRISHWOMAN IS `HEART AND SOUL' OF THE POSTAL SERVICE TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THIONVILLE, France _ The first time Emma O'Reilly understood
that she was something special in the world of European bicycle
racing was when she finished work before a race in Belgium two
years ago, entered the communal dining room and realized that she
was the only woman there.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there were lots of teams,'' she remembered of that race,
the Tour of Flanders. ``Lots and lots of people, and I must have
been the only female. That was my biggest culture shock ever.''
Retelling the incident, she laughed now, as she said she ultimately
laughed then.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what it reminded me of?'' she asked. ``My first day
walking into my electrical work.'' Before she became a masseur, she
served a four-year apprenticeship as an electrician in Dublin and
earned her journeyman's card.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were 44 of us there and no other woman my first day at
the electrical trade center. I thought, `There's got to be another
woman.' That's the way at the Tour of Flanders _ `There's got to be
another woman; there's just got to be another one.' Nope.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Reilly, a 28-year-old (``not 29, I won't be 29 until July
22'') Irishwoman, was and is unfazed. She knows her value to the
U.S. Postal Service team as chief soigneur, a combination of
masseur, confidante and jack of many trades. In addition to
massaging three riders each evening in the Tour de France, she runs
the four-member soigneur staff, oversees the team's supply of food
during the three-week race, often stands at the side of the road to
distribute lunch in cloth bags that the riders snatch as they whiz
by, does their laundry and listens to their tales of woe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emma is the heart and soul of the team,'' said Mark Gorski,
the winner of a gold medal in the bicycle sprint at the 1984
Olympics and now the general manager of the Postal Service
entourage. ``She's so professional and has a wonderful influence on
the other staff members and the riders.
</P>
<P>
   ``She brings a woman's sensitivity to guys' personalities, their
differences in personality, all kinds of things that a male
soigneur just can't bring.''
</P>
<P>
   That being so, why does no other team on the European circuit
employ female soigneurs, even if they are frequent on American
teams? ``It's a cultural attitude about women and their place in
the workplace,'' Gorski said. ``It's the attitude that a woman
traveling with the team 120, 130 days a year is inappropriate. I
think they're wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   So does O'Reilly, but she is not troubled, she said, because
already she sees major changes occurring in the soigneurs' world.
The old school _ the often-shady soigneurs with their suitcases
full of potions and drugs _ is beginning to give way.
</P>
<P>
   ``No disrespect,'' she said, ``but the old school is former bike
riders. They didn't do a massage course and either couldn't get a
job in the real world or didn't want to get out of the cycling
world and this is a way of staying on. They know everybody and it's
comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the soigneurs are becoming more of a half-and-half
mixture. It's much more people in their 20s who know how to do this
job.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Reilly joined the Postal Service team when it was formed four
years ago, moving from her soigneur's job with the Shaklee team in
Colorado. ``I lived in Boulder and loved it, loved the climate,''
she said. ``My coming from Ireland, the climate is heaven: it's
dry, the sky is always blue.''
</P>
<P>
   Before that, ``I used to do with the Irish national team, just
as a hobby. Then it evolved.'' She was working as an electrician in
Dublin, specializing in switchboard and panel control work, when
she decided to take a night course in massage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I could go away with Irish teams and take a holiday
in Europe with them,'' she said. ``And it got bigger and bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   After completing the massage training from September to May, she
took other courses in sports injury and reflexology, ``again at
night, while I was doing electrical work.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually she was plugged into the soigneurs' network, was
offered a job with a California racing team that didn't quite pan
out and joined Shaklee and then Postal Service.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the bias of European teams against women, O'Reilly found
that male soigneurs were supportive of her.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first started, so many of them looked out for me,'' she
said. ``If I've forgotten something, heaven forbid, I can go to
them. Maybe because I'm used to working with men all the time, but
so many of the lads are so decent. Now and then, somebody might
make a joke but I don't even respond, just give them a dirty
look.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does she remember trouble with wives of the riders she works
with. ``Maybe I should take it as an insult that the riders' wives
don't give me any grief,'' she joked. ``They just look at me and
feel very secure.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Reilly has a boyfriend, the representative for a helmet
company, whom she sees sometimes at races. She says that she plans
to work another year as a soigneur and then retire, get married and
have children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still old-fashioned enough to think that if I want to
marry, settle down and have children, it would be OK to stay at
home,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
