<HEADLINE>
UNION BACKS NBA DRUG POLICY 
THE JACKSON DIARY 
U.S. TEAM PREPARES 
END OF LINE FOR JONES 
WILLIAMS NEARS 41
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Billy Hunter, the executive director of the NBA players
association, does not believe the problem is as rampant as it is
perceived. Still, he and the player representatives for the 29
teams agree that with the NBA soon to begin testing for marijuana,
it is time to educate the masses.
</P>
<P>
   During the union's annual meetings in the Bahamas last week,
representatives were told to spread the word to their teammates
about the league's new drug policy. Since marijuana can stay in a
person's system for two to three months, players who use it in July
run a risk of being caught in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly there are guys out there using, and hopefully
they'll get the message that they have to stop,'' Jim McIlvaine of
the New Jersey Nets told The Associated Press last week.
</P>
<P>
   According to rules agreed to during collective bargaining last
January, players who test positive at training camp must undergo
mandatory counseling. A second positive test brings a $15,000 fine,
and a subsequent positive test results in a five-game suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Rookies will be tested four times a season on a random basis.
</P>
<P>
   A player also can be tested during the regular season if an
arbitrator decides, after a hearing, there is reasonable cause to
believe a player has used, possessed or distributed any prohibited
substance.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two years alone, Chris Webber, Mookie Blaylock,
Vernon Maxwell and J.R. Rider have been arrested on
marijuana-related charges.
</P>
<P>
   Steroids were also added to the league's banned substances list
during the last collective-bargaining negotiations, and all players
will be tested when training camps open in October.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone testing positive for steroids gets a five-game suspension
for the first offense, a 10-game suspension for a second offense
and a 25-game suspension for a third offense. Androstenedione, the
testosterone-producing substance taken by baseball's Mark McGwire
and others, is banned by the league.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the marijuana issue has been one of the most troubling
for the league the past two years. That the players have decided to
treat it as seriously as the league says something about the union
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   The Jackson Diary
</P>
<P>
   As Jeff Van Gundy prepares to secure his future with the Knicks
_ he will most likely meet with the Madison Square Garden president
Dave Checketts next week to discuss a long-term contract extension
_ the Knicks' coach can take solace in Phil Jackson's recent diary
for ESPN Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   In the July 12 issue, Jackson essentially paints the portrait of
an organization looking to go in another coaching direction as
early as two months ago. Jackson has often been accused of
campaigning for Van Gundy's job, but he appears to absolve himself
of any ethical wrongdoing in the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, most of the controversy surrounding Jackson's
clandestine meeting with Checketts in April can be traced back to
an informal conversation the two had last year after Red Holzman's
funeral _ prompted by Checketts, according to Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Checketts told me he'd like to have me in the organization in
some way, maybe as a vice president,'' Jackson wrote in his
personal diary for the magazine. ``We didn't really talk after that
until just before the end of the regular season. The Knicks were
about even with Charlotte and Cleveland for the eighth, ninth and
10th spots in the East, and they seemed out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``So my agent, Todd Musburger, and I went to New York to meet
with Dave, who said he wanted me to know that before I started
getting pressured for other jobs, the Knicks were interested in me.
No specific job. ... I told Dave I would talk to him when the
Knicks' season was officially over.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awful the way it all came out in the press, how
Checketts said at first we hadn't met and then had to say we did.
It was terrible for Van Gundy. But as it turned out, Jeff did a
tremendous job of getting a team with a lot of weaknesses all the
way into the finals. So the Knicks were out for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson also wrote that the Lakers were his first choice all
along, and had some candid comments regarding the team's stars:
</P>
<P>
   _ Shaquille O'Neal: ``Shaquille hasn't performed the way he
could. He should be the league's MVP.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Kobe Bryant: ``A kid uneducated in basketball and life. It's
amazing, he's only 20 years old. My boys are almost that old.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Team Prepares
</P>
<P>
   In Orlando this week, the U.S. national basketball team began
preparing for the Pre-Olympic Qualifying Tournament of the Americas
later this month in Puerto Rico, which runs through July 25.
</P>
<P>
   Because a group of non-NBA players did not advance to the title
game of the world championships last year in Athens _ blame the
lockout, if you must _ this version of the U.S. team needs to win
its semifinal game to qualify for the 2000 Games in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   It's almost a fait accompli, with a roster of Tim Duncan, Vin
Baker, Kevin Garnett, Gary Payton, Tom Gugliotta, Allan Houston,
Jason Kidd, Tim Hardaway and Steve Smith _ and recent first-round
draft picks Elton Brand, Wally Szczerbiak and Richard Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping themselves motivated may be the biggest chore, which is
why some other players were brought in to scrimmage against the
team this week. Sacramento's Jason Williams joined Orlando's Bo
Outlaw, Nick Anderson and other Magic players participated in the
workout.
</P>
<P>
   The United States faces Canada in an exhibition Sunday and meets
Uruguay in a first-round game July 15.
</P>
<P>
   End of Line for Jones
</P>
<P>
   John Starks used to say there was an invisible line in
basketball, reserved mostly for players who were never first-round
draft picks and always on the bubble. On one side were many players
who could have been in the NBA. On the other side were the guys who
somehow found a way to cross over, stay on a roster and compete
with the best athletes in the world.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, there is also a line that separates first-round
draft picks. In Nashville, an Aug. 16 trial date was set for former
Knick Dontae' Jones on charges stemming from a nightclub shooting.
He is accused of simple assault with bodily injury, reckless
endangerment and felony vandalism. Jones, who led Mississippi State
to the Final Four in 1996, faces up to 14 years in prison if
convicted on all charges.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting took place April 25 outside a nightclub called the
Players Draft House after an argument between a Memphis rap group
and an entertainment promoter. A Players Draft House security
guard, Darryl L. Tyce, told authorities he saw Jones and another
man firing handguns in his direction. Tyce was wounded in the
stomach and his car was damaged.
</P>
<P>
   The assault charge stems from a separate altercation inside the
nightclub between Jones and a woman, Assistant District Attorney
George Bonds told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he is guilty or not, Jones is clearly approaching his
nadir in his early 20s. Not that he was a can't-miss all-American
destined for NBA greatness, but he was the kind of athletic young
talent who may have been able to find his niche in this league had
he made a sincere commitment to the game.
</P>
<P>
   Like Starks, he was brimming with untapped energy but had
nowhere to put it. Unlike Starks, basketball was not his life.
</P>
<P>
   As a Knick, Jones was one of those locker room cut-ups who kept
his teammates in stitches. In his brief tenure with the team, he
was known best for keeping practices light-hearted and, it probably
follows, not taking the game seriously enough.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was on the injured list for almost the entire 1996-97
season. At one point, he played video games in a security guard's
office of the USAir Arena with Chris Webber after a Knicks victory
on the road. He quipped that it was the most minutes he had played
all season.
</P>
<P>
   During a trip to Atlanta, coach Jeff Van Gundy sent him home
after he slept late and forgot to show up at practice. Remorseful
and contrite, Jones told Van Gundy: ``Good luck at the game, coach.
I know you have to do what you have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   He was genuinely nice and funny. Traded to Boston, Jones played
in 15 games for the Celtics in the 1997-98 season, averaging 2.9
points. He was waived before the start of the 1998-1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   With a criminal trial pending and his NBA career most likely
over, he goes back to being another dreamer on the other side of
that invisible line, maybe never realizing how lucky he was to have
crossed over in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot 20-somethings with lithe, 6-foot-6-inch frames
and impressive vertical leaps, jumping out of community centers and
playgrounds across America and talking about how they dunked on
so-and-so in college and once had a tryout somewhere. What a shame
Dontae' Jones didn't seize his opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Williams Nears 41
</P>
<P>
   For the Knicks to win a title next season, Herb Williams was
chided that he would have to accept a reduced role. Williams
laughed, knowing that at 41 and seldom used anyway, his playing
days are most likely over. Still, as the oldest active player on a
roster last season, Williams would not rule out the possibility of
a return. ... Chick Hearn, the play-by-play voice of the Lakers for
the past 34 seasons, signed a two-year contract last Wednesday.
Having called an incredible 3,114 consecutive Laker games, Hearn,
at age 82, plans to add to one of the great ironman feats in
sports. From West to Chamberlain, Magic to Kareem, Shaq to Kobe and
beyond, it is a pleasant reminder that the more things change in
this league the more they stay the same.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
