<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-MLS-FUTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FOURTH YEAR MLS FEELS FLUSH WITH SOLID OWNERS AND IMPROVED TV
RATINGS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Texas)  (rk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the middle of its fourth season, Major League Soccer
continues to lose money, but league officials say they have the
finances from investor-operators for a minimum of five more
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel chipper and bullish,'' Commissioner Doug Logan said as
the league prepared for Saturday's All-Star Game in San Diego.
``We're right on target with our five-year plan. It has cost us
$100 million to get to this point, but we're in a solid financial
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Counce, the general manager of the Western
Conference-leading Colorado Rapids, had his own optimistic
description of his team's condition. ``We're starting to lose less
money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Logan said the reason for the league's stability came from the
owners' decision a year ago to put up the capital needed to exist
for five more seasons without additional sponsorship or income from
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an unprecedented move that I believe has helped us
tremendously,'' Logan said. ``We've come up with a group of owners
that will stand behind this league.''
</P>
<P>
   The owners are billionaires such as John Kluge, Phil Anschutz,
Lamar Hunt and Robert Kraft. Anschutz, a Denver billionaire, bought
the Los Angeles Galaxy for $26 million last November, only three
years after the cost of becoming an investor-operator of a team was
going for $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Anschutz has been one of the biggest reasons for the financial
security of the league. When a man worth $16.5 billion pours money
into a team it makes the other owners feel more comfortable that
the league is on solid ground.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt made a $26 million investment of his own when he built a
stadium specifically for the Columbus Crew team he operates along
with the MLS's Kansas City Wizards and the NFL's Kansas City
Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lack of success by the MetroStars in the New York
metropolitan area, the league's attendance numbers have gone up
this season after dropping in the second and third years. After 97
games this season, the average attendance is 15,961, up 6 percent
over the 15,147 average of last season.
</P>
<P>
   With some help from the Women's World Cup, the league's
television ratings have also increased.
</P>
<P>
   The first two games televised by Univision, the Spanish network,
averaged a 5.3 rating, according to the Nielsen Hispanic Television
Index. That is a 51 percent increase over last year and appears to
justify two scheduling changes the league made.
</P>
<P>
   In the first three years, Univision showed MLS games at 3 p.m.
on Sunday, following the telecast of games from Mexico. This
season, league and Univision executives decided to move MLS games
to 1 p.m. and start the telecasts June 20, two weeks after the
Mexican League season ended.
</P>
<P>
   ABC and ESPN International, which will televise the All-Star
Game to 130 countries, also have shown an increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been thrilled with the soccer ratings we've seen the
last few years,'' said Mark Mandell, a spokesman for ABC, which
will televise the All-Star Game. ``Between the men's and women's
World Cups, we've seen a bigger increase in soccer ratings than in
any of the other sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Higher attendance and higher television ratings bring more money
from corporate sponsors, such as Mastercard, AT&AMP;T and Honda, who
now pay more than $80 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite signs pointing toward a healthy future, the league
deferred plans for expansion by a year to 2001. Logan will make the
official announcement of that decision at his state-of-the-league
address next Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have two new teams in 2001,'' Logan said, ``but not
before we check some significant loose ends.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Philadelphia and Houston were the cities with the best
chance of getting expansion teams.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the league's 12 existing teams, the Dallas Burn and the
Tampa Bay Mutiny, are still operated by the league, which is
seeking private investor-operators for both.
</P>
<P>
   The San Jose Clash, which was operated by the league the first
three years, has been taken over by the Kraft family, which also
operates the New England Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   As a single-entity venture, the league controls all the player
contracts and has set a salary cap at $1.7 million a team after
starting at $1.1 million the first year. The maximum salary is
still $250,000 and the minimum is $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee you there won't be any radical increase in the
salary cap,'' Logan said. ``The average salary is $84,000, which is
more than twice what the average American makes. We don't have any
spoiled athletes in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
