<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL INQUIRY OF POLICE DRAWS MIXED REACTION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Pa.)  (rk) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ News that federal prosecutors have found systemwide
problems in the New York Police Department's handling of brutality
complaints brought a triumphant ``I told you so'' chorus from
longtime police critics Saturday, though they continued to disagree
about how best to reform the department.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, we have a real opportunity to bring about systemic
change within the NYPD in order to achieve greater accountability
over our NYPD,'' said Norman Siegel, the executive director of the
New York Civil Liberties Union. ``This is good news, yet long
overdue.''
</P>
<P>
   William F. Kuntz II, a member of the department's Civilian
Complaint Review Board, called the findings by Zachary W. Carter,
the U.S. attorney in Brooklyn, ``courageous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's absolutely on the right track,'' Kuntz said.
``There are serious problems of brutality and racism in the
department.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials refused to discuss the investigation, so it
remains unclear whether the department will embrace changes
proposed by Carter or leave itself open to a suit by the Justice
Department that could force reform, perhaps by installing a federal
monitor to oversee the nation's largest police force. Specific
results of the federal inquiry also remained unavailable Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Sunny Mindel, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's press secretary, would
say only that the Police Department and the corporation counsel
``have been cooperating with the U.S. attorney's review, and the
discussions are ongoing.'' Marilyn Mode, the Police Department's
chief spokeswoman, declined comment altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Prompted by the 1997 beating and torture of a Haitian immigrant,
Abner Louima, in a Brooklyn station house, Carter's review is one
of at least 10 focusing on law enforcement agencies nationwide
through a 1994 law authorizing prosecutors to seek changes in the
operations of local police departments in federal courts. Two cases
that have already been litigated, in Pittsburgh and Steubenville,
Ohio, have resulted in court-approved agreements in which police
departments track use of force, civilian complaints and
disciplinary action through databases that are reviewed by
independent auditors.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most vehement critics of the status quo in New York
said they were unsure that federal oversight was the right
solution. Rather, they embraced federal intervention as an
opportunity to shift the political winds in favor of reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've had up to now is political forces, from minority
people and ACLU people, putting pressure on the city to introduce
civilian oversight, and the mayor has successfully resisted it,''
said Paul G. Chevigny, a law professor at New York University who
has written extensively about police brutality and pushed for
changes in New York's complaint review procedures. ``That leads to
a standoff. Introducing the federal government has a tendency to
break that standoff.''
</P>
<P>
   But Chevigny said that a settlement would be better than a
lawsuit, and that a federal monitor was not the most desirable
solution. ``If it's got to be administered against a totally
resistant political system, it's not enough,'' he said.
``Ultimately, without some good faith on the part of the people
running the department, nothing is going to work, or work very
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Eric Adams, president of a civic group representing New
York's black police officers, said city officials had thus far been
``acting like alcoholics in denial by not acknowledging the
problems,'' and that Carter's investigation gives credence to
complaints long voiced in minority communities. He said the city
needed an independent agency with power to gather evidence, because
as long as investigators depend on the Police Department for
information, their work will be compromised.
</P>
<P>
   Current leaders of the Patrolmen's Benevolent Association could
not be reached for comment Saturday, but the union's former
president, James Savage, decried the review's findings, and said
federal intervention would not have an impact on whatever problems
do exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the federal government should stick their nose
into Police Department policy,'' Savage said. ``It erodes the
confidence of the public in the Police Department. It's certainly a
blow to the egos of the cops out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Police boosters and critics alike, however, agreed with the
general findings of the federal review _ that the current system
for handling civilian complaints is not working. Police
commissioners have dismissed one-half to two-thirds of the
complaints substantiated by the review board. Of those that are
upheld, the vast majority lead to minor discipline; only one case
in the board's first five years led to dismissal, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost as if it's this stepchild agency,'' Earl S. Ward
said of the Civilian Complaint Review Board, on which he sits.
``They really have to start saying, look, the CCRB recommendations
need to be given serious treatment. That's not happening right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Siegel, of the civil liberties union, said the review board ``on
paper is the most independent and accountable system in the
country,'' but that it has been ``nullified and sabotaged'' by
mayors and police commissioners unconcerned about brutality.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has to be oversight,'' he said, ``because the system,
the NYPD and the mayor's office, have had ample opportunity to make
systemic reform. They're minimizing and trivializing the issue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
