<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-CONVENTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACIAL PROFILING TOPS NAACP AGENDA 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The nation's oldest civil rights organization
returned Saturday to New York, the city of its founding, to
celebrate its 90th birthday and confront issues as topical as
racial profiling by the police and getting more blacks to use the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People
opened its six-day annual convention at the New York Hilton and
Towers in midtown Manhattan by listing several other concerns at
the top of its agenda, like school vouchers, the backslide toward
segregation, voter registration, the quality of health care, and
preparing for appearances by Hillary Rodham Clinton on Monday and
Vice President Al Gore on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But its two top officials, speaking to reporters, clearly marked
as their top concern the increasing number of allegations that city
and state police departments around the country routinely stop and
harass drivers because they are black.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen open season on black people in New York,
Philadelphia, Pittsburgh and San Diego,'' said NAACP chairman
Julian Bond at a news conference Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Though he said, ``This is an old, old issue for us,'' Bond said
profiling had resurfaced as an urgent topic in the last year,
particularly after incidents in New York City and the admitted use
of racial profiling by New Jersey state troopers.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Bond nor Kweisi Mfume, the NAACP's president and chief
executive, specified how the organization would battle racial
profiling. But Bond alluded to the recent case of police brutality
in New York, in which fellow officers testified against Officer
Justin Volpe, who was convicted of sodomizing Abner Louima, a black
man, in a police station with a wooden stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are particularly pleased that this blue wall of silence has
at least been cracked here in New York City,'' Bond said.
</P>
<P>
   The agenda differs markedly from that of last year's convention,
held in Atlanta, which took direct aim at critics of affirmative
action, including some justices of the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   This year, organizers said they wanted the convention to focus
more on youth, particularly the need to invigorate the NAACP's
ranks with more young people. The organization's membership,
currently about 500,000, rose by 17,000 in the past year, Bond
said, thanks greatly to efforts to recruit more college-age
members. ``Many of them are coming to us,'' he said, including a
group of students at Harvard University, which formed a chapter
this year, the first at the school since the 1960s, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While still tackling educational issues, like school vouchers,
which the NAACP generally opposes, the convention will also focus
discussion on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Mfume, who spoke despite suffering from a bad case
of laryngitis, said he and Bond would also look at what he called
``the digital divide'' between white and black Americans. A federal
survey last year found that 27 percent of white households were
connected to the Internet, compared with about 9 percent of black
and Hispanic households.
</P>
<P>
   As a way to help remedy that, Mfume announced a plan, still not
complete, to open NAACP ``tech centers'' at chapters around the
country, where children and parents could use Internet together.
The centers, none of which are operating yet, would be wired and
financed in part by AT&AMP;T, Mfume said, once negotiations with the
company are completed in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The organization also hopes to link each chapter in the nation
to a dedicated NAACP computer network, Bond said. ``Our dream is
that the whole of 2,200 branches will be interconnected,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to scheduling Mrs. Clinton and Gore, who is running
for president, the convention also invited other presidential
candidates, including former Sen. Bill Bradley, Texas Gov. George
W. Bush and Elizabeth Dole. An appearance by Bradley, scheduled for
Saturday night, was listed as tentative, but neither Bush nor Ms.
Dole will be here.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the lack of any national Republican figures on the
NAACP's schedule, Bond said he and Mfume had tried, unsuccessfully,
to get Bush and Ms. Dole, to show up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned that scheduling conflicts did not allow as
diverse a selection of speakers as we would have hoped,'' Bond
said. ``But we also are confident that we offered the
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Mfume said that both candidates may talk at next year's
convention, before the 2000 election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
