</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: NEWEST HALL OF FAMER STILL FULL OF SURPRISES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ The name of the game John McEnroe always played
best was surprise. Where was the next volley going? When was the
inevitable tantrum coming? What Robin Williams is to comedy,
McEnroe was to tennis. He made it up as he went along. He played it
this way, right through a quirky and typically rambling induction
on Saturday into the International Tennis Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   From his choice of presenter to the way he came to embrace his
fellow inductee to a Wimbledon aggravation he has not yet shaken,
McEnroe was hardly the standard guest of honor. He never had it in
him to be.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Heiden, for instance. Who would have guessed McEnroe would
have chosen the Olympic speed-skating legend turned professional
cyclist turned orthopedic surgeon as his presenter? Some years ago,
they met through a mutual friend, a football player for the Chicago
Bears, and hit it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the friends I feel I don't see enough of,''
McEnroe said.
</P>
<P>
   Why not now? Why not here?
</P>
<P>
   ``John called me up and asked and I was, like, wow,'' Heiden
said. ``I don't really know much about tennis, but he said he was
looking for someone who knew him more from off the court than on.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of which, McEnroe admitted he had to look twice when he
read that he would share his induction ceremony with a lesser-known
Mac. The 70-year-old Ken McGregor won the Australian Open in 1952
but was best known as one half of the doubles partnership _ with
Frank Sedgman _ that won the only male doubles Grand Slam, in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I said to myself, `Who the hell is Ken McGregor?' ''
said McEnroe, proud winner of three Wimbledon singles titles and
four at his hometown U.S. Open in New York. ``What's going on
here?''
</P>
<P>
   At a dinner for the inductees Friday night, McEnroe listened as
McGregor, an Australian, regaled his audience of the very old days,
when attention for tennis players was sparse and money was spare,
and unjust rules created punitive distinctions between amateurs and
pros.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe admitted the experience was educational. ``Ken was a
trailblazer, and made it possible for guys like myself,'' he said,
sounding on a theme he often uses when comparing his own
well-heeled era with the crazy-money one of today.
</P>
<P>
   They were also linked by Harry Hopman, the late, great
Australian Davis Cup captain and fellow Hall of Famer. McGregor
played for three of Hopman's championship teams. McEnroe cut his
permanent tennis teeth, as a 12-year-old charge of Hopman's after
Hopman had left Australia and settled in Port Washington, N.Y.,
near McEnroe's home in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe credited Hopman with imbuing in him the values of the
Davis Cup, which he helped win five times for the United States and
always made himself available for. In a larger sense, McEnroe said
Hopman's influence was about understanding a sense of commitment.
To your country. To your sport. Even to your doubles partner, come
hell, high water, or Wimbledon schedule submerged by rain.
</P>
<P>
   On that touchy subject, McEnroe said he was still nursing the
emotional wounds of Steffi Graf's withdrawal from their Wimbledon
mixed doubles semifinal last weekend. McEnroe noted Saturday that
his first Grand Slam title had been with Mary Carillo, in 1977, at
the French Open. At Wimbledon, he thought he had arranged the
perfect ending to an imperfect story. Center Court. His children
watching. His Hall of Fame induction coming.
</P>
<P>
   Graf pulled out, legitimately citing a minor muscle pull and the
wear and tear of the weather-condensed schedule. On the plane ride
home, McEnroe sat next to Pete Sampras, who, after a while, told
him, ``You really are upset about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course he was. This was how McEnroe competed at 20, 30 and
now at 40. It also happened to be the way Graf went about her
business, focused on the prize, singles-minded to the end. No
wonder McEnroe compared the breakup to the dissolution of his first
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the last to know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   From the time he retired from the tour seven years ago, McEnroe
knew he should have won more. He should never have imploded against
Ivan Lendl in the 1984 French Open final and blown a two-set lead.
He should never have let the big hitters who were taking over the
sport in the mid-1980s get into his head, forcing him to tinker too
much with his game.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wished he had started sooner with the new technology
but then, given the opportunity to play out this point, he realized
he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   His era had Borg and Connors and Vilas and Gerulaitis. It was,
he said, ``an explosion,'' a tennis era unto itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have changed a thing as to when I came in,'' he
decided.
</P>
<P>
   So why complain about Graf, or anything? It's who he is, what he
brought, the element of showmanship and surprise. Whereas McGregor
spoke for five minutes on Saturday, McEnroe went on for about 45.
It was part of his inherent charm, and his champion's conceit. On a
gray, breezy, Wimbledon-like afternoon, McEnroe seized center
stage, and wouldn't let go.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, off in the distance, you could hear the occasional
boom of a cannon being fired, from the nearby re-enactment of the
Civil War. Presumably, in honor of the one John McEnroe waged
spectacularly with tennis, and himself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 1608EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990710.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5492 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-VOICES-     07-10 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-VOICES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN GOP TERRITORY, MANY ARE WILLING TO GIVE MRS. CLINTON A CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. _ At the Cooperstown Diner, where the
waitresses swat regulars who lean back in their chairs, many in the
breakfast crowd said that Hillary Rodham Clinton, the would-be New
York senator who has never lived or worked in New York, could
survive being branded a carpetbagger.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she's honest and forthright and willing to help out, she
can live anyplace she wants,'' said James Leo, 50, who works at a
lumber yard and generally votes Republican. ``My grandparents
weren't born in this country. She can learn.''
</P>
<P>
   And several said that New York City, 250 miles to the southeast,
is so far away that upstaters consider her likely opponent to be an
exotic import as well. ``Giuliano's no different,'' Leo declared,
almost getting the name right.
</P>
<P>
   Despite news coverage suggesting that Mrs. Clinton is some sort
of political UFO touching down on a bewildered Empire State, most
of the dozens of voters interviewed here after her stops on an
inaugural campaign tour last week were already quite attuned to
what is being billed as the biggest Senate race of all time, and
were settling in for the show.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, a Democrat, spent most of her Listening to New
Yorkers tour in Republican territory, where she and her likely
opponent, New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, would have to scrap
for suburban and rural support. Here in Cooperstown, where giant
geranium pots line the Victorian downtown, even traditional
political opponents said Mrs. Clinton had drawn good reviews after
her visits to the local hospital and the National Baseball Hall of
Fame, where she posed with Hank Aaron's ``Powerized'' Louisville
Slugger from his 3,000th hit.
</P>
<P>
   However skeptical some in Cooperstown might be, most said they
were willing to give her a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Simmons, 27, said he knew how she could instantly acquire
her upstate bona fides: go hunting with him. Deer or turkey, her
choice.
</P>
<P>
   Merely accepting, though, will not be enough to win over
Simmons, a welder for a manufactured-housing company. ``It all
depends how hard she hunts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Others did not set the bar so high. ``She's a great lady who has
put up with a lot of adversity,'' said Russ Smith, 63, a Republican
who has driven a school bus here for 42 years. ``You can't be soft
and good.''
</P>
<P>
   Art Callahan, a power company lineman, was excitedly plotting
strategy. ``She would wait until a few months before the election,
then dump Bill!'' he said. ``She'd clean up.''
</P>
<P>
   Reminders were all around, however, that Republicans dominate
this lake-splotched region, which was the setting for James
Fenimore Cooper's ``Leatherstocking Tales.'' (Cooperstown is named
for his father, William Cooper, who founded the village as a
business venture in 1786.)
</P>
<P>
   North of the village, neatly stenciled letters have declared a
roadside outhouse, complete with crescent moon, to be ``Hillary's
Up State Headquarters.'' East of the village, posters say,
``Hillary Go Home to Arkansas!'' and ``Bill's Gals _ Paula, Monica
and HILLARY.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Hall of Fame, Kelly Ryan, a ticket booth attendant, will
turn 18 in time for the election and hopes to make Mrs. Clinton her
first vote. But Kelly reported that when she went home and bragged
about shaking Mrs. Clinton's hand, several people said, ``Oooh!
Wash it!''
</P>
<P>
   Even on the Democratic turf Mrs. Clinton visited, several voters
said she would have to work for their support.
</P>
<P>
   In Albany, Denise Von Kiparski, 39, a state employee who
processes barber, real estate and other licenses, said Mrs. Clinton
had the potential to spark as much excitement among women as
Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura created with his ambush campaign last
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she turns us on, I'll get out and help,'' Ms. Von Kiparski
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Grimaldi, 55, an ironworker and union representative, waited
in pouring rain at an Albany amphitheater to see Mrs. Clinton speak
briefly during the intermission of a play, and later said he was
glad he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she's a fraud,'' Grimaldi said, ``she's doing a good job
portraying herself as sincere _ to me, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   The hard-core anti-Hillary contingent could be found Friday
night in the beer tent at the Otsego County Firemen's Convention,
held among the silos about 25 miles west of Cooperstown, in
Edmeston.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Smullen, 33, a customer service worker, worried that
Mrs. Clinton would import a lot of liberal ideas. ``I'm afraid of
her, to be honest with you,'' Ms. Smullen said. ``She wants to help
the gays, and stuff. In New York state, we've already got enough of
those.''
</P>
<P>
   Although many voters downplayed the issue, some still said they
would always see her as a carpetbagger. ``It's like she looked
around and said, `New York ain't got many people running, so I'll
go there,''' said Brent Burchill, 33, who makes paint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opportunist'' is another word that comes up a lot. ``I think
she'd like to sit in the president's chair,'' said Earle Peterson,
65, a retired veterinarian. ``She feels Bill has blown it, and she
has got to get it done on her own.''
</P>
<P>
   The trappings of the White House also may prove to be a burden.
Several people said they were offended by the small, hand-picked
groups that met her, with the public barred.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the puzzling nature of the First Marriage seems likely to
remain an undercurrent in the race. ``You never hear anybody say
what Bill would do if she wins, which seems really weird,'' said
Lynn Kent, 44, a document imager.
</P>
<P>
   At the Strawberry Festival at St. Mary's Church, a Roman
Catholic parish in Cooperstown, several couples split in their
views of Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``She should run _ back to Arkansas,'' said Peter Bonhote, 65, a
carpentry teacher. But his wife, Ellen, praised her, saying, ``It's
about time she decided to be independent from her husband.''
</P>
<P>
   The Strawberry Festival turned into an ice cream sundae festival
when the berries fermented after the ladies of the church had
carefully hulled them. Toppings spattered everywhere as Steven and
Martha Heneghan fed their four children (ages 2 to 6) at the same
time that they were explaining why they might cross party lines to
vote for Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a very bright woman who can make things happen,'' said
Dr. Heneghan, 41, a surgeon who moved here from the Bronx. ``We
need that upstate.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Heneghan, 34, said she hoped Mrs. Clinton would bring up
issues like homelessness that many politicians are overlooking.
</P>
<P>
   On nearby Brooklyn Avenue, Susan Snell, 43, an architect and
mother of three young soccer players, was taking an evening stroll.
She is undecided about the Senate race, but said her friends who
had seen Mrs. Clinton were impressed by her knowledge and
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine voting for Rudy, and I really can't imagine
voting for Hillary Clinton,'' Mrs. Snell said. ``But I do think I'm
going to have to vote in this one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
