<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.Y.-ENERGY-CONSERVE-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACKOUTS RE-ARM ADVOCATES OF CONSERVATION PROGRAMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ALAN FINDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At a time when the rising demand for energy has
stretched the New York metropolitan region's power systems to the
limit, the state has quietly scaled back its effort to promote
energy conservation. Once a leader among states, New York has
reduced its main program to encourage conservation of electricity
by 75 percent in the last six years, much to the dismay of
environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   Conservationists have challenged the cutbacks by concentrating
on environmental concerns. They say it is important to reduce the
demand for electricity in order to curb air pollution by
diminishing the amount of fuel burned in power plants.
</P>
<P>
   But after the blackouts last week in Washington Heights, the
Lower East Side and other New York City neighborhoods,
environmentalists have seized on what they hope will be a powerful
new argument in the debate: Reducing the demand for electrical
power, they say, would reduce stress on an aging electrical
distribution system and diminish the risk of future power failures.
</P>
<P>
   Few if any environmentalists would claim that the cutback in the
state's energy conservation program caused the failure of
``feeder'' cables that carry electricity to neighborhoods from
local distribution stations, which led to the blackouts. Instead,
they say that a reduction in demand for electricity, especially at
peak moments like the hottest days of the summer, would ease the
strains on the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't say that problems with any single feeder line would
not occur,'' said Edward Smeloff the executive director of the Pace
Energy Project at the Pace University School of Law. ``But
statistically more load means more heat, which causes the failures.
The argument for conservation in the current setting is to increase
the robustness of the distribution system, to increase its
reliability.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The system's reliability, already severely tested in the heat
wave, faces much larger tests in the future, utility experts say.
The increasing demand for energy in the New York metropolitan area
is not being matched by a comparable increase in the systems'
capacity to generate and deliver it, the experts say.
</P>
<P>
   They say the answer lies in four areas: building power plants to
keep up with demand rising 2 percent to 3 percent a year
nationally; adding new transmission lines to bring power into the
metropolitan area; upgrading local lines that deliver electricity,
and adopting more aggressive energy conservation programs.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over changes by state regulators in the arcane world
of energy conservation has gone on for several years with little
public notice. That is in part because the regulations are
complicated, but it is also because fuel prices are at record lows
and electricity rates remain relatively low. Moreover, the benefits
of conserving energy are long term, while the cost of investing in
more energy-efficient equipment is immediate.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are far removed from the days, in the 1970s, when the
Arab oil boycott caused energy prices to skyrocket and conservation
to become a way of life, at least for a while. Just as motorists
slowly drifted back to larger, gas-guzzling sedans and sport
utility vehicles, consumers of electricity have lost much of their
passion for energy-efficient appliances and fixtures.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning a decade ago, state utility regulators tried to
encourage consumers to reduce their demand for electricity. They
created a program that requires power companies to reimburse
customers for some of the cost of replacing light fixtures,
electric motors, air-conditioners and other appliances with newer,
more energy-efficient models. The cost of the reimbursement was
built into the rates that utilities were permitted to charge.
</P>
<P>
   While homeowners and apartment owners could take advantage of
the program, it was aimed especially at businesses, owners of
office buildings and other commercial customers, where the
substitution of modern equipment can cut energy use by as much as
20 percent to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the program's peak years, in 1992 and 1993, power companies
statewide spent nearly $300 million a year to help subsidize the
purchase of energy-efficient appliances and lighting systems. But
then the cutbacks began, first under Gov. Mario Cuomo and
continuing under Gov. George Pataki. Last year, utilities spent $66
million for the conservation effort, according to data compiled by
the Natural Resources Defense Council.
</P>
<P>
   Other states have spent much more. Connecticut utilities spent
$109 million last year to reimburse customers for buying more
efficient equipment, and power companies in New Jersey spent $230
million, according to the Natural Resources Defense Council. In
California, utilities spent $415 million last year in a similar
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have all made a much greater commitment to energy
efficiency funding than New York does now,'' said Larry Shapiro, a
staff attorney with the New York Public Interest Research Group who
follows energy policy. ``In New York, the program has been mostly
dismantled.''
</P>
<P>
   State regulators scaled back the program to help reduce
electricity rates and as part of a broad restructuring of the
industry: moving away from the traditional system, which gave
utilities a monopoly on power distribution, and toward a
competitive market in which consumers will be able to choose among
electricity providers. In the new system, the regulators believe,
the marketplace will encourage efficiency, with some energy
companies trying to attract customers by offering conservation
services. The State Public Service Commission, which regulates
utilities, believes that ``innovative, cost-effective energy
services will develop in this new competitive market,'' said David
Flanagan, the commission's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But many conservationists are skeptical that energy companies
and consumers will spend enough on new equipment to curb the growth
in demand for electricity. The competitive pressure to keep rates
low will make it difficult to increase spending on conservation,
they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a short-term discretionary cost that they could
cut,'' Ashok Gupta, an economist at the Natural Resources Defense
Council, said of the reductions in conservation spending. ``It was
a bad decision to get some short-term savings. It's like not
plugging up the hole in your gas tank because you don't want to
spend the money right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason we need to do it is that markets don't do it,''
Gupta said. ``Developers who build the buildings don't care what
the energy bill will be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
