<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Sunday, July 11 and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Susan Leh at the Daily News, (818) 713-3701.
</P>
<P>
   CALABASAS-BOUNDARY (Los Angeles) _ Leonis Adobe, heart of Old
Town Calabasas and symbol of the thriving city's past as a dusty
stagecoach stop, isn't in Calabasas. Neither is the Calabasas
Farmers' Market, and the Sagebrush Cantina. But if Calabasas has
its way, it will annex all of those spots and a 50-unit condominium
project. By Michael Coit. (Will move in ``n'' California news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   LA-STREETS (Los Angeles) _ For the first time since the 1920s,
Los Angeles is repaving its streets fast enough to keep up with the
rate they are breaking down. But the repaving program falls short
of repairing nearly a century of decay. City crews will resurface
220 miles in this fiscal year _ a 46 percent increase over the
previous year _ but they would have to pour 350 miles of new
asphalt every year over the next decade to smooth the city's
ravaged roads. By Deborah Sullivan. (Will move in the ``n''
California news file.)
</P>
