<SLUG> BC-METS-VENTURA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENTURA SURPRISES METS AND THEN INSPIRES THEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (With BBO-METS-YANKS) 
 (js) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Robin Ventura approached his locker stall in the Mets'
clubhouse Saturday morning, the good-natured ribbing began.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's walking!'' Brian McRae said, in mock disbelief. ``I can't
believe he's walking. It's amazing! I guess they never had gamers
in this city before.''
</P>
<P>
   New York has had plenty of gamers over the years. But McRae was
right about one thing: Ventura deserves the title.
</P>
<P>
   The third baseman, who turns 32 on Wednesday, was not expected
to play against the Yankees at Shea Stadium Friday night. It was
questionable whether he would even play at all this weekend because
of a bruised big toe on his left foot.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Ventura was hobbling around the Mets' clubhouse Friday
afternoon. And he not only talked Manager Bobby Valentine into
letting him play that night, Ventura's defense _ seven assists, two
putouts _ was instrumental in the Mets' 5-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura obviously has a tremendous threshold for pain. His left
foot has bothered him since the first time at bat of the season,
when Florida's Luis Castillo dropped a bunt down the third-base
line in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``The foot was planted, I tried to go the other way and I
sprained my midfoot,'' Ventura said.
</P>
<P>
   The foot has yet to fully heal. And so, when Ventura was hit on
his big toe with a pitch against the Montreal Expos on Wednesday
night, it only made matters worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The foot hurts, that's all,'' Ventura said. But not enough to
keep him from playing against the Yankees. That would take
something much more serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mostly fielding,'' he said. ``If I feel like I can get to
ground balls, then I'll say I can play. You do what you can,
hitting. But if you don't field balls, you're not really good to
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Ventura, a five-time Gold Glove winner, fielded everything hit
his way. And on Saturday he admitted one of the reasons he wanted
to play was that with Al Leiter pitching plenty of grounders
figured to come his way.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura's mere presence at third seems to lift the Mets. Call it
the Willis Reed effect. Reed hobbled out onto the floor for Game 7
of the 1970 National Basketball Association Finals and inspired his
Knicks teammates to a title over the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the Mets and Yankees were playing for lesser stakes.
But Ventura hobbled out to third base just the same. And his
teammates, the winning pitcher Leiter in particular, said Friday
night it picked them up. They were not the only ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a tremendous performance from him yesterday,''
General Manager Steve Phillips said Saturday. ``Just being out
there was significant. It was as if he was a magnet, almost like to
test him, and he handled every play. I thing it was a pick up.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Valentine said, ``Robin has given a real favorable
impression since he got here. And these last few days have put an
accent on what he's brought.''
</P>
<P>
   It came as no surprise, therefore, when Ventura popped his head
in the manager's office Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He walked into the clubhouse, came into my office, sat down
and said he can't wait to have three days of barbecue to rest his
body and foot,'' Valentine said, referring to the All-Star Game
break. ``I looked at the calendar and said three days are coming up
soon, and he said he'll use those three days to rest.''
</P>
<P>
   And as much as Ventura deserved a trip to Boston to play in the
All-Star Game, he deserves the rest even more.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   JAY PAYTON is injured again. General Manager STEVE PHILLIPS said
Payton had tweaked an oblique muscle Friday and will be out seven
to 10 days. Payton has already missed considerable chunks of this
season due to shoulder surgery and hamstring problems. Payton, who
has also had numerous elbow problems, just cannot seem to stay
healthy. He is hitting .388 for Class AAA Norfolk in 26 games. ``We
are concerned about him,'' Phillips said. ``It would be nice to
keep him healthy. The ball comes off his bat different than most
hitters. I don't know if it's bad luck or bad collagen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
