<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5508 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-PARRA-NYT &LR;      07-10 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-PARRA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WELL-TRAVELED YOUNGSTER FINALLY HITS HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Md.)   (bl)  
 By ANDREW R. TRIPALDI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carlos Parra thinks he has finally found his soccer niche with
the New England Revolution of Major League Soccer. And it took only
three years, two trades, hassles with the National Collegiate
Athletic Association, and a series of personal and professional
adjustments on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Things started out simply enough. While attending West Haven
High School in Connecticut, Parra transferred to nearby Hamden Hall
as a junior, partly because his mother wanted him to attend a
private school but also because Hamden had an outstanding soccer
program.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Hamden Hall in June 1996, Parra, a
defensive midfielder, was set to attend the University of Maryland
on a full athletic scholarship in September. Going to college and
playing soccer had been a family goal from the outset, and Parra
was thrilled that he was going to play at the Division I level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking forward to being a part of the soccer program at
Maryland,'' Parra said. ``I was very excited and very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The rejoicing didn't last long. About a week before Parra was to
move to Maryland, the NCAA ruled that he was ineligible for his
college scholarship because his ninth grade English class at West
Haven was academically unacceptable. Encouraged by his family to
take another English class, Parra fulfilled the NCAA requirement.
But, still stung by the ruling, he decided not to attend Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Parra declared his eligibility for the 1997 MLS draft,
and, at 19, he was selected by the MetroStars and became the
youngest player in the league's history. His soccer nightmare
seemed to have turned into a dream come true.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had always rooted for the MetroStars because they were the
local team for me when I was still in school in Connecticut,''
Parra said.
</P>
<P>
   Parra played in four games for New York/New Jersey during the
1997 season. He also spent time with Project 40, a program to
assist the top prospects in the United States between the ages of
18 and 20.
</P>
<P>
   The experience he gained from Project 40 and his youthful
promise on the MetroStars bench didn't help Parra, however, when
Coach Alfonso Mondelo decided to go with veterans.
</P>
<P>
   On June 5, 1998, Parra was traded to Miami for Ramiro Corrales.
Disappointed, but undeterred, Parra embraced Miami and became a
solid contributor to the Fusion. He finished the 1998 season with
two assists in 1,367 minutes over 18 games, establishing himself as
a defensive presence. And Miami made the playoffs, where it lost to
D.C. United in the Eastern Conference semifinals 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   But as the 1999 season approached, Parra, homesick and yearning
to return to the Northeast, expressed his feelings to the Miami
management. On June 4, he was traded to New England for forward
Tony Kuhn and a second round pick in the 2000 college draft. Now on
his third professional team and still young enough to be a college
undergraduate, Parra was coming home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have many veteran players on our team, and at 22, he has
already played in the MLS for three seasons,'' said Walter Zenga,
the New England coach-goaltender, who called the 6-foot-2-inch,
165-pound Parra a strong midfield tackler. ``I think he can
continue to grow and develop into a top player by learning from the
players around him.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, playing alongside his New England teammates John
Harkes and Joe Max-Moore, both veterans of the United States
national team, can only help Parra. And though it took a while,
Parra said he is finally feeling at home with his role with the
Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on how the team is faring, Parra plays 30 to 45
minutes, primarily in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am able to come in the game with fresh legs and win tackles
and get the loose balls,'' Parra said. ``Walter told me that my job
right now is to come off the bench and contribute to the team in
the second half of the game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
