<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENOVATIONS-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH A LOT OF WORK A WRECK CAN BE TURNED INTO A GEM  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.) (rk) 
 By   TRISH HALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You have to wonder. Did it ever occur to the dogs
that their routes had suddenly changed, that they were taking long
detours, walking past construction sites and debris-filled
Dumpsters?
</P>
<P>
   Because for several months, while the owners of Johnny Dog
Walkers were squiring their charges around the Upper West Side of
Manhattan, they were walking even more than usual, looking for
cast-off materials that might be used to restore the owners' new
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   It was a place that needed everything, a place so rundown that
even the typical euphemisms weren't used by the broker _ no mincing
words, no ``with a little TLC this Upper West Side gem. ...'' It
was an out-and-out wreck.
</P>
<P>
   The large one-bedroom apartment with a separate office,
previously occupied by a 92-year-old woman, had a decrepit kitchen,
a bathtub with pipes so corroded water could barely make its way
out, and tons of peeling paint, all of it powder blue, even on the
old oak moldings. The floors were covered with linoleum.
</P>
<P>
   But it was only $110,000 for 780 square feet with a $560
maintenance, a good price for a sunny apartment on West 85th
Street, even three years ago, when they found it. And if John
Kristovich and John Bilka were ever to live in something larger
than a studio apartment, they figured they would have to take on
something with problems. ``No one wanted it,'' said Bilka, 38.
``Which was kind of scary,'' said Kristovich, 34.
</P>
<P>
   It looked as if it would cost about $60,000 to renovate, and the
two men had only $20,000. Buying it in the first place was a big
stretch, made possible only by a loan from Kristovich's father, a
retired policeman in San Francisco who is now a real estate broker.
</P>
<P>
   By looking for old but usable materials, and by doing much of
the work themselves, they hoped to restore the apartment to its
former style, not implant something modern or foreign in the 1899
apartment building. It's not a grand building, by any means, but
their apartment has a great deal of inherent charm, with pleasing
moldings, high ceilings and rooms laid out so that privacy is
maximized.
</P>
<P>
   As so often happens, things didn't exactly go well. Because they
couldn't afford to hire a contractor with a large crew, they hired
a contractor and agreed to do much of the work themselves. Every so
often, Kristovich would hand the contractor a check for $5,000,
until one day he realized that he had already spent $18,000, ``and
we had no kitchen, and no bathroom.''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the contractor basically disappeared, the two men
said, leaving one worker at the job. With that sole worker, they
proceeded to finish the job, learning about construction as they
did it.
</P>
<P>
   For the kitchen, they found an old cupboard in a Dumpster that
very nearly matched an existing one in their now charming kitchen,
with its green-tiled counter top and window box of geraniums. A
Dumpster also yielded a mirrored cabinet for the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were like rats,'' Kristovich said. ``That was something our
contractor couldn't understand, bringing in old crummy stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the bulk of the work was done, and their bill
reached $27,000. Their relationship with the contractor steadily
deteriorated, and at the end, Bilka said, the contractor said,
``OK, that's it, we're outta here,'' and walked out the door.
</P>
<P>
   Bilka was so angry about the mess left behind, he said, ``that I
started throwing bags of garbage at him, paint cans, saying, `Take
it with you.'''
</P>
<P>
   The process was so agonizing that they came to hate the
apartment, and dreaded moving in. ``It was very emotional at the
end,'' said Kristovich. But once the contractor was gone, it was
really over, and they began anew. ``We loved the apartment,'' said
Kristovich. But just to be sure that the bad energy was gone, a
friend came in, with potions of sage and rosewater.
</P>
<P>
   ``She knows about blessing apartments,'' Bilka said, sounding
not like a believer but simply a man unwilling to risk any more
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   For Kristovich, who had been working sporadically as an actor
after graduating with a theater arts degree from UCLA, the
renovation was more than just a way to have a place to live. He
found the process so compelling he gave up acting and enrolled in a
two-year degree program in interior design at Parsons.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Bilka, who had been working in theatrical management and set
decoration for movies, now uses their home office to write. Both
continue to walk dogs and to work on the apartment, although
they've stopped their Dumpster shopping. Recently, Bilka stripped
decades of encrusted paint from the original living room
chandelier, exposing its brass-plated tin, and he has plans to do
the same for the one in their office.
</P>
<P>
   But even before they finally finish, they have been wondering
what it might be like to take on another wreck. Just out of
curiosity, they accepted a broker's offer to come and look their
place over and estimate its value. Told that their place might
fetch $330,000, they are tempted to do it again.
</P>
<P>
   Kristovich, though, is not a mover by nature. ``I'd hate to
leave this place,'' he said. ``I could see being a little old man
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Bilka, though, couldn't be more different. In the early 1980s,
he was working for IBM, and moved so often that his manager once
called him in, worried about the number of new addresses. ``He
asked, `Is someone harassing you? Are you in trouble?''' Bilka
recalled. ``I said, `No, I just like to move a lot.'''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Kristovich's reluctance, it is easy to see that the lure
of the ever-rising real estate market might pull them toward
another project.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're attached to our mothers, too,'' he said, ``but for the
right price, we'd sell them.''(BBOX)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
