<SLUG> BC-NY-COOPS-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG ISLAND: AS RENTS CLIMB, CO-OP SALES AND PRICES TURN UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By DIANA SHAMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After renting in the Park Slope section of Brooklyn
for eight years, Nancy Heiss, who works as a project manager for a
Manhattan office furniture company, decided she wanted to buy
rather than continue as a tenant.
</P>
<P>
   But with apartments in both Park Slope and Manhattan so
expensive, she said, her search brought her to Long Beach, an area
where her parents had once lived, and where she has relatives.
</P>
<P>
   She found a $120,000 one-bedroom co-op at 600 Shore Road through
a local real estate agent, Marilyn Topper, and closed June 16. The
94-unit oceanfront building has an indoor pool. Her apartment has a
side view of the ocean and her $600 a month maintenance includes
taxes and heat. With mortgage payments, her monthly costs are
$1,300, which is $300 less than one-bedroom rentals in Park Slope,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some savings, interest rates were down and I just felt
the time was right for me to buy,'' said the 35-year-old Miss
Heiss.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, the Long Island co-op market was almost moribund in
some areas, and price increases are still lagging behind those of
houses and condominiums.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last market to have been lifted up in the suburbs has been
the co-op market because buyers feel that condominiums offer them
greater flexibility,'' said Kenneth Jacobs, a Manhattan and Yonkers
lawyer who is president of the metropolitan area chapter of the
Community Associations Institute, a national organization of co-op,
condominium and homeowners associations in Alexandria, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Co-op buyers often do not like the idea that boards have so much
control, Jacobs explained.
</P>
<P>
   Owning shares in a cooperative corporation instead of receiving
a deed to property is still an alien concept for many suburbanites,
said Mark Walsh of Consolidated Communities of Long Island, a group
representing 75 co-op, condominium and homeowners associations in
Suffolk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Co-ops have the same pools and amenities as condominiums, the
buildings are in good shape, the grounds are nicely kept and they
are in good shape financially, but people are still a bit leery of
co-ops,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But a turnaround is now being swelled by first-time buyers like
Miss Heiss who are tired of pouring money into rent and by older
purchasers. For those couples, many of whom are selling their homes
at high prices, co-ops offer a way to stay in their communities in
a maintenance-free setting that, unlike a rental, has tax
advantages.
</P>
<P>
   The revived interest in co-ops began in areas like Great Neck,
which has a heavy concentration of apartment houses, but now
appears to be affecting sales everywhere as prices of single-family
houses and condominiums continue to climb.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market started turning around slowly the beginning of the
year and it is now really starting to move,'' said Elaine Nolan, a
Hempstead broker, about her area of Mineola and Hempstead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six months ago, we got three calls a month for co-op loans;
now we are getting 10 to 15 calls,'' said Richard Shyman, the
president of IMS Capital in Melville, a mortgage broker. ``Co-ops
are viable again and mortgage money is there again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Prices are coming back incredibly and we are seeing a lot more
action,'' said Steven Greenbaum, director of property management at
Mark Greenberg Real Estate in Port Washington, which manages about
40 co-op buildings in Nassau.
</P>
<P>
   F OR a long time, ``there was almost no market,'' said Michael
F. Cohen, a Smithtown lawyer who represents 20 co-op complexes in
Suffolk. ``But the price of co-op apartments is so disproportionate
to the cost of homes that people realize they represent a
lower-cost alternative and are something they can still afford,''
he added. ``The co-ops I represent have seen sales and prices they
have not seen for a number of years.''
</P>
<P>
   These observations are echoed by co-op owners. ``Nowhere on Long
Island is the market comparable to what's happening in Manhattan,
but it's definitely picking up after being sluggish for a good
number of years,'' said Michael Herzog, president of the co-op
board at the 68-unit Cedarhurst Park in Cedarhurst.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for a one-bedroom apartment in the building have gone up
to $85,000 from $60,000 in three years, Herzog said, and
two-bedrooms have risen to $120,000 from $90,000. ``We are getting
young couples who can't afford a house and who want to own
something, and older people selling houses who want to stay in the
area,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Ellmer, the co-op board president of the 84-unit Seaview
Terrace in Long Beach, said that would-be buyers were calling at
the rate of ``about five calls a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Prices in the building have seen a ``tremendous jump'' over the
last two years, said Ellmer, a Garden City lawyer. Still, with
prices ranging from $80,000 for a studio to $190,000 for a
two-bedroom, ``the co-ops are reasonably priced for people who have
sold a home and want a smaller place and also for young people just
starting out,'' he said. Many young professionals are coming to
Long Beach, he added, because of the beach community style of
living.
</P>
<P>
   At the Valley Park Estates co-op in Valley Stream, the sponsor,
VP Owners in Great Neck, which still owns 130 of the 436 units in
the complex, had been renting them out for years because nothing
was selling.
</P>
<P>
   Now it has more buyers than empty apartments available, said
Jeffrey Bookman, one of the principals. ``A year ago, we had no
activity,'' he said. ``Now we are selling four to five units a
month.'' With prices for the one- and two-bedroom apartments
ranging from $40,000 to $60,000, and monthly rents for the same
units ranging from $850 to $1,100, ``people realize it's cheaper to
own than to rent,'' Bookman said, adding he has 20 units under
contract.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The major issue for me was owning something rather than
renting,'' said Lucian Gonzalez, an engineer, recently bought a
one-bedroom unit at Valley Park Estates, paying $40,000. With
maintenance of a $495, his monthly costs come to only $800,
Gonzalez said. He had been paying $700 a month to rent a studio
apartment in Howard Beach, Queens. ``I also view my co-op as a
steppingstone to eventually purchasing a house,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Greenberg, a salesman for a hair products company, and his
wife, Diane, who is in real estate sales, moved into the Plaza, a
Lawrence co-op, four years ago, after selling a four-bedroom home
in North Woodmere. The building is next to a country club with golf
and a marina and is a short walk to the train station.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lived in a house for 30 years, and I didn't miss the house
three minutes,'' said Greenberg, now board president at the Plaza,
a luxury building with a pool and a doorman where two-bedroom
apartments now sell for $250,000 (up, according to Mrs. Greenberg,
from $195,000 a year ago).
</P>
<P>
   It is buyers like the Greenbergs who are also fueling the Great
Neck market. People are selling large and unwieldy houses to move
into a community where amenities, shopping and transportation are
all nearby, said Ellen Steinberg-Finkelstein, who specializes in
co-op sales at Trylon Realty in Great Neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago, people would sell their houses and rent, but now
they want to buy because rentals are too expensive,'' she added.
``My problem is that I don't have enough inventory.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of her recent buyers, Doris and Seymour Graylin, came from
34 years of living in a two-family house in Bayside, Queens, moving
last week into a two-bedroom co-op in Great Neck, for which they
paid $300,000, not counting extensive renovations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never another house,'' said Mrs. Graylin, 69. Her husband, a
retired accountant, is 75. ``I don't want to weed the garden
anymore or shovel snow,'' Mrs. Graylin added.
</P>
<P>
   Their new apartment is two blocks from shopping, restaurants and
the Long Island Rail Road station ``so we won't have to drive so
much,'' she added. ``Renting was not an option,'' she said,
``because we wouldn't have any tax benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Prices in Great Neck have been rising, Ms. Steinberg-Finkelstein
said. Studios that started at $30,000 two years ago now begin at
$55,000. A typical one-bedroom has gone to $175,000 from $142,000,
and a two-bedroom to $350,000 from $235,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are reliving 1985 to 1986 again because, with the decrease
in the amount of houses on the market, that leaves co-ops,'' said
Jan Kalman, a real estate agent in Woodmere.
</P>
<P>
   In Roslyn, where small houses start at $250,000 and there is
also a shortage of houses for sale, ``co-ops are the best
alternative if you want to get into a good school district,'' said
Roy Sobel, a local broker. Prices for a one-bedroom start at
$60,000, and a two-bedroom recently closed for $79,500, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people can't afford a home, but they want to buy
something and so they are buying co-ops,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
