u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-HOME-REAL-750(2TAK     07-10 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-750(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESIDENTIAL STORAGE LOCKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One of the frustrations of modern life is having lots
of stuff but nowhere to put it. In a city where closets become
bedrooms, empty space becomes a treasured amenity.
</P>
<P>
   It is not surprising, then, that when co-op or condominium
boards start thinking about converting spare space into spare
change, they often end up thinking about storage lockers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Storage lockers can be a benefit for residents and a
moneymaker for the building,'' said Arnold Roth, president of A&AMP;D
Steel Equipment, a storage locker manufacturer in the Long Island
City section of Queens. ``You take a dirty, dark, empty space and
turn it into a beautiful room that's freshly painted, well-lit and
clean as a whistle.''
</P>
<P>
   Roth's company specializes in building fully enclosed, steel
storage lockers with double doors, a baked-enamel finish and
locking rods that extend through the frame at the top and bottom of
the doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do leave some holes so that air can penetrate,'' he said.
``But they're small enough to keep the critters with four legs
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Roth said that almost any dry, empty space in a building can be
turned into a storage area that residents will pay to fill with
their belongings.
</P>
<P>
   ``An average-sized storage locker can rent for anywhere from $25
to $40 a month,'' Roth said, noting that ``average'' referred to a
locker that is about 7 feet high, 4 or 5 feet wide and 4 or 5 feet
deep. ``In upscale buildings that are short on closet space, you
can get even more money. We sold one building a 7-foot-tall,
5-by-5-foot locker with double-thick metal walls and a metal
ceiling. It even had hookups for electrical fixtures. They rented
it out for $450 a month.''
</P>
<P>
   While average-sized storage lockers in average buildings demand
more average rents, Roth said, what makes them a ``win-win''
proposition for a co-op or condominium is that even a modest rental
charge quickly becomes pure profit for the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's the trick,'' Roth explained. ``Average lockers cost
about $500 to $600 apiece. The co-op board usually buys them with
money from the reserve fund. Then the board rents the lockers to
residents for a monthly fee. That means that if the board gets just
$25 a month, that's $300 a year, and the locker is completely paid
for in about two years.'' After that, Roth said, it's clear profit
for the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put in 50 lockers, and in a couple of years you've
recouped your original $25,000 investment and you're making $15,000
a year in profit,'' he said. ``That's better than investing in
bonds.''
</P>
<P>
   But what if a building just doesn't have an extra $25,000 lying
around? Or what if a building's board just doesn't like the idea of
going into the locker rental business?
</P>
<P>
   No problem, said Josh Goldman, an executive vice president of
Bargold Storage Systems in Manhattan. ``We can take a dark, dismal
area and transform it into a professional-looking storage facility
in a couple of weeks and at no cost to the building.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman explained that when a co-op or condominium board hires
Bargold for its storage-locker needs, the building gets a freshly
painted, well-lit storage area filled with elevator-sized
corrugated steel lockers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We build our 7-foot-tall lockers 4 feet wide by 6 feet deep,''
he said. ``We want them to be big enough to hold a bicycle without
standing it on end.''
</P>
<P>
   Such lockers, Goldman said, can be installed in whatever empty
space a building has available without the expenditure of one cent
of the reserve fund or one iota of energy on the part of the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do everything,'' Goldman said. ``We build the lockers on
site, paint the room, put in new lighting and secure the room with
high-security locking doors. Then we do all the administrative
work, all the marketing, all the billing, all the collecting and
all the signing up of tenants.'' And at the end of every month, he
added, Bargold sends the building a check for 25 percent of all
storage fees it collects.
</P>
<P>
   ``We provide a true amenity for residents with no imposition on
the board,'' Goldman said, adding that the average monthly rent for
a 6-by-6-foot locker in Manhattan is about $45; the average in the
other boroughs and outside the city is about $38 a month. Generally
speaking, he said, Bargold estimates the number of lockers that
will be needed in a particular building at somewhere between 10 and
20 percent of the total number of units in the building.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For boards that like the idea of generating revenue by providing
storage space for residents, but dislike the idea of becoming
locker landlords only slightly less than they dislike the idea of
an outsider siphoning money from the building, there is yet another
alternative: Convert the unused space into cash by building
lockers, allocating shares to the lockers and selling the shares to
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many buildings have allocated shares to areas that are not
physically attached to a particular unit,'' said Arthur I.
Weinstein, vice president of the Council of New York Cooperatives
and Condominiums. ``Buildings often allocate shares to parking
spaces and then sell the shares, and the exclusive right to use the
space, to tenant-shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Generally speaking, Weinstein said, allocating shares to
amenities such as storage lockers is attractive to both the co-op
and its shareholders. The co-op, he said, generates revenue from
the sale of shares to otherwise unproductive space and by
collecting additional maintenance charges on the new shares.
</P>
<P>
   The shareholder, on the other hand, gets to own his or her
storage space rather than having to rent it from someone else, has
surplus belongings close at hand and enjoys the tax benefits of
deducting property taxes and interest on share-loans used to
purchase the shares allocated to the space.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein noted, however, that allocating shares to
nonresidential areas of a co-op can be risky business if it is not
handled properly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Section 216 of the tax code says that all outstanding shares
in a co-op must be issued for residential purposes,'' he said,
explaining that it is that section of the code that gives co-op
shareholders the ability to be treated like homeowners and
condominium unit-owners for income-tax purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, Weinstein said, if a board does not make absolutely
certain that shares allocated to ``ancillary spaces'' are owned
only by existing tenant-shareholders as appurtenances to their
apartments, the entire building could lose its status as a
residential co-op under Section 216 of the tax code.
</P>
<P>
   And that, said Joel E. Miller, a Queens tax lawyer, could result
in shareholders losing valuable tax benefits such as the right to
take deductions for property taxes and the interest on share loans
and the underlying mortgage on the building, and depriving them of
the ability to exclude from capital gains taxes up to $500,000 in
gain realized upon the sale of an apartment that is a principal
residence.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said that the best way for a co-op board to prevent that
from happening would be to tie ancillary spaces like storage
lockers to individual apartments by combining the shares allocated
to both on a single certificate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's critical to keep the shares to ancillary spaces
absolutely tied to a dwelling unit in the building,'' Miller said.
``Because if those shares should come into the hands of somebody
who is not a tenant-shareholder, you could have a very expensive
problem on your hands.''
</P>
