<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5515 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMMERCIAL-REAL-3TAKE     07-10 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMERCIAL-REAL-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSIGNIA GROUP'S EXPANDING UNIVERSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, S.C.) (lb) 
 By JOHN HOLUSHA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It would be hard to argue that Andrew Farkas, the
chairman and chief executive of Insignia Financial Group, is afraid
of change.
</P>
<P>
   Starting the company in 1990, he built it into one of the
largest owners and managers of residential properties in the United
States. Then, in 1996, he acquired Edward S. Gordon Co., one of the
largest commercial real estate services companies in the New York
region, and used it as the base for building a nationwide and
international network of commercial offices.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later he got out of the apartment management business
outside the New York area to concentrate on developing the
commercial side of the business.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently he spent $65 million to acquire Douglas Elliman,
which has a network of offices in upscale New York suburbs and is
the largest residential brokerage in Manhattan. With Douglas
Elliman and Edward S. Gordon as its keystones, Insignia has
announced plans to link commercial and residential operations in an
effort to become a powerful real estate services presence in key
corporate-headquarters cities around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strategy for operating the business is to become dominant
in industry segments,'' said Farkas, who is not yet 40 years old,
during an interview in his newly decorated office at 200 Park Ave.
``That's why Douglas Elliman was such a special opportunity. It
enabled us to become dominant in the No. 1 market in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The move of his corporate headquarters to the former Pan Am
building represents something of a homecoming for Farkas, who is a
native New Yorker. He built the residential management business in
Greenville, S.C., because of the lower costs in that region, but
shifted to New York when he disposed of that business last year.
</P>
<P>
   Farkas is a son of the chairman of the former Alexander's
department store chain, Robin Farkas, who now sits on Insignia's
board.
</P>
<P>
   The company's growth notwithstanding, Insignia's stock price has
remained stuck in the $10 to $12 a share range in recent weeks at a
time when the overall market has been soaring, after trading as
high as $15.50 earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say that publicly traded real estate service companies
as a group are out of favor on Wall Street for reasons that range
from the inherently cyclical nature of the real estate business to
a skepticism about the belief that combining dissimilar service
operations will increase earnings and cash flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Street either doesn't understand his strategy or it
doesn't believe the parts fit together in a strategic sense,'' said
Will Marks of Bank of America Securities. Marks also noted that
Insignia has the shortest track record of its publicly traded
peers, at nine years, compared with 30 to 90 years for companies
such as CB Richard Ellis, Jones Lang LaSalle, Grubb &AMP; Ellis and
Trammell Crow and their predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Insignia is trying to do has not been done at this level
before,'' said David Harris, an analyst with Lehman Brothers. This,
he said, is a problem for investors because they do not have any
similar companies with which to compare Insignia's financial
performance.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to create additional demand for the stock,
Insignia's board authorized the repurchase of $10 million in stock
in October. Last week, the company announced that $7.5 million had
been spent and authorized an additional $10 million repurchase
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Farkas said he expects to acquire other residential brokerage
companies in cities where Insignia already has commercial
operations and to add services, such as providing mortgages to
buyers of residential properties. Today, the company's network is
composed of 49 offices in 25 states and includes 13
commercial-services companies purchased since the Gordon
acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   Insignia/ESG is the biggest commercial real estate services
operation in the New York metropolitan area, having closed 19 of
the 50 largest New York City leasing transactions last year.
Nationally, it completed deals for 100 million square feet of
commercial property and arranged for $3.5 billion in sales and
financing in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Farkas is already established in Britain, Germany and Italy, and
he said he is seeking to acquire existing commercial and
residential companies in other locations in Europe and Asia or
start new companies where suitable acquisitions cannot be
completed. ``Our sights are set on major financial capitals of
Europe, Asia, Canada, Latin America and elsewhere,'' he declared in
Insignia's most recent annual report.
</P>
<P>
   The point of all of this is to build a one-stop-shopping real
estate company for big corporations and the people who manage them.
``We want to be part of every New Yorker's personal and corporate
real estate needs,'' he said in an interview earlier this month.
``The same executives who retain us for commercial space are the
ones who use Douglas Elliman to buy and sell their own co-ops and
condos.''
</P>
<P>
   And since Insignia Residential Group manages 60,000 co-op and
condominium apartments in the metropolitan area, many of those
living in the units are already accustomed to writing monthly
checks to Insignia.
</P>
<P>
   Many industry executives, however, question whether the
synergies that Farkas claims are made possible by combining
commercial and residential operations really exist.
</P>
<P>
   Julien Studley, chairman of the commercial brokerage company
bearing his name, which specializes in representing tenants, said
real estate services companies are hard to manage when they grow
quickly, and called Farkas' plans ``a very challenging task.''
Studley has maintained that real estate service companies are
difficult to manage when they grow quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Mosler, an executive vice president of Cushman &AMP;
Wakefield, one of Insignia's major rivals on the commercial side,
said that ``there is not much synergy between residential and
commercial because they are such different businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are skeptical that the combination will add to
their market share,'' Mosler said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the model for such an effort was the firm of
Coldwell Banker, which added residential brokerage to its existing
commercial brokerage in 1937. The company was acquired by Sears,
Roebuck &AMP; Co. in 1981 and Sears decided to sell the
commercial-brokerage operations eight years later to a company now
known as CB Richard Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to question how successful it was, because Sears
decided to break it up,'' Mosler said.
</P>
<P>
   Farkas contests the analogy. ``Coldwell Banker was different,''
he said. ``It was a single brand and a single management doing both
commercial and residential.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward S. Gordon and Douglas Elliman are different brands and
different businesses that were successful independently and are now
linked only by a common ownership, Farkas said. ``They have
completely separate systems and management and never the twain
shall meet,'' he said. ``The two businesses grew up separately and
achieved dominance, and they just happened to have done it in the
same market.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The importance of the brand was also emphasized by Alan Rogers,
the chief executive of Douglas Elliman, who continued in his
position after the company was sold to Insignia. Douglas Elliman
has more than 780 brokers, supported by a corporate staff of 100 in
15 offices. Last year it completed more than 4,100 transactions
with a total value of $1.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The experience since the acquisition was announced at the end of
May, he said, appears to indicate that there is cross-pollination
between the commercial and residential sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are keeping the Douglas Elliman name,'' he said. ``It is a
great brand that has traditionally been upscale. But more recently
we have been making an effort to be all things to all people, with
a cradle-to-grave philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the approach was to try to connect with young people
when they first move to the city and to stay with them as they
advance professionally and economically. ``They will probably rent
for a few years and then buy something for $400,000 or $500,000,''
he said. ``They will probably upgrade once or twice before they
finally get a big apartment to raise their family.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it is still not clear how the relationship with the
commercial side of the company will work out in the long term, but
he added: ``I've been staggered over the last few weeks about the
contacts we have gotten from ESG. We get calls saying, `I've got
this client, can you help him, can you help this friend?' There
could be a huge opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Siegel, president of Insignia Financial Group, said the
corporate relocations arranged by the commercial side of the
business have implications for employees who will need housing.
``If people are to be transferring into the tristate area, we can
present an analysis to management about the market and whether
there is a need for incentives,'' he said. ``We can present an
entire package.''
</P>
<P>
   The other residential property owned by Insignia is Realty One,
a Cleveland-based brokerage company specializing in
single-family-home sales. Although it is the biggest such company
in Ohio, and thus meets the goal of market dominance, it seems to
stick out in Insignia's mix of commercial brokerage and investment
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Farkas said one attraction was that Realty One was advanced
technically and had a mortgage banking operation, First Ohio
Mortgage, that will almost certainly be added in some form to
Douglas Elliman. The ability to provide mortgage loans without
having to involve third-party lenders aids the brokerage business
by helping to complete transactions and generates income by
charging fees for the services.
</P>
<P>
   Like most such operations, First Ohio groups the mortgages in
pools and sells them to investors.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase of Realty One two years ago was intended to be the
first step in an effort to consolidate the highly fragmented home
brokerage business, Farkas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got Realty One in 1997 at a time when there seemed to be an
opportunity to consolidate the industry into a big national
franchise,'' he said. But after the acquisition, the price of
companies in that business increased beyond what Insignia was
willing to pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the pricing moved away from us we pulled in our horns and
spent the last 24 months learning the business,'' he said. Since
then, he said, the price of brokerage firms has declined, so
Insignia is shopping again, with the Douglas Elliman acquisition
the first addition to the grocery cart.
</P>
<P>
   The price of companies like Realty One or Douglas Elliman is
usually described by dividing the price by the annual income of the
acquired company to produce what is known as a multiple. ``We paid
a lower multiple for Douglas Elliman than for Realty One,'' Farkas
said, ``so pursuing consolidation in major markets makes sense
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Farkas, who worked on Wall Street early in his career, described
Insignia as the equivalent of an opportunity fund, seeking
undervalued investments and selling operations at opportune times
to lock in profits.
</P>
<P>
   This, he said, explains why he got into the apartment management
business early in the 1990s and got out of it last year, with the
exception of New York area operations.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Insignia made investments in multifamily
housing at prices the most recent annual report describes as
``materially accretive to our shareholders'' _ that is, cheap.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy then, as it continues to be, was to consolidate a
fragmented industry. But by 1997 the consolidation was largely
complete, with no big residential management companies left to buy.
``We took the business as far as we could, given our capital
structure'' as a taxpaying corporation, he said. ``Then we looked
for a company with different costs of capital _ a real estate
investment trust _ to merge with.''
</P>
<P>
   The result was a deal with a company named AIMCO that
transferred all of Insignia's residential properties and 8,000
management employees to the REIT, which does not have to pay
federal taxes as long as it distributes 95 percent of its earnings
as dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Insignia shareholders received AIMCO stock equivalent to 20
percent of the company in return for Insignia's residential
properties and now receive dividends that Insignia, as a growth
company, did not pay.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Farkas describes the deal as a good one for his company, which
transferred operations accounting for about 50 percent of its
business in terms of cash flow for a price _ $910 million _ that
was equal to 95 percent of the company's total capitalization.
AIMCO shareholders have benefited as well, since the price of the
company's shares has risen from the mid-$30s to about $43 a share.
</P>
<P>
   That left the restructured Insignia with three operating units,
commercial real estate services, residential management in the New
York area and a capital investment operation known as Insignia
Financial Services.
</P>
<P>
   The investment group now provides only about 2 percent of the
parent company's income _ compared with 72 percent from commercial
services and 26 percent from residential _ but Farkas said he
expects it to be the fastest growing.
</P>
<P>
   He said the commercial deals that Insignia/ESG handles provide
information on potentially attractive investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``They provide a pipeline of investment opportunities that we
can evaluate and deploy our capital alongside our customers in
existing properties and in development projects,'' he said. For
example, the company said it has invested $22 million of equity
capital in 22 existing properties with a total value of $700
million and has put $18 million into five development projects with
a total value of $107 million.
</P>
<P>
   He said Financial Services is also raising funds on Wall Street
for investments that will not show on the company's balance sheet
and is participating in CS First Boston's $500 million Praedium
Fund for International Real Estate.
</P>
<P>
   The unit is also marketing securities for property owners who
prefer using public markets to other forms of financing. ``We want
to be an opportunistic player, like Blackstone, Blackacre and
Apollo,'' he said, mentioning three investment groups.
</P>
<P>
   Like consolidation, growth is something of a mantra for Farkas,
whose largely intact management group has made more than 50
acquisitions since 1990. He said the key to healthy growth is to
maintain financial discipline to avoid overpaying for companies,
and devise financial terms that keep previous owners hard at work.
``We are not an exit strategy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since its inception in 1990 as a real estate investment fund
with $5 million in capital, Farkas said, Insignia has increased
market capitalization to over $1 billion. Total revenues of the
company have risen from $122 million in 1996 to $507 million in
1998, with revenues of $636 million projected for this year.
</P>
<P>
   Insignia has said that the standard measure of economic
performance, net income, is not appropriate for a real estate
company, because its merger and acquisition activity generates a
lot of charges that do not actually cost the company cash.
</P>
<P>
   Farkas and others in the industry prefer to measure financial
performance using what is called EBITDA, earnings before interest,
taxes, depreciation and amortization, which they say approximates
the actual cash generated by the business. By this measure,
Insignia's profits have grown from $15 million in 1996 to $53
million last year.
</P>
<P>
   While Insignia was expanding domestically, the company was also
expanding overseas, particularly in Britain, where it bought two
venerable brokerage companies and combined them into an entity
called Richard Ellis St. Quintin.
</P>
<P>
   (There were two companies named Richard Ellis, one based in
Britain and one in the rest of Europe. An American company then
called CB Commercial bought the continental Richard Ellis and
promptly added it to its corporate name, becoming CB Richard Ellis.
Believing the Richard Ellis brand name has considerable value in
Britain, Insignia has retained it, despite the potential for
confusion.)
</P>
<P>
   In addition to geographic expansion, Insignia plans to begin
relying heavily on technology and the Internet to improve the
efficiency of marketing and transactions. Farkas declined to
elaborate in detail on the techniques the company plans to start
using later this year, but he playfully opened an e-mail on his
desktop computer that included a movable 360-degree picture of a
building lobby. And company documents note that Realty One has an
automated system for pre-approving mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   His goal, Farkas said, is to be a customer's only real estate
company. ``We are not interested in one-time relationship with
customers,'' he said. ``We want to work with them and be there for
them whenever they think of real estate.''
</P>
