u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELGRADE-MILOSEVIC-1S     07-10 1357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELGRADE-MILOSEVIC-1STLD-WRITETHRU-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR NOW, BELGRADERS SHUN ANTI-MILOSEVIC RALLIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to add new 9th graf with updates on flooding in Belgrade.)  (See also KOSOVO-GYPSIES) 
(js) 
 By BLAINE HARDEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ During his 12 years in power, whenever
Slobodan Milosevic has been on the ropes, most of the punches have
been thrown here in the Serbian capital.
</P>
<P>
   This is where the Serbian leader called out Yugoslav army tanks
and used tear gas eight years ago to put down a violent
demonstration against state-controlled television, the key lever in
his control of public opinion. It was here that the depth of urban
middle-class revulsion with Milosevic's rule was shown to the world
in three solid months of daily street demonstrations in the winter
of 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
   But Belgrade, so far, has been a conspicuous wallflower in the
growing anti-Milosevic movement that has found expression across
Serbia in the last two weeks. This city has about a fifth of
Serbia's population and about 40 percent of its educated
middle-class, yet all the action has been in the boondocks.
</P>
<P>
   With rallies in smaller cities across Serbia, the opposition
movement has tapped frustration among restive army reservists who
are home from the lost war in Kosovo and, for most part, unpaid for
their trouble. It also has plugged into discontent among Serbs who
say they fear for their future in the collapsed postwar economy,
are weary of international isolation and are shamed by crimes
committed in their name in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   While Belgrade's city council argued itself into paralysis last
week over the question of Milosevic's resignation, city leaders in
three cities _ Serbia's second and third largest cities of Novi Sad
and Nis, and the northern city of Sombor _ quickly approved
resolutions demanding that he step down.
</P>
<P>
   The delay in Belgrade's involvement in this season's round of
anti-Milosevic demonstrations does not derive from any lack of
ambient animus toward the Yugoslav president, who has been indicted
as a war criminal and has lost four straight wars while turning
once-prosperous Serbia into the basket-case economy of Eastern
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   On the streets here on Friday night, it was difficult to find a
citizen of Belgrade, young or old, middle-class or poor, who did
not believe the time had come for Milosevic to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to see him strung up and hanging in the center of
town,'' said Ivan Tarla, 23, a film student at the University of
Belgrade. ``We are ready to go out into the street, but we need
very clear goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Disillusionment with Milosevic and the general situation in
Serbia appears likely to grow as residents who already endured 11
weeks of NATO bombing contended Saturday with unusual summer floods
that claimed at least one life in central Serbia and left suburban
streets in Belgrade awash. Angry residents who spoke to reporters
seemed to view the floods either as a punishment from God, or a
further sign of Milosevic's neglect of his people.
</P>
<P>
   The fractured opposition movement in Serbia is not planning
demonstrations in Belgrade until late August precisely because it
does not yet have a unified set of goals. Milosevic, meanwhile, is
attending to his main instrument of control _ the same
state-controlled television that Belgraders demonstrated against en
masse in 1991. He will rebuild the bombed television headquarters
in the capital, officials say, before the bridges that NATO smashed
all over Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the largest single opposition party _ the only one that
can guarantee the daily presence of tens of thousands of
demonstrators on the streets of the capital for weeks on end _ has
not yet joined the Alliance for Change, the coalition of smaller
opposition parties that is organizing rallies against Milosevic
outside Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian Renewal Movement, led by Vuk Draskovic, the
self-proclaimed ``king of the streets'' and an on-again, off-again
critic of the Milosevic regime, is sitting on its hands for the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic, who briefly served as a deputy minister in
Milosevic's government before being fired in the middle of the
Kosovo war, has said the time is not yet ripe for demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Polls indicate that in the aftermath of the Kosovo war,
Draskovic's party gained strength and won the support of about 15
percent of Serbia's population, far more than any other opposition
group. His party leads a coalition that runs city hall in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Probably more important, he controls a Belgrade television
station, Studio B, a widely watched alternative to state television
in the capital. Leaders of smaller opposition parties say they must
gain better access to Studio B to whip up mass enthusiasm for
demonstrations in Belgrade.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Draskovic's personal political ambitions seem to be keeping his
party out of the streets. He holds a grudge against Zoran Djindjic,
the key leader of the Alliance for Change. The bad blood grows out
of Djindjic's boycott of an election two years ago, when Draskovic
ran for president of Serbia. Badly needing those opposition votes,
he finished a poor third.
</P>
<P>
   His advisers say Draskovic has decided that the only way to
force Milosevic from power is for a strong individual politician to
rise above a decade of confused infighting among multiple small and
ineffectual opposition parties and give Serbs one clear
alternative. That alternative, in their view, is none other than
Draskovic.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Alliance for Change, while resentful of what they
say is Draskovic's self-involved brand of politics, do not dismiss
his importance _ especially in street demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need Mr. Draskovic's support,'' said Slobodan Vuksanovic, a
senior strategist in the Alliance for Change. ``We need him because
of the number of people he can deliver and because of Studio B.
Belgrade is the heart of Serbia in a political sense. Everything
depends on the success of the demonstrations there.''
</P>
<P>
   Vuksanovic said that in Belgrade, unlike most of the rest of
Serbia, the organizational structure of the ruling and opposition
parties is strong and relatively well disciplined. To pull off a
series of major demonstrations that is big enough not to be
disrupted by Milosevic's police or by supporters of the
ultra-nationalist Serbian Radical Party, he said, the Alliance for
Change has no choice but to try to ally itself with Draskovic.
</P>
<P>
   Successful rallies in the boondocks, then, are a way of
convincing Draskovic and members of his Serbian Renewal Movement
that if they stand on the sidelines for too long they may be left
out altogether in divvying up power in a post-Milosevic Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   There were signals last week that the strategy is beginning to
work, as a surprisingly passionate anti-Milosevic movement bubbled
up in the least likely of Serbian towns. In the southern city of
Leskovac, long dominated by Milosevic's supporters, more than
20,000 people filled the streets on Monday. The protest was
followed by smaller demonstrations, one of them violent, throughout
the week.
</P>
<P>
   Startled and anxious to cash in on popular sentiment, the
Serbian Renewal Movement decided on Wednesday to help locals in
Leskovac organize their demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public-address speakers are ours, but the microphone is
theirs,'' said Bojana Ristic, head of the Serbian Renewal Movement
in Leskovac.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of Draskovic's party conceded in Belgrade last week that
they had underestimated grass-roots anger at the Milosevic regime.
As for future rallies, they seemed to be opening a door that
Draskovic, just two weeks ago, slammed shut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vuk knows when the time comes,'' said Ognjen Pribicevic, a
senior political adviser to Draskovic.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, it seems many people are ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be the first in the streets because I have had
enough,'' said Mira Angelic, 50, a lawyer. ``Right now, there is no
spark to start the fire. But I think it is a question of days and
weeks. The spark eventually has to come from Belgrade.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
