the Kosovo neighbors they turned against, the Gypsies of Kosovo are
living in a precarious state. Black-haired and dark-skinned, the
Gypsies, or Roma as they are also known, live in settlements all
over Serbia and Kosovo. As elsewhere in Europe, they are the most
discriminated against of all ethnic minorities. (Alan Chin/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- July 10, 1999 -- TEACHER-BOOM, 7-10 -- David
Robinson, 23, who is finishing his master's degree at Columbia
University's Teachers College, has been hired to teach English this
fall to 9th- and 10th-graders at the Bronx Leadership Academy.
After years of shying away from the field, a growing number of
college students, including those from elite liberal arts colleges,
now say they want to be schoolteachers. ``I just got a feeling for
the corporate life and realized it wasn't for me,'' says Robinson.
(Philip Greenberg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- July 10, 1999 -- FAA-AIRTOUR-SAFETY, 7-10 --
The Federal Aviation Administration wants to regulate tours flown
by planes like this one, a 1927 biplane making a flight over the
California coast. As long as they do not fly more than 25 miles
from where they take off and land, tour operators are exempt from
many rules. A report by the inspector general of the Transportation
Department concluded in May that the new rule ``has been delayed
too long and should be moved forward quickly.'' (Dave Gatley/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) PROVIDENCE, R.I. -- July 10, 1999 -- CITIZEN-KHRUSHCHEV,
7-10 --Sergei Khrushchev, 64, with a portrait of his father,
Nikita, the late Soviet premier and Communist Party leader. Now a
scholar of the Cold War whose lectures at Brown University are
driven by eyewitness memories, Khrushchev awaits U.S. citizenship,
happily prepared to pledge allegiance to the United States as its
newest patriot. In his father's heyday Sergei Khrushchev had been a
rocket and computer scientist and a firm believer in communism.
(Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) PHILADELPHIA -- July 10, 1999 -- ELDERLY-DRUGS, 7-10 --
Esther and David Welsh at home in south Philadelphia with all of
her medications. As people live longer and acquire more chronic
ailments, the pharmaceutical industry has supplied an endless
stream of remedies, and paying for prescriptions and keeping all
the pills straight is a daily concern. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
