<HEADER>
A5540 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-PEACE-BOS &LR;      07-10 1268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-PEACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARAFAT HAS HIGH HOPES FOR MEETING WITH BARAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat expressed hope
Saturday that his meeting Sunday with Israel's new prime minister,
Ehud Bark, would mark a ``new chapter'' in a peace process mired in
mistrust for most of the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat's comments, coming a day after Barak launched an
ambitious diplomatic mission to restart the Mideast peace process,
demonstrated how dramatically _ and rapidly _ expectations for
progress have been raised by the former Israeli general's move into
office last week.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel and Washington, in particular, anticipation of a
future with peace has replaced the skepticism and bitterness
surrounding the tenure of Barak's predecessor, Benjamin Netanyahu.
The mood has remained more cautious among Palestinians, who say
they want to see what deeds follow the Israeli leader's
more-encouraging comments.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the tone on both sides underlines an unmistakable change
in atmosphere that has occurred as a result of Barak's overwhelming
victory over Netanyahu, whose hardline policies deadlocked the
process.
</P>
<P>
   In Egypt Friday on the first leg of his diplomatic tour, Barak
promised to ``turn every stone'' in his quest for peace. And upon
his return home later that day, he said a de-facto Palestinian
state already exists.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, for his part, directly alluded to the chill that marked
Israeli-Palestinian relations during Netanyahu's tenure. In a
statement released by his office, the president of the Palestinian
authority said he would be attending Sunday's meeting with Barak
``ready to begin a new chapter and to wipe out the past three years
of mistrust.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as they spoke of new possibilities, however, Palestinian
officials said that they expect quick action from the Isaeli
leader. They also served notice that their patience won't last long
if he delivers only promising words.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time is a very precious commodity,'' said Saeb Erekat, the
chief Palestinian negotiator, who also made it clear that he didn't
like some of Barak's initial thoughts about how Israel should
pursue negotiations with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   In his first interview with Israeli television since taking
office, Barak on Friday proposed postponing implementation of the
Wye River interim peace accord, which calls for Israel's withdrawal
from more of the West Bank. Instead, Barak suggested that Wye's
terms be folded into a broader, final settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Erekat angrily rejected that idea, asserting that the
Palestinians should not have to wait for their land _ especially
since Israeli had already agreed to cede it.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can anyone who intends to build trust and restore
confidence and who intends to revive the peace process come and
suggest changes such as mixing between Wye and final status
negotiations?'' Erekat said at his office in Jericho on Friday.
``We won't be taken for a ride. ``We don't have neon signs on top
of our heads reading `stupid.'''
</P>
<P>
   It was uncertain Saturday to what extent each side was posturing
or playing to its own domestic constituencies. That may become more
clear when details of Arafat's meeting with Barak _ and what
proposals they make to each other, rather than float in the media _
become known.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, while they seem anxious for initiatives from Israel,
Arab leaders' hopes and spirits appear to have been raised
considerably by Barak's replacement of Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give the man some time,'' Mubarak said at a conference when
the prime minister was peppered with questions about his timetable
for implementing peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Barak embarked on his diplomatic blitz Friday after only three
days in office. During the coming week or so, Barak will meet with
President Clinton in Washington and with a series of Arab leaders
on their own turf, trying to restore confidence in a peace process
mired in mistrust during the administration of his right-wing
predecessor,
</P>
<P>
   Barak's outreach campaign began at a meeting with Mubarak at his
summer residence in Alexandria. On Wednesday, he will meet with
Jordan's King Abdullah in the port city of Aqaba. Then he will
continue on to Washington to see Clinton, who has made negotiating
an Israeli-Palestinian peace a priority of his foreign policy _ and
whose intense diplomacy helped to engineer the Wye agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The signing of the pact was capped by a historic visit by
Clinton to Gaza, but its implementation has been on hold for more
than seven months since Netanyahu was forced to call for early
elections. Barak took two of those months to form his cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   The implementation of the so-called ``interim'' peace agreement
is now well over a year behind schedule. Its terms include the
withdrawal of Israeli troops from roughly 13 percent more territory
on the West Bank, the release of political prisoners held in
Israeli jails, the start of construction of a commercial port in
Gaza, and the implementation of ``safe passage'' roads to connect
Gaza to the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this could be implemented within two weeks,'' said
Erekat. ``There is no reason why it couldn't be.''
</P>
<P>
   The issues spelled out in Wye are crucial to a collapsing
Palestinian economy and are critical to restoring confidence in a
public that teeters on despair about the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-four percent of Palestinians say they are worse off
economically now than before the historic 1993 peace accord, while
only 11 percent say they are better off.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the encouraging words from Barak about peace, the
Palestinian public as a whole remains deeply distrustful of his
intentions and tell pollsters that they have no more faith in him
than they did in Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Although 70 percent of Palestinians still support the peace
process, but almost the same number ``do not trust the peadceful
intentions of a government led by Barak,'' according to a June 21
poll by the Center for Palestine Research and Studies.
</P>
<P>
   Eventhough Barak has fashioned a political career out of
following in the footsteps of the slain Prime Minister Yitzhak
Rabin, Palestinian observers seem keenly aware that it was Barak
more than any other cabinet minister who objected to the troop
withdrawals from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   And Barak has shown signs that he will a tough negotiator on the
so-called ``final status'' issues that are to take place after the
Wye accord's implementation. They are to focus on Israeli and
Palestinian claims to control of Jerusalem, the return of
Palestinian refugees, and the presence of Israeli settlements on
land captured in the 1967 Six Day War.
</P>
<P>
   Barak already has insisted that the status of Jerusalem is
non-negotiable and that all of ``greater Jerusalem'' will remain
the indivisible and eternal capital of Israel. He has also
indicated that, while he he will not move to reverse the settlement
expansion that took place under Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   However separate the two sides' starting points, some analysts
believe the opportunity for a breakthrough now exists if everyone
concerned shows a real willingness to bend.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is important is to regain the confidence and then the
momentum, so that Israelis and Palestinians share a vision of the
outcome,'' said Ron Pundak, executive director of the Economic
Cooperation Foundation in Israel and a principle negotiator in the
peace process. The realization they all must have, he added, is
that ``hey, we are all in the same boat and will have to make our
way in to the future together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
