CUP-SOCCER: World Cup scene-setter from PASADENA, Calif. By
MECHELLE VOEPEL. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
WAR-SITE: PLEASANTON, Kan. _ What happened just south of here 135
years ago this Oct. 25 was quick _ 10,000 troops clashed; Union
cavalry rolled up the Confederate line; two southern generals were
captured along with hundreds of their men, and gunfire echoed over
the quieting battlefield as the Yankee victors executed vanquished
rebels found wearing scrounged blue uniforms. &QL; 
Thus here in Linn County the final nail was pounded into Gen.
Sterling Price's grand strategy to rive Missouri and its western
borders. His army, which threatened St. Louis, besieged Jefferson
City, and then been driven out of Kansas City, was transformed into
a defeated rabble on the Kansas prairie. &QL; 
For Price and his troops the Civil War ended with the Battle of
Mine Creek, itself an oddity in that most of the fighting took
place in 30 explosive minutes. Now, with its sesquicentennial just
15 years away, little Mine Creek and its historic environs look
north and see the approach of a slower yet far more inexorable
host. By JIM FISHER. Story will move in the ``a''
category.SCHOOL-PROGRAM: KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ David Fair wasn't a
straight-A student, captain of the football team or a kid involved
in oodles of school activities. But he was just what Nu-Tech
Industries wanted: a hard worker with some interest in engineering
and plenty of time. So last summer the company drafted him as the
first initiate in the Grandview High School Employment Scholarship
Program. The innovative program helps companies by supplying
workers in a tight job market. It benefits students by teaching
them a trade and pumping money into a college fund. By ERICA WOOD.
Story will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   EYE-SURGERY: KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Craig Schurig is lying down,
arms resting comfortably at his sides. As a suction ring hugs one
of his near-sighted eyes, a small flap of tissue from the outer
layer of his cornea is lifted by a surgeon wielding a tiny,
high-tech tool. Next, for about 25 seconds, surgeon Daniel S.
Durrie trains a laser on Schurig's cornea, flattening the curve a
bit. Then Durrie deftly brings the corneal flap back down, and it
adheres like Velcro. ``I feel good now,'' the red-eyed Schurig said
after the procedure, which took about three minutes. ``The only
thing you feel is the drops going in, the numbing drops.'' Schurig
has just undergone LASIK surgery at the Hunkeler Eye Centers in
Overland Park, Kan. The 34-year-old assistant football coach at
Pittsburg State University is one of an estimated 807,500 Americans
this year who will undergo the procedure _ first performed a decade
ago _ up from 360,000 last year. By JULIUS A. KARASH. Story will
move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
