<HEADLINE>
COMMITTEE EXPECTED TO SEEK AUTHORIZATION TO CHOOSE SUPERINTENDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Desegregation Monitoring Committee
probably will recommend that it appoint a Kansas City School
District superintendent if the Board of Education cannot reach
agreement with a candidate by a court-imposed deadline of July 19.
</P>
<P>
   Committee members presented their plan at a closed meeting with
U.S. District Judge Dean Whipple last week. School board members
learned of the plan in a memo they received late Friday from the
school district's legal counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The DMC will likely recommend that the DMC be authorized to
employ as its employee a full-time administrator (probably a
retired superintendent), to administer the district on a day-to-day
basis until such time as a permanent superintendent is selected by
the board,'' district lawyers wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Whipple has scheduled a hearing for 10 a.m. July 19. If a
superintendent has not been named by then, Whipple will accept
recommendations as to what actions he should take.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Lance Loewenstein said the desegregation
committee's proposal appeared to stop just short of receivership,
in which the court would eliminate the school board and assume
day-to-day control of the district.
</P>
<P>
   Loewenstein said he interpreted the committee's plan not as a
threat but as a gentle reminder that the school board needed to act
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they want to do this,'' Loewenstein said. ``I
think they vastly prefer us to hire a superintendent. They want to
go home. That's obvious to me. They want out of this quagmire in a
very bad way.''
</P>
<P>
   The memo also says the committee is opposed to allowing Phyllis
Chase, the interim chief administrator for curriculum and
instruction, to remain in the position during the coming school
year.
</P>
<P>
   Some board members have advocated letting Chase continue to run
the instructional side of the district while the search continues
for a permanent superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   Board President John Rios said Saturday that he had yet to
review the memo, but he expressed concern about its contents. He is
among those board members who have expressed support for leaving
Chase in the post.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can tell you is that it's unfortunate they have that
attitude,'' Rios said of the committee. ``I think she's done a good
job in the interim.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
