<SLUG> BC-BBN-NL-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETTER TIMES FOR OFFERMAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When Jose Offerman was named to his only other
All-Star Game four years ago, he remembers how he was mercilessly
booed by the home crowd at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's back in the game with his new team, the Boston Red
Sox, and will be playing Tuesday night at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember they were announcing each of the guys and (the
fans) were giving a lot of applause,'' Offerman said. ``When it was
my turn, they booed me. I can't say it didn't bother me.''
</P>
<P>
   After batting .346 with 25 extra-base hits through his first 38
games of the season, Offerman lately has looked like anything but
one of the game's elite. In his next 43 games, he hit .225 with
just seven extra-base hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a surprise, but it's a nice feeling to be on the
All-Star team,'' said Offerman, who will receive a $100,000 bonus
for his selection to the team. ``It's one of those things _ what
have you done for me lately? _ and that's why I'm surprised.'' &QL; 
Deserving
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore 3B Cal Ripken probably would have been voted into the
All-Star starting lineup regardless of his statistics, but he has
to be pleased that he doesn't have to apologize for his presence on
the AL team. ``With the All-Star Game, you want to feel the most
deserving,'' Ripken said of his 15th election, which tied Rod Carew
for the all-time record. ``This year I feel pretty good about how
I'm playing and I'm looking forward to going.'' Ripken bounced back
from a injury-plagued start to put up some decent numbers going
into the break. He hit his 12th homer of the year Wednesday night
and needs just four more to reach 400 for his career. He is
expected to reach 3,000 hits by late August. &QL; 
Cycling
</P>
<P>
   Chris Singleton, a one-time Giants prospect acquired in a
minor-league trade with the Yankees, became only the fourth player
in the history of the White Sox to hit for the cycle. He did it
Tuesday in a game the Sox would lose to K.C. 8-7 in 10 innings. The
last rookie to hit for the cycle was Oddibe McDowell, for Texas, in
1985. Singleton has been a tremendous find. He won the final roster
spot in spring training and took over for fellow rookie McKay
Christensen as the regular center fielder in mid-May. The Sox got
him in a trade for left-hander Rich Pratt, a non-prospect. &QL; 
Candy man
</P>
<P>
   Former Dodger Tom Candiotti made his first start as an Indian on
Saturday vs. Cincinnati since being signed June 29 after clearing
waivers with Oakland. It came down to Candiotti and Mark Langston
for Dwight Gooden's spot in the rotation. Last Saturday, in a
day-night doubleheader vs. the Royals, Candiotti won the first game
with 52/3 innings of scoreless relief. Langston started the second
game and won as well. Candiotti made 11 starts with the A's. Gooden
has made 393 appearances in the regular season. All but four of
them have been as a starter. Gooden made his fourth relief
appearance Wednesday night in the Metrodome after Bartolo Colon was
ejected for hitting Corey Koskie with a pitch. He retired all four
men he faced. &QL; 
Straight A's
</P>
<P>
   John Jaha might be the A's only all-star, but they are staying
competitive in the West with pitching. Right-hander Jimmy Haynes
started the season 1-5, but he's 5-1 since then, and in his last
four starts, he's been almost unhittable. He's allowed 17 hits in
28.1 innings, going at least seven innings each time while
compiling a 2-0 record with a 2.54 ERA. Before that, the ERA was
5.18. Right-hander Tim Hudson, who faced Randy Johnson on Saturday,
got back at the only team to beat him this year when he stopped
Texas 4-2 Monday. Including time in the minors, Hudson is 11-1 this
season. He's 4-1 since joining the A's last month. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
