<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Castilla acquisition just rumor
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The silly season has begun. General manager John
Schuerholz actually laughed aloud when presented with the rumor
circulating through the Braves' clubhouse this weekend: The club is
acquiring Colorado third baseman Vinny Castilla and moving Chipper
Jones to shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only conversation I've had with (Rockies general manager)
Bob Gebhart in the last month was about Jeff Reed,'' Schuerholz
said. And he didn't get him either.
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz has made his customary midseason calls around the
league, gauging what might be available as the July 31 trading
deadline approaches. But his concern is Javy Lopez. If his catcher
can overcome his knee injury to perform effectively after the
All-Star break, the club will be more passive in the trade market.
</P>
<P>
   If Lopez falters, Schuerholz will pursue a major acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   ``If his injury, for one reason or another, starts to head in
the other direction or doesn't get better or doesn't heal, you have
to get somebody,'' Schuerholz said.
</P>
<P>
   So sorry
</P>
<P>
   Brian Jordan was disappointed that his 12-game hitting streak
ended, one game shy of tying a career-best. But what was worse, he
hit first-base coach Glenn Hubbard with his batting helmet in the
eighth inning, when he attempted to throw it back toward the
dugout.
</P>
<P>
   He explained the helmet got stuck on a finger as he let it go,
sending it in Hubbard's direction. The incident drew an audible
response from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel so terrible,'' Jordan said. ``I apologized about 10
times. I made Hubby sick from apologizing so many times.''
</P>
<P>
   Wounded knee
</P>
<P>
   Although he did not appear Saturday, reliever Russ Springer was
available for service, after being knocked out of Friday night's
game with a line drive off the right knee by Mike Stanley. The ball
just grazed Springer's kneecap and he wears a red welt, two stitch
marks clearly visible, on the right side of the knee. X-rays were
negative.
</P>
<P>
   The best?
</P>
<P>
   Opinions were mixed in the clubhouse before the game on whether
Andruw Jones' wall-banging Friday night catch off a Troy O'Leary
drive was the best of his career. Jones caught the ball on a sprint
over his left shoulder an instant before hitting the ball, bounced
off, picked up his cap in the same motion and trotted in.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get to the point where you almost expect him to make the
play, he does it so much,'' left fielder Ryan Klesko said.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus remains Jones' finest catch came May 8, 1998,
against San Diego, when he chased down a deep Steve Finley drive,
caught the ball from directly over his head and leapt into the
wall, clinging to the padding.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the time, I think I can catch the ball,'' Jones said.
``Any ball they hit out there, you think you can catch.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest vote for Friday night's effort came from left-hander
Mike Remlinger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pitching,'' he said. ``This one was better.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
