<SLUG> BC-BBN-NL-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARLINS DON'T GET THEIR MAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Florida Marlins insisted on Travis Lee for
closer Matt Mantei. They got Brad Penny. That's not necessarily a
bad thing, considering Penny is one of the top-10 pitching
prospects in baseball. But for a team trying to get a new ballpark
by fielding an awful team, the Marlins might have taken a different
approach.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's trade filled a big void for the Arizona Diamondbacks,
who already had blown 14 saves opportunities this season. But they
held their ground on trading Lee, who has been disappointing this
year after a successful rookie year.
</P>
<P>
   Florida, which has been criticized for dumping high-priced
veterans after its World Series title in 1997, isn't saving much
money by dealing Mantei. He is making $375,000 this season. But the
Marlins, who didn't get him a save opportunity until May, thought
they could better use Mantei to improve their long-range situation.
</P>
<P>
   If Florida can sign No. 1 choice Josh Beckett, the addition of
Penny to Double-A right-hander A.J. Burnett and Wes Anderson would
give the Marlins four of baseball's top-10 pitching prospects. &QL; 
You really like me
</P>
<P>
   MVP Sammy Sosa was thrilled to lead the NL in All-Star votes
(2,315,204). Among other things, it meant that he beat Mark
McGwire. ``To be one of the leaders in votes shows me the respect
and appreciation people have given me,'' Sosa said. ``Now I know
that I'm there with Ken Griffey, Jr. and Mark and all the big
names. Now I'm one of them.'' Sosa's All-Star history is
interesting. He did not make the team in '96 even though he was
leading the NL in homers at the break. He was also left off after a
strong start to the '97 season. Last year he was named to the team
but did not play after suffering a minor injury in the final game
before the break. &QL; 
Comeback Kid
</P>
<P>
   After making 162 consecutive relief appearances in the majors
since 1995, Cincinnati left-hander Ron Villone has made six starts
and excelled in the last three, firing 212/3 consecutive scoreless
innings before Houston's Matt Mieske hit a two-run homer. The Reds
signed Villone _ who also played for Seattle, San Diego and
Milwaukee _ to a minor-league contract on April 5 after the Indians
released him in spring training. Now, a pair of Indians shorts hang
in Villone's locker at Cinergy Field, serving as a reminder of how
far he fell. ``They'll be here all year,'' said Villone, who faced
the Indians on Saturday. ``Decoration, motivation, whatever you
want to call it. You've got to remember where you came from.'' &QL; 
Comeback II
</P>
<P>
   San Diego's Andy Ashby threw a shutout at Coors Field on Sunday,
serving another reminder of the worst deal in Rockies history:
Ashby, Brad Ausmus and Doug Bochtler to the Padres for Bruce Hurst
and Greg Harris on July 27, 1993. In case you've forgotten, Hurst
was injured and Harris went 4-20 in one-plus seasons; Ashby is
55-38 with a 3.38 ERA in the last four-plus seasons. To be fair, he
was awful in Colorado, going 0-4 with an 8.50 ERA. ``I have no bad
feelings toward the Rockies,'' Ashby said. ``But I thank God every
day that they traded me.'' &QL; 
How about these Mets
</P>
<P>
   The New York Mets beat the New York Yankees 9-8 Saturday on a
pinch RBI single by Westlake High's Matt Franco. The night before,
the Mets won 5-2 on a three-run homer by Mike Piazza off Roger
Clemens. Today, they end the first half with Orel Hershiser going
for his 200th career victory. Hershiser came back Tuesday on one
day's rest and pitched five scoreless innings to set up today's
game. And though he came in batting just .220 with runners in
scoring position, Piazza is now 5 for 9 lifetime against Clemens.
Piazza also beat Clemens last month with a home run. ``A lot of
people think too much is being made of this series with the
Yankees,'' Mets manager Bobby Valentine said. ``I don't see it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
