<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-REDS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Headstrong Hunter spurs Braves in 11th, ties series
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It became a matter of Brian Hunter's head, both inside
it and out.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter's decision to try a two-strike sacrifice bunt started it
and John Wasdin's ensuing throw that glanced off Hunter's helmet
finished it, allowing Andruw Jones to score all the way from first
base Saturday. The Braves outlasted Boston 2-1 in 11 innings in a
game befitting the best pitching staffs in their respective
leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Way to have a big head, man,'' Brian Jordan said afterward to
Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves close the season's first half this afternoon with the
chance to take a second series from Boston, Greg Maddux facing Red
Sox rookie Jin Ho Cho. Maddux has a hard act to follow, after Tom
Glavine allowed a Jim Stanley home run and nothing else over nine
innings. While the Braves had runners in every inning, advancing
just three into scoring position and leaving them all there,
Glavine, working on three days' rest, pitched a solid six-hitter
which brought him no victory but solace as the season comes to the
All-Star halt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably at a point where I don't want it to stop,'' said
Glavine (7-8), who has lost just once in his past seven starts. ``I
might have in April but right now, I'm happy with the way I'm
throwing the ball. I kind of look at it as two seasons. The first
two months weren't very good. The last six weeks have been really
good.''
</P>
<P>
   The 11th teemed with unlikelihoods. Free-swinging Andruw Jones
walked to open the inning. Hunter fell behind 1-2 but after the
bunt sign was taken off, he stuck with it and put a breaking ball
into play to the first-base side of the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not disobeying orders,'' Hunter said. ``It's (helping) us
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Wasdin's throw glanced off the right side of Hunter's helmet and
rolled off the tarp down the line. Darren Lewis's throw to the
plate was up the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the time when you put a bunt down, I try to take a chance
that, if they slip up, I can go to third,'' said Jones, who
provided the Braves' first run in the fourth with his 16th home
run. ``I was running hard and when I saw the ball get away, I just
kept going.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves are 3-2 vs. Boston in a series of terrific games that
are appealing at least to one player. Glavine said, ``If we see
them again in the World Series, it's fine by me.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
