<DOCNO> NYT19990710.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5568 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-HOMERUNS11-COX     07-10 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HOMERUNS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Another assault on fences
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Since it would never happen again, at least in this
lifetime, 1998's Season for the Ages, the Sosa-McGwire Swat Fest,
was pressed like a dried flower in the back of the public
conscience and put up on a shelf, which was apparently a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Because the flower never died and may well live for time
immemorial, given the hairy-chested state of the contempory game.
As the baseball season's first half concludes tonight, no one is on
pace to break Mark McGwire's 70-homer record, nor even reach Sammy
Sosa's sublime 66. But Sosa (32) is on pace to reach 60 and Tampa
Bay's Jose Canseco (31) is on pace for 59.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson of 1998 was, the impossible is only a swing or two
away. The Season for the Ages may actually not have ended, only
taken the winter off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could happen again,'' said Braves right fielder Brian
Jordan, an eyewitness to every McGwire home run in St. Louis a year
ago. ``With the pace Sammy is on, and you got Canseco over 30 at
the break? Both of those guys? We could be seeing another race in
the making.''
</P>
<P>
   And don't disregard McGwire, who entered the weekend tied with
Houston's Jeff Bagwell with 27 homers. McGwire is 10 off last
year's total at the All-Star break but has hardly broken a sweat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers I have now are not too bad and I haven't even got
hot yet,'' McGwire said recently. ``I would think I'd probably get
hot sometime in the next (three) months.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year's figures from the break are distorted, as the
All-Star Game falls a week later this year than last. But seven
players entered the weekend with 25 homers or more, compared to
nine last year. Sosa's 32 is just one behind his midway total of 33
last year. Seattle's Ken Griffey (28) and Colorado's Larry Walker
(25) cannot be discounted, though the Mariners' new home at Safeco
Park does not appear to be as home run friendly as the abandoned
Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   But the critical ingredients for another home run rush all
remain: diluted pitching talent, smaller parks, stronger hitters
and, perhaps most important, the knowlege that 60- or 70-homer
seasons are no longer mythic but attainable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at how long it took to even get guys to start thinking
about breaking (Roger) Maris' record,'' Braves hitting coach Don
Baylor said. ``I remember when I was just a young player and Reggie
Jackson got off with 42 one year. Everybody started talking about
Roger Maris.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reggie broke out in hives and ended up in the hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   With the mid-'90s and the coming of age of the current slugger
crop, that all changed. Since 1920, there have been 26 50-homer
seasons in major-league history. Eight of those, nearly 30 percent,
have come in the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   If the 1999 field needs a wild card, Canseco is proud to serve.
Having wandered through four American League organizations during
the decade, he reached 30 homers only once in the previous five
years before attaining a career-high 46 with Toronto last summer.
Now 35 years old, he sounds almost stoic about the seasons he
wasted and the present opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've come full circle,'' Canseco said. ``As a baseball player,
no one has experienced as much as I've experienced. I was talked
about being the best player in the world, hands down, by far, at
one point, being this freak that nobody understood. I stood 6-4,
250 pounds and was running 4.3, 4.4 40s. The first guy to do 40-40
(home runs and steals).
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I was, more or less, an outcast in baseball, being
completely forgotten. The worst player. A total joke. Washed up.''
</P>
<P>
   He's never hit 50 before, much less 60. But he has hung on long
enough to join the game's most pyrotechnic era. Maybe he won't get
there. Maybe no one will. But where for decades after Maris there
was a lull, now there is a new optimism.
</P>
<P>
   And for those fathers working on their son's delivery in the
back yard, Jordan has this advice: ``Put the glove down and pick up
the bat, buddy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
