<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BROPEN-NOTES11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. withdrawals not a surprise
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ To read the British tabloids, you would
presume the Americans have become total wimps. Unusual as it is
that several U.S. players have become late withdrawals for this
week's 128th British Open, their losses are being characterized
mostly as reponses to the difficulty of the Carnoustie Golf Links.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carnoustie Blows Americans Away,'' screams one Scottish paper.
``Yanks But No Thanks,'' announces another.
</P>
<P>
   Carnoustie's toughness _ even Scotland's Sandy Lyle pronounced
it as ``evil'' during a recent practice round amidst knee-high
rough _ more likely has been a tiebreaker for players either
injured or not in proper form for a major. In the case of Fred
Couples, who withdrew Friday, it's a combination of poor play and a
10-hour trip from Los Angeles that can not help his weak back.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries have scratched Scott Hoch, who has a foot problem that
requires an MRI; Brad Faxon (broken wrist) and Steve Jones
(shoulder). Poor play has caused no-shows from Ben Crenshaw, Tom
Kite and John Daly. Loren Roberts qualified late and chose not to
cancel plans for a family vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to comment on the Americans' exit Saturday after his win
at Loch Lomond, Colin Montgomerie said, jokingly, ``What, have
Woods and Duval pulled out?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any of the scratching is entirely unexpected,''
said Duncan Weir, the assistant championship secretary of the Royal
&AMP; Ancient Golf Club. ``Ben Crenshaw has not made a cut all year.
Steve Jones' absence is injury-related and Fred Couples' withdrawal
is no great surprise. We had heard it might happen a few weeks
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoch's withdrawal may be seen as a dodge _ he hates the cold and
rain _ but he might require foot surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Els sees a rough Open
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Els bypassed Loch Lomond for extra time to prepare at
Carnoustie, feeling he needs experience there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen rough like it,'' Els said after his first
practice round. ``It's quite unbelievable and I'll be quite happy
when the crowds come in and trample it down. . . . If I could get a
good bet, I'd bet that 4-over par will win.''
</P>
<P>
   Faldo's improved putting
</P>
<P>
   Nick Faldo is starting to see some progress, boosted by a switch
during the U.S. Open to a cross-handed putting grip. He shot a
third-round 68 at Loch Lomond that required 26 putts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've probably improved six shots a round because of it,''
Faldo said.
</P>
<P>
   Carnoustie: The full Monty
</P>
<P>
   With a stretch of nine birdies in 12 holes, Montgomerie became
the first Scot to win in Scotland in 15 years Saturday, shooting a
final-round 64 to take the Loch Lomond Invitational.
</P>
<P>
   The victory surely will make Montgomerie a prime favorite for
Carnoustie, where he shares the course record at 64.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could I possibly feel any better than I do now about
golf?'' Montgomerie said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the fact no player has won Loch Lomond and the Open in
successive weeks, he said, ``That's one gone and one to go, I
suppose,'' then added, ``At the same time I'm not thinking about
Carnoustie at all. Of all my (20) wins, this is the most special.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
