<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-REPUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK SENATE RACE GETS ATTENTION  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Republican leaders, troubled by the party's
failure to unite behind a candidate to take on Hillary Rodham
Clinton in the New York Senate race next year, said Saturday that
they had privately debated whether their national chairman should
intervene to discourage a primary battle.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, several party officials said, the conversation
turned to whether national party leaders should try to force Rep.
Rick Lazio of Long Island out of the race to clear the path to the
nomination for Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   But after what were described as passionate discussions at a
closed-door meeting at the party's summer convention here on
Friday, participants agreed that, for now at least, it would be
most prudent to let the state party try to sort out its own
squabbles among rival factions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concern was that we could implode in New York over
personality problems,'' said Ronald Kaufman, the Republican
national committeeman from Massachusetts. ``In the beginning, it
was about getting Lazio out. In the end, it was more a consensus, a
realization that it's best left to the powers that be in New York
to work out the problem over time.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Nicholson, the party's national chairman, said in an
interview Saturday, ``I'm not actually engaged in trying to broker
anything.'' But he acknowledged that he had been asked whether he
should move more aggressively to unite the New York party.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson said: ``I said I knew Congressman Lazio. He's a very
able congressman and incredible candidate if he runs.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Nicholson said, the party leaders realized ``there
was very likely to be a primary _ and we don't get involved in
primaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio was traveling Saturday and could not be reached. His
spokeswoman declined to comment on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   That Republican leaders from around the nation even discussed
the New York Senate race underscores the degree to which the party
views Mrs. Clinton as a formidable rival in the contest to succeed
Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, a Democrat who plans to retire next
year. It also demonstrates the nervousness among party leaders that
the difficult relations among Republicans in New York could bruise
the nominee.
</P>
<P>
   The competition between Giuliani and Lazio has rekindled
festering tensions among the state's Republicans. Gov. George
Pataki and former Sen. Alfonse D'Amato never forgave Giuliani for
supporting former Gov. Mario Cuomo in his race against Pataki. They
are said to prefer Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Describing the reaction when the conversation turned to the New
York Senate race, John Ryder, a national committeeman from
Tennessee, said, ``There was an immediate emotional reaction _
there's a strong sense that we have to have a united front against
Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And then after serious discussion, people came to a Federalist
conclusion: It's not appropriate for the national party to tell the
states what they ought to do,'' Ryder said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael McDaniel, state chairman of the Indiana Republican
Party, said he feared that a high-profile effort by the party to
intervene in New York could backfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to do everything you can to maximize your opportunity
for victory,'' McDaniel said. ``But it's another thing to have a
big party pronouncement to try to force your will on people. After
a discussion of the frustration of fighting among ourselves, the
prevailing attitude was: Let's not try to strong arm anybody
because that's the state's business. That might force them to arch
their backs and stiffen their resolve even more.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in their public sessions, Mrs. Clinton's expected candidacy
was clearly on the minds of Republican officials at their
gathering, which ended Saturday. Republican Party officials said
they were pulling in large sums of money with mailings that invoke
the prospect of a Sen. Hillary Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech to the membership on Friday, Nicholson devoted as
much time to castigating Mrs. Clinton as he did to criticizing Vice
President Al Gore, the leading Democratic candidate for the
presidential nomination.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
