<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5578 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WOMENS-CUP11-COX     07-10 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WOMENS-CUP11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On top of the world
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Considering the last-minute wins the United
States and China have pulled out over each other recently, going to
penalty kicks in the Women's World Cup finals was far from being an
indignity.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it might have been the most fitting way to end an
exhilarating match between the best teams in the world. After
dueling for 120 scoreless minutes Saturday afternoon, Brandi
Chastain put an end to the drama in the final frame of penalty
kicks as the United States won its second world championship 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain placed a perfect shot in the right side of the net past
Chinese goalkeeper Gao Hong as the Americans won 5-4 in the
penalty-kick round.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. goalkeeper Briana Scurry, magnificent in the semifinal
victory against Brazil on July 4, set up the victory in the third
round by turning away a shot by Liu Ying, diving to her right and
getting both hands firmly on the ball. The Americans easily made
good on all five of their attempts.
</P>
<P>
   A capacity Rose Bowl crowd of 90,185, largely pro-American,
erupted with delight as glittery confetti spewed onto the field.
While U.S. players celebrated, their Chinese counterparts stood
stoically.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in three tournaments, a home team has won a
Women's World Cup. The Americans, who beat China in the 1996
Olympic final at Sanford Stadium, won the first World Cup,
contested in China in 1991. Norway won the 1995 Cup in Sweden after
defeating the Americans in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this spring, the United States and China split two
friendlies on the East Coast, with each team winning in the final
minutes. This one needed all 90 minutes of regulation, plus 30 more
in overtime, before going to penalty kicks.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be fair to say that both teams were playing on their
heels, because they kept attacking ferociously all afternoon. But
the defensive skill and tenacity that marked their play during the
World Cup was superb, and itcarried over into the high anxiety of
the extra session.
</P>
<P>
   The dominating play of Michelle Akers carried the Americans, who
got some chances early, but after a while couldn't penetrate
China's rugged wall of defense. Akers, playing in probably her
final World Cup match, was simply dazzling, throwing her body
around the field and holding the midfield to bolster what has been
times a shaky American back line.
</P>
<P>
   Playing with a bruised nose and a banged-up shoulder, she was
her typical kamizake self, heading away Chinese long balls and
setting up the American offense with her strong leg. But in the
final seconds of the second half, she took a shot to her nose that
put her out of the contest going into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   With her out, the Chinese had the entire middle of the field to
roam, and they took quick advantage. Nine minutes in, scoring star
Sun Wen rambled nearly 30 yards before uncorking a shot deflected
by the United States to set up a corner kick. Fan Yunje got off a
perfect header, but the shot was blocked by Kristine Lilly, who was
protecting the left post.
</P>
<P>
   In the second overtime period, each team had golden chances to
win it. Zhang Ouying dribbled into the box, right in front of
Scurry, but Kate Sobrero made a sliding tackle. On the other end,
Tisha Venturini, an overtime substitution, jumped on a loose ball
in the Chinese box but it was knocked away before she could
maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon MacMillan came on for Cindy Parlow early in the second
half, but that's when China began finding a seam on the right side
of the U.S. defense. Joy Fawcett was beaten by Liu Ying on a touch
pass in the 58th minute and kicked the ball away for a corner kick.
Liu's low shot skimmed off the head of Sun and out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   In the final minute of regulation, Zhang took an excellent pass
from Sun down the middle, beating Sobrero and Carla Overbeck as she
entered the box. But Chastain made a sliding tackle to avert a shot
on goal. With time running out, China had another corner kick, but
the Americans headed away the ball harmlessly to force overtime.
</P>
<P>
   For the first 30 minutes, the Americans had the better of the
play, controlling possession and presenting a strong defense. In
the eighth minute, they were awarded a free kick 35 yards from the
Chinese goal. Mia Hamm served up a ball that a sliding Akers
touched with her leg, but couldn't direct.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the half, after China found some operating room, Akers
tried to keep a ball in play near the end line but tumbled head
first into a photo barricade. On the ensuing corner kick, she
jumped up to head the ball away. In a later midair collision, she
knocked Sobrero, her own teammate, hard to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   China managed only four shots in all, and none on goal, over the
first 45 minutes, while the Americans had one that was saved easily
by Gao. Sun had China's best scoring opportunity on a free kick in
the 40th minute, but her attempt sailed over the crossbar.
</P>
<P>
   Early comers to the Rose Bowl enjoyed kickabouts and tailgate
parties in the parking lots and crowded souvenir stands inside the
gates. But freedom of movement was drastically curtailed between
matches due to the arrival of President Clinton, although the
stands were filled by kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
