<SLUG> BC-SOC-WCUP-TV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST WHO WAS THE UNITED STATES PLAYING FOR THE CHAMPIONSHIP?  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Did China matter to ABC Sports at the Women's World Cup
Saturday?
</P>
<P>
   In an international competition in which one team is the United
States, it is worth analyzing how much attention the network pays
to the foreign team. China, aside from being present for the game,
was not an ABC priority. Of course, Chinese players played the U.S.
team to a draw through 120 minutes. You couldn't miss them. But ABC
made this the American team's show.
</P>
<P>
   Makes you wonder what ABC would have done if China had won.
</P>
<P>
   The favoritism wasn't always overt. J.P. Dellacamera and Wendy
Gebauer knew all the Chinese players' names. But the Chinese team's
strategies and personalities were shorted as if they were faceless
automatons.
</P>
<P>
   The first sign came early. Just as the game started, ABC popped
up a graphic: ``USA Keys to Victory.'' Gebauer ticked off the keys.
Fairness would dictate that a similar list of Chinese keys would
follow. It didn't. Did China sneak into the final? No. Were China's
strengths and weaknesses kept secret? No. Did China play its games
in a hermetically sealed stadium? No.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-minute pre-game show (with 9 minutes 24 seconds of
commercials and promotions) offered little to help a viewer get to
know the Chinese players (it wasn't so hot on the American squad
either), which is odd considering that this telecast should have
been tilted toward viewers less knowledgeable about soccer. (The
halftime show was barren of any analysis; imagine a Super Bowl
halftime without analysis?)
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the game, the U.S. players received better treatment
whenever Dellacamera or Gebauer slipped in personal tidbits. (Did
the Chinese team refuse to give any information to the tournament's
media guide?)
</P>
<P>
   And you had to wonder, with all the crowd shots that ABC used in
the Rose Bowl, was there a Chinese contingent? If there wasn't, why
not? If there was, why didn't we see its members cheering for their
team?
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Dellacamera, who had seemed so fair in his
enthusiasms during U.S. games until Saturday, usually sounded more
excited by U.S. scoring possibilities than by China's. That
unfairness emerged most dramatically during the decisive penalty
kicks that ended with the American team's victory.
</P>
<P>
   When Kristine Lilly scored to put the United States ahead, 3-2,
Dellacamera shouted: ``The shot. Goal!''
</P>
<P>
   When China's Zhang Ouying tied it, he said, without a hint of
emotion: ``Zhang. And she scores.''
</P>
<P>
   Mia Hamm's go-ahead goal was called by Dellacamera with a second
shout: ``Shot. And a goal!''
</P>
<P>
   But Sun Wen's tying goal sounded like a disappointment to
Dellacamera. ``Sun Wen shot and she scores.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Brandi Chastain's game-winner was a simple, joyful roar:
``GOAL!''
</P>
<P>
   After Chastain scored, Dellacamera said nothing for nearly two
minutes, just the right strategy. Let the pictures tell the story.
But had the Chinese left the field? Had they fallen through the
little-known Pasadena Trap Door?
</P>
<P>
   In most post-game championship celebrations, television
directors alternate shots of deliriously happy winners with those
of the depressed losers. But as the American team partied, the
Chinese team might well have been in Beijing. Were they stoic? Were
they weeping? Where was their half of the story?
</P>
<P>
   Not visible on ABC. It would take five minutes from Chastain's
goal for ABC to find the Chinese team (for 30 seconds) as it
accepted second-place medals.
</P>
<P>
   Dellacamera and Gebauer's final comments solidified the belief
that China's players and their efforts did not matter. So they did
not mention China. (Nor did the game's host, Robin Roberts.) But
Gebauer, a member of the victorious U.S. team at the 1991 Women's
World Cup, managed to say she had to compose herself because she
had been crying. Jingo bells. All the way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
