<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star is retransmitting these stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Sunday, July
11. The If you have any questions, please call Patricia Hardin on
the Star's News Desk at (816) 234-4753.
SCHOOL-SUPER: (KANSAS CITY, Mo.) The court-appointed Desegregation
Monitoring Committee will likely recommend it be allowed to appoint
a superintendent if the school board is unable to reach agreement
with a candidate by a court-imposed deadline of July 19. By PHILLIP
O'CONNOR. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
CUP-SOCCER: World Cup scene-setter from PASADENA, Calif. By
MECHELLE VOEPEL. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
WAR-SITE: (PLEASANTON, Kan.) What happened just south of here 135
years ago this Oct. 25 was quick _ 10,000 troops clashed; Union
cavalry rolled up the Confederate line; two southern generals were
captured along with hundreds of their men, and gunfire echoed over
the quieting battlefield as the Yankee victors executed vanquished
rebels found wearing scrounged blue uniforms.Thus here in Linn
County the final nail was pounded into Gen. Sterling Price's grand
strategy to rive Missouri and its western borders. His army, which
threatened St. Louis, besieged Jefferson City, and then been driven
out of Kansas City, was transformed into a defeated rabble on the
Kansas prairie. By JIM FISHER. Story will move in the ``a''
category.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-PROGRAM: (KANSAS CITY, Mo.) David Fair wasn't a
straight-A student, captain of the football team or a kid involved
in oodles of school activities. But he was just what Nu-Tech
Industries wanted: a hard worker with some interest in engineering
and plenty of time. So last summer the company drafted him as the
first initiate in the Grandview High School Employment Scholarship
Program. The innovative program helps companies by supplying
workers in a tight job market. It benefits students by teaching
them a trade and pumping money into a college fund. By ERICA WOOD.
Story will move in the ``a'' category.
EYE-SURGERY: (KANSAS CITY, Mo.) Craig Schurig is lying down, arms
resting comfortably at his sides. As a suction ring hugs one of his
near-sighted eyes, a small flap of tissue from the outer layer of
his cornea is lifted by a surgeon wielding a tiny, high-tech tool.
Next, for about 25 seconds, surgeon Daniel S. Durrie trains a laser
on Schurig's cornea, flattening the curve a bit. Then Durrie deftly
brings the corneal flap back down, and it adheres like Velcro. ``I
feel good now,'' the red-eyed Schurig said after the procedure,
which took about three minutes. ``The only thing you feel is the
drops going in, the numbing drops.'' Schurig has just undergone
LASIK surgery at the Hunkeler Eye Centers in Overland Park. The
34-year-old assistant football coach at Pittsburg State University
is one of an estimated 807,500 Americans this year who will undergo
the procedure _ first performed a decade ago _ up from 360,000 last
year. By JULIUS A. KARASH. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
</TEXT>
