<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-PROGRAM-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH SCHOOL AND COLLEGE SHARE IN TEACHING EMPLOYMENT SKILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERICA WOOD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ David Fair wasn't a straight-A student,
captain of the football team or involved in oodles of school
activities.
</P>
<P>
   But he was just what Nu-Tech Industries wanted: a hard worker
with an interest in engineering and plenty of time. So last summer
the company drafted him as the first initiate in the Grandview
(Mo.) High School Employment Scholarship Program.
</P>
<P>
   The innovative program helps companies by supplying workers in a
tight job market. It benefits students by teaching them a trade and
pumping money into a college fund. Longview Community College
sweetens the mix by offering participants a two-year scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company makes school make better sense,'' Fair said. ``You
actually apply what you use.'' A few weeks ago, he put his final
high school report card on his boss' desk. Straight A's.
</P>
<P>
   Fair, who describes himself as ``not really that great of a
student,'' rotated through several departments at Nu-Tech, which
manufactures airplane parts for military planes, before he found
his niche in engineering. He spends much of his time pulling the
specifications for Boeing jets from the computer.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the $6 an hour he makes, the program receives $3
an hour from Nu-Tech that goes into his scholarship fund, which can
be used at any college or university. He's accumulated $6,500 in
the account and will continue to save.
</P>
<P>
   This fall he'll begin at Longview. When finished there, he'll be
able to use his savings for his third and fourth years of college.
</P>
<P>
   In part because of Fair's success, the program has expanded to
10 other businesses, including the U.S. Toy Co. in Grandview and
Loch Lloyd Country Club in Belton.
</P>
<P>
   The Grandview Chamber of Commerce has pledged to market the
program to businesses outside Grandview in the hope of recruiting
20 companies by the end of 1999. Participating businesses get a 50
percent tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Curtis, executive director of the Grandview Chamber, said
her group also wants to involve other school districts.
</P>
<P>
   Area companies need workers, she said, as evidenced by the fact
that they have more interested businesses than interested Grandview
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``First and foremost, they're needing quality workers
desperately,'' Curtis said. ``They (program participants) could be
around for several years or come back after college.''
</P>
<P>
   Nu-Tech President Charlie Newell said it was a way for companies
to reinvest in the community.
</P>
<P>
   When Fair began with Nu-Tech, Newell said, he was a C student.
Sarah Barrows, a Grandview High School counselor, described him as
quiet and not involved in school activities.
</P>
<P>
   But over the course of the year, working full time in the summer
and part time during the school year, Fair became more focused and
began to set goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It motivated me to do better in school and to be more precise
in my work, more thorough,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, Grandview juniors Dale Gordon and Kelly Parker
joined him at Nu-Tech. Gordon started as a materials handler, but
like Fair, he'll rotate through several departments before he
decides which he prefers.
</P>
<P>
   Parker, who has taken programming classes, helps the network
administrator set up computer software.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can go to school and train for a lot of stuff,'' Parker
said, ``but it's not going to help you until you actually have to
deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The program, Newell said is for laid-back students who wonder
what they're going to do in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are really special students, and someone needs to pay
attention to them,'' Newell said.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Lukenbill, a Grandview junior, said that by working at
U.S. Toy as an order-entry clerk, she was learning communication
skills and how to work with others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a great opportunity, and I love working with
people,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her work and that of the other student at U.S. Toy, Laticha
DeMars, pleases Peggy Holloway, Human Resource manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than anything, it gives students the opportunity to
extend their education,'' Holloway said. ``They're a real asset to
U.S. Toy this year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
