<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5583 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUP-SOCCER-KAN &LR;      07-10 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUP-SOCCER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WOMEN'S WORLD CUP VICTORY SOMETHING FOR THE NATION TO
CELEBRATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MECHELLE VOEPEL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The site of the Granddaddy of the Them All
got a chance to showcase granddaughters Saturday. And what a
heart-stopping show it was.
</P>
<P>
   The Rose Bowl, shrine of college football, was host to the
Women's World Cup soccer championship game, played in front of the
largest crowd _ 90,185 _ ever to attend a women's-only sporting
event.
</P>
<P>
   And the United States, after a scoreless 90-minute regulation
and two 15-minute overtimes, sent most of the fans into a frenzy,
winning 5-4 on penalty kicks.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans, who also won the inaugural World Cup in 1991 in
China, got the clinching penalty kick from Brandi Chastain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very confident, and my team trusted me,'' Chastain
said. ``I couldn't wait to step up and take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chastain, who sent a shot into the corner to the left of
goalkeeper Gao Hong and clinched the championship, ripped off her
jersey _ a standard celebratory move by male players.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, U.S. goalkeeper Briana Scurry stopped Liu Ying's
penalty kick.
</P>
<P>
   To deafening chants of ``U-S-A, U-S-A,'' the players leaped
about with what energy they had left. After receiving their
championship medals, they jogged around the field carrying three
huge American flags, as fans roared.
</P>
<P>
   A cloudburst of confetti littered the field as Scurry ran to the
stands to slap hands with some fans. She then got down on her knees
and saluted the crowd, which was chanting, ``Scurry, Scurry.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton was here, but it didn't take an order from the
commander-in-chief to grant Marine pilot Christian Corry temporary
leave from his post in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Corry was at the Rose Bowl to watch his wife, U.S. star Mia
Hamm, who made the Americans' fourth penalty kick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the whole country was caught up in this, not only fans
of soccer but young girls,'' Clinton said. ``In some ways, it's the
biggest sporting even of the last decade. It's new and exciting for
the United States. It will have a very far-reaching impact, not
only for the United States, but for the world.''
</P>
<P>
   You didn't have to be from the United States, though, to feel
the red-white-and-blue fever _ the Great One, recently retired
hockey star Wayne Gretzky of Canada, sent best wishes Friday night
to the U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
   Fans were up early Saturday, some arriving at the Rose Bowl
around dawn to secure a parking spot and set up a tailgate party.
Or perhaps stake a post near the entrance gates in order to be in
quickly and get a shot at the souvenir stands.
</P>
<P>
   It was somewhat like checkout lines on Christmas Eve, with
excited fans buying everything in sight _ from 12 kinds of T-shirts
to tambourines to soccer balls to Mia Hamm charm bracelets.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere there were men, women, boys and girls with their
faces painted and dressed like flags. Some wore Old Glory in cape
form, a fitting homage to the superwomen on the field, who raced up
and down in the Southern California heat and humidity for 120
minutes before the penalty-kick drama ended it.
</P>
<P>
   The bright-red splashes in the crowd also were proud patriots _
fans of China, the team the United States beat for the gold in the
1996 Olympics. The Chinese fans weren't happy Saturday when Rose
Bowl security guards took away one fan's huge Chinese flag.
</P>
<P>
   That was not because of any anti-China bias; flags of a certain
size were not allowed in the stadium. The Chinese fans booed that,
but it was one of the few times anything but cheers were heard.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain talked in the last week about the fever for the U.S.
women's soccer team that had swept the country, saying: ``You could
cry, it's so nice.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States started its national team back in 1985, and
Michelle Akers remembered how the players and coaches had to sew
the ``USA'' letters on their jerseys back then.
</P>
<P>
   There were times when the U.S. women's soccer team played in
front of 100 or fewer. When the Americans came back from winning
the first Cup, in 1991, no one but their friends and families
seemed to know anything about it.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, though, they felt as if all of the United States was
family, and the World Cup was something for everyone to share.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
