<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SENIOR-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUGHERTY HAS SLIM LEAD AND A LOT OF PURSUERS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL ARKUSH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST DES MOINES, Iowa _ With only one round to go in the U.S.
Senior Open, by far the most important tournament in the galaxy for
golfers 50 and older, the surprise halfway leader Ed Dougherty
remains on top. But only barely, and about a dozen pursuers,
including the tour's premier player, Hale Irwin, still have a
reasonable chance of catching him when the intense pressure of this
major championship in Middle America reaches its peak Sunday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Dougherty, 51, who had a mostly undistinguished career in his
initial go-round on the PGA Tour _ his only victory in 457 starts
came at age 47 at the 1995 Deposit Guaranty Golf Classic _ was
ahead by three strokes entering Saturday's third round at Des
Moines Golf and Country Club, and held together through much of the
day. It certainly didn't appear as if he were going to fade.
</P>
<P>
   But consecutive bogeys at 16 and 17 lead to a three-over 75 for
a total of four-under 212, just one stroke over Irwin, Dave
Eichelberger and Bruce Summerhays. Gil Morgan, Irwins main rival in
1997 and 1998, is only two shots back, and Joe Inman is three
behind.
</P>
<P>
   Even Jim Colbert, who posted his second straight 68 after an
opening-round 80, is still, remarkably, in the middle of it at
even-par 216, only four behind. It is hard to recall when someone
started with a score in the 80s and rebounded in time to win a
major on any tour.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Dougherty, despite his struggles down the stretch,
remains in a very good mood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the best of days but if someone had told me Monday
that, `Hey, Ed, you'll have a one-shot lead going into Sunday, how
do you think you'll handle it? I would have been thrilled,'' said
Dougherty. ``And I still am thrilled. I have lead the Open for
three days. I'm playing with Hale tomorrow. He's the best player on
the senior tour. Whatever happens, happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, with all his valuable experience three U.S. Open
victories (1974, 1979 and 1990) on the PGA Tour Irwin, the
defending champion, is, unquestionably, the clear favorite. Even
more ominously for his respectful competitors, Irwin may be due.
``I don't feel like I have had my round yet in the tournament,''
said Irwin, whose 70 Saturday followed unspectacular scores of 71
and 72.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been respectable rounds, not those kinds of rounds
that I feel like I can generate. And, hopefully, I can have that
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt Eichelberger harbors similar aspirations, though he's
acutely aware of the challenge ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been trying for 35 years to beat Hale,'' said
Eichelberger, ``and it has been pretty hard. In fact, I haven't
done it too many times.''
</P>
<P>
   Irwin actually could have fared even better. He missed a 12-foot
birdie putt at 18 that would have, in retrospect, tied him for the
lead. Yet he could not be too disappointed. He was only one under
par for the tournament until he tapped in for a birdie at 16 and
followed it with a 20-foot birdie putt at 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not in the perfect position,'' he added, ``but I am not
in a bad position.''
</P>
<P>
   Dougherty, of course, is in the best position, but it will be
difficult for him to hang on. He'll be encountering the kind of
final-round pressure that he has not faced too many times in his
career. But big surprises have won before in the U.S. Senior Open _
Larry Laoretti in 1992, Simon Hobday in 1994 _ so anything can
truly happen.
</P>
<P>
   One thing's for sure: No matter who is on the leaderboard on
Sunday, the people will come. All week long, crowds have embraced
this tournament in unbelievable fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's attendance was 47,200, bringing the total number of
fans since Monday's practice rounds to 201,600. This total comes
despite the absence of crowd favorites Arnold Palmer and Chi Chi
Rodriguez, who both missed the cut, and Jack Nicklaus, who withdrew
from the tournament after aggravating a hip that is still
recovering from replacement surgery in January.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
