r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WAR-SITE-KAN &LR;      07-10 1245
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAR-SITE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP GOES ON DEFENSE TO PROTECT KANSAS CIVIL WAR BATTLEFIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLEASANTON, Kan. _ What happened just south of here 135 years
ago this Oct. 25 was quick _ 10,000 troops clashed, Union cavalry
rolled up the Confederate line, two Southern generals were captured
along with hundreds of their men, and gunfire echoed over the
quieting battlefield as the Yankee victors executed vanquished
rebels found wearing scrounged blue uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Thus here in Linn County, the final nail was pounded into
Confederate Gen. Sterling Price's grand strategy to rive Missouri
and its western borders. His army, which threatened St. Louis,
besieged Jefferson City and then was driven out of Westport, was
transformed into a defeated rabble on the Kansas prairie.
</P>
<P>
   For Price and his troops the Civil War ended with the Battle of
Mine Creek, itself an oddity in that most of the fighting took
place in only 30 explosive minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with its sesquicentennial just 15 years away, little Mine
Creek and its historic environs look north and see the approach of
a slower yet far more inexorable host.
</P>
<P>
   Coming are not the cavalry, but surveyors, cement trucks, loads
of lumber, roofers and plumbers, road-building machinery,
utility-line crews, sod-layers, riding mowers and, eventually,
fast-food franchises and shopping malls.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's Louisburg _ just 30 miles up the road?'' asked John
Spencer, a Fort Scott physician whose great-grandfather fought as a
Union cavalry sergeant at Mine Creek. ``Last I looked they had a
McDonald's, a Burger King, a Sonic, gas stations out on (U.S.) 69,
even a Price Chopper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty, 30 years, unless something's done, you'll be looking
at subdivisions around this battlefield.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer and Arnold Schofield, a Fort Scott historian, were
talking about Mine Creek earlier this year while driving home from
a meeting of the Civil War Round Table of Kansas City. Both knew
that in the 1970s Kansas had acquired _ sometimes with less than a
light touch _ 270 acres of the old battlefield for a park east of
U.S. 69 and south of Kansas 52.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the Kansas State Historical Society opened a visitors
center for self-guided walking tours.
</P>
<P>
   But, Schofield said, that was about it.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, he said, the park was just some land that looks
pretty much as it did in 1864, largely unstudied by professionals,
as has been done at the battlefield in Montana where Lt. Col.
George Armstrong Custer and most of his command died.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you had was pristine land, some that'd never been broken
by a plow and that nobody has ever gone over in a systematic way to
figure out what really happened by finding buried cartridge
casings, old bridles, busted-up guns, maybe even graves,''
Schofield said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew _ after the visitors center _ there wouldn't be much
more (done). Plus, you can't go to the Legislature and say you have
some old ground down in Linn County and we'd like so many dollars
just to poke around. Never happen.''
</P>
<P>
   On that trip back to Fort Scott, Spencer and Schofield decided
to form an association, sort of an adjunct venture that could help
out _ print brochures, fund some archaeological investigations,
provide some audiovisual aids and furnish what they called ``land
stewardship.''
</P>
<P>
   The goals were modest. The tax-exempt group, called the Mine
Creek Battlefield Foundation (816 E. National Ave. Fort Scott, KS
66701) would spend a few thousand dollars annually. Kip Lindberg,
curator at the visitors center, and Charles Gentry, a Fort Scott
attorney, rounded out what was called the ``Four Musketeers.'' Soon
after, Charles Conley, Marty Read and Dale Sprague of Linn County
signed on.
</P>
<P>
   The group got into action quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten days or so later the doc is on the phone yelling, `The
Hamilton land is on the market, the Hamilton land is one the
market,' '' Schofield said.
</P>
<P>
   The Hamilton land was the late Reese Hamilton's 80 acres
abutting the east side of the Mine Creek park. Across the Hamilton
land, historians have long suspected, Union Lt. Col. Frederick
Benteen (later an antagonist ofCuster at the Little Bighorn, sent
his brigade smashing into the army of Gen. John Marmaduke,
scattering it and capturing Marmaduke.
</P>
<P>
   ``That acreage is absolutely vital to the battlefield,'' said
Spencer, who added that it shielded the visitors center just to the
east and safeguarded a tract where myriad battle artifacts have
been found over the years.
</P>
<P>
   But the real key to the Hamilton land is the recent discovery,
through ground-imaging radar, of the long-lost Fort
Scott-to-Westport road, which a few old maps merely hinted at. The
road is west of the famed Fort Scott-Leavenworth frontier trail.
Along and on each side of the newly revealed road, now under just a
few feet of soil, Benteen may have sent his troopers forward.
</P>
<P>
   The asking price to settle Hamilton's estate was $120,000, or
$1,500 an acre, high compared with 20 years ago but not out of line
with today's prices of adjacent land. Schofield said Linn County
was already feeling pressure from speculators who want to get in on
the ground floor.
</P>
<P>
   Where to get the money? The Legislature had already written its
bills for the year. Maybe next year, the foundation was told. But
don't count even on that.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton's heirs wanted the money within four months.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we went to a bank, put up some of our own money (roughly 20
percent) borrowed the rest and bought it ourselves,'' Spencer said.
</P>
<P>
   Elliot Gruber, executive vice president of the Civil War Trust
in Arlington, Va., the nation's largest Civil War
battlefield-preservation group, said the purchase of such land by
individuals was all but unheard of.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' he said, ``is dedication.''
</P>
<P>
   Gruber also said it was amazing that the group could purchase
the land only about 90 days after hearing it was available.
</P>
<P>
   Civil War battlefield preservation is now in a race against
time, Gruber said. One acre of battlefield is lost every 10
seconds, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can be preserved must be preserved now,'' he said. ``Land
is just disappearing. The pressure of development is that strong.''
</P>
<P>
   The answer, Gruber said, is the growth in what's called
``heritage tourism.'' People are willing to travel to battlefields
and spend money in nearby towns, he said, as long as what they are
visiting still looks much as it did when it became part of the
American legacy. But surround a site _ any site _ with neon,
plastic and asphalt, he said, and people will drive on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll give you an example,'' he said. ``Chantilly here in
Virginia was a major battle. What's left? A monument in the middle
of shopping malls.''
</P>
<P>
   The Civil War Trust said that Missouri battlefields at Westport,
Independence, Glasgow and Island No. 10 are past saving, and Lone
Jack, Springfield and Lexington are severely threatened. In Kansas,
Baxter Springs and Lawrence have been lost. Only Mine Creek
remains.
</P>
<P>
   Schofield said grant money from other foundations and federal
agencies should recoup the $120,000 spent on the Hamilton land.
Already, he said, members of the Mine Creek foundation are talking
with other area landowners.
</P>
<P>
   The goal, Schofield said, is to acquire about 900 acres, then
hand it over to the state so that Mine Creek can be protected from
any encroachment. Ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just getting started,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 2142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990710.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5588 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-2000-MOVIES-2ndTAKE-L     07-10 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-2000-MOVIES-2ndTAKE-LADN </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: screenings.
</P>
<P>
   Several other projects already stand out from the 200-plus major
movies coming next year:
</P>
<P>
   ``Me, Myself and Irene'' from Fox in the summer. Jim Carrey
stars as a state trooper with a split personality with both sides
of himself falling in love with the same woman. ``Irene,'' played
by Rene Zellweger, is the Farrelly Brothers first film since their
blockbuster ``There's Something About Mary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Patriot,'' from Sony in the summer with Mel Gibson as a
father of seven in South Carolina forced to fight the British
during the Revolutionary War.
</P>
<P>
   ``X-Men'' from Fox with Patrick Stewart, Ian McKellan and Anna
Paquin. The comic-book heroes saga will be directed by Richard
Donner, who brought ``Superman'' to life in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``Erin Brockovich'' from Universal with Julia Roberts as a
real-life Southern California legal secretary who won a
class-action lawsuit over water contamination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Grinch Who Stole Christmas,'' for Universal at
Thanksgiving with Carrey in the first Dr. Seuss story to make it to
the big screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Memoirs of a Geisha,'' late in the year for Sony, directed by
Spielberg and based on the novel by Arthur Golden in which a
9-year-old girl is sold into slavery in 1929.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ali,'' with Will Smith as the legendary boxer for Sony late in
the year in the third teaming with Barry Sonnenfeld, who also
directed Smith in ``Men In Black'' and ``Wild Wild West.''
</P>
<P>
   Other possible hits include Disney's ``Fantasia 2000'' and drama
``Gone in 60 Seconds''; New Line's thriller ``Flight 180'';
Miramax's teen comedy ``Down To You''; DreamWorks' animated ``El
Dorado'' and ``Chicken Run''; Sony's comedy ``What Planet Are You
From'' and ``Charlie's Angels'' with Drew Barrymore; Universal's
``Rocky &AMP; Bullwinkle,'' ``Flintstones 2'' and ``Nutty Professor
2''; Paramount's ``Rugrats 2'' and ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' with
Matt Damon and Gwyneth Paltrow; Fox's ``Cast Away'' with Tom Hanks
and Helen Hunt; and Warner's football comedy ``The Replacements,''
with Keanu Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a wish list of franchise sequels that might never
happen but could be fast-tracked to next year if deals are reached.
Among the sequels reportedly in early stages of discussion:
``Godfather IV,'' ``Indiana Jones 4,'' ``Superman 5,'' ``Total
Recall 2,'' ``Jurassic Park 3,'' ``True Lies 2'' and ``Mad Max 4.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, every Y2K film looks great at this point. But even
the cockiest studio executives remain aware that what seemed
sure-fire on paper can become a dog when moviegoers pony up $8 and
two hours to watch recent misfires like ``EDtv,'' ``Meet Joe
Black,'' ``The Mod Squad,'' ``Deep End of the Ocean'' and ``True
Crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for studios, the bombs have come less often lately.
Several observers believe it's because Hollywood has learned how to
fast-track films.
</P>
<P>
   ``Studios are adapting to trends more readily than in the past,
particularly in hot areas like comedies geared to teen-agers and
date crowds,'' Bucksbaum said. ``It used to take them two years to
figure out trends, which change much quicker than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley Thomas, a producer with the Farrellys, noted that
production began on ``Irene'' less than six months after Fox
received the script. ``This really happened extremely quickly,'' he
added. ``I think everyone realized this was a definite summer movie
after the success with `Something About Mary.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood also has been helped immeasurably by the ongoing boom
in shiny new movie palaces with up to 30 state-of-the-art
auditoriums, massive snack bars and staggered start times. The
so-called megaplexes _ built by the theater owners rather than the
studios _ have been a major driver in box office gains of recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Megaplexes have made it comfortable for people to go the
movies,'' Skislock said. ``People are much more likely to not even
check the paper anymore before they go but rather just show up and
decide what to see on the spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Studios and producers also have fine-tuned the idea of
delivering films aimed at niches such as teen-agers and families.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can get the 13-to-25-year-old demographic, there are
massive amounts of money,'' said Morgan Rector, president of
Imperial Entertainment Group.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as easy as it sounds, according to Warren Zide,
producer of ``American Pie'' and the horror-thriller ``Flight
180.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to make movies that people can relate to,'' Zide
said. ``People need to respect the fact that kids are smarter than
they get credit for. We like to speak up to kids rather than down
to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Zide also said it's crucial to move quickly at a time when many
studios are cutting the number of films released.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make sure the script is as close to production as possible
and we keep moving things along,'' he added. ``A lot of people fall
into overdevelopment, where all of a sudden you've got a script
that's been in development for three years. I'm not saying that
makes the script bad, but we try to avoid it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood also is scrambling to expand the family audience,
which has been dominated by Disney. DreamWorks will release three
animated movies next year and Paramount will follow up with a
sequel to its surprisingly powerful ``The Rugrats Movie'' through
its Nickelodeon unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see a real opportunity to do family comedy,'' said
Nickelodeon movie chief Albie Hecht, who has a half-dozen projects
in development including ``Snow Day,'' ``Fried Worms'' and a Rube
Goldberg project. ``I think `Something About Mary' is great but you
really don't want to watch it with your kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than present the idealized world of Disney movies,
Nickelodeon stresses realism. ``Disney takes the extraordinary for
granted but we bring it to everyday life,'' Hecht said. ``Our films
are going to be very contemporary.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
