NYT-07-10-99 2200EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990710.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5592 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-2000-MOVIES-2TAKES-LA     07-10 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-2000-MOVIES-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDIOS PLAN BIG, BIG YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ What Y2K problem?
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood's movie schedule for next year shows excellent
potential and plenty of depth, analysts and insiders say. That's in
contrast to this year, which most analysts previously predicted
would be remembered as `` `Star Wars' and everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, the movies slated for early 2000 should be
able to sustain current box office momentum, analysts say, amid the
increasingly heated battle for consumers' entertainment dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates for blockbuster status _ ``tentpoles'' in studio
lingo _ have emerged in two highly profitable areas: vehicles for
superstars like Tom Cruise, Jim Carrey, Julia Roberts and Will
Smith, and movies about outer space.
</P>
<P>
   ``The year 2000 schedule is very ambitious and varied with a lot
of tentpole films,'' said Sony distribution chief Jeff Blake, who
counts a half-dozen films as possible mega-hits. ``It's become a
way of life to have strong films and the schedule jammed week after
week so I don't expect any less in 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney distribution head Chuck Viane also sees at least six
potential blockbusters from his studio, adding, ``This year's been
good; next year looks fabulous.''
</P>
<P>
   In a show of bravado, Hollywood's major studios already have
staked out many key release dates for 2000, from 10 months to a
year before the movies even will be released.
</P>
<P>
   ``Studios are claiming dates much earlier than they used to,''
said Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel Source tracking
service. ``They've realized you can release two or three movies on
the same date and still do well.''
</P>
<P>
   There's another key reason why studios are locking up dates _
merchandising.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how producers are offsetting a lot of their increased
costs and why they're not backing off on making big-budget films,''
Bucksbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   Two key projects are already on a collision course. Possibly in
an effort to cash in on next year's expected focus on the future,
Warner Bros. and Disney will both release movies about rescue
missions to Mars.
</P>
<P>
   Warner's ``Mars,'' originally titled ``Alone,'' will star Val
Kilmer as a stranded astronaut and Carrie-Anne Moss as the rescuer.
It will open in March.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's entry, due in late June, is ``Mission to Mars'' with
Gary Sinese, Tim Robbins and Don Cheadle investigating the
disappearance of the first mission. Principal photography under the
direction of Brian DePalma started two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took us three years to get the script right to show a
strong human drama with dangerous and exciting situations,'' said
producer Tom Jacobson. ``We're creating Mars with a combination of
locations like Jordan, the Canary Islands and a 50-acre sand pit in
Vancouver.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson said he was not worried about ``Mars'' taking away from
the audience for ``Mission to Mars.'' ``I'm not one to philosophize
about the business, but I am encouraged by what I've seen this
summer,'' he added. ``If you make a good movie, people will want to
go see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Memorial Day weekend is once again loaded. Warner Bros. will
open ``Space Cowboys'' with Jack Nicholson, Clint Eastwood and
Tommy Lee Jones as retired Air Force pilots retrieving dangerous
space debris. DreamWorks' could roll out ``What Lies Beneath'' with
Harrison Ford and Michelle Pfeiffer in a supernatural thriller
directed by Robert Zemeckis. Disney's ``Dinosaurs,'' with a
potentially ground-breaking mix of animation and live action, will
tell the story of a baby dino raised by monkeys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dinosaurs'' could cost as much as $200million, according to
unconfirmed rumors.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Space Cowboys'' and the two Mars movies, three space
travel movies could be opening within three months. Conventional
wisdom would conclude doing so is a lousy idea, but conventional
wisdom has been wrong recently.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, for example, analysts predicted ``Deep Impact'' and
``Armageddon'' would hurt each other by opening only eight weeks
apart; instead, they combined for $350million domestically. The
lesson was not lost on studios, which are scrambling to fill the
void for sci-fi until ``Star Wars: Episode 2'' opens in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing a generation growing up with tremendous
excitement about space travel and it will take quite a few films to
make people tired about it,'' said analyst Kevin Skislock of Laguna
Research Partners. ``People will go because it's a way to live it
vicariously. With the effects making it so real and something that
can't be replicated at home, we're only at the beginning of a new
wave of interest.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the strongest early buzz for 2000 comes from another
sci-fi film _ ``Minority Report'' from 20th Century Fox and
scheduled to open June 28. Tom Cruise will star and Steven
Spielberg will direct a big-screen version of a Phillip K. Dick
story about a futuristic ``pre-crime'' police squad.
</P>
<P>
   Also on next year's sci-fi radar are Sony's ``The Hollow Man,''
with Kevin Bacon as a scientist who becomes invisible, and Fox's
animated ``Titan A.E.,'' formerly named ``Planet Ice,'' which
already has been seen in trailers prior to ``Star Wars: Episode One
_ The Phantom Menace'' screenings.
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED ON NEXT TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: screenings.
</P>
<P>
   Several other projects already stand out from the 200-plus major
movies coming next year:
</P>
<P>
   ``Me, Myself and Irene'' from Fox in the summer. Jim Carrey
stars as a state trooper with a split personality with both sides
of himself falling in love with the same woman. ``Irene,'' played
by Rene Zellweger, is the Farrelly Brothers first film since their
blockbuster ``There's Something About Mary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Patriot,'' from Sony in the summer with Mel Gibson as a
father of seven in South Carolina forced to fight the British
during the Revolutionary War.
</P>
<P>
   ``X-Men'' from Fox with Patrick Stewart, Ian McKellan and Anna
Paquin. The comic-book heroes saga will be directed by Richard
Donner, who brought ``Superman'' to life in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``Erin Brockovich'' from Universal with Julia Roberts as a
real-life Southern California legal secretary who won a
class-action lawsuit over water contamination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Grinch Who Stole Christmas,'' for Universal at
Thanksgiving with Carrey in the first Dr. Seuss story to make it to
the big screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Memoirs of a Geisha,'' late in the year for Sony, directed by
Spielberg and based on the novel by Arthur Golden in which a
9-year-old girl is sold into slavery in 1929.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ali,'' with Will Smith as the legendary boxer for Sony late in
the year in the third teaming with Barry Sonnenfeld, who also
directed Smith in ``Men In Black'' and ``Wild Wild West.''
</P>
<P>
   Other possible hits include Disney's ``Fantasia 2000'' and drama
``Gone in 60 Seconds''; New Line's thriller ``Flight 180'';
Miramax's teen comedy ``Down To You''; DreamWorks' animated ``El
Dorado'' and ``Chicken Run''; Sony's comedy ``What Planet Are You
From'' and ``Charlie's Angels'' with Drew Barrymore; Universal's
``Rocky &AMP; Bullwinkle,'' ``Flintstones 2'' and ``Nutty Professor
2''; Paramount's ``Rugrats 2'' and ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' with
Matt Damon and Gwyneth Paltrow; Fox's ``Cast Away'' with Tom Hanks
and Helen Hunt; and Warner's football comedy ``The Replacements,''
with Keanu Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a wish list of franchise sequels that might never
happen but could be fast-tracked to next year if deals are reached.
Among the sequels reportedly in early stages of discussion:
``Godfather IV,'' ``Indiana Jones 4,'' ``Superman 5,'' ``Total
Recall 2,'' ``Jurassic Park 3,'' ``True Lies 2'' and ``Mad Max 4.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, every Y2K film looks great at this point. But even
the cockiest studio executives remain aware that what seemed
sure-fire on paper can become a dog when moviegoers pony up $8 and
two hours to watch recent misfires like ``EDtv,'' ``Meet Joe
Black,'' ``The Mod Squad,'' ``Deep End of the Ocean'' and ``True
Crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for studios, the bombs have come less often lately.
Several observers believe it's because Hollywood has learned how to
fast-track films.
</P>
<P>
   ``Studios are adapting to trends more readily than in the past,
particularly in hot areas like comedies geared to teen-agers and
date crowds,'' Bucksbaum said. ``It used to take them two years to
figure out trends, which change much quicker than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley Thomas, a producer with the Farrellys, noted that
production began on ``Irene'' less than six months after Fox
received the script. ``This really happened extremely quickly,'' he
added. ``I think everyone realized this was a definite summer movie
after the success with `Something About Mary.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood also has been helped immeasurably by the ongoing boom
in shiny new movie palaces with up to 30 state-of-the-art
auditoriums, massive snack bars and staggered start times. The
so-called megaplexes _ built by the theater owners rather than the
studios _ have been a major driver in box office gains of recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Megaplexes have made it comfortable for people to go the
movies,'' Skislock said. ``People are much more likely to not even
check the paper anymore before they go but rather just show up and
decide what to see on the spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Studios and producers also have fine-tuned the idea of
delivering films aimed at niches such as teen-agers and families.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can get the 13-to-25-year-old demographic, there are
massive amounts of money,'' said Morgan Rector, president of
Imperial Entertainment Group.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as easy as it sounds, according to Warren Zide,
producer of ``American Pie'' and the horror-thriller ``Flight
180.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to make movies that people can relate to,'' Zide
said. ``People need to respect the fact that kids are smarter than
they get credit for. We like to speak up to kids rather than down
to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Zide also said it's crucial to move quickly at a time when many
studios are cutting the number of films released.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make sure the script is as close to production as possible
and we keep moving things along,'' he added. ``A lot of people fall
into overdevelopment, where all of a sudden you've got a script
that's been in development for three years. I'm not saying that
makes the script bad, but we try to avoid it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood also is scrambling to expand the family audience,
which has been dominated by Disney. DreamWorks will release three
