<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5728 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-YANKS-METS-NYT &LR;      07-10 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKS-METS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PURE STORYBOOK: METS WIN ONE TO REMEMBER  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Yankees bashed nearly a half-mile of home runs
against the Mets Saturday, they came from behind twice and
recovered from what some of them thought was the longest home run
they had ever seen. But the Yankees still needed a single strike to
hold their one-run lead and win this three-ring circus of a ball
game.
</P>
<P>
   The bases were loaded, bottom of the ninth inning, no balls and
two strikes, Yankees and Mets fans alike standing and shouting at
Shea Stadium. The Yankees' Mariano Rivera threw a fastball past the
Mets pinch-hitter Matt Franco. Ball 1, called the home-plate
umpire, Jeff Kellogg, and some Yankees' players and coaches lunged
forward in the dugout, screaming angrily.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera threw another fastball, Franco laced a line drive into
right field, the tying and winning runs scored in the Mets' 9-8
victory, and there was a total meltdown in Queens: the Mets'
professional mien dissolved into adolescent joyfulness as they
rushed Franco on the field, and the Yankees sagged at the shoulders
as they walked off, in one of the most incredible games any of them
will ever play.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, who won Friday night's game, can complete a sweep of
the Yankees Sunday, when Orel Hershiser pitches against Hideki
Irabu. But none of them was thinking about that within the first
hour after Franco's stunning game-winning single. From the quiet
sadness of Bernie Williams, whose misplay set up the decisive runs,
to the grin of Mike Piazza as he told of his 482-foot home run, the
Yankees and Mets reveled in all that was good and bad and great
about Saturday's game. ``The mood swings were incredible,'' Franco
said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Rivera, ``I never had a feeling in a game like that
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy Pettitte pitched six innings for the Yankees and then
managed to find the only quiet place in Shea, in the Yankees'
clubhouse, to watch the final innings on a television mounted on a
beam; deep within the ball park, it was as if Pettitte was within a
sound-proofed room. Already there had been so much craziness.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees jumped ahead, 2-0, on Paul O'Neill's home run. The
Mets took a 4-2 lead in the fourth, after the first of the Yankees'
defensive mistakes. Ricky Ledee and Jorge Posada _ who had made
those mistakes in the bottom of the fourth _ tied the game with
back-to-back home runs in the top of the fifth, and then O'Neill
and Chuck Knoblauch blasted home runs, giving the Yankees a 6-4
edge through six and a half innings. Pettitte settled into a metal
chair at a four-legged table in the silence of the clubhouse and
like a man sitting alone on his couch, watched the pendulum of
momentum swing back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   Ramiro Mendoza relieved Pettitte for the seventh, and after a
bloop double by Rickey Henderson, Mendoza walked John Olerud,
bringing Piazza to the plate; the home run that Piazza crushed to
win Friday's game was foremost in the memories of the 53,792 fans
at Shea. Mendoza fell behind in the count, tried to come back with
a sinker _ and Piazza murdered the pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The sound of Piazza's 34{-inch, 33-{ounce bat striking Mendoza's
sinker propelled Jeff Manto and others off the Yankees' bench. What
a sound. The Yankees' lead was departing Shea along with Piazza's
home run, but that didn't matter; as baseball players, they all
understood the majesty of Piazza's home run. ``I don't usually
watch the other team's homers,'' Manto said. ``But that sounded so
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Said O'Neill, ``When you're on the field and see a guy hit a
ball like that, you almost become a fan.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees in the bullpen beyond the left-field fence saw
Piazza's home run coming, and they stared as if watching a jet take
off from LaGuardia. The ball landed near the top of the
blue-and-white striped tent beyond the left-field fence. Piazza
circled the bases and descended into a sea of excited teammates.
Pettitte watched quietly in the Yankees' clubhouse. Mets 7, Yankees
6.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets' bullpen is not the same without John Franco.
Armando Benitez does not pitch the eighth inning anymore, and
instead of Benitez, Dennis Cook was pitching. Scott Brosius walked,
and one batter later, Posada stepped in to hit. He was playing only
because Joe Girardi had a strained neck, and Posada's fifth-inning
home run had eased the frustration of an otherwise terrible year _
he began the game hitting .199.
</P>
<P>
   Posada did it again: Cook threw a pitch down, Posada lifted it
high and deep to left, and gone, and now it was the Yankees
spilling out of the dugout. Another crossroads, another unexpected
turn. There would be five lead changes and two ties in nine
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera took over for the bottom of the ninth, and the Yankees
could have been forgiven for overwhelming confidence. The last time
they lost a game when leading after eight innings was May 14, 1998,
a string of 124 games. Three outs to go.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera got the first out, then walked Henderson; Mets fans were
screaming, knowing that if two guys got on, Piazza would hit.
Edgardo Alfonzo drove a deep fly just to left of center, and
Williams raced back, feeling for the wall with his right hand. He
had it, he had it.
</P>
<P>
   Williams reached up _ and missed the fly. It bounced on the
warning track, and Henderson, caught by surprise, hadn't advanced
past second; by the time the ball returned to the infield, he had
advanced only to third, Alfonzo to second. ``I should've caught the
ball, no doubt it,'' Williams said through pursed lips.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' infield moved in, with Olerud batting, and Rivera
attacked him with his cut fastball, jamming him inside. Olerud
weakly bounced a grounder to first, where Tino Martinez stepped on
the bag and stared down Henderson at third. Two outs. Groans and
cheers from the fans. Everybody was standing.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza strolled to the plate, but there was no chance the
Yankees would pitch to him with first base open; the Mets' fans
began booing as soon as Posada held four fingers to his right side
to signal an intentional walk.
</P>
<P>
   Bases loaded. Franco was announced as the pinch-hitter for the
Mets. Rivera stood on the mound, waiting, planning to throw cut
fastballs; Rivera buries left-handed batters with his cutter.
Franco knew this, too.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera threw, Franco fouled off the pitch. Another cutter,
strike two. Rick Reed and Cook and a handful of Mets watched in
their clubhouse. Pettitte sat alone.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera fired another cutter right over the middle of the plate,
he thought. ``My heart stopped for half a breath,'' Franco said.
Ball one, Kellogg ruled, and Manager Joe Torre and others yelled
from the Yankees' dugout.
</P>
<P>
   One strike to go. Another cutter from Rivera, and this time,
Franco whistled a low liner through the right side of the infield.
Henderson scored the tying run. O'Neill charged the ball, tried
reaching it on the first hop, couldn't, grabbed the second bounce
and threw home _ too late to get Alfonzo.
</P>
<P>
   Shea exploded. Brian McRae rushed to bear-hug Franco near first
base and the rest of the Mets circled them, yelling and screaming.
The Yankees walked off to join Pettitte's silent world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 2214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990710.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5770 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     07-10 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE BEST 24 HOURS IN METS HISTORY  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If it had been a World Series game, it would deserve
to be put in a time capsule for as long the Yankees and the Mets
play baseball. Or for as long as anybody plays baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Even as a regular-season subway series game, it deserved to have
had red, white and blue bunting on the box seat railings. Of the 11
games the Yankees and the Mets have played now over their three
seasons of interleague confrontations, this was the best. By far.
By any definition of what baseball is all about.
</P>
<P>
   And when the Mets finally won, 9-8, Saturday on pinch-hitter
Matt Franco's two-out, two-run single in the ninth inning, their
loyalists among the 53,792 fans all but detonated Shea Stadium and
the team celebrated as if it had won the World Series instead of
what so many had tried to play down as ``just another game.''
</P>
<P>
   Never before in the franchise's occasionally storied and often
silly history had the Mets had 24 hours like it.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday night's opener of the second segment of the subway
series that concludes Sunday, Mike Piazza, the Mets' $91 million
catcher, hit a three-run homer off Roger Clemens for a 5-2 lead
that Armando Benitez, with two Yankees on base in the ninth,
preserved by striking out Chili Davis as the Mets and 53,820 held
their breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't sit,'' Mets Manager Bobby Valentine was saying
Saturday during batting practice. ``I was walking along the dugout,
telling guys: `This is exciting. This is exciting.'''
</P>
<P>
   For the Mets, that was merely an overture to Saturday's
excitement that endured for nine innings, from Paul O'Neill's
two-run homer in the first off Rick Reed to the Yankee
right-fielder's throw a split second too late to prevent Edgardo
Alfonzo from sliding across with the winning run on Franco's line
drive off Mariano Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   In their nearly four decades, the Mets have had some memorable
consecutive games: three at Shea that won the 1969 World Series
against the Orioles, the Mookie Wilson-Bill Buckner sixth game, and
the homers by Ray Knight and Darryl Strawberry in the seventh game
that won the 1986 World Series against the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   But those three 1969 games were spread over three October
afternoons, and any two of them, back to back, took about 27 hours;
those 1986 games were on a Saturday night and a Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in less than 24 hours, less than 22 hours really, the Mets
had beaten the Yankees twice _ the Yankees whose 1996 and 1998
World Series success has tormented the Mets, the Yankees who before
Friday night had tortured the Mets in six of their previous nine
games since inter-league play began in 1997, the Yankees who hit
six home runs Saturday but still couldn't win.
</P>
<P>
   With the memory of Friday's excitement lingering before
Saturday's game, Louie Armstrong was growling ``What a Wonderful
World'' over Shea's sound system, the ideal theme for what would be
a wonderful game.
</P>
<P>
   After the Yankees took a 2-0 jump on O'Neill's first of two
homers, Piazza's double knocked in a run in the bottom of the
first, then the Mets scratched together the tying run in the
second. In the fourth, Robin Ventura's double sparked their 4-2
lead, but in the fifth Ricky Ledee and Jorge Posada hit consecutive
homers to tie the score. In the sixth, O'Neill hit another. In the
seventh, Chuck Knoblauch hit one for a 6-4 Yankee lead.
</P>
<P>
   But with Ramiro Mendoza pitching in the bottom of the seventh,
Piazza crushed a two-out, three-run homer that soared against the
cloudy sky and landed atop the Mets' blue-and-white hospitality
tent out in what is usually the picnic area beyond the left-field
bleachers, an estimated 482 feet from where he swung. Any further
and it would have disrupted the air-traffic controllers at nearby
LaGuardia Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets led, 7-6, but not for long. Posada's second homer put
the Yankees up, 8-7, and turned the Mets' dugout into so many white
uniforms suddenly cast in stone. For several seconds, nobody in
there moved.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Stanton breezed through the Mets in the eighth, but if
Piazza were to get up again in the ninth against Rivera, the
Yankees' incomparable closer, they needed at least two base
runners. They got them. With one out, Rickey Henderson walked and
Alfonzo doubled over center fielder Bernie Williams' head, but John
Olerud then bounced to first baseman Tino Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Two out, Piazza up, and all those fans, for the Mets and Yankees
alike, on their feet. But Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager, wisely
ordered the Mets' catcher walked intentionally, loading the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine, walking the dugout as he had Friday night, sent up
Matt Franco, a left-handed-swinging sometimes infielder and
sometimes outfielder, to bat for Benny Agbayani as all those fans
held their position and held their breath. Foul ball, strike one.
Swing and miss, strike two. Two pitches later, the Mets had
completed the best 24 hours in their history.
</P>
<P>
   Since losing twice to the Yankees five weeks ago, the Mets have
put together the best record in the big leagues: 23-10 and three in
a row over the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   So put Saturday's game in a time capsule anyway as a tribute to
baseball at its best, to New York-New York baseball in particular.
All those Mets loyalists who were on their feet for Matt Franco's
single and Edgardo Alfonzo's slide were dancing as they departed
Shea, dancing to Billy Joel on the sound system singing, ``I'm in a
New York state of mind.''
</P>
<P>
   And there's another game Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
