<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-PADRES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE LAPSES IN NINTH WRECK RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The blank stare emanating from the eyes of John
Wetteland reflected his agony.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' closer can tolerate physical errors, but
yesterday's mental indiscretion tormented the All-Star.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland violated one of baseball's rudimentary fundamentals by
failing to cover first base on a ball hit to the right side, and
San Diego's Quilvio Veras and Damian Jackson scored _ without the
ball leaving the infield _ on the game's final play to propel the
Padres to a 5-4 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an unacceptable mistake,'' said Wetteland, who committed
only one of the Rangers' three ninth-inning improprieties.
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder Rusty Greer dropped a fly ball, and third baseman
Todd Zeile accepted responsibility for a bunt coverage that went
awry during an inning in which the Rangers ``didn't do a whole lot
right,'' manager Johnny Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Seventh-inning home runs by first baseman Rafael Palmeiro and
center fielder Ruben Mateo hurled the Rangers to a 4-3 lead over
the Padres before the defense's trifecta of torment. It began with
Greer, who dropped a fly ball off the bat of third baseman Carlos
Baerga.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just missed it,'' said Greer, who attempted to catch the
ball with his glove turned up. ``There's no two ways around it. To
make a mistake like that really stinks. It's disappointing. We all
make mistakes, but you don't want to make one there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a long way to run, but I got there in plenty of time,''
said Greer, who stationed himself deep in an attempt to prevent a
potential double. ``I've made that play 100 times. It just opened
the floodgates. It changed the way John had to pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   San Diego's Ed Giovanola, who replaced Baerga as a pinch runner,
advanced to second on the ensuing walk to Veras, and that set the
stage for the Rangers' second gaffe.
</P>
<P>
   Padres manager Bruce Bochy instructed Jackson to attempt the
sacrifice to advance the runners, but it resulted in a bunt single
when neither Wetteland nor Zeile fielded the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile returned to the bag expecting Wetteland to field the bunt
and attempt to retire Giovanola at third base. Jackson's bunt,
though, did not present Wetteland with a play, which made it the
third baseman's play, Zeile said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more my responsibility,'' Zeile said. ``It's my judgment.
I just jumped the gun.''
</P>
<P>
   That brought Reggie Sanders to the plate with the bases loaded
and no outs, but Wetteland got him on a shallow fly ball. Right
fielder Juan Gonzalez made the play and delivered a one-hop throw
to the plate to retire Giovanola, who attempted to score after
tagging at third base.
</P>
<P>
   Giovanola stopped midway down the third-base line, but Veras
also tagged from second. That forced Giovanola to attempt to score,
and it resulted in a double play. Jackson joined Veras in scoring
position with a two-out stolen base, and Eric Owens worked the
count full during the game's final at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland induced the desired ground ball to the right side of
the infield, which Palmeiro stopped by lunging to the ground.
Wetteland, though, broke late toward the bag.
</P>
<P>
   Owens won the foot race for an infield single that scored Veras
from third base, and Jackson raced home from second after Wetteland
failed to control Palmeiro's throw. The ball dropped behind
Wetteland, whose momentum carried him toward first base while the
ball came to a rest on the infield grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I would have bounced off the mound and covered first, it's
all academic,'' Wetteland said. ``That's killing me and I'm sure
everybody else at this point. I threw it and saw it come off the
bat, and I thought, `Finally, a ground ball hit.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I turn around, and it's a lot more toward second base than I
thought. That's not an excuse. Anything hit to the right side, and
we should start toward first base. It's an unacceptable mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland's stare only reinforced his words.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
