<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5773 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-1ST     07-10 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-1STLEAD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: NO GOALS SCORED, TWO CHAMPIONS, A BRIGHT FUTURE 
(HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Full sub for VECSEY-COLUMN)   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The Curse of the Rose Bowl struck again
Saturday. A glorious breakthrough sports tournament was decided by
the utilitarian solution of penalty kicks.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody won _ the United States, in fact, beating China on a
penalty kick by Brandi Chastain after a scoreless tie. The
championship is full and complete and fair. The Americans, who had
been building for this home World Cup, will always be champions of
1999, and the Chinese, who were gracious hosts for the historic
first tournament in 1991, will always be runners-up for this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that it's necessarily fair,'' said Briana Scurry,
the American goalkeeper who punched away one penalty kick to give
the Americans the edge, 5-4, in the grim little coda to the game
itself. ``I guess it's a way of deciding who wins and loses. You
can't ask them to play anymore. But it's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   To fully appreciate Saturday's scoreless tie, you must look at
the past three weeks, go back to the Chinese criss-crossing
America, the Americans making a determined swath toward the Rose
Bowl, the Brazilians outlasting the Nigerians in a 4-3 fast-break
game on a muggy night in Maryland, and eager fans scooping up
tickets until there were no more.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday there were 90,185 fans packed into the Rose Bowl _ once
known only for American football _ making it the largest crowd to
watch a women's soccer game anywhere in the world, and presumably
the largest crowd to watch a women's sports event in history.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, never known as a soccer-loving nation, seemed
captivated by the vibrant athletes from home and around the globe,
giving hope for female athletes in the next century, the next
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the third Women's World Cup itself came to a rather
arbitrary end with the specter that haunts soccer tournaments
around the world. The two teams played 120 minutes without a goal,
exactly as Brazil and Italy did in the men's World Cup finale at
this hallowed football stadium, now known nearly as well for the
world's most popular sport, real football.
</P>
<P>
   That 1994 World Cup ended with Roberto Baggio, the ethereal
little star of Italy, missing a penalty kick.
</P>
<P>
   This one ended with Hollywood Chastain left-footing a shot into
the upper right corner, then tearing off her jersey to reveal a
black sports bra (``momentary insanity,'' she explained later), but
she was visible only for seconds before being engulfed by her
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   The United States contained China in regulation time as the
brave and aggressive old star, the 33-year-old Michelle Akers,
dominated with her range and her will and her booming headers.
Akers, who has had how many surgeries (``I lost count'') and
suffers from chronic fatigue syndrome, went down after a collision
at the goal line at the 90th minute and had to leave the game, and
the United States barely hung on without her.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Americans are champions, and China is an emphatic
second, representing all the other continents that soon will catch
up with the United States and northern Europe in World Cups to
come. At the same time, many Americans will once again question why
championship games like this one must end on something so arbitrary
and limited as penalty kicks.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of goals is no grave crime. Soccer buffs around the
world can accept that the best two teams in the world might play
each other to a standstill. And you could look at it this way:
Penalty kicks are the very essence of the sport _ kicking the ball
past the goalkeeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two champions,'' said Tony DiCicco, the American
coach, once an accomplished goalkeeper. ``We're delighted to have
it, but they could have carried it home with them. It's not the
best way, but you can't have a replay after a game like this.''
</P>
<P>
   DiCicco said the world is stuck with this solution ``until some
genius comes up with a better way.''
</P>
<P>
   No geniuses here. After 120 minutes of soccer, it is not fair to
ask Sun Wen or Mia Hamm to play any longer, just as nobody could
have expected Franco Baresi of Italy or Dunga of Brazil to keep
plodding on indefinitely back in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The Curse of the Rose Bowl also struck in the first game
Saturday, when Brazil beat Norway for third place after a scoreless
tie, also on the dreaded penalty kick.
</P>
<P>
   The championship game began after the normal blatant American
crudity of jet planes blasting overhead during the pre-game
``festivities'' _ plus skyrockets blasting at field level. No other
country in the world is so fascinated by military explosives
combined with sporting events. Someday, somebody will explain it to
me.
</P>
<P>
   There were also the usual traffic delays, searches, blockages
and general indignities produced by the whim of the chief
executive's deciding to take in a sporting event.
</P>
<P>
   The capriciousness of the result could not dim the celebration
on the field or in the stands. Some of the Americans have played
together all of this decade, and Akers goes all the way back to the
first national team in 1985. They have played all over the world,
they won the first championship in 1991 when it wasn't even called
the Women's World Cup, just as the Super Bowl was not the Super
Bowl the first time around.
</P>
<P>
   They won the 1996 gold medal at the Summer Olympics in front of
76,489 screaming fans in Athens, Ga., when NBC could not be
bothered showing a minute of women with muscles performing the
improvisational genius of soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday ABC showed the whole thing live from the Rose Bowl,
where once upon a time pom-poms fluttered on the sidelines and
starlets twinkled in the stands for big college football games.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday there was not a majorette in sight. Instead, 22 women
from China and the United States tore up the Rose Bowl lawn,
kicking a round ball with the side of their boots in the
championship game of the Women's World Cup, the last of this
century, but just the start of something bigger.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
