<HEADLINE>
JERRY FALWELL HAS ADVICE ON SELECTING A SUPERINTENDENT  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARA ROSE WILLIAMS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City School Board needs a superintendent who is
spiritual, moral and a good family man, the Rev. Jerry Falwell said
Saturday during a two-day visit to the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Credentials are important,'' said Falwell, a Baptist minister
and chancellor of Liberty University in Lynchburg, Va. ``But
children should be able to look up to their leader.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said the superintendent should be a good role model.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should be able to say to children, `Do as I do' and to
teach basic values,'' Falwell said.
</P>
<P>
   School board member Sandy Mayer said she ``couldn't agree more.
And if he wants to offer us some prayer, we'll take those too.''
</P>
<P>
   During a news conference Saturday, Falwell, who came to speak
today to the congregation of First Family Church, commented on
several topics, from Kansas City's search for a superintendent to
Hillary Rodham Clinton and Tinky Winky, the ``Teletubbie''
character Falwell's newspaper said was a homosexual role model.
</P>
<P>
   However, on Saturday Falwell denied having said anything about
the little purple character that carries a magical handbag.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never even seen the Teletubbies,'' Falwell said. He said
that several Tinky Winky dolls had since been sent to him and that
he gave them to his grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Falwell said he doesn't have time to worry about children's
television characters because he is more concerned about the torn
moral fabric of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Falwell said his message today to the congregation gathering at
Rockhurst High School would be a call to spiritual commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last generation has been a very sad one,'' Falwell said.
``With the breakdown of the family, drugs, violence and school
violence it has been a tough time for America. This country lacks
leadership, not just political but spiritual.''
</P>
<P>
   Falwell urged pastors to help families rebuild and to encourage
men to do a better job supporting their families.
</P>
<P>
   As for politics, Falwell denounced President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I would rather have Bill than Hillary,'' Falwell said. ``I
think Hillary was the real mastermind of the unacceptable and
unthinkable, like travelgate and filegate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think she will win a Senate seat in New York. The
Clintons are going to find out that the American people are
thoroughly disgusted with them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
