<HEADLINE>
DON'T TRADE GREER, JUST SIGN JUNIOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sigh. How do things like this get started?
</P>
<P>
   Is it because his name isn't something like Juan, or Moose, or
Junior? Is it the freckles?
</P>
<P>
   Or is it simply because Rusty Greer is what he is _
hard-working, underpaid and unquestionably professional _ that his
name always finds itself in trade rumors at this time of the year?
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Greer for Andy Pettitte? You've got to be kidding.
</P>
<P>
   Not this Andy Pettitte. Not the one with the 5-7 record and the
5.56 earned-run average, the one whom opponents are hitting .292
against. Not the Pettitte that can't seem to stay ahead of hitters
anymore and the one who's won only nine of his past 27 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Stop me if I'm missing something here, but Pettitte's days in
New York pinstripes are clearly numbered. He is
arbitration-eligible, and the Yankees seem not to be warming to the
notion of paying an inconsistent 5-7 pitcher $7 million a season.
(He makes $5.95 million now).
</P>
<P>
   Yet, to listen to the talk-show misguided, the Rangers should
take those troubles off the Yankees' hands and, at the same time,
solve Joe Torre's left-field problems.
</P>
<P>
   That's funny. And while they're at it, maybe the Rangers can
sign Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   That's not so funny. In fact, I think Tom Hicks should put his
best man right on it. Forget the ``Sign Verbeek'' bumper stickers.
Sign Junior. Shucks, sign his dad. Sign his five-year-old kid.
</P>
<P>
   This being July, those clearly were the two most provocative
baseball rumors of last week _ Greer for Pettitte, and the chatter
about Griffey being anything but a Seattle Mariner.
</P>
<P>
   The latter surfaced while the Mariners were here last weekend,
when a scan of public records disclosed that club management was
putting a Junior squeeze on its obligations to pay cost overruns at
Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   They played the Griffey Card, in other words. Mariners chairman
John Ellis said in a published memo that if the city's Public
Facilities District insisted upon making the team pay for an
estimated $60 million of the $100 million in excess costs, then
don't be surprised if Junior and Alex Rodriguez aren't around after
the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   They're bluffing, some people think. As columnist Steve Kelley
of The Seattle Times put it, ``If they really wanted to scare
Seattle, they should have threatened to bring back ... Heathcliff
Slocumb.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was first approached about the veiled threat last
weekend in Arlington, Griffey was miffed that his name was again
being used as leverage. He sounded tired of it. In recent weeks, he
also has sounded tired of living at the edge of the baseball earth
_ ``Anywhere we go, it's a long flight,'' he has said _ and of
Mariners management's on-again, off-again commitment to reaching a
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Both Griffey's and Rodriguez's contracts expire at the end of
the 2000 season. It would be a stunning surprise if the Mariners
kept both.
</P>
<P>
   If pitcher Kevin Brown was worth $105 million over seven
seasons, what would an everyday future Hall of Famer such as Junior
be worth? Griffey will be 31 when he plays for his next team, and
he is destined to become baseball's first $20-million-a-season
player.
</P>
<P>
   And worth every penny, of course. In Seattle, people drive from
Alaska to watch Ken Griffey Jr. play.
</P>
<P>
   Colleague Terence Moore wrote in The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution last week that ``somebody who definitely
knows'' says that Griffey already has told Mariners officials not
to expect him back after 2000. Moore said that Junior has four
teams on his wish list.
</P>
<P>
   Reportedly, Griffey is tired of not winning enough, tired of the
tedious travel to and from Seattle, and tired of not being closer
to his wife Melissa, their two kids and their home in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, in other words, has ``Atlanta Braves'' written all over
him. But don't forget Cincinnati, where he grew up and where his
dad is a coach and possibly the next manager. The Griffeys could be
Press and Pete Maravich all over again.
</P>
<P>
   And the Rangers? As always, money talks. Hicks is not afraid to
spend some to make some. How full can a ballpark get, watching its
superstar center fielder go after Hank Aaron's home-run record?
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, it also doesn't hurt that Griffey is fond of Johnny
Oates, Hicks' manager.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, they're quibbling this summer over who's going to
pay for the extra trimmings on $517-million Safeco Field. In the
meantime, a bargain named Griffey could one day slip away.
</P>
<P>
   Greer-for-Pettitte? It'll never happen.
</P>
<P>
   Junior, not a Mariner? Come on down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-10-99 2343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
