<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-AAU-NATIONALS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGIA, ARIZONA GIRLS TEAMS REIGN IN AAU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK MAUCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Georgia Magic coach Michael Green decided to
borrow a plan from football yesterday, and it helped his team
capture the Amateur Athletic Union 18-and-under Girls National
Basketball Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few hours after being blown out, 85-59, by the Alabama
Roadrunners, the Magic pulled off a 70-66 victory over the
Roadrunners to claim the national championship at Mansfield High
School's north campus.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Green's key players had suffered injuries _ Ashley
Hesprich sustained a split chin when she slipped on a wet spot and
fell to the floor, and Nadine Morgan tore a knee ligament. Then the
Magic fell behind by more than 20 points late in the second half.
So, Green decided to forgo an attempt to rally and instead
regrouped his team for another shot at the Roadrunners in the
double-elimination tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was as if someone had pulled the spirit out of us,'' Green
said. ``I made a decision to back up and punt.''
</P>
<P>
   The strategy worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was embarrassing to be beaten like we were earlier today,
but we reserved our energy and concentrated on beating them this
afternoon,'' said Mary Beth Lycett, who broke a 63-63 tie with two
baskets, including a 3-pointer, in the final 1 minute, 37 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Lycett's 3-pointer came with 24 seconds left in the game. She
called it the biggest shot of her life, and her coach agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she hit that, I knew we had the ballgame,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Lycett finished with four 3-pointers, 14 points and grabbed
seven rebounds. Christi Thomas led Georgia with 23 points and nine
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Smith kept the Roadrunners' hopes alive with her fifth
3-point shot of the game with 12 seconds left to close the gap to
68-66. But tournament most valuable player Megan Isom sealed the
victory for Georgia with two free throws with six seconds to go.
 &LR; subheds:17-and-under Arizona Elite 77, Cedar Falls (Iowa) 73
Jessica Combs didn't have the tournament she would have liked, but
she made up for it in the final three minutes of the championship
game. Playing with four fouls, Combs scored eight of her 13 points
in the final 2:54, including going 6-for-6 at the free-throw line,
to rally Arizona Elite to the 17-and-under national title after it
had trailed the Cedar Falls Deery Tigers most of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona took the lead for the final time when Lacy Tolbert hit a
3-pointer with 45 seconds to play to make it 75-73. Kyra Melville
and Lindsey Taylor each added a free throw in the final half a
minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our motto coming in was one game, one day at a time. They
didn't want to come back and play again this afternoon,'' Arizona
coach Cassandra Yancy said after her team went through the
double-elimination tournament bracket 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   Elite used a 15-4 run to take a 60-59 lead with 7:32 left in the
game. Cedar Falls answered with a 12-6 run, however, before Arizona
had a closing run of 11-2.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
