<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-10 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5815 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JETS-BRAWL-NYT &LR;      07-10 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-BRAWL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS PLAYERS ATTACK PATRONS, INJURE POLICE IN BAR BRAWL  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two New York Jets players and a former teammate were
arrested early Saturday after a brawl in a Long Island bar in which
a man and a woman were punched and two police officers were injured
by flying glass from the shattered window of their patrol car.
</P>
<P>
   According to the police in Long Beach, most of the damage was
done by John (Jumbo) Elliott, a left tackle who was once a
contender for football's Hall of Fame, and Matthew O'Dwyer, a right
guard who recently signed a two-year, $2.7 million contract with
the Cincinnati Bengals.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, 34, was charged with assault, disorderly conduct,
public lewdness and harassment, and O'Dwyer, 26, was accused of
disorderly conduct, harassment, assault and criminal mischief, the
police said. The Jets right tackle, Jason Fabini, 24, was also
arrested and charged with disorderly conduct, but played only a
minor role in the melee, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   All three players were released on bail, with Fabini paying
$100, while Elliott posted $10,000 and O'Dwyer posted $50,000, all
in cash, the police said. The suspects were scheduled to enter
pleas to the charges Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach bars have long been popular hangouts and watering
holes for Jets players, many of whom live in the area and train at
Hofstra University in nearby Hempstead. The three suspects, all
offensive players, were apparently celebrating O'Dwyer's move to
Cincinnati, where he was scheduled to join the Bengals Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Joseph Kearnes of the Long Beach City Police Department said
the incident early Saturday at Bogart's, a restaurant and sports
bar at 124 West Park Avenue, was both ``unusual'' and
``disturbing'' in its violence. He said a fight led to a call to
the police about 12:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were all drunk and started a melee in the bar,'' he said.
``They started pushing customers around and one guy did some things
in a bathroom. They are all big guys and they got out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets roster lists all three players as 6 feet 5 inches to 6
feet 7 inches tall and weighing 300 pounds of more.
</P>
<P>
   Kearnes said the episode began when Elliott entered the bar's
women's bathroom and began to urinate in a sink, in front of a
woman. When she protested, he punched her in the chest, the police
said, then walked back into the bar, where police said he punched a
man who approached him. Patrons at the bar said that one of the
other players then threw a beer bottle at a waitress, and the third
player pushed another woman to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   After several police officers arrived, Elliott and Fabini were
taken into custody without incident but O'Dwyer became combative,
Kearnes said. In a patrol car, he kicked out the rear window,
sending glass into the eyes of two officers outside the car, the
police said. Both officers had to be taken to a hospital to have
glass surgically removed from their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   A manager reached at the bar by phone Saturday refused to
comment about the events there. Elliott could not be reached by
telephone Saturday, nor could the agents for him or the other two
players.
</P>
<P>
   O'Dwyer's father, Gerald, who was reached at his home in
Lincolnshire, Ill., defended his son, saying the charges sounded
``out of character.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard to believe, because he is usually
cool-headed,'' the father said. ``He doesn't drink that much and
he's working very hard right now to stay in shape. He was leaving
tomorrow and had just sold his house in Long Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the accusation that his son kicked out the window
of a police car, the elder O'Dwyer said, ``They might have pushed
him; he can get angry.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Parcells, the Jets coach, could not be reached for comment
Saturday, and two of the team's spokesmen did not return calls to
their office phones. Jack Brennan, a spokesman for the Bengals,
said only that if O'Dwyer ``has a problem with the legal system, he
will have to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott and Fabini have been well-regarded players for the Jets
and were two of the pivotal factors in protecting the team's
quarterback, Vinny Testaverde, during what the quarterback recently
called his ``magical season'' last year. Testaverde said the two
players had given him the best protection of his career, helping
him to lead the Jets to their first conference championship since
1983.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott has had previous problems off the field. In September,
he was fined $375 and had his driver's license suspended for 90
days after he was convicted of driving while impaired and making
unsafe lane changes on the Long Island Expressway in Nassau County,
not far from where he lives.
</P>
<P>
   O'Dwyer, who has often been seen partying at Manhattan
nightspots, was also instrumental in the Jets' success. A weight
lifter who can bench-press 465 pounds, he was known as both the
strongest player on the Jets offensive line and a source of
penalties for his team because of a tendency to hit opposing
players after the whistle had blown. ``I've always been taught to
finish the play,'' he answered when once asked about that tendency
by a reporter. But he was recently praised by Parcells as the
player he most admired for reining in his temper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
